<HEADER>
A8979 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-16 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LAKERS WIN WORTH CELEBRATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hey, guys, it's OK to smile.
</P>
<P>
   There's cause for celebration in the land of the Lakers after
they got over a low but significant hump Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   You and I know it. Now, who wants to to tell the players?
</P>
<P>
   The TV cameras showed victorious Lakers trudging off the court
in Houston looking about as joyous as if they'd just walked out of
a two-hour algebra class _ and into a three-hour geometry lecture.
</P>
<P>
   The blank expressions might have been the Lakers' quiet way of
saying their 98-88 victory and 3-1 series rout of the Houston
Rockets were no big deal, only one down and three NBA playoff
rounds to go.
</P>
<P>
   They might have been applying a lesson of 1998, when their
impressive playoff dismissal of the Seattle SuperSonics set up the
Lakers for a sweep by the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels good,'' Lakers guard Derek Fisher told the
Daily News' Howard Beck in the locker room after Saturday's
victory. ``But for me personally, I can remember last season, after
beating Seattle in the Western Conference semifinals, I was a
little (begin ital)too(end ital) excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that really affected the way I played _ and some of
our other guys _ in the Western Conference finals. We really felt
like we had done something after beating Seattle four games in a
row. And we had a big-time letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're going to enjoy this, but probably later tonight
and in the morning, it's all San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be much time to rejoice, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers flew to San Antonio on Saturday night, will practice
there today and will open the conference semifinals against the
Spurs at the Alamodome on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But if they had five minutes on the plane, between wheels-up and
deal-'em, let's hope they toasted themselves with plastic bottles
of spring water.
</P>
<P>
   From where you and I sat, watching the No.4 seeds embarrass the
No.5 seeds on their home court, it looked like an accomplishment
worth saluting.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody was certain they'd get this far _ not 20 days ago
when the self-same Rockets handed the Lakers their sixth defeat in
eight games, when Glen Rice was lost in the offense, when defense
seemed to be an afterthought, when fans were pining for Eddie Jones
and _ it had come to this _ Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happened next. A team meeting. A Rice arrival. A
defensive revival. A four-game winning streak to end the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as some of us waited for old habits to return just as
quickly, the young Lakers continued to play hard and smart, and
embarrassed the veteran Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it turned out they not only didn't need Jones and
Campbell, they didn't need Rice when all their other weapons were
working.
</P>
<P>
   They took command of the game shortly after learning that Rice
would have to watch from the bench because of stiffness in the
shooting elbow that required surgery in January.
</P>
<P>
   Without thinking about it, they also sent a timely message to
Rice, since the victory came a day after he publicly pleaded for
changes in the offense to get him more shots.
</P>
<P>
   Between Shaquille O'Neal (a game-high 37 points) and Kobe Bryant
(24, including 13 in a row in the first half), with timely shooting
by Derek Harper and Robert Horry, Rice had plenty to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   After weathering the eight lead changes in the fourth quarter to
win Game 1, addressing their defensive shortcomings to run away
with Game 2, and emphatically answering the questions that followed
the Rockets' Game 3 victory, the Lakers have reached not just the
second round but a new level.
</P>
<P>
   The big obstacle might not have been the Rockets, an
uncomfortable combination of age and inexperience, but the bad
habits and self-doubts that could have been left over from the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough, and they know it, as their subdued demeanors
indicated. Maybe we're getting carried away and all the Lakers have
really done is set up their fans for disappointment in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers won a playoff series and put the regular season
behind them Saturday. (begin ital)That's(end ital) cause for
celebration. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0015EDT &QL; 
