<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8984 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-FUTURE-AZR &LR;      05-16 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-FUTURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS PINPOINT BIG NEEDS  
 OFF-SEASON COULD SEE SEARCH FOR TOUGH GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - First order of business for the Suns this off-season:
Look up the Dallas Mavericks in the Rolodex. Or maybe Don Nelson is
already on speed dial.
</P>
<P>
   After all, in 1996 the Mavericks took A.C. Green and his
contract off the Suns' hands and in return gave them an All-Star
point guard, Jason Kidd, as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And last summer the Mavericks gave the Suns a first-round draft
pick for Steve Nash that landed Phoenix in the draft lottery. Nash
signed a big contract extension with Dallas and then had a
forgettable season.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the criticism Nelson has taken in Dallas over the
lottery pick, he might not be accepting calls from Phoenix. But
it's time for the Suns to start wheeling, and possibly dealing, in
the wake of another early playoff exit.
</P>
<P>
   Where do they go from 27-23 and a three-game sweep at the hands
of the Portland Trail Blazers en route to a fourth straight
first-round playoff departure?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be tougher, that's the No. 1 thing,'' Suns Coach
Danny Ainge said. ``We need some interior defense and some interior
offense. If you watch the teams that are successful in the
playoffs, they have at least one guy they can go to who is going to
make the defense double-team.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, those big, tough interior players are rather
expensive and everybody else wants them, too. The Suns also hope to
add athleticism in the process, not just size and bulk.
</P>
<P>
   The club has two first-round draft picks, the Mavericks' choice
which will fall anywhere from one to 11 in the draft, depending on
where the Suns are drawn, and they have their own choice, No. 16 in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns owe Chicago a first-round pick to complete the Luc
Longley deal, which they must hand over this year or in 2001. The
Suns must let the Bulls know by May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``The known is better than the unknown,'' said General Manager
Bryan Colangelo, indicating the team is likely to keep the 16th
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the team has both salary cap exceptions available, the
mid-range exception of about $2 million and a $1-million cap
exception.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, any team in the league that's over the salary cap _
as the Suns are _ can sign as many players to minimum contracts as
the team wants. Those minimums, which rise with years in the
league, can go up to $1 million for a 10-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the playoffs, but another first-round exit is not what
we have in mind any year, much less this one,'' said Colangelo.
``But we've got a chance to build on all the positives we did
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to add athleticism and toughness, and we can address
at least one of those with the first pick. With the cap exceptions
we have, we'll be able to add some pieces. The timing part is
waiting to see who falls through the cracks, the Rex Chapmans and
the Cliff Robinsons.''
</P>
<P>
   First, however, the club hopes to re-sign their own top free
agent, forward Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing Cliff is one of our top priorities,'' Ainge said.
``And that's easier said than done with the kind of year he had.
You can have a plan, but there are 29 teams trying to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of free agents available, and some great
players should they decide to exercise early termination clauses in
their contracts _ such as Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers, David
Robinson of the Spurs and Penny Hardaway of the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, however, are not in position to bid on the big-time
free agents this summer. Their only hope would be to convince a
player to sign for less than market value, and give them the big
payoff a few years down the line.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, the Suns will be looking through cap exceptions,
draft picks and trades.
</P>
<P>
   (The draft got better with the recent additions of Rhode Island
forward Lamar Odom and Duke forward Corey Maggette.)
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also may be helped by an overload of point guards in
this summer's draft, including Arizona's Jason Terry, Maryland's
Steve Francis, UCLA's Baron Davis, Utah's Andre Miller and Duke's
William Avery.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have Jason Kidd, so depending on how high they land in
the draft with the Dallas pick, they could have the flexibility of
trading up or down to a team in need of a playmaker, getting a
forward or shooting guard along with another pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, we're the ones trying to be creative to move up,''
Colangelo said. ``This year we might be hearing from the teams
trying to be creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge believes the quickest method of making significant
improvement is through trades. However, he knows it also is the
most difficult way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to get a lot better with a
19-year-old from the draft, who might be a star someday but isn't
yet,'' Ainge said. ``But it's very difficult to pull those (trades)
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have a lot of forwards _ some of whom would have to be
signed before they could be traded, but the only player on their
roster with blockbuster value is playmaker Kidd and he's an
untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a logjam of forwards that are not great athletes,''
Ainge said. ``But it's not a simple as adding athletes and losing
everything you have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge believes guard Rex Chapman will bounce back from his
disappointing season, and said he's got a better feel for his
personnel and how to make it work around Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not planning on burying Rex Chapman,'' he said.
``We still have big plans for him in the future. At some time, Rex
is going to have to take a diminished role as a third guard, but I
don't know if that's next year. A lot depends on his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot about Tom Gugliotta and Luc Longley this
season, and they learned a lot about playing with Jason.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ainge said he liked the club's three rookies, Gerald Brown
(who has his option in his contract for another season), Toby
Bailey and Pat Garrity, who all got some time despite having no
summer league to develop, a brief training camp and virtually no
regular practices during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Pat played better than any of them when he had an
opportunity to play,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved what Randy (Livingston) brought from a toughness
standpoint. I wasn't afraid to put him in against maybe the best
defensive guard in basketball (Greg Anthony). I'm excited about our
young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the rest of the organization, but club President Jerry
Colangelo and his son Bryan never have remained dormant in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is happy that we've been eliminated in the first round
four years in a row,'' Jerry Colangelo said. ``That's not
satisfactory. But there's a real commitment to turn this around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0018EDT &QL; 
