r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ROCKIES-AZ     05-16 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ROCKIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACE BOUNCES BACK  
 JOHNSON, D-BACKS' BATS SUBDUE ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Every time Randy Johnson pitches for the Diamondbacks,
he says he likes to build on what he did in his previous start.
</P>
<P>
   He said that after giving up six runs and a career-high 13 hits
on Monday against Montreal, ``I had a lot of building to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander began Saturday's start against the Colorado
Rockies and went in the opposite direction, giving up a leadoff
home run to Neifi Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Then he quickly turned things around _ and put the Diamondbacks
on top of the NL West. Johnson gave up just two hits the rest of
the way and struck out 11 while getting more than enough support
from his offense in a 9-2 victory in front of 40,853 at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to losses by the Giants and Dodgers, the victory gave the
Diamondbacks a share of the division lead _ tied with the Giants
(21-16) _ for the first time in their two-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, meanwhile, improved to 4-1 with his third complete game
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to make my pitches a lot of games,''
Johnson said. ``There's always one inning that things don't go the
way you want them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to make perfect pitches, but you realize that's not
going to happen. So getting ahead of guys (in the count) is
important. That's what I did today. I pitched the way I wanted
to.''
</P>
<P>
   He did it with his trademark fastball, which reached the upper
90s on numerous occasions. Yet his other pitches, particularly his
slider, make him more effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more there than just a good arm,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``For those of us who saw him early in
his career, to see how far he's come with his command . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller, who had three of Arizona's 16 hits,
including a solo home run in the seventh inning, said the way
Johnson's slider moves down and in on right-handed hitters, ``You
can forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks center fielder Steve Finley can't forget about
facing Johnson last season in the National League playoffs when
Finley was with San Diego and Johnson was with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the other side, and I know what it looks like, or
better yet, don't know what it looks like because I never really
saw it,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gave up an unearned run, primarily because of his
fielding error, in the third inning as Colorado took a 2-1 lead.
The Diamondbacks scored twice in the fourth on a run-scoring
ground-rule double by Travis Lee and a groundout by Miller, then
opened things up with a five-run fifth against right-hander Darryl
Kile (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   A two-run homer by Finley, his eighth of the season, was the key
ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you give a guy like Randy a lead like that, it's usually
lights out,'' Finley said. ``There are only a few pitchers around
who you can say that about.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer was Finley's third in a week. He also had a
fourth-inning single. He raised his average to .232. Is that a sign
that he is starting to emerge from his early-season struggle?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so, but I'm not going to worry about it,'' he said.
``I'm going to take it as it comes, day by day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's so great about this club is that we all chip
in. Call it ham-and-eggin'. Everybody picks up the slack, and it
puts everybody at ease. We can beat you a lot of different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Arizona position player had at least one hit. Miller and
Tony Womack had three each.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Luis Gonzalez was among four players with two hits.
He increased his club-record and personal-best hitting streak to 27
games with a single that drove in Womack with Arizona's first run
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams also had a pair and became the first
man in the league to drive in 40 runs. He didn't drive in his 40th
last season until the club's 83rd game June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Womack continued to turn on the speed, grabbing the league's
stolen base lead with his 19th and 15th in a row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
