<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-AZR &LR;      05-16 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLANGELO TO RAISE FUNDS FOR DEMOCRAT BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politics, it seems, isn't like sports. You don't
have to root for just one team.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix sports mogul Jerry Colangelo, a registered Republican,
said Friday that he will host a fund-raiser on June 24 at Bank One
Ballpark for Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley, the
former New Jersey senator and basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it might seem an odd plan: Bradley heading into
Republican-dominated Arizona, into the back yard of GOP
presidential candidates John McCain and Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Quayle have previously received financial help
for their campaigns from Colangelo, who is president of
basketball's Phoenix Suns and managing general partner of
baseball's Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said there is no conflict. Like team-oriented players,
everyone seems to know exactly where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, Bill knows I'm a registered Republican and
knows that I'm actively supporting John McCain and that I've been
of some assistance to Dan Quayle,'' Colangelo said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Colangelo helped Quayle by hosting a fund-raiser at
the sports executive's home. Meanwhile, Colangelo contributed
$2,000 to McCain's presidential campaign during the first quarter
of 1999, according to Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Dan I was committed to John some time ago, but I said I
would help him,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Bill Bradley came to see me (more than a year ago) to talk
about his aspirations. We talked about differences, to some degree,
from a political point of view. And yet, because I've known him for
some time and respect him a great deal and feel that he would make
a very viable candidate on the other side, I told him I would be of
some help.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon, especially among wealthy contributors, to
donate to more than one candidate for the same office, even those
of different political stripes. Conversely, candidates frequently
accept donations from executives with opposite viewpoints on the
issues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel this is awkward at all,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he has known Bradley since Bradley's playing days
with the New York Knicks in the late 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's sports links are playing a large role in his push for
the Democratic nomination. A few weeks ago, Willis Reed and Dave
Debusscherre, both former Knicks teammates, joined Bradley at a New
York fund-raiser. Former Chicago Bulls Coach Phil Jackson, also a
teammate on the Knicks, has been accompanying Bradley on the
campaign circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo's fund-raiser will coincide with the visit of slugger
Mark McGwire and the St. Louis Cardinals to play the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these political fund-raisers are in hotels, and
they're lunches or dinners,'' Colangelo said. ``Somebody said,
`What about doing something a little different?' Rather than a
sit-down dinner, it's going to be an informal, hot-dogs event _
more of a `Baseball with Bill' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The event will begin at a microbrewery adjacent to the ballpark.
Guests will likely migrate to the St. Louis game afterward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
