<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     05-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ AND LUCK: THE MIDAS TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sometime after another day in the sun and another
cruise-control victory, someone delivered the news to Luis
Gonzalez:
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic won the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, happened to be the name of the horse Gonzalez
drew in the blind clubhouse pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say he won more than a dollar,'' equipment manager
Chris Guth said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, luck is fleeting. Not prone to sit down and stay a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has fortune in a stranglehold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also won the Kentucky Derby (pool),'' Guth said. ``With a
31-1 shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means he's one win removed from the Triple Crown. And if
the streak is still alive when the gates open at the Belmont . . .
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years ago, Gonzalez was a 10-year-old growing up in
Tampa. He was a huge fan of the Cincinnati Reds. And, yes, he
remembers when Pete Rose slapped together a 44-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Gonzalez said. ``He's my favorite player.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, just four pitches into his first at-bat, Gonzalez'
hitting streak reached 27 games. It is now tied for the
third-longest streak of the decade, and if he reaches 30, it will
qualify as a national event. The media will multiply and descend,
hover over every at-bat. A writer from ``Sports Illustrated'' is
already combing the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize there weren't that many players with streaks
of more than 20 in the '90s,'' Gonzalez said. ``But I'm just having
fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A single today, and he's halfway to DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That streak is unbelievable,'' Gonzalez said. ``You play 162
games, and he got 56 straight. No one's come close to that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Diamondbacks crushed the Rockies, and the story
lines are everywhere: The redemption of Jay Bell. The smoldering
Matt Williams. The catalyst spark of Tony Womack. The intense
leadership of Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   For now, they are a five-tool team. They are 14-4 at Bank One
Ballpark. They are compelling, exciting, worth the price of
admission. And with this organization, that's saying something. If
the Diamondbacks don't go flat, they could carry the pulse of the
desert over the next few months, making up for all the playoff
games not won by the Suns and the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the unexpected drama, nothing compares to
Gonzalez. He is the left-handed power stick sorely missing from
last season's lineup. He is everything Karim Garcia will never be,
proof that Joe Garagiola Jr. doesn't spend his afternoons flipping
pencils into the ceiling. After all, the Tigers not only traded
Gonzalez for Garcia, they threw in an extra $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to talk about (Gonzalez' streak) too much,'' Manager
Buck Showalter said. ``But he's swinging the bat just like a
three-hole hitter should.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Gonzalez' fourth team in as many years, but he is no
journeyman. Rather, a player who is just starting to peak. He is
also widely known around the major leagues as one of the nicest men
in the game, and if this is the work of good karma, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know with these things,'' Gregg Olson said.
``Whenever I win at cards, I pitch terrible. Whenever I lose at
cards, I pitch well. You can guess that I won a lot of money early
in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez doesn't know what to think. He remembers a streak back
in 1997 that lasted 23 games. He remembers a fluke at-bat against
Todd Worrell, and a ground ball that somehow weaseled through his
wickets. And now . . . 27 and counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, everything has been falling in,'' Gonzalez said.
``You have to have a lot of luck involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, or you could never explain this:
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning on Saturday, a section of BOB was
designated as the subject of a daily contest. Anyone who catches a
line drive in that area would win $5,000 on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Gonzalez ripped a foul ball down the right-field
line, screaming into the designated section, plucked out of midair
by a lucky fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about that, helping a guy walk out of here
with $5,000,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can only keep luck strapped to the chair for a little
while longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys who want me to go looking for wallets with
them,'' Gonzalez said. ``Or go to Vegas with them.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
