<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WORD ON SCHOENFELD, BUT COYOTES MAY JUST KEEP HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been almost two weeks, about the time Coyotes General
Manager
 &UR; Bobby Smith said it would take to determine Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld's
future in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But it's going to take a little while longer. And time might
actually be on Schoenfeld's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lengthy meeting with Jim last week,'' Smith said,
``and I told him we'd meet again, probably within the next two to
three weeks, to resolve the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   An interesting choice of words, considering Smith suggests
Schoenfeld's job status shouldn't ``be an issue'' at all. Smith
said it had become one ``because of the team's elimination, No. 1,
from another first-round playoff loss and, No. 2, because of Jim's
comments after Game 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who has one year remaining on his three-year
contract, predicted the Coyotes would win Game 7 against the St.
Louis Blues, saying, ``I would tell you I would stake my job on it,
but that's already been done, so I'll just say we're going to win
Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever a mandate from above that clearly tied
Schoenfeld's security to a first-round Phoenix victory, something
the franchise hasn't accomplished in eight straight postseason
trips? No one will say, although Schoenfeld's post-game comments
after Game 6 increased the building speculation that some type of
ultimatum might exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Jim about his remarks,'' Smith said, ``and he
maintained to me they were merely an effort to take pressure off
the players. . . . I don't know. I thought it was a curious thing
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto with Schoenfeld's ``unlike them, we've got points to
waste'' quote after a particularly nasty game with the Mighty Ducks
of Anaheim. The Coyotes went on to lose 11 of 13 games as the Ducks
battled back from a 15-point deficit in the standings to pull
within two points of Phoenix in the race for the No. 4 playoff seed
in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he had completely understood Schoenfeld's frustration
and that the coach's comments were simply ``an angry, emotional
reaction'' after a chippy game against a heated rival.
</P>
<P>
   So Schoenfeld won't get canned over a couple of remarks. And
it's hard to blame him for the team's first-round exit when the
Coyotes were so short-handed against the Blues, even though they
blew a 3-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   The real question should be whether Smith and owner  &UR; Richard
 &UR; Burke are comfortable with Schoenfeld's coaching style. Is he
getting the most out of his players, or is he crimping some of
their styles, at least offensively, with his punishing brand of
physical hockey? Players should be able to adapt, but this past
season's collection should have been able to produce at better than
12 percent on the power play, too.
</P>
<P>
   They scored 205, 18th in the 27-team NHL. But they only gave up
197, a team record for fewest in a season. Twenty clubs gave up
more. Does the system really need to be changed? If so, can
Schoenfeld adjust if he is retained?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence Jim can coach any number of styles,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Call it an educated guess or simply a hunch, but Smith will make
a brief statement within the next several days to announce that
Schoenfeld will return next season as coach. &QL; 
Bam Bam Barnaby &QL; 
He's at it again. Bad Boy  &UR; Matthew Barnaby, the guy who once
threatened to take a run at his own goalie ( &UR; Dominik Hasek), &UR; flew
off the handle the other day in Toronto during Pittsburgh's playoff
series with the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   After getting heckled by a fan at the Air Canada Centre, he
swung his stick at the walls and ceiling in the runway leading from
the visitors' bench to the locker room. The incident caused between
$200 and $300 in damage, and the Leafs said Barnaby, now with the
Penguins, can expect a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been sent anything,'' Barnaby said. ``And if I do
get something, I'll be sending it right back. There's no chance of
me paying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Penguins Coach  &UR; Kevin Constantine agrees with Barnaby about the
area in question at the arena. There just isn't enough room between
the players and fans, he said, and someday, the incidents could
become much worse. &QL; 
Broadcast alert
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' television and radio broadcast teams likely will
remain intact for at least the next few years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Television play-by-play man  &UR; Doug McLeod and color commentator
 &UR; Charlie Simmer, &UR; along with veteran radio voice  &UR; Curt Kielback and
first-year analyst  &UR; Jimmy Johnson, &UR; were offered multiyear pacts
Monday, and all are expected to agree to terms at some point this
week.
</P>
<P>
   There were come concerns the team might lose McLeod to the
expansion Minnesota Wild, where he once was the voice of the North
Stars, but McLeod has told team executives he planned to stay in
the Valley for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose NHL playing career was cut short a year ago with
the Coyotes because of post-concussion syndrome, made major strides
in his first season in the booth. Don't expect him to remain in
broadcasting forever, though. Johnson shows aspirations of being
NHL coaching material and, perhaps down the line, NHL management. &QL; 
Sutterville
</P>
<P>
   Another Sutter brother has joined the coaching ranks. This one,
though, will also own the team he plans to coach.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, former NHL center  &UR; Brent Sutter, who recently retired
after 17 seasons spent between the Islanders and Chicago
Blackhawks, purchased the Red Deer (Alberta) Rebels, a Canadian
junior team in the Western Hockey League. The price tag was $3
million (U.S.) and Sutter, one of six brothers to play in the NHL,
will be the team's head coach as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Darryl Sutter coaches the San Jose Sharks, and  &UR; Brian Sutter
coaches the Calgary Flames. Both were among finalists to coach the
Coyotes in recent years. &QL; 
Just wondering
</P>
<P>
   Why did the Florida Panthers raise their ticket prices for the
sixth straight year? Know what it costs for two season tickets in
the club-level area? Try $7,740. Who can afford that nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   Does  &UR; Mark Recchi's &UR; new five-year, $25 million contract with the
Philadelphia Flyers set the standard for this summer's crop of
unrestricted free agents? Perhaps, but San Jose's
 &UR; Vincent Damphousse won't get nearly that much, and Colorado's  &UR; Theo
 &UR; Fleury will get more.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Coyotes be interested in veteran
 &UR; Lance Pitlick, who unexpectedly became an unrestricted free agent
and likely won't re-sign with the Ottawa Senators? Count on it.
Pitlick is a great leader who always leaves it all on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Edmonton Oilers be able to sell 13,000 season tickets
by the NHL's May 31 deadline in order to receive $2.5 million
(U.S.) in relief under the league's Canadian currency equalization
plan?
</P>
<P>
   Who will the Los Angeles Kings hire to replace Coach  &UR; Larry
Robinson, whose contract was not extended? Many think it will be
former Sabres Coach  &UR; Ted Nolan, who was unceremoniously canned two
years ago after winning the Jack Adams Trophy. But don't bank on
it.
</P>
<P>
   How is it that Penguins superstar  &UR; Jaromir Jagr was able to
shake off that pesky groin injury so quickly? Toronto Coach  &UR; Pat
Burns suspects it was never that bad to begin with, saying, ``You
don't skate like he's skating with a groin injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr credits acupuncture for his speedy recovery. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
