<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN STILL NOT OUT OF OWNERSHIP PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports out of Charlotte, N.C., are that the talks between
 &UR; Michael
 &UR; Jordan and Hornets owner  &UR; George Shinn are over and there will not
be a deal for the sale of the club to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations broke off last week because Jordan, to nobody's
surprise, insisted on control of business and basketball decisions.
Shinn offered 100 percent control over the basketball operation,
but wanted equal say in business decisions. Jordan wanted both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would always confer (on decisions),'' Jordan told the
``Charlotte'' ``Observer.'' ``The issue was how to resolve
deadlocks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to blame Jordan for wanting total control. After all,
he's offering more than $80 million for half the team. And having
control of basketball decisions doesn't mean much if he doesn't
control the money, which will determine what the basketball
operation can do.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn is notoriously cheap. The club has lost stars such as
 &UR; Alonzo
 &UR; Mourning, Larry Johnson, Vlade Divac and  &UR; Glen Rice because Shinn
would not pay them the big contracts it takes to keep players of
that value.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who reportedly has a net worth of $500 million, even
offered to buy Shinn out entirely for $165 million _ $5 million
more than Shinn has said the club is worth. He paid $32.5 million
for it 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn turned the offer down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have agreed to a 50-50 split, but ultimately my
decisions had to be it,'' Jordan told the ``Observer.'' ``He wanted
to keep the business (control). It wasn't about money. I offered to
buy him out. It was about control, and we never were able to get
that resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's over, right?
</P>
<P>
   Something says maybe not. Shinn is fighting accusations of an
alleged sexual assault, and he has run the franchise pretty much
into the ground. The team wants a new arena, and Shinn will never
bolster support for one.
</P>
<P>
   And there's nothing more that NBA Commissioner  &UR; David Stern
would like to see than Jordan as an owner in the league _ and Shinn
in the background.
</P>
<P>
   So Shinn needs Jordan. Nobody else is going to give him $80
million and not have control, or an agreement to eventually get it.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA wants Jordan, who's presence would immediately improve
the worth and visibility of the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   And Jordan has the money, corporate backing and leverage to make
a deal to his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has rekindled dead negotiations before. He can do it
again. &QL; 
Payton's Place &QL; 
The ``Seattle Times'' reported that  &UR; Gary Payton wants improvements
in the SuperSonics or he wants out of Seattle. Payton later denied
he said that, and the paper stood by its report.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that Payton is unhappy after his
club missed the playoffs for the first time in his career in  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Westphal's &UR; first season as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things don't improve, I'm done with it,'' the ``Times''
quote Payton as saying. ``I've had articles written about me saying
I'm a joke for this, a joke for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, take me off this team, and we'll see what the joke is.
People are blaming me _ as always. Well, take me off this team, and
it'll be different. It'll be a lot different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans know. I come out every night and play. I've been good to
Seattle, good to my teammates for nine years. I've never said
anything negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is always telling me I don't need to get into it
with anybody. But I'm starting to get to the point where i don't
care about that anymore. I've always tried thinking about being
around guys, respecting them and not hurting their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guys haven't thought about my feelings, and I'm starting
to see that. I've been taking it for four or five years, and it's
getting bad for me. So I'm going to go in there and tell the guys
what I want. If it's not what they like, then get rid of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Priorities &QL; 
Dallas Coach/GM  &UR; Don Nelson said his first priority is re-signing
free agent power forward  &UR; Gary Trent in the off-season, and his
second priority is getting former Suns forward  &UR; Cedric Ceballos
under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos, who makes his off-season home in the Valley, suffered
two broken wrists in a game this season _ and finished the game
before sitting out the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Give it to me! &QL; 
 &UR; Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers has a termination clause in his
contract, but nobody could pay him more than the Lakers. So he's
not going anywhere, right?
</P>
<P>
   One wonders after what O'Neal told the ``Houston Chronicle.''
And with the money he's already made in the game, movies, music
recordings and videos, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wants to win and, as you can tell, he'd rather do it NOW.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people like to use the word `Patience,' but I
don't have any patience,'' O'Neal said. ``I wasn't born with
patience, and I don't have any patience now. I like to get (stuff)
done now, but I guess we have to be patient with one another and
just learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq was just getting warmed up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that type of person. I'm the type of person that, if
they start putting (stuff) off till next year, then it's time for
me to (expletive) quit. I like to get it done now. If I want a
(four-star word) car, I need to get it done now. I'm not going to
order the (five-star word) and then go get it next year. I want it
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same with championships. But that's just the type of
person I am. Maybe I'm wrong for not having patience. I know it's
going to be hard, and I'm going to have to have patience. But I
don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   That, we could tell. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at 602-444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
