<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE STILL FOLLOWS COWBOYS LIKE SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Coach  &UR; Barry Switzer got most of the blame. When he left
the Dallas Cowboys 16 months ago, their image problem was supposed
to go away.
</P>
<P>
   But after former Cowboys offensive tackle  &UR; Mark Tuinei died 10
days ago from taking a combination of heroin and a stimulant, the
franchise is reeling again.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, who played a team-record 15 seasons, had been retired
for only nine months. A current player, reserve fullback  &UR; Nicky
Sualua, was with him when he died.
</P>
<P>
   Sualua didn't immediately call 911 when Tuinei lost
consciousness almost right away after taking the heroin, according
to Plano, Texas, police. Instead, Sualua performed CPR on his
friend, then drove to Tuinei's house in Plano and remained in the
car with him overnight. Finally, the next morning, when Tuinei
wasn't breathing, Sualua called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer's replacement,  &UR; Chan Gailey, can't be held responsible
for the death or Sualua's poor judgment. He never even coached
Tuinei. He has been around Sualua for only one season.
</P>
<P>
   But controversy with the Cowboys never seems to end.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Gailey's first training camp, he had to endure
``Scissorsgate,'' the affair in which offensive guard  &UR; Everett
McIver suffered a deep cut to the neck in a dormitory incident.
</P>
<P>
   What other team has had a player get hurt during haircuts?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have been determined to clean up their act _ no more
havens for players to bring strippers for sex and drugs _ so they
passed on Marshall wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss in the first round of
the 1998 draft. Moss killed them and became an All-Pro his rookie
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have received much criticism for bypassing Moss to
take North Carolina defensive lineman  &UR; Greg Ellis, but Irvin told
Moss not to blame the team. He said Moss should blame Irvin for his
numerous off-the-field problems scaring off the team.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's death is a tragedy. Why would he experiment with heroin
when, at 39, he had so much life ahead of him? In fact, he had just
been hired as an offensive line coach at his old high school in
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei was one of the Cowboys' most popular players. Offensive
lineman  &UR; Dale Hellestrae, a Scottsdale native, said the only time
he ever saw Tuinei in a bad mood was after he spent a night
sleeping in a hotel bathtub to escape defensive tackle  &UR; Leon Lett's
snoring the night before a game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tuinei is dead, and Lett's future with the club is in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The ``New York Times'' reported earlier this spring that Lett
had another positive drug test, a substance-abuse violation that
could cause him to be suspended for, at minimum, a year.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer can't be blamed. He's long gone, enjoying retirement in
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Gailey's turn to find out how tough it is to coach the
Cowboys, and he doesn't even know whether he'll have his best
player, cornerback  &UR; Deion Sanders, who still is recovering from a
toe injury.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some media reports that the team could release
Sanders for salary-cap reasons. Others say he could miss anywhere
from a month to half a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cowboys aren't void of talent and should contend for
a playoff spot. But the stain on their franchise might not be wiped
clean for years. &QL; 
Golf world &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leland Hardy, agent for Saints rookie running back  &UR; Ricky
 &UR; Williams, should be tired of golf by now. He played 10 days with
team officials before Williams agreed to an eight-year, $16.215
million deal Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and team officials decided to play each day until they
came to contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the golf was played at the Dancing Rabbit Golf Club in
Philadelphia, Miss., where Saints Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka is a member.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the eight years are up, Williams' contract could be
way below market value. He said he has no plans to renegotiate
after a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a throwback player,'' Williams said. ``I'm not pro free
agency. I'm not going to get into a deal wanting to go somewhere
else. With the contract, I'm going to be able to make great money
if I'm playing well after four years. So that shouldn't be an
issue.'' &QL; 
Comeback kid &QL; 
Mesa High School alum  &UR; Robert Holcombe got the Rams excited last
season when he rushed for 84 yards and two touchdowns in his first
game, a 20-17 loss to the Cardinals last September.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the season, he had gained only 230 yards and
had a 2.4-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were so down on Holcombe, they traded for Indianapolis
running back  &UR; Marshall Faulk the week of the draft. But Coach  &UR; Dick
 &UR; Vermeil, after seeing Holcombe perform during their recent
minicamp, thinks the second-year pro is back in their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Holcombe is a different kid today than he was a year
ago,'' Vermeil said. ``He's calmed down a little bit. He's so wound
tight, so intense that sometimes it's a negative. I think he's much
more aware, more understanding of how you've got to run the ball in
the National Football League. I've been impressed with his
improvement.'' &QL; 
Tough negotiator &QL; 
There's no wonder late Jets owner  &UR; Leon Hess was able to get
Coach &UR; Bill Parcells away from the Patriots two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't play poker with someone who negotiates oil contracts
with  &UR; Moammar Gadhafi,'' a club official said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, who owned the Amerada Hess oil company, went face to face
with Gadhafi many years ago in an oil deal. Hess said that during
the talks, one of Gadhafi's guards put a revolver on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, recalling the incident, said later, ``And, uh, I'm still
here.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Former Cardinals linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller, who signed a one-year,
$1.3 million deal with the Browns last week, told the Cleveland
media he thought he was as valuable to the Cardinals' defense as
quarterback &UR; Jake Plummer was to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is making a killing selling licensed dreadlock wigs in
honor of Williams, the Heisman Trophy-winning running back from
Texas. &QL; 
