<HEADLINE>
FOX MAKES MOST OF LATEST START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - More dirt. More sweat.  &UR; Andy Fox was fired up.
</P>
<P>
   He was back in the Diamondbacks' lineup Saturday, starting at
shortstop in place of  &UR; Tony Batista.
</P>
<P>
   It came on the heels of Fox's three-hit performance as a starter
on Wednesday, including a two-run homer in the ninth inning that
helped Arizona rally for an 8-6 victory over Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy's been swinging the bat well,'' Diamondbacks Manager
 &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter said. ``We've got to get him out there for another game.
But Tony will be back Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox started 122 games at six positions in 1998, but he has had
to take a different approach this season, particularly at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you're not going to have four at-bats in a game, much
less start two games in a row,'' he said. ``You can't afford to
work on something with your swing or wait to see what a pitcher
has, maybe even until your next at-bat. You have to make sure you
get into the (batter's) box and be ready. It's more immediate, more
result-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can work on things during batting practice, but the
biggest thing is the speed difference in the game. You just have to
combat it the best way you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox singled in his first at-bat Saturday. He was at his best in
the fifth inning when he stroked an opposite-field RBI single
through the hole between third base and shortstop, and went to
second on the throw to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado catcher  &UR; Henry Blanco tried to get him at second,
he threw the ball into center field, and Fox advanced to third. &QL; 
Catch-22 situation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showalter continues to alternate catchers  &UR; Kelly Stinnett and
 &UR; Damian Miller. Yet Stinnett is hitting .157 with one home run and
two RBIs while Miller had three hits and two RBIs Saturday,
including a solo homer in the seventh inning, to give him a .326
average with three homers and 15 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Kelly is pressing a bit, and there's nothing wrong
with that,'' Showalter said. ``We know he wants to make more of a
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep both of them fresh. How many guys catch over
100 games any more? Not many. The most important thing is the
catching, the receiving. Our two guys block the ball better than
anybody in baseball.'' &QL; 
Avoiding disaster &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks TV analyst  &UR; Bob Brenly's heart jumped into his
throat Friday night when he accidentally knocked a lava lamp being
used in a ``Disco Night'' promotion off the ledge in front of him.
It would have landed in the crowd if not for a wire screen that
runs across the top of advertising signage just below the press
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to hit it with my hand. I thought, `Oh, no,'
'' Brenly said. ``I got lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
