<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8996 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     05-16 2640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD PROBLEM  
 DODGERS PLAY DOWN TO LEVEL OF OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how many face lifts the Los Angeles Dodgers receive,
they always seem to have the same identity as their recent
predecessors, who couldn't seem to shake the tag of chokers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Dodgers showed signs of imploding once again, a
trait this club has taken on for most of the past five years.
Second baseman
 &UR; Eric Young called a team meeting the day after the Dodgers became
the first club this season to lose a series to the Florida Marlins,
holders of the game's worst record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not time to panic or anything like that,'' Young said.
``That's not what this is about. We know we've got a good club and
we can win this (division). But there are things we're doing that
we need to do better, stuff you can't do if you're a contending
club. It's not one guy, or even one thing. It's a lot of little
things that add up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice enough, but Young didn't hit into the heart of the problem
quite the same way left fielder  &UR; Gary Sheffield did last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be playing better than we are,'' said Sheffield, who
has spent one year and one day with the Dodgers. ``We're too
lackadaisical, and it shows. I know we're not intimidating anyone
right now. We haven't showed anybody any reason to be afraid of us.
We did the first six games, but there's been nothing since that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about the Braves. They've done it for so many
years. When teams play them they think, `Man, they're good.' But
when you don't play with a lot of intensity, you're going to get
beat and teams are going to be saying, `They're not that good.' We
have to change that philosophy. We just have to want it. How bad do
we want it? To me, it doesn't seem like we want it that bad, like
teams are going to give it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Division-leading San Francisco rarely leads the league in any
statistical categories yet won the National League West in 1997 and
lost a one-game playoff for the wild-card spot last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with rankings, it's attitude,'' Sheffield
said. ``Watch the Giants and the way they play the game, and watch
our team and the way we play the game, and you can see who wants
it. I watch the Giants play, and it's exciting. They're up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be honest about it. They do all of the little
things. They make all of the plays. They score four runs when they
should have scored only one _ they get the bunt down, they take the
extra base on a guy, they take out the second baseman (on a double
play).''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered their weekend series in St. Louis with a
14-14 record since starting the season 5-1, which included a
three-game sweep over the Diamondbacks. Los Angeles was 10-4 when
facing a club with at least a .500 record and 9-11 against losing
clubs, a sure sign of playing down to its opponent's level. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the new slew of ballparks built in recent years and under
construction, identify the oldest major league stadium still in
use. &QL; 
Head games &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat surprising Giants, who are playing their final
season on Candlestick Point, aren't about to leave without trying
to squeeze one more playoff appearance into the old wind-blown
park.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who host the Diamondbacks for a three-game series
starting Monday, are 13-7 at their home park and have not been
ashamed about trying to mess with their opponents' minds during
these early-season games, which have been colder and windier than
most in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place sucks,'' Atlanta's  &UR; Ryan Klesko said after the
Braves lost two of three to the Giants last week.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco catcher  &UR; Brent Mayne did his part during the
Braves series, engaging in some light chatter with most every
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy who came up, I said to him, `Isn't this terrible?'
'' Mayne said. ``I think it got into their heads. They said, `Yeah,
I can't believe you play here every day. It sucks.' I guess I just
reaffirmed the obvious in their minds.'' &QL; 
Heads up! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, erratic reliever  &UR; Mark Wohlers did little to
dispense of the notion that he cannot find the plate. Cincinnati
pitching coach  &UR; Don Gullett found an old inflatable batter to stand
up next to home plate while Wohlers worked on his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He nicked him a few times, and he got him good once,'' Gullett
said with a laugh. ``We call him Pitcher's Pal, but if he could
talk, I'm sure he wouldn't think that's his name right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, Wohlers visited with clinical psychologist
 &UR; Richard
 &UR; Crowley, who helped former Dodgers second baseman  &UR; Steve Sax find a
way to throw to first base and also has helped  &UR; Steve Blass, the
original ``can't-find-the-strike-zone pitcher,'' who is finally
able to play catch with his kids and grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   After just one session with Crowley, Wohlers threw a majority of
strikes during a bullpen session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't throw one bad ball in 12 minutes,'' Gullett said.
``What he did today was the best he's done. Unbelievable.'' &QL; 
The shifty Athletics
</P>
<P>
   When Oakland third baseman  &UR; Olmedo Saenz was forced to leave
last Tuesday's game in Detroit because of a knee injury, Athletics
Manager
 &UR; Art Howe reached into his bag of tricks to to help preserve the
victory in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Howe moved the versatile  &UR; Tony Phillips in from the outfield to
start the inning at third base and placed slick-fielding infielder
 &UR; Jorge
 &UR; Valendia at second base when a left-handed hitter was batting. When
a right-hander stepped into the batter's box, Howe switched
Phillips and Valendia.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the inning Howe made the players swap spots.
Valendia, the better defensive infielder, wound up making the
assists on the second and final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said, ``I had to do something to get us on ESPN. That was
the only way to do it.'' &QL; 
Bombs away
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's three-inning, 18-run uprising last weekend was
simply too impressive not to be dissected once again. To recap: The
Indians trailed Tampa Bay, 10-2, heading into the bottom of the
sixth at Jacobs Field when they turned up the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians sent 33 batters to the plate in just the sixth,
seventh and eighth innings while scoring four, seven and seven
runs, respectively. Cleveland had 16 hits in the three innings to
demolish the Devil Rays, 20-11. And don't forget, the Tribe did not
bat in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in some wild games in my career, but never
one where we came from so far behind to win by so many,''  &UR; Travis
Fryman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was so crazy that Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove had  &UR; Rich
DeLucia warming up and planned to insert him into the game in the
eighth to pitch out the string and preserve the rest of his
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But once the Indians made a game of it, Hargrove sat DeLucia,
basically a mop-up man, and had closer  &UR; Mike Jackson begin warming
up. But the more runs the Indians scored, the less likely there
seemed a need for Jackson. So Jackson sat back down and DeLucia
warmed up again and wound up pitching a scoreless ninth. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit of a trick question, because it's actually a tie.
Boston's Fenway Park and Detroit's Tiger Stadium (then called Navin
Field) opened April 20, 1912. With the Tigers scheduled to move
into Comerica Park next season, Fenway Park will assume the role of
oldest major league stadium. Chicago's Wrigley Field is next on the
list, having opened in 1914. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandDespite his 5.88 ERA, Tribe is 6-0 in &UR; Dwight Gooden
starts.  &QL; 
2. HoustonThey remain relatively obscure, but Astros have all the
pieces firing.  &QL; 
3. NY YankeesAnaheim remains the one club undaunted by the Yankee
mystique.  &QL; 
4. San FranciscoBeat Atlanta in a series for the first time in
three years.  &QL; 
5. AtlantaLost a series last weekend for the first time; then lost
another.  &QL; 
6. ArizonaIs it too early to start the  &UR; Matt Williams for MVP
campaign?  &QL; 
7. NY MetsBack East after a troubling trip through Arizona and
Colorado.  &QL; 
8. TexasMay regret not pulling away while the rest of the division
is ailing.  &QL; 
9. OaklandCame off a most impressive 8-2 road trip and getting
strong pitching. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaEntered the weekend without having won consecutive
games.  &QL; 
29. MontrealConfidence was greatly shaken during three-game sweep
in Arizona.  &QL; 
28. MinnesotaQuick, name two Twins? Didn't think you could.  &QL; 
27. BaltimoreBeating cupcakes like Chicago and Detroit doesn't
erase the O's holes.  &QL; 
26. San DiegoAt least the Padres have  &UR; Tony Gwynn's assault on
3,000 hits.  &QL; 
25. DetroitManager  &UR; Larry Parrish wants to see more offense from
his lineup.  &QL; 
24. ColoradoDemoted the second member of its rotation last week;
not a good sign.  &QL; 
23. CincinnatiAmazingly, Reds just added a sixth reliever last
week.  &QL; 
22. SeattleHappy to have SS  &UR; Alex Rodriguez back in the lineup. ON
THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Philadelphia Phillies: Terry Francona, considered one of the
brighter up-and-coming managers in the game, is making quite a name
for himself and the Phillies so far. This club has a solid young
nucleus that includes third baseman  &UR; Scott Rolen, center fielder
 &UR; Doug
 &UR; Glanville, catcher  &UR; Bobby Estalella and first baseman of the future
 &UR; Pat
 &UR; Burrell. Ace  &UR; Curt Schilling sports a 2.80 ERA, and  &UR; Carlton Loewer
and Atlanta-castoff  &UR; Paul Byrd show signs of belonging in a
big-league rotation. The results are piling up as they leapfrogged
the Mets for second place in the NL East last week. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; St. Louis Cardinals: Forget  &UR; Mark McGwire: This club's problems
have been exposed in recent weeks. The pitching staff is giving up
way too many walks, constantly falling behind in the count and
becoming vulnerable because of that, pitching coach  &UR; Dave Duncan
said. The overall staff ERA was 5.01 entering the weekend series
against the Dodgers at Busch Stadium, where the Cardinals were 6-10
before the weekend, compared with 11-6 on the road. St. Louis' best
pitcher is
 &UR; Kent Bottenfield, who needs one more victory to reach a career high
of six. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Philadelphia Phillies reliever  &UR; Yorkis Perez, making quite an
astute observation while sitting in the bullpen and watching
another high-scoring game at Colorado's Coors Field last weekend, a
game eventually won by the Phillies, 10-8: ``Man, whoever scores
the most runs in this game is going to win.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
After spending a grand total of five games in the minor leagues
after being drafted last June, pitcher  &UR; Jeff Weaver has made the
meteoric rise to the big leagues in Detroit. Weaver digested and
produced everything the club threw at him during spring training.
Now that he has started six games, he has a 3-3 record with a
respectable 3.27 ERA to go with it. In Weaver's three losses, he
has given up nine earned runs in 17 innings while striking out 16
and walking just five. The Tigers have managed to score four runs
in those three defeats. Tigers teammates have taken to calling
Weaver ``Roy,'' which is short for Rookie of the Year. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; It could have been a lot harsher: During Baltimore's visit to
Cleveland last week, a plane circled over Jacobs Field with a
banner that read, ``Albert &AMP; Art _ Now Balti-Morons.'' It was
clearly a dig at former Indians outfielder  &UR; Albert Belle and  &UR; Art
Modell, who took Cleveland's football team to Baltimore a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; With his kind of practice, you'd think he had this
 &UR; thing down: One of the strangest injuries ever occurred last week
when Texas'  &UR; Juan Gonzalez strained his right hamstring during a
home run trot. He actually came out of the game because of the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A bit too much partying, perhaps?: The Los Angeles Dodgers
entered this weekend with a 5-0 record in games played on Saturday
but 0-4 (they had one rainout) when playing on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Doug Ault.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If he's this mad, maybe there's something to this
 &UR; story: Seattle's  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. was incensed when he learned
about a Cincinnati columnist's assertion that the perennial
All-Star may be headed to his hometown of Cincinnati once his
contract expires in 2000 because he visited his father,  &UR; Ken
Griffey Sr., for some batting tips during day off.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What if his nickname had been Mooner?: Florida Manager
 &UR; John Boles is one person in the game still allowed to call Los
Angeles GM  &UR; Kevin Malone by his college nickname, Hoghead. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Texas'  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro did the unthinkable last week when he
passed  &UR; Cal Ripken Jr., as the major league leader in games played
during the 1990s. Palmeiro entered the weekend series with 1,401
games to Ripken's 1,398.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's four-time Cy Young Award winner,  &UR; Greg
 &UR; Maddux, is 5-5 with a 4.28 ERA and has given up seven home runs in
his past 12 starts dating back to Sept. 1 last year. His current
4.57 ERA this year is his highest ever after seven starts, and that
counts his rookie season in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   When he played for Cleveland,  &UR; Albert Belle hit .333 with 68
home runs and 181 RBIs in 746 at-bats when playing at Jacobs Field.
In 56 at-bats at Jacobs Field as an opposing player, Belle is
batting .214 with one home run and 10 RBIs. Belle has also left 32
runners on base in the 14 games he has played in Cleveland since
leaving after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's perennial All-Star shortstop,  &UR; Barry
 &UR; Larkin, has nearly 13 years of major league service yet has never
hit a grand slam. In 5,826 at-bats entering the weekend series, he
is 18 for 76 (.237) with 63 RBIs when batting with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he won three of his five decisions and posted a 3.03
ERA,  &UR; Ramiro Me ndoza was sent to the New York Yankees bullpen to
make room in the rotation for  &UR; Hideki Irabu. The move stems more
from a necessity in the Yankees suddenly vulnerable bullpen than
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's  &UR; John Vander Wal needs one pinch-hit to become the
14th player ever to record 100 pinch-hits in a career. Now that
he's starting, though, it might be difficult for him to achieve the
mark.  &UR; Manny Mota is the career leader with 150 pinch-hits. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Ready to throw in the towel, the San Diego Padres appear prepared
to make just about anyone on their roster available via trade.
Among the more desirable players might be  &UR; Chris Gomez,
 &UR; Ruben &UR; Rivera,  &UR; John Vander Wal,  &UR; Jim Leyritz,  &UR; Phil Nevin and
everyone in the bullpen except closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen the necessity to trim to a four-man rotation, the
Seattle Mariners are desperately looking to make a trade to acquire
a pitcher. On the trading block are outfielders  &UR; Butch
 &UR; Huskey and  &UR; Matt Mieske. Most of the Mariners talks have centered
on Boston and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The struggling Florida Marlins are considering massive roster
moves that could see as many as seven players demoted to the minor
leagues. ``You can't continue to spin your wheels at this level
without their being some repercussions,'' said Manager  &UR; John Boles.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins, still looking to pare salary, appear
willing to part with relievers  &UR; Eddie Guardado,  &UR; Mike Trombley and
 &UR; Rick Aguilera, who would need to waive his no-trade clause in
order to be dealt.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if left-handed starter  &UR; Kent Mercker is
removed from St. Louis' rotation very soon. Mercker has not been
able to get past five innings in any of his six starts. He entered
his weekend start with an 8.02 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta infielder  &UR; Mark Lemke is expected to sign a
contract with the independent league New Jersey Jackels this week.
So what? Well, Lemke wants to become a pitcher. He has been
fiddling with a knuckleball with Hall of Famer  &UR; Phil Niekro. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
