<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER TAKES STEP FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Tim Belcher might have solved his problems after
giving up just two runs and three hits in 61/3 innings Friday night
against Tampa Bay. It was his second victory of the season, and the
first since April 16.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Belcher figured out, though, will stay his little
secret for now. He already left the ballpark when reporters were
allowed into the clubhouse after Friday's game, and Saturday, he
politely declined reporters' requests for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one start does not mean Belcher is out of the woods. His
ERA remains the worst on the staff at 8.78. But it was a step in
the right direction, said catcher Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw strikes, he kept his fastball down and he threw a
nice split-finger,'' said Walbeck, who caught Belcher on Friday.
``He worked both corners and kept people off balance. Most
importantly, he kept the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's next start will be Thursday in Baltimore. Walbeck
might get the chance to catch Belcher again for that game and
wouldn't mind if he was Belcher's regular catcher. With three
catchers on the roster, playing time is at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck has already become Omar Olivares' regular catcher. Todd
Greene usually catches for Steve Sparks while Charlie O'Brien works
with Chuck Finley. Neither Belcher nor Ken Hill seem to have needed
a regular batterymate.
</P>
<P>
   ``With three catchers, it's difficult to keep everybody sharp,''
Walbeck said. ``At the same time, it keeps everybody rested. I've
never been on a team that had three catchers, but if that's how
(manager) Terry (Collins) wants to do it, that's fine. It's easier
to get prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to fit in: The Angels acquired pitcher Mark Petkovsek
from the Cardinals last December not knowing exactly what role he
would play. They just knew he could pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek has been both starter and reliever during his six-year
major league career. He prefers to start, but out of the bullpen,
he's 3-1 with a 1.56 ERA in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came over here, it was the same situation as St. Louis
_ whatever and whenever the opportunity was, I like the
challenge,'' he said. ``You could say starting opportunities are
not here this year. That's the way it goes. But I didn't have any
preconceived expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   So Petkovsek has become a middle man, usually pitching an inning
or two at a time but capable of going more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team has a good streak going, it's easy to see how
everything pans out,'' Petkovsek said of relievers' roles. ``But
when you're struggling everything looks confusing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-PARENTS-AZR &LR;      05-16 2668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-PARENTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPMENTALLY DISABLED PAIR MEETING PARENTING CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an evening just like any other for Mary Begaye and her
husband, Ken. They go for a walk after dinner near their Flagstaff
home, holding hands in the dimming light, flanked by their sons,
ages 13 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Mary asks the boys if they have finished their homework. They
assure her they have, knowing full well she won't check it. She
wouldn't understand it if she did.
</P>
<P>
   Ken and Mary are mildly mentally retarded, adults whose minds
are more like those of young teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   They have become a rare success story, a tribute to an era that
is becoming more enlightened about the needs and abilities of the
developmentally disabled. Forty years ago, they would have been
forcibly sterilized. Twenty years ago, Mary's babies would have
been quietly put up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the help of a consultant supplied by the state
Department of Economic Security, they face the challenges of
rearing two adolescent boys who are not retarded, Alvin and
Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   It's a love story.
</P>
<P>
   Ken and Mary met in Flagstaff, Ariz., during a job-training
program for people with developmental disabilities. Ken says it was
15 years ago. Mary says it was just 10, though their older son,
Alvin, is 13. Numbers aside, she knows one thing for certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is my first love,'' she says, smiling at a blushing Ken.
``I thought, `He's a good, nice gentleman.' I liked the way he
smiles and he talks. I told him, `You know what? We need to get
together.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They dated, talking long walks to a store for snack food. They
married in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   His parents came from Tuba City for the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her we would live together forever,'' Ken says.
</P>
<P>
   Mary says the words ``my husband'' with great pride. Ken says
his wife is ``a good woman.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an air of innocence about them, of young teenage love,
devotion and silliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight, but we don't get divorced,'' Mary says. ``We talk
about our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Begayes are by no measure typical of mentally retarded
people who become parents. Most are single mothers who live with a
parent or other relative who does most of the rearing of the child.
Seldom are the fathers involved. Sometimes, they are not even
known.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of forced sterilization and a huge decline in
institutionalization, the number of mentally retarded parents is
rising, though experts disagree on how many of the estimated 7.5
million developmentally disabled Americans have kids. By one count,
120,000 babies nationwide are born each year to mentally retarded
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   And as many as 40 percent of the children end up in foster care,
more often from neglect than abuse. Sometimes, they are taken as
soon as they are born, turned into state Child Protective Services
by hospital staffers who assume the child won't be well cared for
because of the mother's mental capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Ken, a Navajo, is short with a barrel chest and lots of wavy
black hair. At 45, he still has the shy smile of an adolescent boy.
When he talks, it is after much thought, and he speaks
rhythmically, punctuating his sentences with ``mmm hum,'' like the
character Billy Bob Thornton played in the movie ``Sling Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary, who is Apache, is tiny, too. ``I'm chubby,'' she says
laughing. Her long black hair is twisted up on her head. Her dark
eyes are small and close together, her smile big and quick. She is
38.
</P>
<P>
   She never had any doubts about her goal in life. ``I wanted to
be a mother,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mental retardation _ still the proper medical term although not
considered politically correct _ has many causes, from illness in
pregnancy to lack of stimulation in infancy. Only 30 percent of
cases are hereditary.
</P>
<P>
   And because almost 90 percent of mentally retarded people are
only mildly affected _ meaning they are only a little slower than
average _ advocates say that, given the right support and
instruction, most mentally retarded parents can care for and rear
their own children.
</P>
<P>
   Ken and Mary have the same desires, the same need for intimacy
as other adults. They both wanted a family. It is a natural desire
not limited to people who score higher on I.Q. tests, says Roger
Deshaies, assistant director of the state DES developmental
disabilities division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anyone else, they can be married and be successful or be
married and be failures,'' he says. ``They can be excellent parents
or terrible parents, just like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the warmth of her living room, Mary brings out a half dozen
tattered photo albums, showing off pictures of her and Ken's
wedding day, of the boys as babies, of faraway cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Ken points to one of his mother. On their wedding day, he says,
she told him: ``Don't ever fight with your wife. If you do, I'm
going to spank you. Mmm hum. That's what she told me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken named their first son after Alvin the Chipmunk, the cartoon
character, Mary says. Patrick was born a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Mary proved herself a good mother. She kept the boys clean and
their diapers changed. She followed a feeding schedule by watching
the clock and counting the bottles the boys drank each day.
</P>
<P>
   When Alvin was 10 months old, DES hired Becky Raabe, a nurse and
family support consultant, to watch over the Begayes. Raabe taught
Mary how to keep the children warm by wrapping them in blankets,
not pushing their cribs up against the furnace. She reminded Ken
that the kids couldn't be left alone. She taught them about putting
the boys in ``time out'' when they behaved badly instead of
spanking.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Raabe stops by twice a week and calls almost daily.
She is the family's house mother, teaching Ken and Mary about
rearing children and good nutrition, hygiene, budgeting and house
cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Mary remembers telephone numbers that Raabe has to look up in
her day timer. Yet, the couple will always need reminders, Raabe
says, about keeping the house clean, making sure the boys wear
coats in the cold and helmets when they ride their bikes. They need
help filling out paperwork for things such as food stamps and
paying their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Raabe doesn't make decisions for the family but guides Mary and
Ken in making them.
</P>
<P>
   They will never be able to provide the same guidance as normal
parents. But some parents born with greater abilities do far worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, they work really well together,'' Raabe says.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing for Raabe to teach Ken and Mary is how to
discipline their children. They understand that their children
should not steal or play with fire. They know not to let them ride
their bikes in the street.
</P>
<P>
   But Raabe is not sure if they understand the more subtle
consequences of their boys' behavior. If the boys run in and out of
the house unchecked, yelling at the top of their voices, for
example, neither Ken or Mary seems to notice. That same behavior,
though, will get the boys in trouble at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're oblivious to some of this stuff,'' Raabe says.
``They're very tolerant of the chaos and the commotion whereas the
rest of us might not be.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing about rearing two boys, Ken says, is ``how to
teach them what's right and what's wrong. And not to be too shy.
Mmm huh. You've got to talk to your kids. Let them stay in school,
so they can win lots of trophies.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the boys are respectful of their parents. Most of the
time, they do what they are told. Other times, they pay their
parents no mind.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin is lanky and taller than both his parents. His shiny black
hair is cut like his brother's with heavy bangs. Patrick could be
Alvin's twin, though he is shorter and moves faster. He talks for
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Though Patrick and Alvin did not inherit their parents'
retardation, the boys' lives are different than other children's
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   They lag in school.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick is considered ``normal,'' although he gets tutoring in
math and reading. Alvin, although not born developmentally
disabled, is in special education.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the boys' days are filled with the things of other
families _ school, homework and watching television, basketball and
dinner at 6.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their parents can't always read the notices they bring
home from school or the directions on the back of over-the-counter
cold medicine. Sometimes, the house is ill-kept.
</P>
<P>
   And Mary or Ken might say that something happened last year when
it was really just two months ago. Neither could make change for a
$20 bill.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: The Begayes love their boys, and the boys
clearly adore their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``She spoils me,'' Alvin says, talking about the cars and
firetrucks his mother has bought him over the years and the meals
she makes.
</P>
<P>
   Ken nods toward Alvin's three bowling trophies on a bookcase in
the living room. Mary talks proudly of her sons' accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   They say nothing about the fact that they are mentally retarded,
and their children were not born that way. It is simply how things
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have dreams. They love their children so much, and they
want their children to have opportunities. They don't limit what
their children do,'' Raabe says. ``They just want them to be the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Because neither Mary or Ken reads very well _ though they both
graduated from high school _ they give any letters from the boys'
schools to Raabe. But they proudly attend all parent-teacher
conferences, open houses and school events.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin is in the seventh grade at Flagstaff Middle School. His
academic difficulties stem more from the environment he grew up in
than genetics, Raabe says. He wants to be a mechanic or
firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick is in the sixth grade at Kensey Elementary School. By
all measures, he is normal, though he gets some tutoring in math
and reading. He says he wants to be an animator and an
archaeologist _ ``digging for stuff and going to new places and
finding stuff that you never knew existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick gets himself and his brother up every morning for
school. The boys get their own breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   In the small kitchen with the washer in one corner, Ken lines a
pan with foil while Mary washes the chicken before covering the
pieces with flour and black pepper. He puts it in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   She washes fresh broccoli and puts water on to boil for
macaroni. The cupboards and refrigerator are full of healthy food _
rice, fruit, vegetables, pasta _ and very little junk food.
</P>
<P>
   The boys come back, and Alvin grabs four bananas, peeling one
and eating it with the other three hanging on his shoulder. He eats
them all and then eats three pears, one after another.
</P>
<P>
   The Begayes live on fragile finances _ welfare, disability
assistance and Mary's two part-time jobs. Ken cannot work. In
addition to being mentally retarded, he has epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   On Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays, Mary starts work at Goodwill
Industries at 9 a.m., though the bus gets her there a half hour
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit around and drink coffee and chit-chat until it's time
to start work,'' Mary says.
</P>
<P>
   It is Mary's favorite part of the workday. She puts the lunch
Ken made her _ a bologna sandwich and fruit _ in the refrigerator,
plops an ice cube in her coffee and talks with her co-workers, who
are also developmentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Ken receives about $300 a month from Supplemental Security
Income, the federal disability program for the poor. They receive
food stamps. The rent on their house is about $400 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The money Mary earns is put into an account managed by the
county fiduciary, along with the $500 Alvin receives from SSI. From
that account, Mary receives a weekly allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Raabe manages the rest, making requests for additional money for
things such as clothes, shopping or going out to eat. Raabe takes
Mary grocery shopping every week. Ken and Mary used to manage all
of their own money, but, at the end of the month, little was left
to pay bills. Without Raabe's oversight, they spent freely and gave
money to friends.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mary or Ken's family lives nearby or helps out. They
would be on their own except for Raabe.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, they do resent her telling them what to do
all the time and how to spend their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they get mad at me sometimes,'' Raabe says. ``We've
joked over the years, `You can divorce me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is a voluntary program. The Begayes can pull out at any time,
but they don't. And, sometimes, Mary calls Raabe ``Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Ken and Mary seem to know that the life they lead is
better than what it could have been. They have more freedom than
some other developmentally disabled people they know. They live
like anyone else in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   While Mary is work, Ken stays at home with the boys. He has a
load of laundry in the washer. The kitchen and living room are
tidy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mom told me, `You don't be lazy.' Mmm huh. `Get up and cook
for your wife,' she told me,'' Ken says.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Cherokee woman listening to the eagles. Mmm hum,''
he says, holding the pencil drawing to the light. ``They fly across
the full moon. Mmm huh.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken is teaching his sons to draw and weave baskets. He is
teaching them to speak Navajo and hoop dance. On the weekends, they
make fry bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mom told me to teach them,'' Ken says. ``Mmm hum.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants them to be proud of their Indian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The family lives in a public housing project nestled among the
pine trees, though neither he or Mary is sure how long the family
has been there. Maybe four or five years, Mary says. Theirs is a
two-bedroom house right next to a small park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get our own place, so no one will tell us what
to do, and we can have a dog and a garden,'' Mary says.
</P>
<P>
   The couple has qualified for Home of Our Own, a federal program
that provides developmentally disabled people with long-term,
low-interest fixed mortgages. Soon, they can buy a $75,000 house.
</P>
<P>
   Ken wants a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   At the park, the boys pile into a plastic car on sturdy metal
springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's your driver's license?'' Mary jokes. Neither she or
Ken can drive.
</P>
<P>
   The boys make parachutes out of string and plastic grocery bags.
They toss them into the air. One lands near Mary's feet and she
throws it back to Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kids always make you laugh. They are always busy, busy,
busy,'' Mary says.
</P>
<P>
   It is a such a different life than in the 1920s when the U.S.
Supreme Court upheld laws that prevented retarded people from
having kids. Some states even let doctors forcibly sterilize
retarded adults. And even after the Supreme Court reversed itself
in 1942, parents of retarded children continued to have them
sterilized.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, 200,000 mentally retarded people nationwide lived
in public institutions. By 1994, that figure was 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mentally retarded children entered public schools for the first
time in 1975 when it became illegal for schools to turn them away.
At the same time, advocates successfully pushed for a broad range
of rights, including sexual relationships, parenthood and
employment.
</P>
<P>
   As the boys get older, they'll find they know more than their
parents, Raabe says, and the normal rebellion of adolescence could
become a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' futures include algebra, research papers and midterms,
things that their parents likely won't understand and won't be much
help with.
</P>
<P>
   The boys face dating and broken hearts and the lure of drugs,
alcohol and gangs. They have important decisions to make that will
have lasting consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Already into adolescence, Alvin and Patrick are growing up fast.
The question is, can they grow beyond their parents without leaving
them behind?
</P>
<P>
   Patrick is a staunch defender of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take care of me, and they tell me to go to school and get
good grades in school,'' Patrick says. ``They want me to be
smart.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
