<HEADLINE>
ELBOW GREASE DOES THE JOB FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Glen Rice figured the Lakers couldn't win without
involving him more in the offense. It turned out, happily for all
parties, the Lakers could win without even having Rice in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's right elbow, the same one that underwent surgery in
January, was sore and swollen Friday night. He tried to warm up and
shoot before Saturday's Game 4, but the elbow wouldn't cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Already trying to rebound from a lopsided Game 3 loss, the
Lakers now had lost their best shooter and the third prong of their
offense.
</P>
<P>
   It took three players to compensate, but that trio ensured the
Lakers a 98-88 victory Saturday and a series win.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox started in Rice's place and scored nine points. Robert
Horry and Derek Harper came off the bench to combine for 25 points,
eight rebounds and eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the Lakers needed to avoid a trip back to L.A. for
Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us what we needed today,'' Derek Fisher said. ``We
missed Glen's 18 points a night. And those guys made up for it.
Harp stepped up big. JR (Reid's) defense was amazing. Rick stepped
up. Robert stepped up. Guy after guy, those were the types of
things we talked about. Each guy on this team is capable of helping
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice has been listed as day-to-day, and his status is unclear
for Monday's game _ the conference semifinals opener in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen came to me, he kind of had a tear in his eye, because he
wanted to play,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``I told him, `Don't worry
about it. I need you during the long run, not the short run.' I
kind of had a meeting with Kobe, Rick and Rob and said we all got
to step our game up tonight. We did.''
</P>
<P>
   A sense of anxiety could have easily set in, considering the
circumstances and the 14-point loss to Houston in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed right past it, because nobody really knew it was
coming,'' Derek Fisher said of the loss of Rice. ``We didn't really
have time to adjust, we just had to go play.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers felt comfortable relying on their three former
starters. Fox and Horry were the starting frontcourt last season
when the team won 61 games. Harper started most of this season and
most of his 16-year career.
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't surprising to see any of them make the clutch plays
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Horry both defended against Scottie Pippen, who
destroyed the Lakers with 37 points in Game 3 but had a quiet 19
this time out. Harper stayed step-for-step with Brent Price, who
managed just five points after burning the Lakers with his 3-point
shooting two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge. Huge,'' coach Kurt Rambis said of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Fox found out he was starting less than an hour before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenaline was going, rushing, but I felt comfortable,
really comfortable,'' he said. ``That's the way it's going to have
to be at certain points throughout the course of this playoff run
here. Guys are going to be asked to make big plays other than Kobe
(Bryant) and Shaq (O'Neal) and Glen. ... It's got to be a total
12-man effort to go further than the first round.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
