<HEADER>
A9004 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX     05-16 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO LIFTS DALLAS PAST ST. LOUIS TO A 3-2 LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ At least you can't fault the Stars' timing.
</P>
<P>
   Playing their biggest game of the playoffs last night before a
hungry crowd of 17,001 at Reunion Arena, the Stars resurrected
their moribund power play and shot down the St. Louis Blues, 3-1,
in Game 5 of their best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals
series.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-for-5 performance with the man advantage came at a time
when the pressure was highest _ and it clearly sent the hiss of a
relief valve surging through the Stars and their fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was pretty much must-win,'' said Stars center Mike
Modano, who set up one power-play goal and one shorthanded score.
``We needed this tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gives the Stars a 3-2 lead heading into Game 6
tomorrow in St. Louis. A loss would have put them on the brink of
playoff elimination going into Kiel Center, where they are 0-5-1 in
their past six games, including Games 3 and 4 of this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't think we can win up there, but we don't
ever want to force an elimination game,'' said Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk, who scored his team-leading sixth playoff goal. ``We
needed this one for a lot of reasons, to get the lead, to put the
pressure on them, to take control of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have done just that, and they've answered a few
questions that have been dangling over their heads _ questions that
were placed there by fans and media before Game 5. Still, Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said the team shouldn't start believing it has
answers just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play was good, our goalie was excellent, that's
about it,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have to play a lot better if we
expect to win in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock didn't like the fact the Stars were outshot, 31-16,
that Belfour had to put up another impressive performance to stake
the Stars to a win. The coach wasn't pleased that the Stars escaped
by about an inch from a potential goal by Blues' rookie sensation
Jochen Hecht with just under a minute remaining _ the goal was
disallowed on video replay because of a skate in the crease. And
mostly, Hitchcock said, he wasn't happy that his team's performance
was uneven after it took a 2-0 first-period lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play at a lot higher level of determination, and
all of our players know that,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars struggled in attack time, they also did a lot of
things right. They had only 12 giveaways compared to 15 for the
Blues. They also dished out 54 hits _ led by nine from captain
Derian Hatcher _ to 41 for the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they took an early lead thanks to special-teams
play and then played simple hockey the rest of the night. The Stars
avoided the turnovers that the Blues have feasted on, and they
played physical when the puck stayed in their end for long periods
of time.
</P>
<P>
   The end result was a good dose of ``Stars hockey'' _ get an
early lead, extend that lead with the power play and sit on that
lead the rest of the game. It was a style that helped the Stars go
51-19-12, including 40-7-7 when scoring first.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had that 2-0 first-period lead on goals by Jere
Lehtinen and Jamie Langenbrunner. Once they did, they were then
able to avoid high-risk plays the remainder of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk gave the Stars a 3-0 lead when he deflected in a
Derian Hatcher shot at the 10:52 mark of the second period. That
proved crucial when the Blues' Scott Young scored to make the score
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   It proved even more soothing when Blues rookie Hecht appeared to
have a goal with 57.3 seconds remaining to cut the deficit to one
goal. However, Hecht's goal was disallowed on video replay because
the back edge of his skate was in the goal crease.
</P>
<P>
   The same rule took away a potential game-winning goal from the
Stars in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, bad rule for us. Last game, bad rule for them,'' Hecht
said. ``Next game, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars know is that next game will be played with at
least a cushion _ a margin for error. The Blues lost theirs last
night.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-T     05-16 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING GIVES BULLPEN A NEEDED DAY OF RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rick Helling's first pitch this season
produced a keepsake for a spectator with a $15 seat at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Juan Encarnacion hit the first of 11 home runs Helling
surrendered in his first eight starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-game winners _ the fraternity Helling joined last year _
don't surrender a home run for every four innings pitched.
Twenty-game winners keep the ball within the playing field and
relievers in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Helling produced that exacta during last night's 8-1 victory
against the Baltimore Orioles at The Ballpark. The Rangers' fourth
consecutive victory and sixth in the past seven games moved the
defending American League West champions six games above .500 for
the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a ballgame like this from one of our starters,''
said manager Johnny Oates, whose bullpen pitched four or more
innings during four of the previous seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (4-4) scattered six hits and two walks in his
eight-inning appearance and retired 13 of 14 batters after
surrendering a second-inning, run-scoring double to Orioles third
baseman Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of nights here are tough nights for a pitcher,'' Helling
said. ``This is definitely a hitter's park. The ball usually flies
out of here because of the jet stream. I was just focused on
keeping the ball down. Tonight was probably the best night for me
in terms of keeping the ball down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got beat, I wanted to get beat on ground balls and line
drives. I didn't want to get hurt on long fly balls. The way the
wind was blowing, you could really get hurt on a long fly ball to
right-center field. I didn't want to get beat on one pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Juan Guzman _ who recorded four strikeouts and
allowed only two hits _ matched Helling for four innings before his
lower back stiffened.
</P>
<P>
   That forced Baltimore manager Ray Miller to turn to left-hander
Doug Johns, whom the Orioles recalled Friday from Triple-A
Rochester. Johns (0-1) would emerge as the loser after designated
hitter Rafael Palmeiro deposited a 2-0 fastball into $15 seats at
The Ballpark with his three-run homer in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro enters this afternoon's series finale 6-for-10 with two
home runs and six runs batted in against the Orioles, who he left
in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my job, man,'' Palmeiro said. ``Just doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers continued to pummel the Orioles' bullpen _
particularly right-hander Mike Fetters and left-hander Jesse Orosco
_ while Oates' bullpen relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer, catcher Ivan Rodriguez and third
baseman Todd Zeile collected run-scoring singles during the
Rangers' four-run seventh inning, and right fielder Roberto Kelly
forced in the final run by drawing a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   Oates summoned right-hander Tim Crabtree to pitch a scoreless
ninth inning after Helling's 122-pitch performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal as a starting pitcher is to throw a complete game
every night,'' Helling said. ``That's not always going to happen.
In fact, it usually doesn't. I just try to give the team as many
innings as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has been going out there a lot lately. When we
went to a four-man rotation, they started getting a lot of innings.
They're still getting a lot of innings. They need some nights where
they don't have to do that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
