<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9006 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     05-16 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVE LITTLE TIME TO CELEBRATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The chest bumps and high fives and shouts were
contained to the basketball court. By the time the Lakers walked
off the Compaq Center floor and into the locker room, the
celebration of their first-round playoffs triumph was over.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs, owners of the Western Conference's best
regular-season record, await at the Alamodome. And the Lakers have
no time to bask in whatever glory a first-round win affords them.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfaction? Pride? Any feeling of accomplishment after a rough
season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Rick Fox said. ``It's obviously a step in the
right direction, but walking off the floor and walking into here
(the locker room), it was rather quiet. We felt like we hadn't
accomplished a whole lot, which is the right attitude. We haven't
done anything, really. A couple extra dollars of playoff share, but
that doesn't amount to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't if the Lakers can't get past the Spurs, the
NBA's hottest team the last two months and a favorite to win the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had owned the Spurs for most of the last two seasons,
winning six straight. But the last meeting _ the Lakers' first
since the Eddie Jones-Glen Rice trade _ was a disaster, a 108-81
Spurs blowout on April 24 at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   That loss came during the Lakers' late-season funk. Two days
later, the Rockets routed the Lakers as well, and that prompted the
team meeting that spawned a six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a totally different team right now,'' said Fox, noting
the Lakers' dedication to winning with defense. ``I don't want
everyone to start praising us for it, because that's the kiss of
death for us. But I definitely give kudos to everyone in this
locker room for recognizing where our wins are gonna come from and
then going out and making it the focal point of our game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mindset they'll need to counter MVP candidate Tim Duncan
and fellow Twin Tower David Robinson. The Spurs advanced with a 3-1
series victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna have to continue to do a lot of the things we did
in this series,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``We're gonna have to
step it up defensively. They're playing very well as a team and
they do a great job of putting you in situations where you have to
guard all five guys. They obviously have two very quick, agile,
mobile big men who do a lot of damage inside and outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Talk about curses. The Rockets have inexplicably lost 15
straight games (playoffs an regular season) on NBC and 19 of their
last 20, dating back to the 1997 playoffs. . . . After being
outrebounded by 12 in Game 3, the Lakers lost the rebounding edge
by a less-damning four on Saturday. Scottie Pippen still hurt them,
grabbing nine rebounds in the first quarter and finishing with 17
(nine offensive). . . . The Lakers and Rockets have split the six
playoff series they've played _ in the last five series, the winner
advanced to the Finals on three occasions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BURN-CLASH-TEX     05-16 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-CLASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE DEBUTS WITH TWO GOALS AS BURN DEFEATS SAN JOSE, 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Anyone who attended last night's Burn game in hopes of
seeing San Jose Clash forward Raul Diaz Arce add to Major League
Soccer's all-time career scoring record may have felt let down.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Burn, Diaz Arce continued his scoring slump
with miss after miss. Even better for the home team and its fans
was who found the back of the net: Burn rookie Bobby Rhine. In his
first MLS start, the former University of Connecticut standout
notched both goals to lead the Burn to a 2-1 victory at the Cotton
Bowl in front of 16,372 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional game for me,'' said Rhine, who was
joined in his first start with fellow rookie Paul Broome. ``First
because Thursday, my grandparents happened to come down for the
weekend, and, by luck, I was fortunate enough to start the game.
For them to be here is as big a thrill for me as scoring was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second of the three-game series between the teams,
scoring could have been much higher. They combined for 25 total
shots, trading near misses. The Burn snapped a two-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz Arce's missed shots could have been decisive goals for the
Clash (5-4). His first opportunity would have given San Jose the
lead in the fourth minute, but his close-range volley slammed off
the crossbar. A second-half miss would have given the Clash the
go-ahead goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn, instead, took the early momentum on Rhine's
ninth-minute score. In a combined effort from Rhine and Oscar
Pareja on a give-and-go play, Rhine first headed down a ball to
Pareja. Former Burn player Joey Martinez was an unlucky pawn in the
play, as Pareja's pass beat Martinez and set up Rhine perfectly for
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   From there, San Jose began to bolster its offensive output, with
a more pressing attack. The Clash came through with the equalizer
from Wade Barrett in the 32nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   Burn leading scorer Jason Kreis didn't score, but he had a hand
in the winning goal. He directed a shot off a 25-yard free kick
past a two-man Clash wall. Rhine was in perfect position for the
rebound after San Jose goalkeeper Joe Cannon couldn't hold onto the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this level, mistakes that we made tonight are going to be
punished, and we got punished both times,'' Clash coach Brian Quinn
said. ``First on Joey's ball and then when the wall broke down. The
other problem, obviously, is that we have to finish our chances.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-16 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Preseason promise ends with a postseason thud
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
A season that began with championship hopes riding into town in a
white stretch limousine and a police escort rode off
unceremoniously Saturday in a truckload of bricks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' season came to a crashing first-round playoff halt,
possibly taking the career of Charles Barkley with it, when the Los
Angeles Lakers rolled to a 98-88 win Saturday at Compaq Center,
clinching their NBA Western Conference playoff series three games
to one.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA championship dreams that swelled to expectations with
Scottie Pippen's celebrated arrival and the rejuvenated health of
Hakeem Olajuwon and Barkley did not last one week of the postseason
when the Rockets' shooting touch left them and they could find
nothing to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets needed a late run to make even 31 of 87 (35.6
percent) of their shots. And their frontcourt legends never could
dominate enough to slow a Lakers charge driven by Shaquille
O'Neal's most unstoppable offensive game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat by a better team. I really believe that,'' Barkley
said, the results too clear to debate the few points that might
have changed things Saturday or in the series. ``I know people
around here like to make excuses and live in the past. The Lakers
just have a better team than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers left little doubt. Their playoff victory, taken
fittingly for this odd season on the Rockets' home court, was so
clear, Barkley said he is close to announcing his retirement, his
hopes for a first NBA championship apparently out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we are going to be a year older next year and I
don't know what we can do,'' Barkley said. ``We have some great
guys, but the big question is how good can we be? I'm leaning
toward retirement. That is what is realistic. I'm not going to play
just for money. I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Saturday's game for playoff survival slipped far beyond
the reach of mere will, which was enough Thursday to have prolonged
the series, winning seemed far from the Rockets' reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could go all the way, if only we could get out
of the first round,'' Olajuwon said. ``I look at the rest of the
teams out there and when you see them, you know you can compete at
any level with them. But the team that we're playing here,
especially for myself, is different. You are more on the defensive.
You have to contain and just push. When you see the way Shaq is
playing now, they are hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   As the season ended, Barkley's right eye was blackened from
Thursday's contact with Brent Price, Pippen had blurred vision in
his right eye and a sore back from a collision with J.R. Reid, and
Olajuwon was treating a sore left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Though the three combined for 57 points, that was 10 less than
Barkley and Pippen put up in the Rockets' series win. And neither
Barkley nor Pippen could command the double teams needed to help
the Rockets' shooters, who until the meaningless last two minutes
could make just four of 27 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers, playing without Glen Rice, who was out with a
sore right elbow, could ride O'Neal to 37 points despite missing
nine free throws. Kobe Bryant, their rapidly developing prodigy
guard, had playoff career highs of 24 points and eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Scottie and Hakeem would have had to reach way back in
our past to match that,'' Barkley said. ``We were able to do it in
one game. We weren't able to do that for more than one game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the inability of the Rockets' latest Big Three to
reach back to recreate their glory days will prove the season's
epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough,'' Pippen said. ``I know everything is going
to reflect back to me, that maybe I wasn't the answer, that Scottie
couldn't carry them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably the biggest piece of the puzzle, the one they
were looking forward to making this season easier, and it was in
fact very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen could not alone be blamed. But that was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen brought Thursday's energy and urgency, but made just six
of 23 shots to finish with 19 points to go with 17 rebounds.
Barkley was solid, but could no longer dominate, making seven of 13
shots for 20 points. And Olajuwon found his touch late, but spent
most of the day, as he had most of the series, locked in a losing
battle with O'Neal and a mismatch of mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't change his style,'' Olajuwon said. ``When you're the
only shot-blocker in there, there's nothing you can do. And when
he's making those shots, it's over. You can't give him anything
near the basket because then it's a dunk. You can't move him. You
just have to make him work for his shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to look at it from a basketball point of view
where he has all the advantages and he uses them.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could have been said for the Lakers as a whole
Saturday. But for all their troubles, the Rockets made one
significant run and late in the third quarter, after trailing by 17
in the first half, had a shot to tie the score. With Olajuwon,
announced as doubtful for the second half, making three tough
jumpers and Michael Dickerson nailing a 27-footer to beat the shot
clock, the Rockets were within three eight minutes into the half.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Sam Mack, who replaced Pippen after his violent collision
with Reid left him with blurry vision, had open 3s to tie the
score. But fittingly for the game, the series and the season, they
came up short. By the end of the quarter, the Lakers led by seven.
And within minutes of the fourth quarter, O'Neal was rolling and
the lead was back to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple plays we had it there, we could have made
an extra pass or a shot and the crowd would have gone crazy and got
us even more pumped up,'' Barkley said. ``But we never could finish
those plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And though the opportunities were there, they never could finish
the season with the promise with which it began. It ended instead
with one postseason win and a frustrating conviction that it could
have been much more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
