<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Streaking Astros deck Giants 10-5
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The San Francisco Giants can only hope the low-scoring games that
once epitomized baseball at the Astrodome will be on the agenda
tonight when the Astros turn back the clock by wearing uniforms
replicated from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the amount of muscle-flexing the Astros have been
doing lately, most of them are probably close to busting through
the seams of their current threads. The Astros will have to worry
about that later; for now, they're too busy making alterations on
the earned run averages of opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   They cut up Mark Gardner and the Giants 10-5 Saturday night in a
game that wasn't as close as the score indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton pitched five no-hit innings and won his fifth
consecutive decision, while Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell combined
to drive in seven of the Astros' 10 runs. Biggio was 4-for-4 and
reached base in each of his five plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have won 12 of their last 15 games, including five in
a row _ their longest winning streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like is that we're starting to gain some
confidence,'' Bagwell said. ``When you do that, good things tend to
start happening. We know we can score some runs, and when that's
the case _ and your pitching holds the other team down _ you're
going to have a lot of chances to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have been winning games at a clip better than almost
every team in baseball. Their 23-12 record is second only to
Cleveland (26-9) in the majors. It also matches the best 35-game
start in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some satisfaction in it (the Astros' record) in the
sense that this team has not lost its intensity,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``I was a little worried about that in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were a little sluggish when we got off to the
slow start early this season, but from the second week on, our
intensity and our concentration have been exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have just as easily been talking about Hampton, who has
rebounded nicely from a bad season debut. The Astros have won seven
of his eight starts, and Hampton has been locked into a zone over
the last four.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's .267 opponents' batting average over his first four
starts was impressive, but the fact opponents are hitting just .154
against the lefthander in his last four starts is downright
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had stretches like this in the past,'' said Hampton, who
improved to 8-0 against the Giants in his career. ``But the
difference is I made the mistake of looking too far ahead back
then. Now, I'm only concentrating on my next start. It's fun to be
in a groove like this. You feel like you're going to get a win
every time out.''
</P>
<P>
   That must be the flip side of how Giants starter Mark Gardner is
feeling these days. The veteran righthander lost his fourth
consecutive decision and is still looking for his first victory of
the season. Meanwhile, he watched the Astros boost his ERA to 10.88
with Saturday's shellacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad luck and bad pitches make for a bad start,'' Gardner said.
``But it will turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner faced the minimum number of batters through the first
two innings, but the Astros sent seven batters to the plate in the
third when they converted two hits, a walk and a hit batsmen into
four runs. The biggest blow was Bagwell's 10th homer of the year _
a three-run blast into the pavilion in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't kill it,'' Bagwell said of his first home run since
May 5. ``It just barely made it, but I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's home run ended the Astros' homer drought at three
games, the longest of this season and last season. Of course, the
Astros proved they could overpower their opponents without the long
ball during their homerless streak when they held a 32-14 scoring
advantage on their opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio rediscovered his home-run stroke in the fifth inning when
he yanked a three-run blast over the left-field wall. He had gone
15 games and 63 at-bats without a homer before he unloaded on
Gardner, who ranks among the National League leaders with nine home
runs allowed in just 22 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Ken Caminiti scored on Carl Everett's single to
right in the fifth inning, although Caminiti's run was aided by
Ellis Burks' error in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Giants catcher Scott Servais ended the no-hit drama with a solo
home run to lead off the sixth inning. It was the first home run
Hampton had allowed since April 29, a span of 27 innings. The
Giants added another run in the inning on Jeff Kent's sacrifice
fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware of the no-hitter, but you really don't start
thinking about that kind of stuff until the seventh or eighth
inning,'' Hampton said. ``My location wasn't as sharp as I would
have liked. It was good early, but I got out of rhythm, and
fortunately I was able to find it again. I actually made a couple
of mistakes over the middle of the plate. I had pretty good stuff,
but it was nothing extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants added three runs off Brian Williams in the eighth
inning, but Scott Elarton squelched the comeback bid with 1
scoreless innings to close out the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
