<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lakers' bench helps Rockets take a seat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
According to the shouts of one Rockets fan Saturday, Robert Horry
stinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You weren't saying all of that when I was helping put those
two banners up there, were you?'' Horry responded, after draining a
3-pointer and keeping his wrist in post-shot position, leaving the
smoking gun raised high for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   According to Horry, the fan then shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive him, Horry. Forgive him and the other 16,284 who made up
a sellout crowd at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been difficult for them to remember the banners you
helped the Rockets win, when you were so busy making sure the
Rockets would not add to that collection this year.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, who left Houston in a trade following the 1995-96 season,
had a playoff game like those he was accustomed to having when he
was part of the Rockets' championship seasons (1993-94 and '94-95),
hitting five of seven shots, including 2-for-4 from the 3-point
line, for 12 points with two blocked shots in 27 minutes off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Horry was part of a trio of Lakers reserves who proved to be the
difference as the Lakers clinched the best-of-five first-round
series with a 98-88 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In shootaround today, I was shooting it pretty good and I just
wanted to come out and try to do the things the team needed,''
Horry said. ``We need everybody to step in, fill their roles and
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper, who had not had a double-figure scoring game since
March 26 (23 games ago), came in to spell Derek Fisher at point
guard and scored 13 points. And Rick Fox, who averaged less than
six points in 19 minutes of play in the first three games of the
series, stepped into the starting lineup for an injured Glen Rice
and hit four of nine shots in 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, Fox and Horry combined to score 34 points, 18 more than
their combined average in the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to step up,'' said Harper, who is in his 16th
season. ``I've been in this situation a lot. I feel comfortable and
confident out on the basketball court. I've been resting the latter
part of the season and I just feel good. I feel like I can go out
and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper was running the offense when the Lakers took control in
the second period and built a 17-point lead at 47-30, and he was on
the floor the entire fourth period to help Los Angeles keep the
Rockets at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me, it's about all of us collectively,'' Harper
said. ``It was an opportunity that (the bench) took advantage of,
more than anything. It's nothing against (Fisher) or nothing
against anybody else. Those guys have played well. My hat's off to
the whole team because lately we've been playing as a team. We've
really been together and the factor that we're together, that's
what's helping us be successful as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has been on a perfectly timed roll of late,
beginning with four games remaining in the regular season. But the
contribution of its reserves has been unsteady.
</P>
<P>
   In the series opener, Horry, Harper and Fox played a combined 63
minutes but managed only five points among them.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's production was welcomed and could not have come at a
better time. Rice, who averaged 18.7 points in the first three
games, had a sore elbow that caused him to miss the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers missed him, of course, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've (started) before,'' Fox said. ``I think veterans in this
league welcome the opportunity to set the tone in the game and to
feel the rhythm of it from the start. For me, the adrenalin was
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it's going to have to be at certain point
throughout the course of this playoff run. Guys, other than Kobe
(Bryant) and Shaquille (O'Neal) and Glen, are gonna be asked to
make big plays. Tonight it was Harp and tonight I had to step in
and start. It's gonna be a total 12-man effort for us to be able to
go further than just past the first round.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
