</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OLAJUWON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hakeem hands over torch to O'Neal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
For most great pro athletes, the hardest part of their career is
passing the torch. They need the ability to step back, push aside
the ego and acknowledge they are no longer the best at what they
do.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon is not one of those.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon, a certain Hall of Famer, was the NBA's dominant center
for many years, using a unique blend of quickness, strength and
footwork to present incredible matchup problems for every team.
</P>
<P>
   But after Saturday's 98-88 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers in
Game 4 of the Western Conference opening-round series before 16,285
at Compaq Center, a game that eliminated the Rockets from the
playoffs, Olajuwon was telling everyone what had become obvious:
Shaquille O'Neal is the best player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strength and his size are definitely a problem,'' Olajuwon
said. ``You have to give him a lot of credit. Even when you beat
him (with a move), he can recover. He is very quick to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of the big man, so when I see the way Shaq has
developed, and the way he is still developing, it brings joy to me.
I am happy to see that because I can see now where he is definitely
the best big man in the league, and he still has a tremendous way
to develop. Definitely he is the best. There is no question about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after O'Neal's 37-point, 11-rebound game Saturday.
Just about everyone on the Rockets took a turn at guarding O'Neal,
who responded with a variety of shots that was staggering. The jump
hook in the lane. The spinning fallaway. The soft kiss off the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the trademark, leg-splayed power dunk that leaves the
backboard vibrating for what seems hours.
</P>
<P>
   No defense worked. And it wasn't just Saturday's game. O'Neal
averaged 29.5 points in the four games, leaving little but mangled
bodies in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with Shaq is that even though I know what he is
going to do, I still cannot stop him,'' said Olajuwon, who finished
with 18 points and 10 rebounds Saturday. ``I know when he is
shooting that shot (the turnaround in the lane), I can't jump
because I'm bracing myself (against O'Neal's body) just to hold him
(away from the basket). So when he shoots, I can only hope that he
misses. I've not experienced that against any other player _ until
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon remembers when he was the dominant force in the NBA,
when he was the one making opposing centers look foolish with their
efforts to stop him. Remember David Robinson in the 1995 Western
Conference finals? Remember when Olajuwon scored at will over
O'Neal in the '95 NBA Finals, when the Rockets swept the Orlando
Magic for their second straight NBA title?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different style of basketball back then,'' Olajuwon
said. ``We had different teams, different styles. When you look at
it now, you can see the maturity and the experience he has
developed. He has more polish, and he is passing the ball better.
And he's stronger and bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon paused and laughed at that last line. Stronger and
bigger. As if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, back then, when he wore a Magic jersey, O'Neal was a
mere 300 pounds. He now tips the scales at almost 335 pounds, and
it's all muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand what I'm saying?'' Olajuwon said. ``He's
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon just shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The style of basketball that I played back then was different,
too,'' Olajuwon said. ``Back then, it was more like a free-lance,
creative scheme, where I was real comfortable. We did not do that
in this series, except for the first game (a 101-100 Lakers victory
where Olajuwon scored 22 points on 10-of-13 shooting). Other than
that, we did not play that style.''
</P>
<P>
   And they're not likely to. Olajuwon, 36, understands he is on
the downside of his career. Teams are no longer built around him.
What O'Neal, 27, can only dream of are memories for Olajuwon. He
has enjoyed the view from the top, so coming down isn't so
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between 1995 and Saturday, O'Neal passed him on the
climb up those same heights, and Olajuwon thinks there is nothing
but better things ahead for the massive Lakers' center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of areas where he can improve, where he can
become a unique big man in the history of the game,'' Olajuwon
said. ``He can get (to the point) where nobody of that size could
do that many things. He creates so many different problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is fakes and agility, but he has all these same
things, plus size. I have to give him credit, and I must wish him
well to continue to develop to be a better player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
