</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets can only watch as Lakers, time zip past
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was about growing up and growing old.
</P>
<P>
   It was about knowing when it's time to pitch the keys to the
kids and letting them stay out as late as they want. It was about
staring right into those bright, hungry eyes and remembering when
you used to see that look in the mirror every day.
</P>
<P>
   It was about seeing Shaquille O'Neal scream and watching Kobe
Bryant bounce and skip off the floor and remembering when that was
you.
</P>
<P>
   When it was you slashing, cutting, jumping and playing. When it
was you going behind the back, twisting your body in mid-air and
dunking. When it was you posting up, lofting shots mere inches
above outstretched arms. When it was you blocking shots, slamming
dunks, laughing on the opponent's floor and moving on in this NBA
championship race.
</P>
<P>
   It was about knowing when someone else's time has come. And
wondering if yours has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just better than us,'' Rockets forward Charles
Barkley said of the Lakers. ``I really believe that Me and Scottie
and Hakeem would have had to reach way back in the past to match
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Lakers 98, Rockets 88 Saturday at Compaq Center.
It was time passing by and torches being passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' season is over. They will return a year from now
probably with almost the exact roster that took the floor Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But what they and the Lakers both had to realize in the wake of
a playoff series that belonged to Los Angeles from the moment
Pippen stumbled in Game 1 and the Lakers stood tall, was that these
are teams headed in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley may retire; it seems he is leaning that way and he will
tell us soon. Olajuwon certainly has at least one, maybe two or
three terrific seasons left in him. Given a training camp and more
time, Pippen may find a comfortable place in the Rockets system.
</P>
<P>
   There also may be a new rookie joining the team and maybe a
free-agent acquisition or two. And certainly Cuttino Mobley and
Michael Dickerson will only improve.
</P>
<P>
   But will it make a difference? This is the brink of the Lakers'
era, and this series showed why.
</P>
<P>
   For one impressive, memorable day _ Thursday night _ the Rockets
reached back and grabbed their glorious days out of the air. The
Rockets showed these giddy kids exactly how it was done when they
were kings.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon played dreamy. Barkley defied odds and even the 7-1,
330-pound O'Neal for 23 rebounds. Pippen slashed and dunked with
remarkable ease.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just one day. This series-clinching Lakers effort
was reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old guys don't get better, they get older,'' Barkley said.
``This ain't golf. There's no senior tour. Let's face it, we're
going to be a year older next year.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers still will only be getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were younger, more athletic,'' Olajuwon said. ``They were
faster. They were stronger inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing epitomized the way this series broke and the way the
Lakers made a bold step past the Rockets than O'Neal working inside
against Olajuwon like he was just another big man trying to hang
on.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing said more about the development of Bryant as a
Jordanesque kind of player than the way he drove past Pippen at all
the critical moments, including a behind-the-back dribble and drive
to the hoop in the decisive fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal backed Olajuwon under the basket almost at will. He
blocked four of Olajuwon's shots, which maybe never has happened
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing on a different level,'' Olajuwon said of O'Neal.
``It's all about advantages. He's the best big man in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, taking advantage of shooting guard Glen Rice's absence
in the game because of injury, blasted to 13 first-quarter points,
setting the standard for the game and playing better than anyone
the Rockets had.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Game 3, Scottie threw the first punch,'' Bryant said.
``They made a statement. But today, we had more energy, and they
had to match us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets didn't. More significantly, they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when the Rockets swept the Orlando Magic in the
NBA Finals and Olajuwon was unmatched in the game, O'Neal could do
nothing about it. He was just a kid. He tried to keep up with the
master of spinning in the post, faking and pumping around O'Neal,
Dream-shaking. But he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday and throughout the series, it was all O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you a secret,'' O'Neal said. ``When a guy is
your idol, you learn everything he does. You respect him. Hakeem
has always been my idol, and that was the difference. I knew what
he was doing out there, and I didn't go for the first fake.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was better. For some legends such as Olajuwon that is
something that is impossible to admit, but this was so obvious and
Olajuwon was so classy about the reality of it all.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal practically shot Olajuwon's age, scoring 37 points and
slamming down so many big baskets in Olajuwon's face down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never happened (to me) before,'' Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   Time has passed. O'Neal and Kid Kobe are growing up. The Rockets
are growing old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know around here people like to make excuses and live in the
past,'' Barkley said. ``But they were just better than us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
