</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Retirement would beat losing for Barkley
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he's gone, and everything seems to indicate he is, Charles
Barkley failed to achieve his sole objective as a Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley didn't come to Houston for the bucks, the golf courses
or, despite his own joking to the contrary, our famous array of
``gentlemen's'' clubs. He wanted to be a Rocket, forcing a trade to
make it happen, because he honestly thought he had a better chance
to claim an NBA championship here than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   And he will choose not to return for one reason only: Because he
doesn't believe he can win a championship here.
</P>
<P>
   Money? The Chuckster doesn't need it, even though he became a
veritable pauper by NBA standards in 1999, playing for the
veteran's minimum of $1 million _ and feeling immensely thankful
for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got $30 million in the bank,'' Barkley said Saturday after
the Lakers had eliminated the Rockets from the playoffs in what may
have been the last game of his 15-year, Hall-of-Fame career. ``If I
spend all that, I deserve to be broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf? Who cares? There are roughly 120 courses in the Phoenix
area, where he makes his permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   No, the sole source of Barkley's motivation was his desire for
that elusive ring. It always has been, first in Philly and later in
Phoenix. He is as driven and tunnel-visioned an athlete as ever
played this or any other sport. If you don't believe that by now,
shame on you for not paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley most assuredly didn't come to Houston to win us over, to
make us like him. I've come to know the guy pretty well and I can
assure you he wastes not a second worrying about how people view
him. What you see is what you get, take it or leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what you saw against the Lakers, if you were paying
attention, was the consummate warrior on display, a 36-year-old
knee-surgery rehab patient sell out as totally as an athlete can.
Although he finally showed signs of fatigue in Saturday's 98-88
defeat, his 20 points led the Rockets and his nine rebounds gave
him 55 for the four games, or 13.8 per.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Rudy Tomjanovich to reflect on Barkley's grand finale, if it
was indeed one, and he brings up the end of the second game, when
Barkley wasn't even playing because the Lakers were hopelessly
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles was on the bench cheering for the second-teamers,''
Tomjanovich said. ``The guy just has such amazing energy and
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's Game 3 heroics _ 30 points, 23 rebounds in a Rockets
rout _ made for one of the finest performances in playoff history,
his or anyone else's. He literally willed himself into having such
a monster series and, although the Rockets may be going home for
the summer, he goes with them knowing he didn't leave a bit of
himself, not a DNA molecule, unspent.
</P>
<P>
   Which is essentially the problem, a big part of the reason why
he suspects retirement is the right choice for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win with talent, not will power,'' he said. ``And that
(what he accomplished against the Lakers) was far more about will
power than it was talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get better when you get older. I've got to be
realistic. I'll be 37 years old and next year is gonna be a full
season, a full six months, not three. I've got to know we've got a
chance, or I don't want to put myself through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that, under the Bird exemption, Houston could pay him
up to $14 million in 1999-2000. Repeat after me: It's not about the
$$$. Barkley is not your greedy, money-grubbing clich of an
athlete. He's as against the grain as they come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just be leaving more to my freeloading relatives to fight
over when I die,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Charles will speak with Rudy T and basketball veep Carroll
Dawson at some future date, hoping they can tell him what he wants
to hear, that the Rockets will be able to improve themselves in
some way to make another title run viable. As they are currently
constituted, Barkley said with his typical candor, he doesn't
consider them contenders.
</P>
<P>
   He loves the team, in respect to its mix of locker-room
personalities. But he doesn't love its prospects for going the
distance, for climbing the mountain that has taunted him since he
reported to the Sixers as a pudgy, already brash rookie in the fall
of 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see us getting better,'' he said, ``and we obviously
weren't good enough as it was. I'm just being realistic when I say
I'm leaning toward retirement. I don't want to hang around to be
pretty good. I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   These Rockets couldn't because the backcourt was too young and
perhaps the fabled frontcourt was too old. Still, the Chuckster
leaves satisfied. As he's wont to tell us, his life has been the
good life. He wouldn't trade it for any he's aware of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a championship,'' he said recently, ``but I don't need
a championship because I know I did everything I could personally
do to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if this is it, if it never happens, so be it. Just don't be
dumb enough to accuse him of piking, or not caring. We've seen lots
of athletes come and go in Houston. None cared more, or had a
bigger heart. Not a one of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
