A9022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HNS &LR;      05-16 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Belfour's heroics carry lackluster Stars past Blues
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ The situation called for something special, and a two-goal
victory seemed to suggest that the mandate had been met.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock's scowl said something completely different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play was good, our goalie was excellent and that's
about it,'' the Dallas Stars coach said after his team's 3-1 win
Saturday night over the St. Louis Blues gave the Stars a 3-2 edge
in this best-of-seven NHL Western Conference semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   And the downside?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that if we're going to win another game in this
series, we will have to play a lot better for 60 minutes than we
did tonight,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this was hardly the sort of emphatic statement the
regular season's best team wanted to make in a must-win Game 5 of a
second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas was outshot 31-16, including a 25-9 margin over the final
two periods. The Stars needed Ed Belfour to turn back 30 of those
shots as much of the final 40 minutes were played in the Dallas
end. After going up 2-0 in the first 9 minutes, 43 seconds, the
Stars basically retreated into a defensive shell and tried to
withstand the attack of the quicker, faster Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas did barely. And things would have been a good deal more
tense at the end had Jochen Hecht's goal with just under a minute
to play not been waived off after replays showed Hecht had part of
a skate in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   So the Stars retain home-ice advantage going into Monday night's
Game 6 at St. Louis. That didn't mean they left themselves or
anyone else particularly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second period was a bad period for us,'' said center Mike
Modano, who assisted on two goals. ``We put a lot into the first
and ran out of gas in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the middle of the game on, Eddie made some great saves.
He made it easier for the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, and some strong special teams work, would be the
difference in this one.
</P>
<P>
   A paltry 1-of-21 on the power play coming into the game, the
Stars finally cashed in on two of them in the first 10 minutes. The
first, however, came with St. Louis skating with the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With Jamie Langenbrunner in the box, Modano picked up a turnover
in the neutral zone and was off on a rush down the right side.
Spotting Jere Lehtinen breaking in from the left, Modano set up
Lehtinen for a wrist shot that gave goalie Grant Fuhr no chance.
</P>
<P>
   In need of a quick start, Dallas had just that with a 1-0 lead
only 3:47 into the game, and doing it in a shorthanded situation
only added to the lift.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, the Stars finally made something happen on a
power play of their own. Again, Modano was the catalyst, finding
Langenbrunner sitting on Fuhr's doorstep and hitting him with a
perfect pass that Langenbrunner directed in at 9:43, making it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour kept it that way as the Blues outshot the Stars 8-1 in
the first nine minutes of the second period. He held on long enough
for Dallas to add another power-play goal _ a Joe Nieuwendyk
deflection of a Derian Hatcher blast at 10:52 _ but the three-goal
lead lasted less than a minute as Scott Young got an unassisted
goal when he banged a shot through Belfour's legs at 11:19.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the way, only that disallowed goal by Hecht would
get past Belfour, and the Blues gave the winning goalie his due.
Still, as they headed home, they had every reason to be confident
about earning a return for a Game 7 here Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we lost tonight, we played hard,'' defenseman Al
MacInnis said. ``Special teams were the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a better situation than after the first two games
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And to hear Hitchcock tell it, the Stars can either plan for a
more inspired effort Monday night, or plan for Game 7 two days
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played tonight isn't going to be good enough to win
the fourth game in this series,'' he said. ``We're going to have to
play better, and we know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
