<HEADLINE>
PRONGER'S STRUGGLES HURTING BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ St. Louis defenseman Chris Pronger looked annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   He had just seen his Blues start slowly, play poorly and fall
easily in Game 5 _ a 3-1 loss that has them a single defeat away
from beginning a summer of golf.
</P>
<P>
   He had himself partially to blame, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has got to play better than he did tonight,'' Blues coach
Joel Quenneville said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' chances for upsetting the Stars relied on solid play
from Pronger and Blues defenseman Al MacInnis. So far, Pronger and
MacInnis have played anything but.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis has a pair of assists in the series despite averaging
better than 35 minutes a game. It's a far cry from his three-goal,
six-assist performance in St. Louis' opening-round series against
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He has been struggling to unleash his well-documented slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think he's getting shots,'' Quenneville said. ``I
think we need a little more traffic. He'll find a way. He's got a
lot of shots on net. He's just missed, too, so find a way to get
them through and that's a dangerous weapon for us again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger has simply been struggling.
</P>
<P>
   He has one assist, despite averaging in excess of 36 minutes a
game. He's also a minus-4 this series. In layman's terms, he's been
on the ice more when the Stars have scored than when the Blues
have.
</P>
<P>
   He played a big role in Dallas' shorthanded goal that opened
scoring less than four minutes into Game 5. Pronger allowed Stars
center Mike Modano to slip by him along the boards, and a couple of
seconds later that mistake ended up in the Blues net. Modano
whipped a pass to Jere Lehtinen for an easy goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Scotty \RYoung\S was going to get the puck back,''
Pronger said. ``I just kind of was flat-footed there, and I didn't
get my body in front of him enough and he squeezed by.''
</P>
<P>
   Young had been looking for Pronger to bang Modano in the boards,
but Pronger didn't. He just didn't seem to be the same player,
offensive or defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, offensively, you can look at the power play,''
Quenneville said. ``It hasn't scored at the rate it has all year or
in the previous series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that'll sum it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger and MacInnis lead St. Louis' power play, which has been
less than beneficial. The Blues are 2-for-25 with a man advantage
in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to a very talented player is pressure,'' Modano said.
``The less time you give them to make plays, the more often you
force them into a play they're not comfortable making, force them
to make a play that's a little more creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Said MacInnis: ``Our power play has struggled most of the
series. It's got to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say it, but for the Blues' power play to be better he
and Pronger have to be better, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al's been good,'' Quenneville said.
</P>
<P>
   A second passed, maybe two, and he realized just how bad that
sounded. It sounded like an indictment of Pronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prongs has been good, too,'' Quenneville quickly added. ``It
was just one of those nights. He's a top player. He'll bounce
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues need it to be soon, very soon.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
