<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO SHINES FOR THE STARS IN CRUNCH TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The puck dropped, and in the most important period of
their most important game of this exceedingly important season, the
Stars took control.
</P>
<P>
   The puck dropped, and in the opening 20 minutes of this acutely
important game, Mike Modano stepped center stage.
</P>
<P>
   He wears the spotlight well. Never mind the grumbles about the
balky power play.
</P>
<P>
   These are the nights when the Modanos of the NHL are supposed to
shine. And Modano's first period provided enough luster that the
Stars were able to follow the silvery path home.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' 3-1 victory, aided by two highlight-reel Modano
assists, does not necessarily mean the war with the irksome St.
Louis Blues is over. Tomorrow night's Game 6 in St. Louis will not
be Ed Belfour Appreciation Night.
</P>
<P>
   But it's so close _ again _ that on a warm spring night, the
Stars can almost smell ... well ... Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Kielbasa, right? Or maybe it's those infernal tire plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked the whole season for the home ice,'' Modano said.
``And so far it's been a real factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now the pressure is on them'' tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   With a conspicuous sigh, the Stars eased that grip from around
their own necks last night. Top-seeded teams with Stanley Cup
ambitions aren't supposed to back themselves against second-round
walls.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 minutes into Game 5, it was obvious that the change of
scenery had re-energized the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first period was real key,'' Modano said. ``We were all
real pumped up. We wanted to grab the lead and go with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get the shorthanded goal, and things kind of
rolled from there. We had chances the whole period.''
</P>
<P>
   The dominating 20 minutes staked the Stars to a 2-0 lead and
enabled them to muck through a fickle second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got an extended lead early in the hockey game and became
far too protective,'' said coach Ken Hitchcock, the occasional
perfectionist. ``Once they got the momentum buildup, we had a heck
of a time stabilizing.''
</P>
<P>
   From the cheap seats, however, it looked like old-time Stars
hockey. With a two-goal lead clenched between their teeth, the
Stars seemed content to check and grind the visitors into
submission.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the night's biggest difference, the Blues' Blair
Atcheynum said, ``Special teams was the key for them. Being down a
couple of goals is hard against this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Stars' special-teams heroes on this night, none
seemed more special than Modano.
</P>
<P>
   His first assist came when the Stars were shorthanded, less than
four minutes into the game, and was born of prime-time effort.
Working along the boards, Modano was able to pull the puck away
from St. Louis' Chris Pronger and steam in on Al MacInnis. The
defenseman seemed to anticipate Modano shooting, but instead Modano
laced a crisp pass across to a closing Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   The next assist came on, of all things, a power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were paying a lot of attention to Brett \RHull\S, and he
was in the middle of the ice,'' Modano said. ``And I was able to
get the pass across to Jamie \RLangenbrunner\S. It's all about
getting the puck and throwing it toward the net.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Modano's burden, of course, to be expected to do these
sorts of marquee things. When the power play chugs along at less
than a 10 percent clip, it is Modano who is asked what's wrong.
When the Stars let the series come home in a 2-2 knot, it is Modano
who is pressed for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, on such an important night, he had them.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
