<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD LUCK HAUNTING ANGELS' HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Ken Hill must have walked under a ladder, or maybe a
black cat crossed his path. How else could one explain the Angels
pitcher's recent bad luck?
</P>
<P>
   Hill _ called the key to the staff by manager Terry Collins
before the season started _ continued to pitch effectively Saturday
night, but once again had nothing to show for it in a 3-1 loss to
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays before 36,939 at Edison Field. The Angels'
winning streak ended at four.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (1-3) went 72/3 innings _ his longest outing of the season
_ and gave up three runs and six hits. It was the fifth time in his
past six starts he's gone at least seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   During that stretch he has only one victory, and that came when
the Angels scored 17 runs. In the other games, the offense has been
lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' lack of offense had a lot to do with Devil Rays
starter Tony Saunders (3-3), who gave up only one unearned run and
three hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels entered the game 5-1 against teams that started a
left-handed pitcher, including 3-0 at home. As a team, they were
hitting .305 against lefties compared to .261 against righties.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Saunders rendered those numbers meaningless by
baffling the Angels hitters. The Angels' only run through seven
innings came on their only hit through seven _ Mo Vaughn's two-out,
RBI single in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays shortstop Kevin Stocker made a bad throw after
fielding Andy Sheets' grounder earlier in the inning. Sheets took
second on a walk to Randy Velarde and scored on Vaughn's
ground-ball single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Hill threw well, but couldn't handle Jose Canseco. Canseco was
the only Devil Rays batter to get a hit until Fred McGriff singled
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, Canseco had three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco doubled in the first inning but was left on base. In the
fourth, he singled to lead off the inning, went to third as Hill
walked McGriff and Herbert Perry, and scored when John Flaherty hit
into a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Canseco led off with a single, went to third on
McGriff's single and scored on a sacrifice fly by Perry to give the
Devil Rays a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill took it into the eighth inning, but ran out of gas. Perry
ripped an RBI double to center to score Quinton McCracken, knocking
Hill out of the game and giving the Devil Rays a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finally appeared ready to get to Saunders in the
eighth after Matt Walbeck led off with a double, and one out later
went to third on Darin Erstad's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   But with Vaughn on deck, Velarde hit a 2-0 pitch to Stocker at
shortstop, who started a rally-killing double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
