<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS     05-16 1970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT UNIQUELY QUALIFIED TO FIGHT FOR CLIENTS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By RON BORGES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fortunately for Leland Hardy, he's a man with six
tongues and no chin.
</P>
<P>
   If it were otherwise, Hardy might not have been on a fancy
Louisiana golf course the last week negotiating Heisman Trophy
winner Ricky Williams's contract with New Orleans Saints capologist
Terry O'Neill. It's more likely he'd be negotiating his own deal
with Don King or Bob Arum to arrange a far more dangerous meeting
for himself with the likes of Lennox Lewis or Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, Hardy was a recent graduate of the Wharton
School of Business at the University of Pennsylvania who spoke six
languages and was working in General Motors's executive training
program. Like many young men, he also harbored dreams of athletic
glory, and those dreams led him to the world-renowned Kronk Boxing
Club in Detroit, home of Thomas Hearns and Emanuel Steward.
</P>
<P>
   The boxing ring might seem an odd training ground for a future
corporate executive, investment banker, adviser to tennis's
Williams sisters, and eventually chief negotiator for the all-time
leading rusher in college football history, but so it has been for
Hardy, whom Steward remembers as a young man always living in two
worlds. One was the corporate world of designer ties and starched
shirts. The other was the dank, sometimes corrupt world of boxing
reptiles and no shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leland was always very business-conscious,'' the Hall of Fame
boxing trainer recalled from his office in Detroit. ``The first
time I met him in 1984 he was a little bitty amateur down at the
Nationals, but he organized a boxer's union and they elected him
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy had only recently entered the ring, having boxed for the
first time while a sophomore at Indiana (Pa.) University on a dare
when a Golden Gloves team from a local prison showed up at the
school's gym. Hardy took on a former offensive lineman in the
heavyweight fight and, as he remembers it, ``I was shoe-shining the
guy, moving, jabbing. I'd never put on gloves, but I looked
spectacular that night. That's how I caught the bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was the Pennsylvania state amateur champion and on his
way to the Nationals, where he met future world champion Frank
Tate. Both were unhappy with the conditions the amateurs faced and
decided to form their short-lived union. Steward agreed to help and
Hardy never forgot it.
</P>
<P>
   After taking two years off to complete his graduate studies at
the Wharton School, Hardy ended up in Detroit, fighting for Kronk
and investigating overseas manufacturing facilities for General
Motors. It was the start of two roads that led him to Ricky
Williams and an agent's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were really only three months when I was a full-time
boxer,'' Hardy recalled. ``That was after I left Emanuel and went
to fight for Ray Leonard's boxing team. Other than that, I was
always a student or working in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Hardy left Leonard, he headed for New York to strike
out on his own, working for the investment banking firm Bear,
Stearns and fighting what New York boxing-scene fixture Johnny Bos
recalled as ``one of the greatest fights in the history of the Felt
Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   It was March 30, 1989, and Hardy was in with a tough kid named
Ike Padilla. Hardy was coming off a first-round knockout loss at
the hands of Eddie Cruz and was 1-2-1, with both defeats coming by
KO. This did not bode well for him against Padilla, a Bronx
heavyweight who was 3-0 with three knockouts. But some nights are
magic. Now let Bos tell the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were five knockdowns in three rounds,'' said Bos, the
excitement rising in his voice. ``Ike's down. Ike's up and Hardy's
down. Hardy's up and Ike's down. They didn't have such good chins,
but they were there to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leland ends up stopping Padilla in the third and he got two
more good knockouts after that. Then things didn't go so good for
him. It was always feast or famine with Leland in boxing, but he
was an exciting fighter. If he had a decent manager with some
originality, he might have been built into an attraction. You've
got to hope he does a better job managing Ricky Williams's career
then he did managing his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously though, Leland's a bright guy. When I heard he was
off representing athletes, I wasn't surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Hardy after he was stopped by Pete Wabuda and Lusran
Taramov in back-to-back fights in 1990 that dropped his official
record to 4-4-1. The Taramov fight was his last, a fourth-round TKO
in Japan that convinced him the corporate world was the place for a
200-pound heavyweight with dynamite in his hands but china in his
chin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are days when Hardy forgets that those four losses
were all by knockout and remembers only his four professional wins,
which all came by KO as well. He recalls them because that's what
he's still seeking  &UR; today &LR; : a spectacular victory for his latest
creation, a sports agency for Master P, the rapper who is backing
him with funding from his highly successful No Limits recording
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went as far as I could as a fighter,'' Hardy recalled. ``I
took two years off to go to the Wharton School but right after I
got out I went back to boxing. Fourth of July, 1986. I gave myself
a shot and managed my own affairs but eventually I knew it was time
to move on and here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Move he has, to corporate America. Now he is trying to meld
together two other diverse endeavors _ hip-hop music and the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gave me a shot to be an agent,'' Hardy said. ``I always
felt it would take an alignment between sports and the hip-hop
culture to get my chance. I tried it with Puff Daddy and LL Cool J
but they never quite understood the power of their medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with Master P, we have six NBA players and Ricky and we
just signed Laron Profit from Maryland. He's our first client who
didn't come from another agency, and we believe he'll be a No. 1
NBA pick. We're moving now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy understands from both his athletic background and his
business sense that it's the heavyweights who generate the big
capital, and Williams is as much a heavyweight as anyone coming
into the NFL in recent years. Saints coach Mike Ditka risked his
future on Williams when he traded his entire draft this year and
the heart of it next year to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, there's No Limit to what this contract will
mean to the Saints, to Williams, and to Hardy, a heavyweight who
was always willing to take big risks for the shot to land a
knockout punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important for us is the structure we build around
Ricky,'' Hardy said. ``If we do all the right things, who knows
where it could lead? Isn't this what every retired fighter is
supposed to be doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Only if they have his kind of chin _ and his kind of head for
business, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Football fans can often be ``out there,'' and Patriot fans
historically have gone farther out than most, but few have taken
their loyalty as far out as Dan Barry plans to. Barry is an
astronaut from South Hadley who will be aboard the space shuttle
Discovery later this month. Each astronaut is allowed to take a
personal item into space, and Barry called the Patriots recently to
ask if he could take a team banner on his flight. The launch is
scheduled for May 27 . . . The NFL Management Council has decided
to give the Indianapolis Colts a break. After the death of
third-round choice Brandon Burlsworth in a car accident the week
after the draft, Indianapolis will not have its rookie pool figure
lowered by the value of that slot. This was not the case a year ago
when the Oakland Raiders lost second-round choice Leon Bender,
because he had signed a contract before his death . . . The death
of former Dallas Cowboys tackle Mark Tuinei from heroin and a
stimulant known as Ecstasy brought back to mind something Patriots
assistant coach Dante Scarnecchia has often said to his players:
``There's a game of football and a game of life, and to be
successful you've got to win at both of them.'' Somebody should
have reminded Tuinei that his life didn't end when his football
career did after the 1997 season . . . Patriots safety Chris Carter
has not attended any of the offseason conditioning workouts in
Foxborough because he's back at the University of Texas working on
a medical degree. That's a better use of his time . . . Kansas City
Chiefs tackle Glenn Parker spent a week as an intern at the Robert
Mondavi winery in Napa, Calif. Parker, who developed an interest in
wines while growing up in California and had it rekindled by some
French-Canadian hockey players he got to know while playing in
Buffalo, spent part of the week tasting 40-50 wines. ``I learned to
spit,'' Parker said. ``I can tell you, drinking is much better than
tasting.'' Parker got the internship through the league's
continuing education program, which has placed more than 300
players in internships this offseason and seen another 100 return
to school to finish their undergraduate degrees or pursue graduate
ones . . . Children are always trying to come up with something
unusual for Mother's Day, but Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe and
his brother, Colorado University quarterback Adam Bledsoe, went
over the top this year. They gave their mother laser eye surgery.
The idea was Adam's. The bill went to Drew. Fair enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs' signing of 42-year-old Warren Moon as backup to
Elvis Grbac already has Kansas City newspapers speculating on a
quarterback controversy. Moon only added to it when he said at a
press conference to announce his arrival in Kansas City that, ``I
know that Elvis Grbac is the man. Quarterback controversies only
come when one guy doesn't do well and the other guy does well. I'm
very confident he's going to play well. If that doesn't happen,
then that's where I step in.'' Sounds to me like a controversy
that's about two losses away from happening . . . Longtime league
officials remain mystified that University of Miami running back
Edgerrin James has yet to hire an agent to represent him in
negotiations with the Colts. James, surprisingly, was the fourth
player, and first running back, taken in last month's draft but is
the only first-rounder without an agent. Ed German, James's
half-brother and a medical student, is ostensibly in charge of
negotiations and has hired former Florida state attorney Tyrone
Williams and federal lobbyist Pierre Rutledge as advisers. Neither
is certified by the NFL Players' Association to represent players,
so someone else is likely to be hired, at least as a figurehead.
``This guy's interviewed about 100 agents,'' an agent said. ``He
seems to want people to work for him for free. That's not work.
That's charity.'' German wants an agent to accept a fee of $50,000
or less to negotiate a multimillion-dollar contract. Considering
that the league slots draftees and the teams basically divide their
rookie salary pool in a way that gives the bulk of it to the No. 1
choice, James's value is already well-established. Based on that,
I'll do the deal for him for $40,000 . . . Some guys will do
anything to get something for nothing. The laser eye surgery
performed on Colts running back Keith Elias was carried live on the
Internet at ahn.com. last week. The one-hour procedure, an
alternative to wearing contacts or prescription goggles, corrects
nearsightedness, farsightedness, and astigmatisms . . . Here are
two early leaders for the 1999 Rookie All-Name Team that headline
writers will be rooting for: Sirr Parker, a running back out of
Texas A&AMP;M whom the Chargers plan to convert to wide receiver, and
Geoff Noisy, a wide receiver who signed with the Bengals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
