<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY LOSES IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Patience is the buzz word lately when it comes to
the Galaxy under new coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   But that served little solace Saturday night as Los Angeles
suffered its most bitter defeat of the young season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a season-high 20 shots, the Galaxy couldn't make any of
them count in a 1-0 shootout loss to the Tampa Bay Mutiny at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 11,378 -- which whistled and bristled at every wasted
scoring chance in the final minutes -- watched Tampa Bay outscore
Los Angeles, 4-2, in the shootout as the Mutiny stole a point and
kept the Galaxy from earning a precious three that looked like such
a sure thing early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Musa Shannon's shootout goal was the difference for the Mutiny
after the Galaxy's Ezra Hendrickson sent a low right-footer that
goalkeeper Scott Garlick got a piece of before glancing off the
left post to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about everyone else, but I've reached that
point,'' said Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, referring to not
being satisfied with simply creating scoring chances. ``I don't
think anyone is in dispute that we're creating chances, but that
isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just have to step up and put the ball into the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 20 shots were numerous near misses, including two
headers on goal by midfielder Maurico Cienfuegos, a shot off the
cross bar by Joe Franchino and a chance from 10 yards out that
Welton fired directly at Garlick three minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Galaxy -- the same way it did in a 2-1 loss at Kansas
City a week ago -- dominated the flow of the game and appeared much
more cohesive than at any time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, for one, seemed to flash much of the form of last
year when Los Angeles set MLS scoring records and humiliated
opponents with its potent offense.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Galaxy also made Tampa Bay midfielder Carlos
Valderrama a non-factor as wave after wave of offense made its way
upfield.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Steve Jolley was one who was able to find plenty
of positives in terms of looking ahead to what appears to be coming
for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds funny, but for the first time all year, I felt like
we were clicking on all cylinders,'' Jolley said. ``When this thing
(scoring drought) blows over, we're going to start thrashing teams
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't dominated a team like that in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but the Galaxy's scoring funk allowed Tampa
Bay to leave Los Angeles with its first win ever after four losses.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmid said he sees the team coming along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've said before, you gotta give us at least 10 games,''
Schmid said. ``Today we played better than we did last week. ...
Sometimes in soccer, it just doesn't go in for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman, the few times he was challenged, made sure of that from
a defensive standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy keeper was brilliant, stopping Shannon on a
point-blank chance in the second half and tipping away first-half
blasts by Jefferson Gottardi and Mauricio Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   In the shootout, Cobi Jones and Clint Mathis matched Tampa Bay's
Pete Marino and Jorge Salcedo for a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   R.T. Moore put the Mutiny ahead with a left-footer that bounced
under a diving Hartman. Then came the key break for Tampa Bay, when
Cienfuegos fired one directly at Garlick, setting the stage for
Shannon's game-winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
