<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL-WOODS MATCH A TV SHOW WITHOUT DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ David Duval and Tiger Woods will go head-to-head Aug. 2
in a made-for-TV prime-time event. The winner gets $1.1 million,
the loser $400,000. Wow. Have a little plastic excitement with your
graphite and titanium.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at IMG and ABC have themselves a sure-fire ratings
hit, or so they think, but what they don't have is an event with
merit. It will make Duval richer. It will make Woods richer. It
will make the game poorer. It's nothing more than ``Shell's
Wonderful World of Golf,'' but at least those folks had the decency
to promote their show as an exhibition between intriguing
personalities with some sort of exotic golf course as backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   The people behind Duval-Woods, though they deny it is their
intention, are selling a ``once and for all'' match-race concept, a
la Ruffian vs. Foolish Pleasure, because by now everyone has heard
the tired debate about which player should be ranked No. 1. Woods
was there for a long time but Duval overtook him after a torrid
stretch of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Head-to-head battles between the game's best players are what we
look for each week but rarely witness. That is because they must
happen spontaneously; they cannot be invented. We would all love to
see Duval and Woods shoot it out, but in the US Open, or the
British Open, or the PGA, or any of those Buick events, for that
matter, just so long as there is some legitimate pressure and
competition thrown into the mix. This Aug. 2 proposal makes the
Senior Skins game feel like a Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, the golf gods smile on us and present a
gift: Snead-Hogan at Augusta National, Palmer-Hogan-Nicklaus at
Cherry Hill, Nicklaus-Miller-Weiskopf at the '75 Masters,
Watson-Nicklaus at Turnberry in '77. All of them classic
confrontations, none of them staged out of greed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if they want to add a little spice, how about this? The
loser has to agree to play the Greater Milwaukee Open, John Deere
Classic, and B.C. Open in each of the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? What pressure? All Justin Thompson had to do was eagle
the par-5 18th at Sterling CC to give his team a victory in the
recent New England Division 1 college championships. No problem.
``He hit driver, 3-wood, and holed out a sand wedge,'' said
University of Rhode Island golf coach Tom Drennan, still a bit numb
after the dramatic victory. It enabled the Rams to edge Connecticut
by one shot and run their mark to 253-0 against New England
competition since April 1997. The dramatic eagle also vaulted
Thompson into a playoff with Yale's Eddie Brockner, which the URI
sophomore won on the fifth hole. URI is host team for this week's
NCAA East Regional championships at Rhode Island CC in Barrington,
and the 23-team field includes such powers as Georgia Tech (Matt
Kuchar you know, but teammate Bryce Molder may be better), Florida
(with Steve Scott), and Clemson (John Engler and Jonathan Byrd are
ranked nationally in the top five). URI, UConn, and Yale are the
New England representatives, and while he concedes his team is an
underdog to get one of the top 11 spots into the national event,
Drennan says, ``We have realistic expectations going in. I wouldn't
predict, but these guys surprise me all the time.'' Three
Massachusetts products _ Jim Salinetti from Stockbridge, Josh
Hillman from Greenfield, and Joey Pohle of Williamstown _ are at
the heart of Drennan's club . . . One team that won't be at Rhode
Island CC is the University of Virginia, which means no homecoming
of sorts for James Driscoll, the two-time Massachusetts Amateur
champion. Driscoll, a junior, ``was a little off this spring,''
said Virginia coach Mike Moraghan. ``He had two Top 10 finishes and
always had one or two good rounds, but never really put it all
together.'' . . . Wake Forest did not make the field, either, but
senior Michael Capone of Cranston, R.I., did earn an individual
spot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his tribute to Gene Sarazen Wednesday, Arnold Palmer raised a
good point: ``They probably should have just called it the Sarazen
wedge.'' Sarazen, of course, invented the sand wedge back around
1931. He got the idea, of all things, from an airplane ride with
his friend Howard Hughes. Sarazen spent many summers in Lake
Sunapee, N.H., though he lived most of his final years in Marco
Island, Fla., where two of his closest friends were Ken Venturi and
Pat Bradley . . . It was also a sad week for Ben Crenshaw, whose
father died after a long fight with thyroid cancer. Charlie
Crenshaw accompanied his son to The Country Club in 1968 for the US
Junior Amateur, Ben's first competition outside of Texas, which is
another reason why the place will hold special meaning for the US
Ryder Cup captain come September. In March, the Francis Ouimet
Scholarship Fund announced a $50,000 scholarship in Charlie
Crenshaw's name, and when he told his father the news, ``you
wouldn't believe how happy that made him,'' said Ben . . . It
appears as if Mark Calcavecchia has a partner for the JCPenney
Classic: Danielle Ammaccapane. The LPGA Tour veteran criticized
Karrie Webb, Annika Sorenstam, and Se Ri Pak for lacking
personality and not doing more to promote the Tour. Webb and
Sorenstam were offended, and rightfully so, because it's absurd to
think they should try to be what Nancy Lopez used to be. The LPGA
Tour may have problems, but Webb and Sorenstam certainly aren't
among them. Ammaccapane, meanwhile, should take a lesson from
Calcavecchia, whose ill-advised comments at the Masters (he said
that Palmer should stop playing in the event) touched off a barrage
of criticism. A Palmer spokesman said Calcavecchia had sent a
letter of apology, though he did not say what the letter said. ``I
took some heat for my dumb remarks, mostly from my wife, Sheryl,''
Calcavecchia told Golf World . . . The weather is getting warmer,
so perhaps there's no need for chicken soup. But with Father's Day
approaching, you may want to think about ``Chicken Soup for the
Golfer's Soul,'' a delightful compilation of 101 stories that has
just hit bookstores. More than 4,000 stories were submitted, said
Mark Donnelly, who with his wife, Chrissy, had the tough task of
narrowing them to 200. A panel of 40 then pared the list to 101.
Why golf for the latest in the `Chicken Soup' series? ``Most of the
lessons we need in life we learn on the golf course. Golf is
something people need,'' said Mark, an avid golfer (as is his
wife). ``In this fast-paced world, isn't it interesting that such a
slow-paced sport is our favorite?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
