<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-INCIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR DISASTER AT PIMLICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ A tragedy was narrowly averted Saturday at Pimlico
Race Course when a man stepped onto the track during the seventh
race as eight horses bore down on him an eighth of a mile from the
finish of the $200,000 Maryland Breeders Cup Sprint. Jockeys
maneuvered their horses to avoid the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I turned for home, I couldn't believe my eyes,'' said
jockey Jerry Bailey, whose Yes It's True was leading at the time
and eventually won the race. ``I thought I saw a man standing on
the track. And, as I got closer, I realized it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The man had climbed an 8-foot wire fence in the infield, veered
across the turf course, and made it onto the main track, slightly
inside the eighth pole. He was standing on the track for at least
15 seconds as the horses charged out of the final turn and headed
for the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in the middle of anything like that,'' said
Pat Day, the jockey on The Trader's Echo. It was a comment echoed
by other jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, the trainer of Yes It's True, said ``that's why
those guys (jockeys) are so great. They didn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Security officers quickly apprehended the man, with one officer
throwing him to the ground and putting his face into the dirt. He
was taken into custody. Police identified him as a 23-year-old male
and said he has been taken to a local psychiatric facility.
</P>
<P>
   Artax, the overwhelming 4-5 favorite was bearing directly down
on the man until the last instant, when Jorge Chavez swerved to the
inside and the man took a small step to the outside. A shaken
Chavez said the man ``hit me on my (right) leg'' as Artax swooped
by. Actually, the man threw a handful of dirt that missed Artax and
hit Greenspring Willie, compromising his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody could have been killed,'' said Chavez. ``(The man)
could have been killed, my horse could have broke down, anything
could have happened. It was very dangerous out there for the horses
and jockeys and everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pimlico stewards studied the videotapes over and over and
determined the man had thrown a fistful of dirt at Artax and
impeded him. The stewards, after much discussion, declared Artax a
non-starter and hundreds of thousands of dollars were returned to
bettors who had backed Artax.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez was among several jockeys who said Pimlico should have
had security guards along the infield fence, behind which were as
many as 50,000 fans. Pimlico CEO Joe DeFrancis said the track had
more than 1,000 Baltimore police officers, National Guardsmen, and
other security personnel ``and there's nothing you can do if a
suicidal person'' is determined to get on the track.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous such incident in the United States came at
Suffolk Downs July 4, 1966, when Ted Luppino, a mental patient,
jumped into the path of Happy Voter and Taunton as the horses
galloped to the wire of the Mayflower Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The horses pinwheeled the man, who was not hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
