<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-MENIFEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENIFEE BACK FOR SECONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ No respect. Charismatic just doesn't get any respect
at all.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, finishing second in the Kentucky Derby makes a
horse more popular than winning it. Saturday marked the third
consecutive Preakness that the Derby runner-up was favored over the
Derby winner, and the third consecutive time the Derby winner won.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday marked the largest gap in the odds as Derby
runner-up Menifee was 2-1, and winner Charismatic was 8-1.
Charismatic won easily Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Charismatic, who has been haunted by the ghost of being a
former claimer, will get some respect. And the Menifee camp is left
to ponder the dilemma of being second best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to run through a seam, and I couldn't get through,''
said Pat Day, who was aboard Menifee. ``I had to back out and make
another run. He made a nice run through the stretch, but we didn't
close any ground on the winner. My congratulations go out to the
winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee is a handsome animal and he worked well at Churchill
Downs prior to shipping to Pimlico. His trainer, Elliott Walden,
exuded a quiet confidence that the media picked up on, and Menifee
became the horse to beat. The favorite did run well, but he was no
match for Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic just handed us a beating,'' said Walden. ``I
really can't make any excuses, although Pat said he thought he had
to sit a little longer around the turn than he would have liked.
There was a hole he was trying to get to, but it just closed up.
Charismatic ran a great race. Menifee really ran his heart out, but
we just got beat. It hurts to be second again, but not as bad as if
we had lost only by a head. The pace was really quick in there and
I think, after the last two days, a lot of the riders were thinking
that they needed to be on the rail, the way the speed has been
holding up. It's very possible that a lot of the riders overgauged
the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden also trained Victory Gallop, who gained a measure of
revenge over Real Quiet last year when he denied him the Triple
Crown by catching him at the wire to take the Belmont Stakes by a
nose. However, Walden isn't sure he wants Menifee to take a third
swing at Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my plans, it would look kind of funny if I didn't
run in the Belmont, because Real Quiet beat us pretty good here
last year. But the winner today won with a little more authority
than I really like to see my horse get beat with.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic didn't get enough respect in Baltimore, and,
perhaps, trainer Bob Baffert got too much. Baffert trained both
Silver Charm and Real Quiet, but this Triple Crown season has been
a disaster for him. All three of his entries ran out of the money
in the Derby, and Saturday his filly, Excellent Meeting, pulled up
at the three-eighths pole, suffering from a breathing problem.
Excellent Meeting took a pounding while running fifth in the Derby,
and several of Baffert's opponents mentioned they thought two weeks
was to soon to run a filly who had been in such a rough race.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got halfway down the backside, she had just
fallen out of the bridle,'' said Kent Desormeaux, who rode
Excellent Meeting. ``She was out of the picture, and had no hope.
At the three-eighths pole, I backed off her, and tried to save her
as best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, whose reputation has recently taken a beating, was left
to explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has equine asthma,'' he said. ``Kent said he had
no horse going down the backstretch. I think when he snatched her
up on the first turn, he might have displaced her palate. She's
fine at the barn. She was doing too good to come into the race and
run the way she did. Now, we'll just have to regroup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
