<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-16 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURSE CORRECTION BY COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The ongoing atrocities perpetrated on the NBA viewing
public this season have not gone unnoticed by those who move and
shake the league. (How could they?) Changes are in order.
</P>
<P>
   A special committee consisting of commissioner David Stern, his
deputy, Russ Granik, his generalissimo, Rod Thorn, and several
influential owners will meet during the playoffs and throughout the
summer to recommend potentially sweeping changes. The game you see
next season may look a lot different. As they say in Besancon,
where Bruce Bowen did have a jump shot, vive la difference!
</P>
<P>
   While nothing specific has been recommended, or even debated,
look for the following issues to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   --Defenses: The NBA may finally be willing to give the zone a
chance. No one can figure out the illegal defense rules anyway, and
simply allowing any and all forms of defense would be a challenge
to coaches everywhere. But the main impetus is this: The easiest,
most effective way to beat a zone is to advance the ball and get it
to the basket before the zone can be set up. That's one theory,
anyway. However, the prospect of Shaquille O'Neal lurking in the
lane would militate against a lot of drives and slashes and force
teams to take outside shots. That's not all that different from the
way it is now.
</P>
<P>
   --The shot clock: There are a number of ways to wiggle this one,
ranging from reducing the time to not resetting it after certain
plays.
</P>
<P>
   --The lane: One obvious issue is already on the books, the
three-second violation. Referees will be told to enforce it. They
did it with the hand check and the players got the message. The
same could be true for this one. (Then again, they could also
enforce palming, but that might make games last longer than the
director's cut of ``Doctor Zhivago.'') The lane itself is also up
for discussion. Should they adopt the international lane? Or should
they extend it by a foot on either side?
</P>
<P>
   --Coaching: This is one thing the league can't adjudicate, but
it is almost universally recognized that coaches are responsible
for the dumbing down of the offense. The way the movers and shakers
see it, the players will adjust to any changes. So will the
referees. The goal is to ensure that the coaches are forced to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   The good news here is that there are people who matter who see
what we've seen and are equally mortified. They see a decade-long
decline in scoring, a dilution of talent brought on by expansion,
not-ready-for-prime-time players leaving college too early, and
overzealous coaches determined to extract every last tick out of
the 24-second clock.
</P>
<P>
   The key is that the committee is a relatively small one. The
normal route is for the Competition and Rules Committee to
recommend changes, but that's a 29-member body with a lot of
individual agendas that can make the process unwieldy and, by
extension, uneventful. This committee is smaller and has the
authority to recommend changes and then browbeat the other owners
with ``Easy Dave'' Stern holding the hammer. It is determined to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone else happen to notice that the Celtics averaged more
points a game, shot a higher percentage, and held opponents to
fewer points and a lower field goal percentage while Kenny Anderson
and Antoine Walker were out? We were all trumpeting the Anderson
Factor prior to this season, noting how the team and Walker
benefited from his presence. Well, in the nine games they missed
(counting the Washington game in which Walker was hurt), the
Celtics benefited from their absence (sse chart). So who needs 'em?
We've already mentioned that Rick Pitino should be pushing Anderson
westward to the cap-friendly, point-guard-starved Clippers in
exchange for Lorenzen Wright in a sign-and-trade. Maybe the
Clippers would go for that only if, say, Walker were included for
LA's No. 1 pick and another body. That would enable the Celtics to
draft Steve Francis, Lamar Odom, or whomever and eliminate two big
problems: the big salaries of Anderson and Walker and the obvious
fact that their three best players play two positions . . .
Speaking of soon-to-be NBA point guards, UCLA sophomore Baron Davis
has decided to enter the draft and should be a top five pick.
Ex-Bruin Bill Walton, who still bleeds blue and gold, was horrified
by the decision. ``It's a huge mistake,'' Walton said. ``Here's a
very talented player and a nice young man who hurt his leg and came
back too soon. He struggled at the college level physically and his
team couldn't even beat Detroit Mercy in the NCAA Tournament. And
now he figures he's going to be an NBA star? These young players
get such bad advice. It's sad. It hurts all levels of basketball.
He's obviously got game, but are we talking about one of the very
best players? He's not there yet. He's walking away from the most
important asset that he'll ever have _ the ability to train his
mind at UCLA. If it was another school, like USC or Notre Dame, I
could understand. In that case, he'd be making the right choice.''
. . . As this was being written, Odom and Duke's Corey Meggette
were still fence-straddling regarding entry into the draft. Has
there even been a situation in which the consensus No. 1 waited so
long? A sleeper who's making big strides is high schooler Jonathan
Bender from Picayune, Miss. ``He's got a chance to hit the top
six,'' said Celtics general manager Chris Wallace. Bender is a
6-foot-11-inch, 210-pounder who has committed to Mississippi State,
which, of course, means nothing. Wallace said Bender is not in the
same class as Kevin Garnett or Kobe Bryant but is better than the
recent high schoolers such as Jermaine O'Neal, Al Harris, and
Rashard Lewis. The other high school entrant, Leon Smith of
Chicago, is probably a late first-rounder, Wallace said. ``He's got
a pro body,'' Wallace said of the 6-11, 250-pound Smith . . . The
Celtics not only will lose their first-round pick (unless it's in
the top three), but they also don't have their own second-round
pick, either. They are slated to pick 37th, but the Knicks have
first dibs on that choice courtesy of the Chris Mills deal. If the
Knicks don't want it _ and Wallace thinks New York will take it _
then the Grizzlies can take it thanks to the Tony Massenburg deal.
The Celtics won't go away empty-handed. They have the 55th pick,
from Orlando through Denver, courtesy of the Eric Williams deal.
That ought to keep the suits waiting in breathless anticipation . .
. Hey, Dave Checketts, we know that the Madison Square Garden
tenants aren't exactly championship regulars. But don't you think
four banners for the 1993-94 Rangers is a bit over the top? Can you
imagine if the Celtics did that? (They actually did at one time,
then pulled down all the division and conference banners.) The
1993-94 Rangers have banners for winning the division, conference,
regular season (best record), and, oh yes, the Stanley Cup. The
last one should be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He says he's not going through withdrawal, but we don't believe
him. For the first time since he arrived in Chicago in 1985, GM
Jerry Krause is a man without a playoff team. And this isn't the
same as, say, Pete Babcock or Jerry Colangelo missing out. The
Bulls not only made it, they stuck around for a while. (In the two
years prior to their first title, they made it to the conference
finals.) ``It's different,'' Krause says. ``But if it was the same
team, and we were having this conversation . . .'' Krause says the
season went about as he expected, which is hard to believe until
you factor in their injuries. Brent Barry, Ron Harper, Mark Bryant,
and Toni Kukoc all missed time, and we saw what they can do when
they're healthy: beat the Celtics. ``We knew it would be rough. But
you do what you have to do and grin and bear it. That's life. We
lost Michael Jordan. He not only was a superstar on the court, but
he was a superstar in the locker room and people don't talk about
that. Guys depended on him in that room.'' Krause said his
rebuilding plan _ he says he has one, but will go no further _ has
not taken a hit with all the re-signings this season. The reason:
He feels that only a certain special player can play the triangle
offense that the Bulls still use and plan to keep using. ``I read
about all these lead guards who we lost,'' Krause said, referring
to Stephon Marbury, though not by name. ``Well, we never had a lead
guard here. We never had anyone dominate the ball unless the whole
thing broke down and we needed Michael in the last 10 seconds. You
have to have a high basketball IQ to play the triple post. Dennis
Rodman had a basketball IQ of about 300. He was unreal. Off the
court, his IQ is for you to debate. But on the court, it's unreal
how quickly he picked it up.'' Many of the ex-Bulls have said their
problems in adjusting to their new teams has been the triangle, or
lack thereof. No one else plays it because it does require patience
and learning. Few teams have the inclination for either . . . The
Suns came back to America West Arena down, 0-2, to the Trail
Blazers and, for the first time since 1985, did not have a playoff
sellout. They weren't alone. The Magic didn't sell out either of
the first two games against the Sixers, the Timberwolves had empty
seats for the first game against the Spurs, and the Pistons
couldn't even draw 15,000 in the 22,000-seat Palace of Auburn Hills
for their first playoff game against the Hawks . . . Suns boss
Colangelo said the year was ``a downer'' and added that his team
was up against it right from the start. ``They changed the rules
and one of our players (Antonio McDyess) was heisted,'' he said.
``Then, we underachieved. We were overmatched by Portland in terms
of athleticism and depth. We have a lot of work to do.'' In
describing the player he wants, Colangelo freely admitted that
McDyess fits the description (young, athletic, powerful). He's
still steamed at the way that went down. He said the team now has a
better feel for Tom Gugliotta ``and what we need around him. We
need to complement him.'' Googs is what he is, and the Suns found
out he cannot defend in the post. Brian Grant bludgeoned him in the
Portland series. Still, Phoenix has a lottery pick (Dallas's,
thanks to the Steve Nash deal) and will send Jason Kidd to Secaucus
for good luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
