<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ARE FIRST-RATE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ First place in May isn't listed on anybody's resume.
It almost certainly won't be remembered by John Valentin, who can
be excused if he doesn't recall anything about Saturday's game,
including his decisive two-run double in the Red Sox' 6-5 win over
the mistake-ridden Blue Jays, after twice taking shots to the head.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Sons of Jimy Williams, winners for the eighth time
in nine games, a first-place tie with the Yankees on a Sunday in
May is still infinitely preferable to taking the 10-count before
they've even laced on their gloves.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' win, coupled with the Yanks' fifth straight loss, drew
the teams even at 20-15 and represented the latest the Sox have
been in first place since the Sons of Kevin Kennedy won the
American League East title in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives added juice to this week's three-game set against
the Yankees that begins Tuesday in Fenway Park, as if the teams
need anything extra to ensure a full house on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody picked us to do anything in this division,'' said Mike
Stanley, whose two-run pinch homer in a three-run seventh was
another catalyst to the Sox' first win in 12 games in which they
had trailed after six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every publication you read already was conceding them the
division title,'' Stanley said. ``They won 125 games last year, and
after adding (Roger) Clemens, everything you read said they're
better, and all they'd have to do is put their gloves out and the
same thing was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it just doesn't work that way. They're still a
phenomenal team, no matter what they're doing right now. But it
will be important for us to see how we match up, see how we play
against them. It's not a make-or-break series, but it will give you
a good barometer.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin could have used an icepack after taking a
95-mile-an-hour fastball from Blue Jays righthander Roy Halladay
off the earflap of his batting helmet in the first inning. He
turned at the last moment to avoid what could have been an
unspeakable outcome. ``Oh, he hit me good,'' Valentin said. ``It
had my ears ringing, but luckily it didn't hit me in the head.
That's why I was able to stay in the ballgame, but it was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in the seventh, while beating out an infield topper to
third baseman Tony Fernandez that was generously scored a base hit,
Valentin was clotheslined by Toronto first baseman Carlos Delgado,
who was pulled into Valentin's path by Fernandez's off-line throw.
</P>
<P>
   That shot left Valentin, whose helmet cut into his nose, hunched
over with his eyes watering for a few moments, but again he waved
off trainer Jim Rowe and manager Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go home,'' Valentin said. ```I quit. This game's
over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, it would be. But first, Valentin came around to
score on rookie Brian Daubach's ground-rule double to draw the Sox
within a run, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then after Stanley, pinch hitting for Reggie Jefferson, followed
with a his home run off Blue Jays reliever Dan Plesac in the
seventh to give the Sox a 4-3 lead, Valentin doubled home Darren
Lewis (walk) and Trot Nixon (bunt that was played into a single by
Blue Jays reliever Billy Koch) in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Those runs proved the difference as the Blue Jays scored twice
in the inning off Sox relievers Mark Guthrie and Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it turned out good that I stayed,'' Valentin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays used three pitchers _ Halladay (21), Koch (24),
and ex-Sox farmhand Peter Munro (23) _ who were still in diapers
when 36-year-old Sox starter Mark Portugal borrowed his first
lighter. But it was 25-year-old outfielder Shannon Stewart who was
most guilty of being an excitable boy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Jays down a run with two on and their best two hitters,
Shawn Green and Delgado, due to hit against Guthrie in the seventh,
Stewart attempted to steal third while the ball was still in
Guthrie's glove _ and the pitcher was looking right at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a good move,'' said third baseman Valentin, who
was awaiting Stewart's arrival, ball in glove, after Guthrie turned
and tossed it to him. ``Obviously, he thought maybe I was
daydreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he noticed how far off the bag Valentin was playing
the lefthanded batting Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I messed up,'' Stewart said. ``I'll take it like a man. I was
looking at Valentin, and he wasn't paying attention. I didn't look
at the pitcher, but (teammates) told me he was looking right at
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The win went to John Wasdin, who pitched 1 1/3 innings of
scoreless relief and is 2-0 since his return from the minors, but
not before the Blue Jays got a look at Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox closer, tested in his first save opportunity since
coming off the disabled list last Monday, returned to his familiar
point-to-the-sky routine, setting down the Blue Jays in order in
the ninth for his fourth save, first since April 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing good ball and getting good pitching,''
Valentin said. ``Now with Flash coming back, we should be stronger
in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are still two games to be played on this side of the
border before the Bombers arrive. But from Block Island to
Wilbraham, you know what they're thinking over their morning
bagels.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, start your barometers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
