<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAL-MART-VERDICT-HNS &LR;      05-16 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAL-MART-VERDICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JURY SOCKS WAL-MART AND UNIT WITH $624 MILLION VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``f'' categories.) 
 By ADOLFO PESQUERA  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A jury here has awarded a Mexican company more
than $624 million after finding Wal-Mart and a Wal-Mart subsidiary
acted with malice when it broke a partnership deal to distribute
groceries throughout Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, jurors will return to court to decide how much
Wal-Mart and its subsidiary should pay in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The jury verdict on Friday came after four hours of deliberation
in the case that has been tried in state District Judge Martha
Tanner's court for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary telephone call from her chambers Friday
afternoon, Tanner and lawyers for both sides attempted to convince
editors at the San Antonio Express-News not to report on the
verdict until after next week's decision on punitive damages, even
though the verdict was handed down in open court.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner indicated she was concerned that publicity about the
verdict might sway the jurors when they take up the issue of
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   After Express-News attorney Thomas G. Coghlan discussed the
matter with the judge and the lawyers for both sides, Tanner
decided not to take court action blocking the release of the jury's
verdict. Coghlan said Tanner then issued a gag order forbidding
participants in the case from discussing the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The action comes six years after Valores Corp. of Monterrey,
Mexico _ Mexico's second-largest wholesale grocery distributor _
filed a breach-of-contract suit accusing Wal-Mart and its
subsidiary McLane Co. Inc. of reneging on a deal to be its partner
in a wholesale grocery distribution operation in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, based in Temple, Texas, is the nation's largest
wholesale grocery distributor to convenience stores and has annual
sales of more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Valores, owned by Gilberto De Hoyos and Jose Chapa, does much of
its business with mom-and-pop stores and in home delivery.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Robson Walton, the chief executive officer of
Wal-Mart and the son and heir of the late Sam Walton, testified
that the Valores deal ``had not been finalized'' even though McLane
issued a news release announcing its new joint venture with
Valores.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that McLane had in fact agreed to the deal with
Valores but failed to live up to the agreement and breached its
fiduciary duty to Valores.
</P>
<P>
   The panel concluded that Wal-Mart knowingly participated in
McLane's breach, intentionally and willfully interfered with the
McLane-Valores deal and that McLane and Wal-Mart acted with malice.
</P>
<P>
   The damages _ the exact sum Valores had sought _ were based on
future earnings Valores claimed it would have achieved had the
partnership held together for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ricardo Cedillo, a lawyer for Valores, the Mexican
firm and McLane agreed on Sept. 9, 1991, to create a 50-50
partnership to be named Chapa-McLane S.A.
</P>
<P>
   McLane was the recognized leader in distribution technologies,
said Valores lawyer Kendall Montgomery of Houston. ``McLane was to
provide the know-how, and Valores was providing the know-who,''
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   McLane issued a news release announcing the joint venture on
Nov. 11, 1991, and by late spring 1992 architectural plans for a
new distribution center in Monterrey were 95 percent complete,
Cedillo said. The groundbreaking was set for July 1, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the press release went out, Wal-Mart received a
complaint from another major Mexican company, CIFRA, Mexico's
largest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   CIFRA had its own joint venture with Wal-Mart to create a chain
of Sam's Club warehouse stores and CIFRA president Henry Davis
expressed concern about the McLane project to Robson Walton,
according to documents filed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Cedillo argued, Wal-Mart executives were
telling officers at McLane to ``slow the documentation _ don't go
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, defense attorney Seagal V. Wheatley
portrayed Drayton McLane, McLane's chairman and CEO, as
enthusiastic about the potential of the North American Free Trade
Agreement when he turned his attention to starting a partnership in
Mexico in 1990. McLane owns the Houston Astros baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   But Wheatley claimed that as talks progressed, it became clear
to McLane it would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley tried to convince jurors that the deal fell apart for
reasons that had nothing to do with actions by Wal-Mart's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, 1992, in what Cedillo referred to as the ``doomsday
meeting,'' Valores was told by Wal-Mart and McLane officials that
the Chapa-McLane venture would not proceed.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, McLane vice president Robert Hudspeth forwarded
to Wal-Mart vice president Harry Johnson an outline of information
developed from the Chapa-McLane project that would be used to
develop a new company called McLane de Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   With the list of Valores' clients and their needs in hand,
McLane de Mexico became a Valores competitor, but the venture
failed within several months, Cedillo said in closing arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
