   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ A profile of the Yugoslav leader.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Dateline TK) _ Developments concerning the
fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Chinese liberals and political
dissidents are assessing what last week's nationalistic,
anti-American outburst, and the possible worsening of
Chinese-American relations, will mean for their struggle for a more
free and democratic society. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Anger continued to percolate here on
Sunday over the NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
even as officials from both sides gave signs that the height of the
crisis had passed. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica) _ Montenegrins fear a ``creeping
coup'' by their Serb partners in the Yugolsav federation. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline TK) _ Developments in Macedonia. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-VOTE (Jerusalem) _ In a stunning turn of events, two
minor party candidates withdrew from the prime minister's race on
Sunday, paving the way for what polls predicted what be a
conclusive victory on Monday by Labor Party leader Ehud Barak. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Los Angeles) _ The Clinton administration has
maintained a studied public neutrality in the Israeli campaign for
prime minister. But it has employed little guile in concealing its
rooting interest in the victory of Ehud Barak, the Labor Party
candidate. By James M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Uppington, South Africa) _ If South Africa's
second post-apartheid election campaign has offered any surprise at
all, it is the fuss that the Democratic Party has engendered. The
party and its antecedents, which traditionally represented wealthy,
English-speaking white liberals, consistently opposed apartheid and
were small but nagging irritants to the former white supremacist
Afrikaans-speaking regime. But even the ANC, which is expected to
coast to victory, perhaps with a two- thirds majority, has turned
its guns on the DP. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ARABS (Cairo) _ With his first foray into the Arab world,
Iran's president is taking a crucial step in a process of reaching
out to other countries. It is every bit as significant, but also as
tricky, as the rapprochement he has begun with the West. By Douglas
Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-VOTE (Guatemala City) _ Guatemalans vote on a
referendum to grant the country's indigenous population equal
rights.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PENSIONS (Ludony, Russia) _ Russian debts are a funny
business, as big Western banks have learned to their horror and
chagrin. A pensioner here long ago stopped trying to figure out
when she will get her money. As she sees it, retrieving a pension
from the backlog that has piled up at the regional administrative
center of Pskov is sort of like a lottery. Either your number comes
up, or it doesn't. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   HAWAII-BAYWATCH (Haleiwa, Hawaii) _ The biggest economic fish
caught in Hawaii this year is not a new factory or a high-tech
software start-up or a new planeload of Asian tourists, whose
financial troubles continue to keep them away in droves. No, the
biggest fish is David Hasselhoff, the head-lifeguard of
``Baywatch,'' which is to begin filming here in July, rechristened
``Baywatch Hawaii.'' By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Lamoni, Iowa) _ Gore speaks on education; it's
billed as the first policy address of the campaign. By Ethan
Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-REUNION (Charlottesville, Va.) _ More on the Jefferson
family reunion, and the decision by the family's executive
committee to put off any vote on allowing descendants of Sally
Hemings, the slave with whom Jefferson had a child, into the group.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-DECLINE (Undated) _ Crime in the United States dropped
dramatically last year, the seventh consecutive year it has fallen,
according to preliminary figures released by the FBI. The number of
violent crimes and property crimes each fell 7 percent in 1998,
creating the largest annual decline since crime began to decrease
in 1992. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   BREASTCANCER-STUDY (Undated) _ A new survey of women who took a
drastic measure to prevent breast cancer, having both healthy
breasts removed, shows that nearly 70 percent are satisfied with
their decision and would make the same choice if they had it to do
over again.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-POLITICS (Washington) _ Lots of senators are appearing on
talk shows to discuss gun control. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-POLITICS-SMITH (Washington) _ A profile of Sen. Gordon
Smith, at ground zero of the gun debate. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ A look at the Dole campaign. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
<P>
