<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9114 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-16 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE JUMPS THAT DOMAIN GUN
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Febreze, a new Procter &AMP; Gamble product that neutralizes pet
odor, has been the target of animal rights activists who believe it
is dangerous to pets.
</P>
<P>
   The company is so worried about rumors spread via the Internet,
says Advertising Age, that it has registered the following domains,
to prevent anyone else from using them: febrezekillspets.com;
febrezekillsdogs.com; febrezekillsbirds.com; febrezesucks.com; and
ihateprocterandgamble.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE ON FINE ART ANALYSIS: THE MONA LISA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Turning from last week's argument against over-analyzing
paintings, Personals stumbled upon  &UR; Joseph Harriss &LR; ' Smithsonian
magazine essay on &UR; Leonardo DaVinci &LR; 's Mona Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   Harriss presents theories a-plenty: Mona Lisa's closed-mouth
smile, for instance, was thought to be because her teeth had been
blackened by ``16th century style mercury treatment for syphilis
... A Danish doctor found that the model had congenital palsy
affecting the left side of her face, backing up his theory by
pointing out that she had the typically large hands of such
patients. After due study, an orthopedic surgeon in Lyons, France,
decided that Mona Lisa's semi-smile resulted from her being
half-paralyzed either from birth or as the result of a stroke; one
indication of this ... was that her right hand looks relaxed but
her left hand is strangely tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a computer, &UR; Lillian Schwartz &LR;  of Lucent Technologies
reversed a self-portrait of Leonardo and juxtaposed it with the
Mona Lisa's face. Noses, mouths, foreheads, cheekbones, eyes and
brows all lined up, leading Schwartz to conclude that the artist
began with a portrait of a woman, who became unavailable in the
midst of his painting, whereupon he used himself _ without his
beard _ as a model.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HE FINAL TALLIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Politically-minded movie fans frustrated by the TV camera's
quick sweep over the audience when  &UR; Elia Kazan  &LR; received his award
at the Oscars, will turn to a definitive analysis of the response,
in Brill's content:  &UR; Warren Beatty &LR; ,  &UR; Meryl Streep &LR; ,
 &UR; Helen Hunt  &LR; and  &UR; Kurt Russell  &LR; were among the nine people giving a
standing ovation;  &UR; Nick Nolte &LR;  and  &UR; Ed Harris &LR;  were shown sitting
silently; two shots showed a mix of standers and sitters, and two
showed  &UR; Steven Spielberg  &LR; and  &UR; Kate Capshaw &LR; , seated and
applauding.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers would have thought the protest was a dud, which was what
many newspapers concluded. Daily Variety's  &UR; Army Archerd &LR;  told
Brill's Content, though, that the shots were misleading, and only a
quarter of the audience had risen for Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   - Members of the restaurant workers union picketed a fundraiser
last week for the writers' group PEN at Cipriani's, a fancy New
York restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports in the New York Post and Daily News:
 &UR; George Stephanopoulos &LR; ,  &UR; Gay Talese &LR; ,  &UR; Thomas Cahill &LR; ,  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Newman &LR; ,  &UR; A.E. Hotchner &LR; ,  &UR; Paul Auster &LR;  and  &UR; Spalding Gray  &LR; refused
to cross the line.
</P>
<P>
   Actor's Equity president  &UR; Ron Silver &LR; ,  &UR; Art Buchwald &LR; ,  &UR; Susan &LR; 
 &UR; Cheever &LR; , &UR; Dan Rather &LR; ,  &UR; Oliver Stone &LR; ,  &UR; David Remnick &LR; ,  &UR; E.L. &LR; 
 &UR; Doctorow &LR; ,  &UR; Ben Bradlee &LR; ,  &UR; Alan King &LR; , &UR; Salman Rushdie &LR;  and  &UR; Arthur &LR; 
 &UR; Miller  &LR; _ who said ``It was more important for me to help PEN than
worry about crossing a line'' _ crossed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Susan  &LR; and  &UR; Gary Woodward &LR; , the parents of  &UR; Louise &LR; 
 &UR; Woodward &LR; , who was convicted of killing a baby in her charge, have
been charged with making an allegedly fraudulent claim on the fund
that was supposed to pay for her legal bills. The Woodwards are now
separated, says the Daily Telegraph, which says that one charge
involved an invoice for accommodation during Louise Woodward's
trial. The couple actually stayed in the home of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Wen Shi &LR; , a research doctor at UCSF, noticed when he visited
the immigration office in San Francisco last week that ``Aliens''
was playing on the waiting room TV.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``(Her work) is a cross between the floating surrealist &LR; 
 &UR; imagery of Marc Chagall, the biomorphic forms of Paul Klee and &LR; 
 &UR; the light touch of Alexander Calder. ... She's the art world's &LR; 
 &UR; best secret.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  - New York curator  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  on the paintings of
novelist  &UR; Tama Janowitz &LR; , ``the Art world's best kept secret,'' in
his estimation. Jones hung a Janowitz painting of mushrooms in a
``Grrrl Power'' show in Manhattan over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
