<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WINTER-NYT &LR;      05-16 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WINTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARVIN S. WINTER, 78, MANHATTAN DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marvin S. Winter, a Manhattan real estate developer
for more than 50 years, died on Friday at New York University
Hospital in Manhattan. He was 78 and had homes in Manhattan and
Delray Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was heart failure, said his son James, of Rye
Brook, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Winter, whose father, Benjamin, was a prominent real estate
developer in New York City early in the century, was born on Aug.
21, 1920, in Manhattan. He was graduated from Washington and Lee
University in Lexington, Va., in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   After college and service in the Army, Winter entered the family
business and expanded it into the commercial and residential real
estate markets in Chicago, Philadelphia, Miami and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   His holdings in Manhattan included 800 Fifth Avenue, at 61st
Street, a commercial and residential building constructed on the
site of the former Dodge mansion; 730 Fifth Avenue, at 57th Street,
known as the Crown Building, and 210 Central Park South.
</P>
<P>
   Winter was also a founding director of the Community National
Bank of Staten Island, which was later sold to Chemical Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son James, Winter is survived by his wife, Eleanor;
two other sons, Benjamin of Rye, N.Y., and Douglas of Highland
Park, Ill.; a daughter, Karen Miller of Sudbury, Mass.; two
sisters, Ethel Schanzer and Natalie Ballen, both of Manhattan, and
10 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WIGODER-NYT &LR;      05-16 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WIGODER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: ISRAEL)  
 GEOFFREY WIGODER, 76, EDITOR AND BROADCASTER IN JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geoffrey Wigoder, a broadcaster, scholar and editor of Judaica,
died on April 9 in Jerusalem. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a brain hemorrhage after a fall, said Andre Balog,
a friend and colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Wigoder was born in Leeds, England, and earned degrees in
medieval Jewish history at Trinity College, Dublin, and Oxford
University. He also attended the Jewish Theological Seminary in New
York, where he met his future wife, Devorah MacDwyer. The couple
immigrated to Israel in 1949 and settled in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1950s Wigoder was overseeing the overseas
operations of Israeli radio, and in the 1960s and '70s he worked as
a correspondent for the British Broadcasting Corp. and The
Yorkshire Post, at one point making daily broadcasts about the
trial of Adolf Eichmann.
</P>
<P>
   He also collaborated with Cecil Roth, a scholar of Judaica at
Oxford and Hebrew University in Jerusalem, on the one-volume New
Standard Jewish Encyclopedia. The two scholars then began work on
what was to become the 16-volume Encyclopedia Judaica. When Roth
died in 1970, Wigoder took over as editor in chief. An updated
version of the entire work was published on a single CD-ROM last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wigoder's credits also include ``The Encyclopedia of the Jewish
Religion,'' ``Jewish Art and Civilization'' and ``The Story of the
Synagogue.'' His ``Dictionary of the Jewish-Christian Dialogue''
was commissioned by the Paulist Press in New York in 1995. He also
lectured at Hebrew University, where he founded Israel's first oral
history department, and was one of the founders of the Museum of
the Jewish Diaspora in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; two sons, Meir and Shimshon, both of
Tel Aviv; a sister, Thelma Ruby of London, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
