<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-VALAIRE-NYT &LR;      05-16 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-VALAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEMARY VALAIRE, 68, BALLET TEACHER AND DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rosemary Valaire, a ballet teacher and a director of the
Westside Ballet of Santa Monica, Calif., and a former dancer with
the Royal Ballet of England, died on May 7 at her home in Los
Angeles. She was 68.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a brain tumor, said Jim Brunet, director of public
relations at the Westside Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Valaire, whose original surname was Feuerheerd, joined the
Royal Ballet in 1946 and performed with the company on its first
tour in the United States in 1949. She moved to Los Angeles soon
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 she began to teach at the Westside School of Ballet in
Santa Monica and became co-director of Westside Ballet with Yvonne
Mounsey, its founder. Ms. Valaire's students included Monique
Meunier and Jock Soto, principal dancers with the New York City
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Valaire was also known for reconstructions of ballet
classics. She worked with Mary Skeaping on American Ballet
Theater's 1976 production of ``The Sleeping Beauty,'' which she
also staged for several other companies in the United States and
abroad. Other reconstructions by Ms. Valaire included ``Swan
Lake,'' ``Coppelia'' and ``Les Sylphides.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Valaire's marriage to Stephen Weiss ended in divorce. She is
survived by two daughters, Claudia Petursson of Kirkland, Wash.,
and Alison Tunney of Santa Monica; a son, Andrew Weiss of Los
Angeles; a sister, Patricia Troop of London, and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
