 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, May 17:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (coded e)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-FEATURES
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-ACTORS (Los Angeles) _ Profit-starved TV networks are in a
fever to develop fall series that attract younger audiences, and
Hollywood has been suffering an acute shortage of actors and
actresses in their teens and 20s for the pilot season. By James
Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   DEGAS-NEW-ORLEANS (New Orleans) _ A Degas exhibit in New Orleans
reveals much about his extended family and the character of this
boisterous, mysterious city, which now claims the artist as one of
their own. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   REVISIONS-THEATER (New York) _ There is certainly a civil war
going on in the American musical theater. On one side is the
musical as a big costly spectacle; on the other is the musical as a
vocal and physical ritual. By Margo Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   STRAVINSKY-BALLET-REVIEW (New York) _ Two straight weeks of
Stravinsky's music is what the New York City Ballet has been
offering since Tuesday, when the company returned to its repertory
programs following the 10-day run of ``Swan Lake'' that opened its
spring season. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   MIDNIGHT-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Peter Ackerman's latest
play, ``Things You Shouldn't Say Past Midnight,'' is all about the
mindless extremes we go to in categorizing one another, by race,
age and sex, and how these labels get in the way of a good time. By
Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   WORD AND IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   KORDA-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ As Michael Korda notes in
``Another Life: A Memoir of Other People,'' his engaging memoir of
a life in publishing, the daily chores of a book editor do not make
for dramatic narrative. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   MACARTHUR-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``MacArthur,'' the four-hour
portrait that begins Monday night on PBS' ``The American
Experience,'' does justice to MacArthur's tactical abilities even
as it takes account of a political obtuseness that at times verged
on megalomania. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (coded f)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRIALS-II (Whittier, Calif.) _ Dr. Robert Fiddes' Southern
California Research Institute was one of the most corrupt research
enterprises ever discovered by law enforcement. And the abuses of
this one doctor point to weaknesses in the new system that has
developed in recent years for testing experimental drugs, which,
for thousands of private-practice doctors, has become a sideline
for making money. Part two of a two-part series. By Kurt Eichenwald
and Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHPOINT-DSL (San Francisco) _ Northpoint Communications,
which just went public, is emerging as a leader among the growing
crop of companies offering a type of high-speed Internet access
over telephone wires, known as digital subscriber line _ or DSL _
service. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MININGCO-ABOUT (Undated) _ Miningco.com is changing its name as
of Monday to About.com _ a name the company says better captures
what this newly public Internet company is all about. By Saul
Hansell.
