<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-HYPE17-COX     05-16 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-HYPE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `It's only a movie' Right!
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Star Wars'' creator George Lucas said ``The
Phantom Menace'' is ``only a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to the hundreds of people who have spent the
past six weeks camped outside movie theaters in New York and Los
Angeles to be the first to buy tickets for ``Star Wars: Episode I _
The Phantom Menace,'' which opens Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For those fans and the tens of thousands who lined up last
Wednesday in Dayton and other cities to purchase advance tickets
for the first new ``Star Wars'' film in 16 years _ along with the
45,000 who attended the Star Wars Celebration two weeks ago in
Denver and the estimated 2.2 million people who will take Wednesday
off from work to see the film _ ``The Phantom Menace'' is much more
than a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth installment in Lucas' mythic sci-fi series is a
cultural phenomenon. The highly anticipated first prequel to the
original trilogy is projected to break box office records next
weekend and gross as much as $400 million domestically.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Berger, a University of Dayton senior and president of
the UD Fantasy and Science Fiction Appreciation Club, said Lucas is
trying to be modest and cushion sky-high fan expectations by
putting the heavily hyped film in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's more than just a movie,'' said Berger, 21,
who has seen the original trilogy 15 times. ``It's the breeching
point between the generation that hadn't seen the `Star Wars'
movies on the big screen and the generation that had.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas expects a backlash, given the stellar anticipation for his
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fully aware that some fans, unfortunately, have got
themselves into a situation, both in the fact that they've gotten
much older and the film is really for young people, and the fact
that they have these amazing expectations about the film, which the
film can't possibly meet,'' he said last week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker is also aware of the so-called ``Star Wars flu.''
The Federal Bureau of Labor Statistics reported that up to 2.2
million people will take off from work Wednesday for the ``The
Phantom Menace's'' premiere, costing companies in the United States
more than $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I heard the same thing happened when `Godzilla' came
out, so I don't know what that actually means,'' Lucas said. ``I
think it has more to do with people not wanting to go to work than
just going to the movies. But I'm a little surprised at the amount
of attention the film has gotten. We have actually tried very hard
to not let the film be over-hyped, but it kind of got out of
control and got over-hyped anyway. There's not much you can do
about these things, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said the enthusiasm of people waiting in lines and
snatching up merchandise is just a spontaneous reaction from fans
who have enjoyed the ``Star Wars'' movies and want to repeat that
enjoyment. The 30 members of the UD sci-fi club all lined up for
opening-day tickets. ``There are some people who've got tickets for
every showing,'' Berger said. ``Like the 10 o'clock, the one
o'clock, the three o'clock, the five o'clock, etc., etc.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace's'' cast members are somewhat taken aback
by the hysteria surrounding the film. Natalie Portman, who plays
Queen Amidala and only saw the original ``Star Wars'' after being
offered the role, thought it was going to be just another big
action movie. ``I thought it was going to be like `Independence
Day' or one of those kinds of things that a lot of people see,''
she said. ``But I didn't realize it was going to be like the event
of the decade that people are calling it now.'' Portman said she
would have been a lot more intimidated and pressured while making
the movie had she known how much hype was going to be created
around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole culture around it is kind of fascinating and strange
to me,'' said Liam Neeson, who portrays Jedi Knight Qui-Gon Jinn.
``Not because of the quality of the films. It's something in the
psyche in all of us as human beings that we at once recognize these
incredible mythological stories that are fairy tales. And fairy
tales exist because they help to bring a very complex world into an
understandable kind of form that helps us through life. And they
seem to be, these films, successful all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The original trilogy _ ``Star Wars'' (1977), ``The Empire
Strikes Back'' (1980) and ``Return of the Jedi'' (1983) _ has
grossed almost $1.8 billion worldwide, including the 1997 reissues.
The first film opened in limited release on 50 screens, topping
``Jaws'' as the all-time box office champ six months into its
yearlong theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, ``The Phantom Menace'' will open at 12:01 a.m.
Wednesday on 5,000 screens in 2,950 theaters. Although the film is
opening in fewer locations than ``Godzilla'' (3,310 theaters) or
``The Mummy'' (3,210), industry analysts predict it will break
records for the biggest single day, weekend, five-day and
first-week box office tallies. Currently, ``The Lost World:
Jurassic Park,'' holds those records, with grosses of $26.1
million, $72.1 million, $98.8 million and $104.9 million,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if Lucas can top the $600 million domestic
gross of the reigning king of the box office, ``Titanic.'' The
director again played down the expectations, saying the film's
chances of beating the original ``Star Wars'' ($460 million) are
slim to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think it will beat `E.T.' ,'' which made $399
million, Lucas said. ``I expect it to be one of the Top 10 grossers
of all time, and if it wasn't, I would probably be very
disappointed. But it's not the end of the world. I think the film
will make its money back even if it wasn't one of the Top 10
grossers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas doesn't see it as a contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a movie,'' he said. ``I made it because I enjoy making
the movies. I hope it does well. I really don't have any interest
or desire to be No. 1 or win an Academy Award or count how many
good reviews I get as opposed to how many bad reviews I get. That's
not what it's really all about. It's about the process of making
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
