A9156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-WATSON17-COX     05-16 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-WATSON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author fills in details of `Star Wars' saga
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In a cozy house in Flamingo Park in West
Palm Beach, a woman sits applying mortar to the cracks of the Jedi
legend.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Jude Watson has been writing a series of
``Star Wars'' novels for young adults, published by
Lucasfilm/Scholastic.
</P>
<P>
   The books carry titles such as ``Jedi Apprentice,'' ``Captive to
Evil'' and ``Amidala Journal.'' ``Jedi Apprentice,'' for example,
is a prequel to the prequel _ Obi Wan Kenobi is 13 years old in
Watson's books, whereas he's about 25 in ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of freedom within the parameters,'' says
Watson. ``I can take the characters to any planet, I can give them
any adventures. But essentially the story has to be about a
13-year-old kid coming of age.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she embarked on the series that spins off ``The Phantom
Menace,'' Watson saw the script, which was little help because so
much of the impact of the ``Star Wars'' films is purely visual.
Slightly more helpful were some line drawings of the characters and
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Still not enough. So she did what a resourceful, desperate
writer is supposed to do _ she got on the Internet, checked out the
official Star Wars Web site and took a look at some stills.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's husband is a curator at the Norton Museum of Art. She
got the ``Star Wars'' job because she's been writing for 14 years,
and has published about 70 books, mostly in the young adult
category, but some historical fiction as well, written under a
variety of pseudonyms.
</P>
<P>
   Watson did a series spinning off the popular TV series ``Saved
by the Bell'' under the name Beth Cruise, chosen by her publishers
because Cruise relates to Tom Cruise, and Beth is a solid ``best
friends'' name.
</P>
<P>
   Watson works for two editors, one at Scholastic, the other at
Lucasfilm. Of the two, the one at Lucasfilm is probably the most
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my book, I had Natalie Portman's character (Queen Amidala)
be of royal lineage, but when the manuscript went in, it came right
back. They'd checked with George Lucas, and he said, `No, she grew
up on a farm.' He's got the whole thing in his head. So, you
adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Is she prepared for all ``The Phantom Menace'' hype? ``I hadn't
thought about the popularity issue until this month, as the
enormous publicity machine crawls forward. But the fun of it is the
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Books such as Watson's, essentially commissioned as marketing
spin-offs, are done on a flat-fee basis, with no royalties paid.
That's the downside; the upside is that the flat fee is generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really need an agent. The price is the price, and they
own things like foreign rights. I don't like writing for hire, but
for Lucasfilm, I'll make an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   The young adult market is increasingly difficult; now, 12- and
13-year-olds read Stephen King and Danielle Steel, just as their
parents do. The ``Star Wars'' books _ Watson has done five so far _
arrived at a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about writing for kids is the letters; they all
say, `You're my favorite writer,' or `Your books are my favorite
books.' I always answer the letters with the pseudonym I used for
the book.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so she's read the script of the new film, and she knows how
it ends. But does she know what Paul Harvey would call the rest of
the story?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I know,'' she smiles. ``Ewan McGregor ends up becoming
Alec Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
