<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KORDA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIDBITS FROM A PUBLISHING EDITOR WHO LED A CHARMED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds : Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Michael Korda notes in his engaging memoir of a life in
publishing, the daily chores of a book editor do not make for
dramatic narrative. So readers may come away without a clear notion
of exactly what Korda, the editor in chief of Simon &AMP; Schuster, has
been doing to earn his pay over the past 40 years or so, except for
poring over manuscripts for hours on end and lunching out five days
a week. Fortunately, he admits to being a born speed reader, and
the book is evidence of his talents as a lunch guest.
</P>
<P>
   Having already shown his agreeable way with an anecdote in
``Charmed Lives,'' the best seller about his famous family of
Anglo-Hungarian Jewish movie makers, Vincent, Alex and Zoltan
Korda, as well as Auntie Merle Oberon, he now turns to men with
names like Simon, Schuster, Shimkin, Schwed, Schulte and Snyder,
who helped run Simon &AMP; Schuster from its years as a cottage
industry through its many ever-expanding incarnations, carrying
along Korda with them.
</P>
<P>
   His account of the jostlings for control and the changes that
swept book publishing between the 1950s and 90s are enriched by
shrewd assessments of big players like Charles G. Bluhdorn of Gulf
&AMP; Western, who swallowed up Simon &AMP; Schuster after swallowing up
Paramount. Korda delivers a lot of information about the book
business very lightly, with diverting asides about the celebrities
he has encountered, including the likes of Harold Robbins and
Irving Wallace, Truman Capote and Tennessee Williams, Richard Nixon
and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Their appearances give the author an opportunity to display his
skills as a raconteur. Here is his quick description of Robbins,
whose novels sold in astronomical numbers in the 1950s and 60s:
``He wore a silk shirt, open to the navel, exposing a thick mat of
chest hair and several gold chains. His hairy wrists were adorned
with chunky gold bracelets and a gold watch, so that every time he
moved them he clinked and clanked.''
</P>
<P>
   Korda reports that on one occasion the novelist, who didn't like
writing but did like the money, knocked off the first half of a
novel, took a break of a few months to spend his advance in
partying, then returned to the second half, which his editor soon
discovered had little do do with the first half. When Korda offered
to stitch the parts together lest readers find themselves
perplexed, Robbins told him, in a colorful phrase, what they could
do. The book was published as written and nobody complained.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh lines abound. Korda reports this exchange between Capote
and the famous agent Irving Lazar as, with the help of their Hermes
pocket diaries and Cartier gold pencils, they tried to get together
for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Capote: ``Lunch with Jackie, cocktails with the Paleys, dinner
at the Bombolanas, you know them, Irving, surely. That's it for
Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazar: ``Lunch with the Princess Borbon y Parma, cocktails with
Marietta Tree, dinner at Lenny Bernstein's _ that's it for
Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   He also describes an eerie tour of Richard Nixon's home in New
Jersey, where, he assures us, the former president kept referring
to himself as a distant presence: ``This is the desk at which Nixon
wrote all his books.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Korda tells of his success in writing his own
books while advancing in the Simon &AMP; Schuster hierarchy. He managed
without apparent strain to accommodate himself to whoever was in
charge at the moment, even finding kind words for Richard Snyder,
who ran the company during his ascendance and whose personality and
methods of operation were not widely beloved in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   One nonadmirer of Snyder, Henry Robbins, a much respected editor
who was brought to Simon &AMP; Schuster to give the house some literary
quality, is treated with untypical roughness by the smooth Korda.
He writes, in what comes across as wry distaste, that Robbins took
himself and literature seriously and ``was inclined to confuse
them'' and tells of Robbins' throwing a soup plate at Barry Diller,
an emissary from the publisher's West Coast masters. ``I'm not
going to sit here and listen to some goddamn movie person tell us
how to publish books!'' he shouted and walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Henry, who I must reveal here was my editor for a time
at Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. Many mourned his premature death. It
seems to me what Korda portrays as a stiff-necked pretension to
guardianship of literary values was in fact a principled editorial
stance that never found much of a place at Simon &AMP; Schuster or in
the Korda career as he himself describes it. You don't become
editor in chief by throwing soup plates at the boss.
</P>
<P>
   But this is more a book about personalities than about
principles. For example, there's Tennessee Williams arriving at
Lutece late for a lunch date and ``missing the fact that there were
two or three steps in front of him, took a nosedive straight to the
floor, landing in a heap just short of our table.'' When he was
brushed down and guided to his chair, Williams said: ``Ah believe
ah'll have a vodka. Better make that a double.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
`ANOTHER LIFE &QL; 
A Memoir of Other People' &QL; 
By Michael Korda &QL; 
530 pages. Random House. $26.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
