<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER REUNITED WITH LOST TREASURE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ That trademark laugh in his voice, and his ring back on
his finger, John Carter couldn't help but state the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable!'' said Carter. ``Good stuff like this doesn't
happen to me. Other people, yeah, but not me _ it's usually the bad
stuff that happens to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the former Bruins forward who lost an eye to a freak
on-ice accident earlier in the '90s, recently was reunited with the
NCAA championship ring he lost some 13 years ago while swimming in
the Mystic Lakes that separate Arlington and Medford.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond-studded ring, a keepsake from Carter's days at RPI
and its national title in 1984-85, slipped off his hand when he was
swimming in the summer of '86. All these years later, Jim
O'Connell, a certified scuba diver for some 25 years, found it
while testing equipment this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw something sparkle in the muck, in about 30 feet of
water, and I thought, `Well, well, I've got something here,' ''
said the 40-year-old O'Connell, who grew up on the lakes and now is
a facilities manager for Genome Therapeutics, a biotech company in
Waltham. ``I'd just bought some new gear, and when I found it, my
immediate thought was, `Hey, I just paid for the gear.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Upon closer examination, however, O'Connell, only a casual
hockey fan, soon realized that the owner would be easy to find. In
near-showroom condition, the ring carried Carter's name and RPI's
record on the front. A friend of O'Connell's at work soon was in
touch with Carter's sister, and within days O'Connell was handing
the ring back to its rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in awe,'' said the 36-year-old Carter, whose story
was first reported in the Woburn Times and subsequently carried
nationally on wire services. ``I'm getting calls from all over the
country about this . . . Kansas City and Wisconsin . . . people
think it's really something. So do I. He's a good guy, giving it
back like that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell didn't ask for a reward, but Carter gave him $50.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who played for the Bruins from 1985-86 to 1990-91 and
who currently is a mental health worker at a state hospital by
night, this spring completed his first season of coaching hockey at
Nichols College. The club finished 8-15-1 (there were no rings) and
Carter hopes for improvement next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough Division 3 hockey,'' he said. ``We only had 28 kids
out last year. But we finished OK. We won five of our last six
games and it looks like we've got 65 kids who are coming out.
You're always looking for that diamond in the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they're there, as O'Connell can testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most valuable thing I've ever found, by far,'' said
O'Connell, who was diving that day with his brother, Ken. ``It's a
beautiful ring, all diamonds. I picked it up and said, `This is a
beauty, and it will pay for all this gear.' But as the hours went
on, I realized, `Well, hey, I won't get rich, but I guess I've got
a great story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No knowing officially whether Brian Sutter will be back as
Flames coach, but signs point to his return. General manager Al
Coates is on record as saying he'll recommend to the owners that
Sutter be brought back (the club holds the option) . . . The water
only grows murkier in Pittsburgh, where unresolved bankruptcy
proceedings leave the league not knowing how to proceed with
scheduling and a litany of other key issues (player contracts,
etc.). Another possible new suitor, Mark Cuban, entered the picture
a couple of weeks ago. Cuban is the founder of Broadcast.com and
grew up in suburban Pittsburgh. Former superstar Mario Lemieux
submitted a plan, endorsed by the NHL, to bankruptcy court, and
Cuban might join the Lemieux group. At least one other group,
headed by investment banker Chip Gesner, formerly of Connecticut,
could enter a bid this week. Cuban has the deep pockets preferred
by the NHL. Last month, Yahoo agreed to buy Broadcast.com for $5.7
billion, and Cuban's cut was approximately $1.2 billion. NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman said last week that there is another
buyer willing to step in and pay off all creditors _ to the tune of
some $85 million _ and move the team out of town. The mystery man?
Paul Allen, owner of the Seattle Seahawks and co-founder of
Microsoft . . . The Rangers could make offseason bids for Theo
Fleury and/or Vincent Damphousse, both of whom are unrestricted
free agents. Coach John Muckler has scouted both of them during the
playoffs. Meanwhile, Damphousse and the Sharks didn't make it out
of the first round _ they were losers to Fleury's Avalanche _ which
means the Habs must settle for a second-round pick in 2000 as
compensation for sending Damphousse to San Jose. The deal had the
Habs getting a first-rounder this year if the Sharks made it to
Round 2 . . . Abe Pollin's sale last week of the Capitals,
according to insiders, will leave Dick Patrick, the club's
president, with an 8 percent ownership interest in the ongoing
venture. If the club's final sale price (yet to be determined,
because it's part of a Capitals-Wizards-MCI Center package) is
upwards of $90 million, Patrick's stake could be worth $7 million
or more. Pollin is selling because he had too much money tied up in
the building. His accountants told him to diversify his holdings .
. . Got to love the way former Canuck Ivan Hlinka keeps his Czech
Republic squad running strong. As at the Olympics, the Czechs edged
Canada in a shootout at the World Championships and Hlinka swapped
netminders in the middle of the shootout. Now there's nerve,
bringing in a goalie who hadn't blocked a single shot for 60-plus
minutes. Hlinka, 49, also coached the Olympic squad in '98, winning
the gold medal with Dominik Hasek and Jaromir Jagr. Hlinka was
among the first Europeans to find their way to the NHL. His former
Canucks teammate and countryman, Jiri Bubla, now runs a cleaning
service in Vancouver . . . In case you're wondering, former Bruin
Rosie Ruzicka did not play for the Czechs at the Worlds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet around the Red Wings that Chris Osgood will be
in net Sunday when the Winged Wheels resume their series with the
Avalanche. The king of practical jokers, Osgood, sidelined by a
knee injury, the last few days has been lathering up phones with
Vaseline _ a real earful when Wings trainers answer their calls . .
. Voters in Arizona hit the polls Tuesday to decide whether an
aging mall on the Phoenix/Scottsdale line will be rezoned as a
stadium district, for the purposes of building the Coyotes a new
home. The referendum is expected to pass, but it no doubt would
have had more momentum behind it if the Coyotes hadn't been pushed
out of the first round by the Blues . . . Pierre Turgeon's sudden
injection of grit _ not to mention a couple of dramatic overtime
goals _ has all but guaranteed that the Blues will bring him back
for at least one more year. As the season wound down, Turgeon's
return looked doubtful, but now the Blues have virtually no choice
but to make him at least a qualifying offer (at minimum, a match of
his current $4.6 million salary) . . . Ted Leonsis, who must be
approved by the NHL as the new majority owner of the Capitals, says
he'll let kids sit in his owner's box at the MCI Center, preferring
himself to sit in the stands. A man of the people, who happens to
have about $1 billion from his America Online holdings . . . ``You
can't coach size,'' says Vancouver GM Brian Burke. With that in
mind, the Canucks last week finally came to contract terms with
6-foot-4-inch, 210-pound blue liner Bryan Allen, their No. 1 pick
(fourth overall) in last June's amateur draft. Even if Allen
doesn't make it next season, look for the Canucks to deal a
defenseman or two for help up front. The likeliest candidates:
Bryan McCabe and Adrian Aucoin . . . One big problem in the Red
Wing attack right now is the loss of Igor Larionov, who is down
with what is being called a dislocated finger (with a cast the
length of his forearm?). No Larionov means they're without their
top quarterback on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Thrashers, ready to do business this fall after
stocking their lineup in the June expansion draft in the Hub, still
haven't picked a coach _ a sure sign that the top candidate
probably was coaching in the NHL this season . . . Ted Nolan would
be a logical candidate for the Los Angeles and Atlanta openings (he
was the first to submit cover letter and resume to Kings GM Dave
Taylor). Nolan has not returned numerous messages on his home
answering machines left by the Globe and at least one other major
paper . . . Jacques Demers is considering hiring fired Kings coach
Larry Robinson, the former Montreal great, to work as an assistant
in Tampa. Demers, GM and coach of the Bolts, already has three
assistants on the job, including former Boston University star John
Cullen . . . Devils center Petr Sykora bolted overseas to play in
the World Championships when the Devils were knocked out of the
playoffs. By the time he arrived in Norway, he was too late to
practice with the Czechs, so he jumped on the ice with the Slovaks.
The next day, he helped the Czechs hammer the Slovaks, 8-2. ``I
guess that happens,'' said Czech winger Martin Rucinsky, ``when
you've got dual citizenship.'' . . . Speculation is bubbling again
that Oilers boss Glen Sather could be recruited to run either the
Sharks or Kings. It's possible, but only if Sather grows tired of
trying to remain competitive with such a tight budget in Edmonton.
His other lucrative business ventures up north, including extensive
realty holdings in Banff, also would make it difficult to leave . .
. Dominik Hasek's agent, Rich Winter, calls rumors of a Hasek trade
in the offseason an ``absolute lie.'' Added Winter, ``I know for
sure he'll retire as a Sabre.'' Hasek will pocket $15 million over
his next two seasons and the club holds an option that would pay $9
million in 2001-02.
</P>
</TEXT>
