<HEADLINE>
CREW FEELS RIGHT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The Columbus Crew took a significant step into
the future Saturday night. And they did so at the expense of the
Revolution, taking a 2-0 victory in the first match at their
soccer-specific stadium, before a festive, sellout crowd of 24,741.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica-born Jeff Cunningham consecrated the field with a
spectacular 10th-minute goal and set up Stern John for a
58th-minute header as the Crew remained in first place in the
Eastern Conference. The Revolution fell to fifth place with 7
points in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   But the main attraction on a windless, 70-degree night was the
Crew Stadium, a $28.5 million construction which was completed in
less than 10 months. Lamar Hunt, the Crew's major investor, acted
quickly to build the facility at the Ohio State Fairgrounds after
two previous initiatives failed.
</P>
<P>
   Several prospective investors and other MLS groups participated
in related activities during the week, and indicated they will try
to duplicate the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the intimate atmosphere was comparable to some European
stadia, though lacking roofing. Fans, some sitting within 8 feet of
the playing field, were involved, and some were passionate enough
to fling a couple of paper cups onto the field after a
controversial decision by referee Brian Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, this was a celebration, a tribute to Hunt, who
personally conducted tours during the week, and spent
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night polling fans about the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere was incredible,'' Revolution striker Joe-Max
Moore said. ``The field was in great condition, the dimensions are
perfect, and I'll look forward to playing here, even though the
crowd is like a 12th man for Columbus. My hat is off to Lamar Hunt.
He is a man of vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crew were emotionally charged at the start and took control
early. Columbus kept possession for the first two minutes as the
Revolution simply followed passes, becoming spectators themselves.
And the Crew capitalized as John stripped Ted Chronopoulos in the
Revolution end, and found Cunningham on the right side of the
penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham made an excellent first touch, allowing him to turn
quickly and fire into the upper far corner of the net, leaving
player-coach Walter Zenga no chance.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to awaken the Revolution, who soon began dictating
the action. Paulo Dos Santos, starting at right back in place of
Mike Burns (hamstring strain), Edwin Gorter, Ivan McKinley, and
Giovanni Savarese had the best chances to tie. Mark Dougherty saved
Dos Santos's 25th-minute, left-footed blast and, seconds later, a
close shot by Johnny Torres off a corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew went into a counterattack mode, with Jamaican
midfielder Andy Williams keying the offense. John, the MLS's
leading scorer last year with 26 goals, shot high in the ninth
minute of the second half, then headed in four minutes later to
clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it was 1-0 we started to play and we played some good
soccer,'' Gorter said. ``We had some good possessions and we were
dangerous on set pieces. But you get yourself in trouble when you
lose the ball in silly ways, and we did that more than once. They
have one or two of the quickest players in the MLS, and eventually
they are going to score if you give them those kind of chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have struggled with injuries this season and they
were missing starters Imad Baba (groin), Richard Goulooze (calf),
and Burns, and midfielder Jair entered late because of a stomach
virus. John Harkes made his Revolution debut, playing 15 minutes
after recovering from a sprained right knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   But Harkes could not rescue the Revolution, which lacked a
finishing touch despite having Moore and Savarese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
