<SLUG> BC-ROW-PENN-NORTHEASTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN MIGHTIER THAT NORTHEASTERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has been a season in which the youthful Northeastern
crew (only two seniors) has been experimenting at stroke. After a
disappointing sixth-place finish in the Eastern Sprints last week,
Northeastern coach Buzz Congram made a couple of moves in his
varsity heavyweight boat.
</P>
<P>
   First, he put last year's stroke, senior Bill Plifka, who
returned for the first time this season from a shoulder injury, in
the No. 7 seat. Then he promoted freshman Austin Eichelberger from
the novice boat to the varsity, putting him in the fourth seat.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congram's maneuverings managed only the same results.
Saturday, in the 30th annual Burk Cup on the Charles River, the
University of Pennsylvania, which finished third in last week's
Easterns, crushed Northeastern by open water, 5 minutes 54.02
seconds to 6:02. Penn (5-1) led by two-thirds of a boat in the
first 500 meters and kept it there until the 1,500-meter mark,
where the Quakers pushed it to more than a length and cruised home
to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern (2-3) hopes its experimenting at stroke is over,
with Plifka returning to his old post in two weeks for the IRA
Championships on the Cooper River in Camden, N.J. Now it's a matter
of getting better and faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little shaky,'' said Congram. ``We went with a new
lineup to see if we could get a little more horsepower in the boat.
It seemed at the sprints, we didn't have enough and it didn't quite
work out that well against Penn. In the next two weeks, before the
national championship, we'll see if we can work out a few of the
bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest NU boat, which was put together Wednesday, looked
out of synch, showing its lack of practice together. ``That's not a
lot of time and they kind of rowed that way, very rough and not
real good,'' said Congram. ``It was a gradual thing for Penn's
speed throughout. Overall, it's faster and it had a more efficient
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern wasn't smooth from the start. ``It was kind of
scrambled,'' Plifka said. ``The catches weren't there. It was a
little bit rushed. We just haven't rowed together to get a good
rhythm going. The longer we practice, the better we're going to
get.''
</P>
<P>
   For Penn, the event served as a good tuneup for the IRAs. ``We
were pleased with the race, but we've got our work cut out for us
in two weeks at the IRAs,'' said Penn coach Stan Bergman, whose
boat has five lettermen (including coxswain) from last year's team.
``We had a good start against Northeastern and that's one of the
things we've been trying to work on. We actually had a pretty good
sprint and we're trying to make a better move in the middle of the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Quakers are led by senior stroke Garrett Miller, who won the
Crash-B sprint college championships the last three years and was
second in the internationals in February at the Reggie Lewis Track.
He has been on the US national world championship team the last two
summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably our best start of the season,'' said Miller of
Saturday's race. ``We've done a lot of work on it in the past, to
the point where it's slowly becoming our strong point. Once we got
open water, you get where you can relax a lot more with our boat
picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn had to work hard to place third at the Easterns. ``We were
fifth going into the last 300 meters and we had a good sprint,''
said Bergman, whose team was fourth in the IRAs last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
