<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VOTE-930&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 WITHDRAWALS LEAVE NETANYAHU AND BARAK IN ONE-ON-ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Ehud Barak is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also ISRAEL-U.S.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a stunning turn of events, two minor party
candidates withdrew from the prime minister's race on Sunday,
paving the way for what polls predicted would be a conclusive
victory in Monday's elections for Labor Party leader Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, Yitzhak Mordechai, the Center Party leader and former
defense minister, reluctantly ended his ambitious candidacy as the
first Sephardic Jew to run for prime minister. He endorsed Barak,
and reiterated his party's central tenet: that, above all, Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, his former boss, must be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   And Benny Begin, leader of an ultra-nationalist coalition, also
pulled out of the race. A right-wing purist who felt that Netanyahu
had betrayed his supporters by turning over West Bank land to the
Palestinians, he declined to throw his support to the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   In the final hours before Monday's voting, the political ground
shifted consequentially. It turned what had been a five-way
contest, with a run-off scheduled for June 1, into a one-round
showdown between Barak, 57, and Netanyahu, 49, leader of the
conservative Likud Party. Azmi Bishara, the first Israeli Arab ever
to run for prime minister, quit the race on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Without Mordechai in the race, most polls showed Barak, a
kibbutz-born, highly decorated former general, definitively leading
the prime minister _ by as much as 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis, however, are cautious about such polls,
particularly in light of the 1996 election, when Shimon Peres, then
the Labor Party leader, was predicted to win but eventually lost by
the slimmest of margins to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   A cautious, almost dispassionate strategist, Barak has been very
hesitant to show too much optimism lest his voters grow complacent
and stay home on Monday. But on Sunday he gave a particularly
rousing speech, draping a get-out-the-vote message with a
triumphalist appeal to Israeli national pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the millions who wish to see the love of Israel re-created
among us, I say to everyone _ now,'' Barak said. ``This is the
time. We can once again unify our country.''
</P>
<P>
   For his televised appearance, Barak spoke at a campaign rally in
a plowed potato field outside Raanana, where Barak signs were
planted every few feet like crop markers. Behind him stood hundreds
of Israeli flags, well-scrubbed children on the shoulders of
smiling Israelis, and an ethnic rainbow of cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, in stark contrast, assumed the stance of a fighter,
punching his opponent even as he pleaded with defectors from his
party to return. In a televised press conference inside the prime
minister's office, he attacked Barak as an Arab sympathizer and a
leftist. He sat flanked by three of his ministers, including
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, and behind him stood several men
wearing signs taped to their shirts: ``We came home to Likud.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must ask everyone in the national camp not to repeat the
mistake made in the '92 elections,'' Netanyahu said, referring to a
split in the right wing that ensured the victory of the late
Yitzhak Rabin, the Labor Party leader at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu continued: ``We must give the left no possibility of
establishing an Arab state in the heart of Israel, on the outskirts
of Tel Aviv, which would endanger all of us here and our very
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   At Netanyahu's press conference, he was virtually heckled by the
reporters, who challenged his right to hold what amounted to a
small campaign rally in his government office. It was apparently
unprecedented here in Israel for an incumbent to mix his two roles
in such a fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai's somewhat quixotic candidacy has provided several
turning points in this campaign _ especially a television debate
last month in which Mordechai skewered the prime minister, tainting
his reputation as both unflappable and a wizard of the small
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, by bowing out, Mordechai made his greatest impact yet.
If he had continued his candidacy, which was expected to receive
about five or six percent of the vote, there would likely have been
a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   And the dynamics of the campaign would have been reborn in a
two-week, face-to-face contest between Barak and a sitting prime
minister who is believed to be a master of direct political combat.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been especially true if an expected shift
occurred in the parliamentary vote, solidifying a center-left
majority and galvanizing some swing voters to return to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   As Mordechai's standing in the polls plummeted, he spent the
last few weeks denying that he would withdraw. Sunday, ashen-faced
and with black circles under his eyes, Mordechai said grimly that
he had reached his decision in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai said he chose to pull out partly because he was scared
that Netanyahu would resort to divisive and even dangerous
electioneering tactics _ and that he would be indirectly
responsible for what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tremble and I am worried about what will happen if these
elections continue another two weeks,'' he said. ``As a responsible
man, I cannot shoulder the fear that things could end up in
bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, who was dismissed as defense minister in January by
Netanyahu, said he had been shown incontrovertible data just Sunday
morning that proved he could not ``reach the target.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he urged his supporters to switch allegiances to Barak,
he offered a somewhat tepid endorsement. He referred to Barak's
lack of political experience, and said, ``I'm familiar with his
limitations.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stiff on the public stage, loose and irreverent in private,
Barak is a former army chief of staff who advocates moving quickly
forward in the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort. He is a hawkish
dove, in the model of Rabin, but also a champion of secular
democracy in a country where religion and state are naturally
entangled.
</P>
<P>
   Hailing Mordechai's decision to quit, Barak embraced the Center
Party as an ``important part of any government we will set up after
the elections.'' Both he and Mordechai denied that any deal between
them had been struck, but it is probable that Mordechai would join
his Cabinet in a senior position.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Mordechai's supporters to be defecting mostly to
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu claimed that Mordechai's followers were tying up
his phone lines and swarming his offices, so eager were they to
switch their loyalties to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people driving here from all over the country _ we
can't even make room for them _ saying they've had enough, they're
coming home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bishara, the Israeli-Arab candidate, withdrew without
endorsing Barak, Netanyahu charged that his withdrawal from the
race was coordinated with Labor ``with the blessing and support of
Yasser Arafat,'' the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``To reach an agreement with Bishara is to reach an agreement
with anti-Zionist forces, and I think that will really be reflected
in Barak's coalition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of a bitter, divisive campaign, many Israelis cheered
Mordechai's and Begin's withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been in favor of a short campaign,'' said Natan
Sharansky, the Russian immigrant leader whose constituency
represents a swing vote now split between the two candidates.
``Political mud is not medicinal. If we can cut two weeks of
political mud, it will contribute to the health of the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
