<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant weather in the Northeast will be eroded by an
increasingly moist onshore flow. A large area of high pressure,
with a central pressure near 30.50 inches, is stationary just south
of Nova Scotia. At the same time, a weak ocean storm is drifting
northward between Cape Hatteras and Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure difference between these weather systems will
transport ocean-cooled air inland from Virginia to Cape Cod. As the
moist air is heated from below while moving inland, a deck of
clouds will form. Air ascending the east slopes of the Appalachians
will produce overcast skies from the northern Smoky Mountains to
the Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sunshine and very warm weather are likely across the
interior Northeast as breezes begin to blow from the southwest.
Readings may rise into the 80s in northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Several clusters of thunderstorms will erupt ahead of a cold
front crossing the Middle West. Hail and flooding rains are
possible in Illinois, Wisconsin and eastern Missouri. A few
powerful storms should form in southern or eastern Texas.
Thundershowers will be scattered across the Mississippi and lower
Ohio valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly sunny and very warm conditions will dominate the interior
Southeast and Florida. Active sea breezes may trigger isolated
thunder near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will mark another surge of chilly air from
the North Pacific. It will be dull, damp and cooler in most of
Washington, Oregon and western Montana. Dry weather is likely from
the western Dakotas into the central Rockies and across the
Southwest. The deserts will be rather hot.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Midnight Sun
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a week, the sun has shone all the time along the
north coast of Alaska. Last Monday marked the start of nearly three
months of continual daylight at Barrow, the northernmost point in
the state. Since then, each day has seen the midnight sun become
visible a few miles farther south. By June 21, the sun will shine
for 24 hours as far south as Kotzebue on Alaska's west coast and
the northern sections of the interior Yukon Valley. The marvelous
geometry of the earth's tilted axis of rotation adds a brilliant
dimension of continuous sunshine to these harshest climate zones in
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
