<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAELI-ELECTIONS16-C     05-16 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAELI-ELECTIONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Israeli election to be decided today among two remaining
candidates
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli election for prime minister narrowed to
just two candidates Sunday, with incumbent Benjamin Netanyahu
trailing badly in polls behind his old army commander, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates dropped from the race on the eve of today's
vote, eliminating any prospect of a June 1 run off election.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis now face a clear choice.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Netanyahu, confrontational toward Israel's Arab
neighbors and allied with Jewish fundamentalists, appears to be
outflanked by the left-wing Barak and his largely secular
followers, who favor rapid progress in the negotiations with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a 57-year-old former general and Israel's most decorated
soldier, confidently approached the end of a campaign that
commentators say is run with the discipline of a military
operation.
</P>
<P>
   At a small rally in a sunny field near Tel Aviv on Sunday, he
continued his theme of togetherness and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two ways in this country,'' Barak declared.
``Netanyahu's way, which has led to this stalemate, and our way,
which will bring change and bring unity and bring love for
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture was starkly different from a news conference held
earlier Sunday by the combative, 49-year-old Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Seated behind a table in the crowded prime minister's office, he
accused Barak of making a deal with Israel's Arab enemies in order
to win Arab votes. He also singled out members of the Israeli media
he said were biased and accused Barak of financing his campaign
with ``illegal money.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to deals he claims Barak made with the withdrawing
candidates, particularly an Arab candidate, Netanyahu said, ``This
is a very sad moment in the history of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak denied all the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite polls that shown Netanyahu trailing, he said he would
win because voters would resent Barak's maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   While polls in Israel are famously uncertain _ voters boast
about lying in surveys _ they have played a key role in this years
race. As minor candidates have seen their poll numbers slip, they
have dropped from the race hoping to help one of the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing hours of the campaign, Barak 's lead appears
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli pollster Hanoch Smith said a survey of 1,000 voters
conducted Thursday and Saturday showed Barak beating Netanyahu 54
percent to 46 percent in a one-on-one race. Other polls have had
similar figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already bigger than I can believe,'' Smith said. ``It was
expanding the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's eight point lead would be a landslide in a country known
for close elections. In 1996, for example, Netanyahu beat Shimon
Peres by less than 1 percent of the nearly 3 million cast.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's standing was bolstered by the weekend's withdrawals of
trailing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Arab candidate Azmi Bishara withdrew from the race
and his Arab supporters were expected to support Barak. Another
minor contender, extreme right-wing candidate Benny Begin, dropped
out Sunday and his voters will likely favor Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But, Barak benefited heavily Sunday from the dramatic withdrawal
and endorsement of the trusted former general Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai had been Netanyahu's defense minister before he
accused his boss of being habitually dishonest and endangering
Israel with his aggressive style.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing his poll numbers sliding and fearing political turmoil in
a country known for bitter politics, Mordechai said he wanted the
race to end in a quick Barak victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tremble and I am worried about what will happen if these
elections continue another two weeks,'' Mordechai said. ``As a
responsible man, I can not shoulder the fear that things could end
up in bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai was applauded by his supporters, even as some wept.
</P>
<P>
   (Optional cut)
</P>
<P>
   Their new Center Party claims to be a moderate alternative
between the left wing of Barak and the right wing of Netanyahu.
But, mostly, they said their goal was to oust Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was polling in single digits, if Mordechai had
remained in the race, he would likely have caused a runoff and
given Netanyahu two weeks to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Mordechai's voters had previously supported Netanyahu's
Likud Party. They abandoned the prime minister when Mordechai left
him, and pollsters predict the bulk will now vote for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu urged his former supporters to ``come home.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his office had been ``flooded'' with Mordechai voters
now coming back to Netanyahu and he produced a few such voters at
his press conference. One burly man wore notebook-sized
hand-written taped to his chest claiming, ``I'm coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   Avraham Burg, a member of the Israeli parliament in Barak's
Labor Party, told Israeli television that Netanyahu's press
conference was ``strange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's telling people to come home,'' Burg quipped. ``It's kind
of like a homeless person asking people into his living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
