<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERMIT-PROTEST-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT EASY BEING GREEN: KERMIT TAKES STAND ON COASTAL BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Miss.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's friendly, fuzzy and as green as they come. But
when Kermit the Frog joined top members of Congress to promote a
measure that might encourage offshore oil drilling, some
environmentalists were hopping mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kermit the Frog is selling out the coast? How embarrassing!''
said Richard Charter, co-chair of the National OCS Coalition, an
organization helping to shape policy on outer continental-shelf
drilling. ``I'm sure Kermit doesn't know about some of the time
bombs in this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists don't dispute that parts of the bill authored
by Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., would actually save ponds and lily
pads by redistributing oil royalties and allocating states $900
million for land and water conservation.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say there is a catch. Under Landrieu's
Conservation and Reinvestment Act, states that allow drilling near
their coast would get a bigger chunk of money to deal with the
harmful effects of oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics see that provision, called coastal impact
assistance, as an incentive that would tempt states searching for
cash to encourage more drilling and put their coastlines at risk
from a spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Kermit would like that,'' said Lori Williams,
vice president for ocean programs at the Center for Marine
Conservation, which opposes Landrieu's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club and other environmental groups are so unhappy
with the impact assistance that they switched their support and
endorsed competing legislation that does not link funding to a
state's proximity to offshore drilling.
</P>
<P>
   Kermit leaped into the political dispute Wednesday when the
internationally beloved Muppet was made available for satellite
television interviews from Washington alongside Landrieu and Sens.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, and John Breaux, D-La.;
and Reps. Billy Tauzin, R-La., and Chris John, D-La., sponsors of
the House version of the coastal measure.
</P>
<P>
   During lighthearted chats with newscasters in New Orleans,
Dallas, Tampa and other cities in Louisiana, Alabama, Mississippi,
Florida and California, Kermit and the politicians talked about the
potential environmental benefits of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Masters, a spokesman for Landrieu, conceded that some
environmental organizations have reservations about the measure,
but said a ``huge'' number of conservation advocates back it as a
way to funnel money to their causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical environmentalists see this as a great vehicle to
fully fund the Land and Water Conservation Fund,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kermit, who is said to have a home in the Mississippi
marshlands, never meant to get bogged down in a political battle,
said his handlers at the Jim Henson Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Kermit's participation, it's merely about protecting
the environment,'' said Jeff Cusson, director of domestic public
relations at the Los Angeles-based company. ``It's merely in
support of saving the wetlands.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company didn't do a lot of research about the bill
because its chief concern was raising awareness about wetlands
loss. Kermit has already been a spokesfrog for the Louisiana
Department of Natural Resources in its statewide Save the Wetlands
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists credited the bill's backers with getting
Kermit on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's actually pretty creative,'' Williams said. And
while the marine conservationist said there were flaws in the bill,
``We think there's potential there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth is a writer in the Washington bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
