</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-ACTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY TV PILOTS, SO FEW YOUTHS TO STAR IN THEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, England, Wash., Texas, Ky., Fla., Calif.)   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Robert Hutchinson had done a few television
commercials as a middle school student here, then lost interest in
acting. But he did a few more commercials recently and then,
hearing about more opportunities for young people, decided this
spring, as a 16-year-old, to try for a part in a pilot for a new
television show.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not prepared for what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   He was quickly invited to several auditions and then, with
little testing, given a leading role in a pilot for a series
focused on teen-agers for the WB network, ``Minor Threat.'' It was
one of two offers he received.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot to happen so quickly, but I think I can handle
it,'' he said. ``A lot of my friends _ girls, too _ have been doing
really well making pilots this year. I'm just taking it a step at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He was far from alone. The profit-starved television networks
are in a fever to develop fall series that attract younger
audiences that advertisers pay a premium to reach, and Hollywood
has been suffering an acute shortage of actors and actresses in
their teens and 20s for the pilot season.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Letterie, the WB casting chief, said that her company,
produced about 15 pilots focused on younger characters, and that to
cast all the parts she often had to take big leaps on untested
talent because of the intensity of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a lot more willing to take a risk now,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The networks and casting agents have been signing up
inexperienced actors, making deals with young people after a
minimum of testing and throwing previously unheard of sums at
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Shulman, a senior vice president and head of casting at
20th Century Fox Television, said actors in their late teens and
early 20s were getting roughly $20,000 an episode for a prime-time
series, compared with about $7,500 just a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just for making the pilots they are frequently being paid about
$40,000, she added, compared with no more than $10,000 a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shulman added that most casting directors have been widening
their networks of scouts to places they would not have considered
before. Ms. Shulman said she has been in touch with talent scouts
in London for the first time, as well as in Seattle, Austin,
Houston, Louisville, Orlando and Miami.Seattle, Austin, Houston,
Louisville, Orlando and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For another pilot, a drama called ``Eli's Theory,'' WB went all
the way to Australia to find Rel Hunt, who plays a 16-year-old
tough. He was in such demand, Hunt said, sounding incredulous
still, that he auditioned for three pilots a day this spring and
eventually received several offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems every second pilot is about young people here,''
Hunt said. ``I feel really lucky. It's a great time to be a
teen-ager in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Carly Pope, an 18-year-old from Vancouver who had never done
television but landed the lead in a pilot for a high school drama
called ``Popular,'' added: ``I'm still just trying to wrap my brain
around what's been going on. There's tremendous opportunity. My age
group has a kind of monopoly now.''
</P>
<P>
   Something like 110 pilots have been produced this year by the
four major broadcast networks and the two nascent ones, and perhaps
40 will make it onto the fall schedules. Most scheduling
announcements will be made this week.
</P>
<P>
   Young actors figure prominently in about 25 to 30 of the pilots,
far more than at any time in the past, television executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Money, of course, is driving this trend. Advertisers are paying
big premiums for spots on shows that appeal to younger viewers,
generally the 18- to 49-year-old group, but mostly the younger end
of that age bracket. The models for the new wave of series are
several successful shows like ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' and ``Felicity,'' all on WB.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers reportedly pay about $200,000 on average for a
30-second spot on ``Dawson's Creek.'' The same length spots on
``Nash Bridges,'' on CBS, go for about $105,000, according to
Advertising Age, even though ``Nash Bridges'' is watched by 13.4
million viewers, according to Nielsen Media Research, compared with
5.25 million viewers for ``Dawson's Creek.'' But the WB show's
viewers are, like its actors, significantly younger than those for
``Nash Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   The new youth-oriented shows frequently take place in high
schools and are about the difficulties of young people fitting in
with their peers or their families. The theme of youthful
alienation takes a literal turn in ``Roswell,'' a drama pilot for
Fox Broadcasting about teen-agers who are space aliens searching
for their origins.
</P>
<P>
   Fashions always change from season to season, as medical dramas
replace police dramas, for instance, or workplace sitcoms push
family sitcoms aside. But rarely has there been such a big
generational shift, both in the casting and content of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in one scene in a Fox high school drama called
``Get Real,'' in which an incredulous boy pointedly tells his
amazed high school chums, ``Paul Newman, that salad dressing guy,
is, like, this famous actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Savage, an agent who specializes in young actors and
actresses, said, ``It was almost a war, just a frenzy this year.''
She said she placed her clients on an extraordinary 17 pilots this
season. ``And before, when you cast the kids you had to cast the
parents,'' she added. ``But a lot of these shows are just about
teens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, the president of 20th Century Fox Television,
which produced ``Get Real,'' said his network had to drop one pilot
because it could not round up enough actors and, in one instance,
resorted to an open casting call to find fresh young faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been a limited talent pool, but this has made it
much, much worse,'' he said. ``There's too much production and not
enough talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Mossler, a senior vice president and head of casting at
Paramount Network Television, said her studio produced two youth
pilots, one for CBS and one for NBC, but had to drop a third
because it could not cast the lead parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute they walk in the door, if they're any good, you
structure a test deal because you know if you don't in five
minutes, someone else is going to offer them something,'' Ms.
Mossler said of the young actors.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of the times is that many pilots are being filmed
with young actors who have already done other pilots, a practice
called taking an actor in a second position. In other words, the
studios are taking a risk, since they can move forward with their
show only if the actor's first pilot is rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time in this business when you'd never test a
person for second position,'' said Ms. Mossler. ``Now we are
testing for second position. We will even test for third position.
These are desperate times.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the shortages worse is the fact that teen-age feature
films are also hot. Movies like ``Never Been Kissed,'' ``Varsity
Blues'' and ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' to name just a few,
have also soaked up many of the younger actors on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Cami Patton, who cast a pilot called ``Grapevine'' for CBS, said
the rush of teen-age movies had created a sort of anti-television
snobbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were kids I'd never heard of who said they wouldn't do
television, just features,'' she said. ``And the truth is, they can
get away with it. It's never been like this before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
