u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-500&AMP;ADD-     05-16 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA, A QUIETER ANGER LINGERS OVER EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Anger continued to percolate here Sunday over the NATO
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, even as both Chinese
and American officials gave signs that the height of the crisis had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Chinese newspapers all carried front-page
articles about President Clinton's Friday night phone call to
President Jiang Zemin, who had refused to accept earlier calls from
Clinton since the bombing. And on Sunday, the People's Daily
featured stories about the need to strengthen China, rather than
about American ``imperialism'' and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Li Lanqing told a visiting diplomat Sunday
that the Chinese government still firmly supported ``reform and
opening up.'' That is the catch phrase used to describe the
pro-Western, market-oriented economic policies of the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday, the U.S. ambassador to China, James
Sasser, who has worked hard at nurturing closer ties with Beijing,
said the relationship between China and the United States was not
lost and could be repaired over time. He noted that there had been
many points of contact between the countries in recent years, from
joint-venture businesses to military exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bridge is superficially still quite damaged, but it's
structurally sound,'' said Sasser, who spent four days stuck inside
the embassy here during the protests. ``There are a lot of things
that are still in place here, even though there's got to be a time
to get over things, a time of healing on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, five days after the end of angry demonstrations that
left both the U.S. and the British embassies in shambles, the roads
of the leafy embassy district were filled with the usual mix of
cars, bikes and pedicabs. The police presence was still heavy,
though, and several blocks around the damaged U.S. Embassy remained
closed.
</P>
<P>
   The official New China News Agency on Sunday pointedly wrote
about American businessmen and tourists visiting Beijing,
apparently in an attempt to emphasize that visiting Westerners
would be safe. The U.S. Embassy in Beijing will partly reopen on
Monday, although many areas will remain temporarily closed _
including its busy visa section, which was damaged by stones in the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to overstate the quiet rage directed at the U.S.
government that still burns inside many Chinese and that found
protean displays this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Two quickie books on the embassy bombing, which killed three
Chinese, are already out and have become instant best sellers.
Their titles, ``Chinese People Cannot be Pushed Around'' and
``China Cannot Be Bullied,'' give a sense of the popular mood.
</P>
<P>
   China's state-run television stations substituted old home-grown
films, or even Yugoslav war epics, for the many American movies and
sitcoms usually on China's airwaves. CCTV-5, the central
government's sports channel, replaced popular National Basketball
Association games with Filipino basketball, noting that because of
the bombings the network had pulled ``certain shows.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At one university campus, about 20 percent of students scheduled
to take the English proficiency exam required by Western companies
and American universities did not show up on Saturday, according to
the Beijing Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood seems to have shifted away from one that mixed
anger, xenophobia and a desire for revenge to a more
forward-looking impulse _ a shift that has been actively promoted
by China's leaders and the government-run press in the last two
days.
</P>
<P>
   The news media have been urging students to convert their angry
energy into hard work and study in order to build a stronger China,
and several have advocated continuing the ``road of opening up and
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night at Beijing University, where students
organized anti-American protests last week, there were still many
impromptu discussions about the meaning of the bombing and how
China should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Students say they are angry that the Western press has not
carried more about the Chinese people who died in the bombing _
newspaper and news service employees whose pictures now adorn
campus bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many students refuse to believe that the bombing was a
mistake. It is inconceivable that the world's highest-tech army
could commit such a blunder, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Most are sure that it was an intentional act by NATO or the
United States or at least some faction of the American command that
wants to see China undermined. The latest Internet ``news'' from
China is that a B-2 bomber flew straight from the United States to
bomb the Chinese Embassy, without NATO's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pure anger is increasingly tinged with pragmatism.
``I think the hatred will be deeply rooted in the young
generation's hearts _ though it is not toward the American people
but the American government and its values,'' a student at Beijing
University said this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that most students would still support the current
policy of engagement with the West, adding, ``They understand that
the reform and opening is good for them individually as well as for
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEGAS-NEW-ORLEANS-ART     05-16 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEGAS-NEW-ORLEANS-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A DEGAS SHOW, IMPRESSION OF NEW ORLEANS' TANGLED PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Charles Musson, an engineer for an oil company
here, stood in front of a portrait of a child at the New Orleans
Museum of Art, astonished. The painting, of a well-groomed
dark-eyed boy of 9, dates from 1855. The painter was Edgar Degas,
then 21. The subject was Degas' brother Rene.
</P>
<P>
   Musson, 47, is Rene's great-grandson and thus perhaps in the
most direct line of descent from the painter himself, who never
married or had children. But if the thread that connects him to art
history is slender, it is also vivid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both my daughters look exactly like him,'' Musson said. ``Same
nose, same eyes, everything.'' It might well be said that the same
oblique but penetrating relationship exists between Edgar Degas and
New Orleans, the city where his mother was born and which, despite
only a single visit by the artist, now claims him as one of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   It is a relationship underscored by the exhibition Musson was
viewing, ``Degas and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in
America,'' which presents roughly 40 of his works and is the
centerpiece of Louisiana's celebration of 300 years of French
presence here. Both by what it includes and leaves out, the show
resonates with the character of a boisterous, mysterious city where
tangled social currents can flow unnoticed for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Sex, money, politics, race. They were all roiling concerns in
Degas' extended family, whose members were the focus of his work
during his visit here in the winter of 1872-73, and who, to judge
from the paintings, he saw in a troubled light: the men engaged in
business, fending off financial calamity; the women in melancholy
isolation at home, the children in seemingly aimless play.
</P>
<P>
   But there was even more going on than Degas portrayed. Almost
spookily, one of his paintings foreshadowed disaster in his
brother's marriage, a rupture so severe that Rene's descendants
would renounce the Degas name. (Rene spelled it De Gas.) And what
Edgar didn't paint was nearly as telling; a branch of the family,
living within the city then and now but only peripherally addressed
by the museum show, was black. In subsequent years, that line of
the family had a split of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The museum ``chose to embrace one opportunity and in doing so
missed another,'' said Christopher Benfey, a cultural historian who
has written at length about New Orleans. ``It's a very interesting
show about a very interesting detour in the history of French
Impressionism. The opportunity it misses is the degree to which the
Degas visit was a complex New Orleans story involving all the
divisions within the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago a book by Benfey, ``Degas in New Orleans,'' set
the city astir by revealing that a branch of the Degas family in
this city is descended from a black woman, Constance Vivant, who
had six children with Vincent Rillieux, a brother of Degas'
maternal grandmother. One of the children, Norbert Rillieux, became
a prominent engineer responsible for advances in sugar refining.
</P>
<P>
   Benfey's book went on to point out the membership of several of
Degas' close relatives here, including Rene, in the Crescent City
White League, a fundamentally racist group bent on wresting
political power from the more diverse (if no less corrupt)
post-Civil War carpetbaggers.
</P>
<P>
   That the mix of race, family and politics at least obliquely
concerned the family at the time of Degas' visit seems
indisputable; and that the family would not know of Norbert
Rillieux, given his achievements, is unlikely. Degas himself wrote
frequently in his letters home about black people observed in the
street, black women taking care of white children.
</P>
<P>
   But with the exception of one partly obscured figure in one
painting, he didn't paint them. In his book Benfey argued there
were psychological implications to this disjunction, and he
recalled that argument in a catalog essay for the exhibition, which
runs to Aug. 29. ``In summary, the exotic for Degas hit a bit too
close to home,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond this and other catalog references the exhibition pays
scant attention to the racial context of the New Orleans paintings.
And although several Musson descendants were invited to the museum
opening and gala, no effort was made to locate and invite the
descendants of Vincent Rillieux and Constance Vivant, some still in
the city and listed in the phone book. It was not until after the
opening that their identities became known to museum officials, who
then invited them to a reception of their own, to be held later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Rillieuxes nor the Mussons knew of each other before
Benfey's book; they have still never met. And in interviews,
several Rillieuxes, all aware of their ancestor Norbert, seemed
happier to be invited in the end than they were angry to have been
excluded initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really upset,'' said Dolores Rillieux Turner, a
special education teacher. ``It bothered me in a way. I think we
should have been recognized, but not to the point where I was
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Ms. Turner said, the more pressing split in the family
was not between the Rillieuxes and the Mussons, but between the
light-skinned Rillieuxes and the dark-skinned Rillieuxes, who over
the course of generations have never reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's some story,'' said Edwina Rillieux, whose husband,
Sidney, is Dolores' brother, and who has traced the family history
as far back as Edmonde Rillieux, Norbert's younger brother. ``My
husband had white cousins who lived within walking distance of us,
and we didn't know them. My husband and his brothers and sisters
don't know too much about his daddy's side. It was a hush-up thing
in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials seemed puzzled by the suggestion they were
insensitive. The Rillieuxes were never part of the research for the
exhibit because they had no direct connection to Degas' art, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an art museum, not a history museum,'' said Sharon
Litwin, the assistant director for development. ``We focused on the
lineal descendants of Rene De Gas. We couldn't and didn't focus on
lateral parts of family and their association because they didn't
have any art.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``There's a great deal of research still to be done,
and I hope it will be done, by the appropriate institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, half of a six-figure grant from the financial
services company, Lazard Freres, that supported the exhibition went
to Dillard University, a historically black institution here, to
underwrite a summer symposium on the Afro-Creole community in New
Orleans. Michael L. Lomax, the president of Dillard, who is also a
new museum board member, was critical of the exhibition
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a long history of interracial mixture in this
city, but it's not something discussed or acknowledged very much,''
he said, speaking carefully about what he obviously considered a
delicate matter. ``So in one sense it's not unusual that the
Mussons had an Afro-Creole side of the family with descendants
alive today. And it's not unusual that it's not acknowledged. What
gives it an unreal quality now is that there's a been a book
written about it. It seems highly unusual that only part of the
story is told. In an otherwise superb exhibition, it isn't really
acceptable that the African element of the French presence here is
not acknowledged.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Degas arrived here at the end of October 1872. He was 38
and not yet famous, having only begun to explore his great
subjects: the dancers, the horse races. He came here to visit his
uncle, Michel Musson, who had rented a mansion on Esplanade Avenue.
Edgar's own brothers, Achille and Rene, had preceded him across the
ocean, and Rene had not only joined Michel's cotton business but
also married his daughter, Estelle.
</P>
<P>
   Before he returned to Paris the following March, Edgar worked on
two dozen or so pastels, drawings and paintings, 17 of which are in
the exhibition. Virtually all are indoor scenes (he was having
trouble with his eyes, which pained him in the harsh winter light),
and only one is an acknowledged masterpiece: ``A Cotton Office in
New Orleans,'' lent by the Musee des Beaux-Arts in Pau, France.
</P>
<P>
   But the portraits of unidentified invalids and particularly of
his cousins, Michel's three daughters _ Mathilde, Desiree and
especially Estelle _ show a side of Degas that has rarely been so
scrutinized. The paintings are not merely pensive; they are,
overall, very sad and created not only with intellect but also
empathy.
</P>
<P>
   Estelle, who lived until 1909, led a tragic life quite nobly.
Several of Edgar's studies of her are included in the exhibition,
the first of which dates to 1865, in France. She was in mourning
after her first husband had been killed in the Civil War, leaving
her alone and pregnant at 20. This, along with several later
paintings, shows Estelle as beautiful but grim; in two different
pictures she is portrayed in a corner, hemmed in by furniture and
competing for the viewer's attention with a vase of flowers; in
another, she is posed on a couch, off center, looking away into the
distance. She always seems to be bearing great trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estelle is the heroine of this exhibit,'' said Gail
Feigenbaum, the museum's curator of painting and the show's chief
curator.
</P>
<P>
   It was in France that Estelle and Rene fell in love, and he
brought her back to New Orleans. Shortly thereafter she lost her
eyesight; then, five years after Edgar's visit, Rene left her and
their children for a neighbor, America Durrive Olivier, who was
married herself and with whom he returned to France and had a
second family.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal split the family; Edgar and Rene did not speak for
years, and the surviving children reclaimed their mother's maiden
name, Musson, as their own. Rene's two sets of children were
reportedly unaware of each other, and when he died in 1921, the New
Orleans family sued the French family for its share of the
inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   The rift is recalled in a painting titled ``Children on a
Doorstep,'' which provides a view through the back doorway of the
house on Esplanade. It is both an eerie and eerily prescient work,
in which children are distractedly playing but none of the faces
are as cleanly etched as that of the family dog, and in which the
house visible through the door is the Oliviers'.
</P>
<P>
   The Esplanade house, where as many as 18 people were living
during Degas' visit, has been out of the family's hands since 1885.
In 1920 a real estate developer split it in two. Despite the public
attention now focused on the artist, it is a private organization,
the Edgar Degas Foundation, which receives no government or museum
funds, that is renovating the site for public view. Its founder,
David E. Villarrubia, an airline pilot, is renting upstairs
bedrooms to tourists to pay for the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The painterly gene has not traveled the generations well; few in
the family are artistically inclined. One who is, Emma Glenny, a
great-granddaughter of Rene and Estelle, lives in Baton Rouge, La.
``I'm a potter,'' she said. ``How can you be a painter in this
family?''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the slender connection endures. ``The first thing I
ever drew was a galloping horse,'' Ms. Glenny said. She was
referring to one of Degas' bronze sculptures that she grew up with
in the home of her grandfather Gaston Musson. He was the son of
Rene who, after his father's absconding, discarded the family name.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures, a set of 10 wax figures _ horses, dancers,
bathers and a woman holding a basin _ were bronzed after Degas'
death in 1917. There were three such sets, one of which was made,
at Rene's direction, for the American side of the family. Of the 10
figures, the museum has one, a small walking horse, a gift from
Gaston Musson; the rest were sold to collectors before his death in
1953. They constitute the sum total of Degas' works that devolved
to the family in America.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston's grandchildren remember playing with them and recall
that when company came, their grandfather, to show off, would flip
cigar ashes into the basin. In any case, no one in the family got
rich from the sale of the bronzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been able to authenticate this,'' said Edmund
Martin, Gaston's grandson, a retired advertising man who lives in
Lynchburg, Va., ``but I think it was for $750 each.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter from here to a friend in Paris, Degas wrote,
``Louisiana must be respected by all her children, and I am almost
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he almost remains. In the end, it seems, the artist's
legacy in New Orleans has something of the ineffable quality of New
Orleans itself. As Charles Musson remarked, looking at the portrait
of Rene but thinking of his daughters, ``I'm amazed at how we
haven't lost the look.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
