<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACARTHUR-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MACARTHUR': THE GENERAL AT THE CENTER OF THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
the New York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Douglas MacArthur, ``theater of war'' was more than just a
casual image. Throughout his often brilliant, often contentious
career, he saw himself at stage center, the protagonist of battles
against his country's enemies and his own military and civilian
superiors. With his orotund phrases (``Let no heart be faint. Let
every arm be steeled.''), selected props (the riding crop, the
battered cap, the corncob pipe) and an affection for the
first-person singular (``I shall return''), he was never the model
American general, yet for many he was an inspiring leader of
American forces through momentous decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``MacArthur,'' the four-hour portrait that begins Monday on
``The American Experience,'' tells his story from his years at West
Point at the turn of the century and his courageous service in
World War I through his early defeats and ultimate victories in
World War II to the confrontations with the White House that ended
his military career. Although far from uncritical, Austin Hoyt's
carefully balanced approach does justice to MacArthur's tactical
abilities even as it takes account of a political obtuseness that
at times verged on megalomania. Along the way are glimpses of him
as an affectionate father and something of a ladies' man, with a
mistress called Dimples.
</P>
<P>
   By the outbreak of World War II, MacArthur had already had an
eventful, controversial career. His use of force in 1932 to disband
World War I veterans who marched on Washington to demand their
bonuses brought him a worrisome reputation as an aspiring general
on a white horse. President Franklin D. Roosevelt called him one of
the most dangerous men in America.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur's main aide during his time as Army chief of staff was
Dwight D. Eisenhower, an officer of strikingly different
temperament and style. MacArthur would later deride Eisenhower as
``the best clerk I ever had,'' to which the man who became his boss
cracked back, ``I studied dramatics under MacArthur for seven
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Monday's two hours is given to the ordeal of America's
early defeats by Japan on Bataan and Corregidor. Tuesday night
brings a sharp look at military politicking as MacArthur, who led
the war against Japan, fought against giving precedence to the
European front. After fulfilling his promise to return to the
Philippines in victory, he showed new qualities in the occupation
of Japan. Although President Harry S. Truman called him in his
diary `` Prima Donna, Brass Hat, Five-Star MacArthur,'' he was
widely praised for his success in setting Japan on the road to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's two hours also cover the Chinese entrance into the
Korean War, which sent U.S. troops on a 300-mile retreat.
MacArthur, courting Truman's Republican critics, went public with
his complaints about the conduct of the war and, in a memorable
confrontation between military and civilian authority, was
dismissed. As the newsreels of cheering crowds and admiring members
of Congress confirm, his return home was triumphant. But in his try
for the 1952 Republican presidential nomination, voters showed a
strong preference for his less flashy, less unsettling sometime
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MacArthur's son, Arthur, turned away from family
tradition, did not enter West Point and went on to study
literature, opera and theater, which may be taken as a tribute to
his father, the performer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: MACARTHUR'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday and Tuesday nights at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Produced, written and directed by Austin Hoyt; directed and
co-produced by Sarah Holt; Bernice Schneider and Ms. Holt, editors.
Music by Michael Bacon. Narrated by David Ogden Stiers. ``The
American Experience'' is produced for PBS by WGBH/Boston. For ``The
American Experience'': Margaret Drain, executive producer; Mark
Samels, senior producer; David McCullough, series host.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
