<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FESTIVAL OF MYSTERIES IN NEW YORK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1841 Edgar Allan Poe wrote ``The Murders in the
Rue Morgue,'' inspired by events in New York City, thus becoming
the father of the crime fiction genre and insuring the city's place
on the literary mystery map.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend 300 scholars, academics and fans of mystery fiction
will gather at the New-York Historical Society to honor Poe and
celebrate New York's crime fiction legacy at the first New York
Festival of Mystery, called ``Murder in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a fan conference and an academic conference,'' said
Harold Augenbraum, the director of the Mercantile Library of New
York and an organizer of the festival. ``This will cross the two.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference will include symposiums on traditional authors
like Poe and S.S. Van Dine as well as contemporary writers. On
Sunday walking tours will visit sights mentioned in the fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an S.S. Van Dine story, a character takes a taxi from
Irving Place up to Grand Central Station, where the murderer is
hiding at a gate on the street,'' Augenbraum said. ``You read about
a location in a story, then you go out, and there it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the event are $75 and can be ordered through the
Mercantile Library of New York at (212) 755-6710.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVISIONS-THEATER-NYT     05-16 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVISIONS-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AN UNCIVIL WAR BETWEEN THE MUSICAL SPECTACLE AND
RITUAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is certainly a civil war going on in the
American musical theater. On one side is the musical as a big
costly spectacle, mobilized to overwhelm the audience with sets,
special effects and choreography that alternates tableaux with
frenetic aerobics. On the other is the musical as a vocal and
physical ritual, featuring human beings with personality and
sometimes even character, people with voices and bodies that
receive and transmit rhythm and melody, whether singing and dancing
or walking and talking.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the struggle between the musical score as a
generic theme park or an entity as specific as any neighborhood. Of
course there is the individual song. Is it a cobbling together of
sure-fire phrases and harmonies?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it so exact in sound and shape that wherever it goes _
into a jazz club, onto a pop chart _ you know it? This tension
between adaptability and originality is what makes a popular song
classic.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's take two shows as examples of this war, extreme in
that they share the same subject but have nothing in common when it
comes to money invested, size or quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War,'' currently on Broadway at the St. James
Theater, is a sluggish panorama meant to dramatize the war from the
viewpoint of Northerners, Southerners and slaves, with Frederick
Douglass thrown in as a tour guide, and the voice of Lincoln
sounding like that of a radio commentator. We see touching
19th-century photographs. We see strobe-lighted battles with
rolling bodies and smoking guns. We hear a score by Frank Wildhorn,
the man also responsible for ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' and ``Jekyll
and Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reunion'' had a cast of six, and a limited run in an Off
Broadway theater on Theater Row that is scheduled to close soon for
renovation. The production by Amas Musical Theater is actively
looking for new backers and a new space, both of which it richly
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   It is about the struggle of the North to mobilize politically,
militarily and emotionally, to decide, even as soldiers are dying,
just what it is fighting for and against. It has a frame that
reminds us just how obsessively _ from ``Uncle Tom's Cabin'' to
``Birth of a Nation'' to ``Gone With the Wind,'' ``Roots'' and
``Glory'' _ that we have turned our history into myth and show
business.
</P>
<P>
   The six characters in ``Reunion'' are members of a theater
troupe. Twenty-five years to the day after Lincoln was shot in
1865, they are presenting what the manager calls, with
blood-and-thunder gusto, ``A Musical Epic in Miniature ... the
story of the late war to save the Union, woven from the very words
of those engaged in that heroic struggle, bedecked with the
never-to-be-forgotten melodies of those tempest-tossed years.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is a documentary collage culled from multiple sources:
Lincoln and Douglass again, yes, but also soldiers, nurses,
journalists, slaves on the Underground Railroad, and Lincoln's
clever young secretary. Most especially there is his foe, in the
shape of an ally, the arrogant and imperial Gen. George McClellan,
who attempted his own kind of secession when he ran against Lincoln
for president in 1864.
</P>
<P>
   As for those ``never-to-be-forgotten melodies,'' they were sung
at the time, and you still know plenty of them: ``Steal Away,''
``Wasn't That a Wide River,'' ``Tenting on the Old Camp Ground,''
``Beautiful Dreamer,'' ``John Brown's Body'' and ``Battle Cry of
Freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The show could easily have become a precious little artifact, a
museum piece in miniature. Instead it became a small packed theater
of war, a series of strategic encounters of history, minstrelsy and
melodrama; of music as entertainment, catharsis and patriotic gore;
of a small band of players and a vast national enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile ``The Civil War'' joins what I consider an infamous
band of musicals like ``Titanic,'' ``Miss Saigon,'' ``The Phantom
of the Opera,'' ``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``Sunset Boulevard.''
The spectacle becomes the story, and the music is a gaudy melange
of styles borrowed from others and adaptable, with some changes in
lyrics and orchestrations, to almost any story.
</P>
<P>
   Self-importance is what unifies the elements of Wildhorn's
score. The self-importance of third-rate musical theater
declamation; of faux-humble balladeers like Garth Brooks; of
spirituals sung with an air of ``I can be dignified but I can
display Negro abandon'' (though the presence of a calypso beat at
one point was baffling), and of 1960s rock guitar solos (meant here
to convey anguish on the battlefield).
</P>
<P>
   Let us say, then, about the big Broadway musical today what
Abraham Lincoln's secretary said about the United States during the
war: ``The world has seen its iron age, its silver age, and its
golden age. This is the age of shoddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly my point isn't simply that ``Reunion'' deserves a second
chance; it is that small, inventive musicals, with period or
original scores, with fictional or nonfictional books, must have
enough time and space and money to find their audience and not only
in New York. These are the kinds of works that can and should be
seen across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most interesting ones I have seen in the last few
months are what I will call chamber musicals. There was ``Running
Man,'' produced by the Music-Theater Group in association with the
Here Arts Center in SoHo. It is a psychologically haunted family
elegy and romance, the tale of a lost son, a grieving daughter and
guilt-driven parents, with a book by the poet Cornelius Eady and a
complex, beautiful score by the jazz composer Diedre Murray. This
fall it goes to the new Prince Music Theater in Philadelphia, then
to the Brooklyn Academy of Music, followed by a national tour.
</P>
<P>
   There was ``Body of Crime II: A History of Women in Prison,''
produced at La Mama E.T.C. and, one hopes, bound for another space
soon. ``Crime'' is a puppet drama with music, and its creator,
Theodora Skipitares, is every bit as gifted and accomplished as
Julie Taymor of ``The Lion King.'' Her work is quite different
though.
</P>
<P>
   Large or small, her puppets have uncannily specific faces and
bodies, and sometimes those bodies open up to reveal even more
detailed interiors: visions of what these creatures are planning
and dreaming. She favors the documentary collage form, moving from
the Salem witchcraft trials to riots in Bedford Hills, N.Y., and
moving from rue to terror to wit.
</P>
<P>
   The score (music and lyrics) by Barry Greenhut contains some of
the smartest genre music I've heard recently: pungent and exact
renderings of 18th-century hymns, 20th-century blues and
extraterrestrial disco. (What's the difference between generic and
genre? Generic music repeats and dilutes; genre music reimagines.)
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime Broadway repeats and regurgitates whatever it
can gobble up from novels, history or movies. Look for ``Saturday
Night Fever'' this fall. Fasten your seat belts. It's going to be a
bumpy night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
