<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAWAII-BAYWATCH-ART-9     05-16 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-BAYWATCH-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPING HAWAII GRATEFUL FOR `BAYWATCH' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALEIWA, Hawaii _ The biggest economic fish caught in Hawaii
this year is not a new factory or a high-tech software startup or a
planeload of Asian tourists, whose financial troubles continue to
keep them away. The biggest fish is David Hasselhoff, the hunky
head lifeguard of ``Baywatch,'' which is to begin filming here in
July, rechristened ``Baywatch Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   To a state struggling through the seventh year of a sluggish
economy, the arrival of the ``Baywatch'' brand name _ the
syndicated show is seen in 140 countries and broadcast in three
languages in China alone _ is being heralded as a return to the
heady boom years when ``Hawaii Five-O'' and ``Magnum, P.I.''
symbolized Hawaii's international appeal and seemingly limitless
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature appropriated $1.7 million to help build a
lifeguard station that will serve as a set in this sleepy surfing
village on Oahu's north shore, and a tank for filming underwater
shots, and Gov. Benjamin Cayetano himself negotiated concessions
from the Teamsters union to cut costs. The fight to win the show,
which was prepared to leave Los Angeles for Australia, was
front-page news for days this winter, and local television news
programs kept a nightly ``Baywatch watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to help,'' said Mike Ells, as he and his young
daughter, Carly, ate a ``shave-ice,'' the delectable local version
of a snow-cone, on the back of his truck here one recent afternoon.
Ells, 49, came to Haleiwa from California 30 years ago to surf the
north shore's legendary waves, and now owns a business building
small trailers for boats and surfboards and renting electric
generators for construction. In 1990, he said, he had $2 million in
sales and 18 employees; last year, he had sales of $1.2 million and
a dozen workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generators don't rent because there's no projects to work
on,'' said Ells, who made sure he handed a prospectus offering his
services to the executive producer of ``Baywatch Hawaii,'' Gregory
Bonnan, at a town meeting one night to discuss the impact of
filming. ``I hope I can get some business out of it, that's for
sure,'' Ells said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cayetano, who narrowly won re-election to a second
four-year term last fall after battling the economic downturn for
his entire tenure, cannot suppress a slight chuckle when the
subject of ``Baywatch'' comes up in an interview. But for the
governor and his colleagues in government, who hope the show might
generate $20 million for the local economy and produce 200 jobs,
those familiar red swimsuits and bronze skin are no laughing
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Film and TV production has tripled in Hawaii since I became
governor,'' Cayetano said, and last year the Legislature passed a
bill giving special tax breaks to film and television productions
that come to Hawaii and use Hawaiian products or the state's name
in the show title. ``Hawaii has kind of overcome its image that
it's not an easy place to do business'' because of high costs and
union corruption, Cayetano said. ``It's a clean industry for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Baywatch'' deal was particularly attractive, Cayetano
said, because the show not only agreed to add ``Hawaii'' to its
name but offered a guarantee of two years' production here. ``It's
a very valuable piece of advertising for us,'' the governor said.
``We couldn't buy that kind of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Baywatch'' is still just a drop in the deep bucket of
Hawaii's enduring economic downturn, a downturn that many local
experts say portends permanent structural changes in an economy
that can no longer be expected to grow in the high single digits
each year, and that can no longer depend on tourism as the sole
engine of growth. Indeed, statewide hotel occupancy figures ticked
up just slightly for the second consecutive month in March _ after
a year of monthly declines _ but only because of an increase in
travelers from the mainland and Europe, and discounting at hotels
in Waikiki.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, local economists say, the state will be lucky to post 2
percent growth this year, and must look to diverse ``niche''
industries in fields from biotechnology to marine agriculture and
research if it is to prosper in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll never be the kind of employment engine that the visitor
industry was, or that the plantations used to be'' before the big
sugar and pineapple industries here were supplanted by lower-cost
competition from Central America and Southeast Asia, said Jack
Suyderhoud, a professor of business economics and associate dean of
the college of business at the University of Hawaii. ``But there
are some real prospects in diversified agriculture, by genetic and
seed companies that have latched onto the multiple growing season
here.''
</P>
<P>
   A larger conundrum, Suyderhoud said, is that Hawaiians have yet
to reach any real consensus as to what the future should hold in
terms of growth, and that each new proposal, whether for forestry
on the Big Island, new resorts or even film and television
production, brings an accompanying debate about its impact on the
environment and relaxed quality of life that drew many mainlanders
here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the natural inclination is for people to want the best
of both worlds, which is wealth without the negative aspects of
wealth, like congestion and crime and the need to lock the door,''
Suyderhoud said. ``We as a community have had a really difficult
time deciding what we want.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its annual session that just ended, the state Legislature was
heavily embroiled in political infighting, and the consensus view
of local critics was that it left the economy largely unaddressed,
though it did pass an excise tax cut intended to reduce the
``pyramiding'' pass-along effects of that tax on wholesalers.
Because of high transportation costs for consumer goods and fewer
economies of scale in an island chain whose total population is
just a bit over 1 million, the general rule of thumb is that
whatever costs $1 on the mainland costs $1.25 or $1.30 here.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnan, the ``Baywatch'' producer and creator, who retains his
30-year certification as a Los Angeles County lifeguard, said that
after 200 episodes shot in Santa Monica and Pacific Palisades,
Calif., it was time for a change of scene. But he said the show
could never have afforded to move here without the concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia had made a significant proposal, and there it costs
about 62 cents on the dollar,'' said Bonnan, who was here last week
doing research and announcing the casting of three local hardbodies
_ two men and a woman _ as part of the show's new ensemble. ``This
is without a doubt one of the most expensive places, but the people
have made such a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Some locals in Haleiwa, which is no more than a wide place in
the Kamehameha Highway in Oahu that curves up to the north shore,
have worried that the filming will disrupt their own surfing and
patch of paradise, especially if tour buses come rumbling up the
road to show off the location to Waikiki tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't happen,'' said Ells, who has watched the
value of his house in nearby Mokuleia skyrocket from $135,000 in
1980 to $900,000 six years later and then plunge back down to
$450,000 now. ``But I'm willing to take the chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
