<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO VOWS TO CONTINUE AIR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Double parentheses should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO officials said Sunday that weekend attacks
were directed largely against Serbian artillery and armor in south
and southeastern Kosovo. Weather hampered pilots somewhat, but NATO
officials voiced determination to continue the air war despite what
they called regrettable civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman in Brussels, told reporters on
Sunday that Saturday night's sorties took out targets in Kosovo
including six Serbian tanks. NATO aircraft ``also focused on
armored vehicles, artillery pieces, other military vehicles, troop
concentrations, and military storage and command-and-control
facilities,'' Shea said at NATO headquarters. NATO also struck at
industrial facilities, including electrical power serving iron,
steel and copper plants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air defenses were relatively light, with just two surface-to-air
missiles fired as NATO flew 539 sorties, said Maj. Gen. Walter
Jertz, a NATO officer in Brussels. The pace of the air war was
somewhat lessened by bad weather, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen, appearing on the CBS News
program ``Face the Nation,'' said that it was still unclear what
happened near the Kosovo village of Korisa, where Serbian
government officials said that more than 80 civilians died in a
NATO air raid on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have acknowledged attacking the site, saying that
the strike was directed against a military compound about 1,000
yards from the village, adding that the civilian casualties might
have been caused by Serbian commanders pressing refugees into the
area to serve as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not the Serbs moved in these refugees as human
shields is yet to be determined, but that's a very distinct
possibility,'' Cohen said. ``I think there's no level to which
((Yugoslav President Slobodan)) Milosevic and his troops won't sink
in terms of using these refugees as human shields and for other
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said he could not corroborate an interview reported by a
German radio station in which an Albanian from Kosovo claimed to
have seen refugees herded by Serb forces into the area near Korisa,
where dozens of them were killed as they slept, apparently by bombs
dropped from NATO warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But Shea said NATO believes, based on reports by Kosovar
Albanians, that civilians may be ``taken away and placed at
factories, at production plants, at airfields, at military bases,''
as so-called human shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of indications, but evidence is difficult,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also expressed concern at reports that the Yugoslav army
has been stopping refugees as they try to enter Albania from the
Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, whose government has leaned toward
the West and opposed Milosevic's tactics in Kosovo, despite being
Serbia's sole remaining partner in the Yugoslav federation that
Milosevic heads.
</P>
<P>
   On the CBS broadcast, Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, deflected questions about why Apache helicopters
sent to Albania weeks ago have not yet been deployed against
Serbian forces. The New York Times reported Sunday that the Apaches
have been withheld from action because senior Pentagon military
officers, fearing they would be too vulnerable, have resisted the
exhortations of Gen. Wesley Clark to deploy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be ready at any time that we are ready to use
them,'' Shelton said. ``Basically we will use them at a time and
place of our choosing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
