</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LIBERALS HOPE ANGER AT EMBASSY BOMBING CAN BE USED FOR
THEIR CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing to correct slug)  (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In assessing the impact of last week's nationalistic,
anti-American outburst on their cause, Chinese liberals and
political dissidents say there may be more immediate hard-line
attitudes from the country's leaders, but hope that the outburst of
activism will galvanize a generation forced to keep quiet for the
last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and the deadly
attack on China's embassy in Belgrade have caused some Chinese to
question the sincerity of American ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people will feel disillusioned about Western values, and
that will make it more difficult for people like myself who lean
toward them,'' said Yu Jie, a 26-year-old author of essays of
social criticism and a graduate student at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because they have no choice, many democracy advocates
are searching for a silver lining in the week's tumult, hoping that
political passions reawakened for the first time since the
Tiananmen Square pro-democracy demonstrations of 1989 may
eventually turn their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been said that people these days didn't care about
politics,'' said Wang Yongqing, a 57-year-old longtime dissident.
``But these events show that there is still a lot of passion about
the fate of the country,'' he said from his home in the southern
city of Hangzhou, where he and others are struggling to keep alive
the banned China Democracy Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this turns out to be a force for good or not we'll
have to wait and see,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   An anguished mix of emotions has coursed through those who
actively promote democratic values in China, ranging from liberal
scholars pushing the boundaries of tolerated discourse to the
smaller core of dissidents who court prison by posing a frontal
challenge to Communist Party rule.
</P>
<P>
   All say they shared the general anger and hurt over the bombing
of a Chinese Embassy by a supposed friend. But many also felt deep
chagrin as the patriotic fury of university students, traditional
harbingers of change here, was directed not at China's political
shortcomings but at the evils of the U.S. government, the main
champion of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   A leading liberal scholar said that ``those young faces looked
the same'' as those during the huge student-led demonstrations of
1989. He added: ``Everything looked the same: the emotions, the
clothes, the banners. Except the slogans were different.''
</P>
<P>
   This scholar, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he hoped
that Americans would not overreact to the anti-American outburst,
which he regards as shallow and stoked by propaganda. ``The
students found a target for releasing aggression that had
accumulated over 10 years,'' he said. Since the crackdown in 1989,
he said, ``students have had no place to express their voice, to
speak out on their dissatisfactions with society.''
</P>
<P>
   Another liberal, an editor who was active in the 1989 movement
who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said, ``The
demonstrations have helped train the students in street politics,
and the long-term repercussions for the government are dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversations in recent days, liberals and open dissidents
all were quick to note that the government had skillfully
manipulated public emotions through its control of the media, and
that alternate voices were suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many also acknowledged that the diet of inflammatory news
was so effective because it tapped into genuine nationalistic anger
that reflected the widely held view here that the United States
aims to prevent China from taking its rightful place as a world
power. This feeling could veer in unpredictable directions.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, political conditions were tightening this year
even before the bombing of the embassy in Belgrade. As June 4
approached _ the 10th anniversary of the smashing of the Tiananmen
Square demonstrations _ anyone known as a leader from that period,
and many of today's liberal intellectuals, were warned not to speak
with foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the fledgling China Democracy Party was nearly
extinguished as three leaders were given long prison sentences.
Sporadic arrests and trials of dissidents have continued.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the economic reforms of the last 20 years, allowing more
private enterprise and foreign contacts, have seen Chinese gain
steadily more freedom in their personal lives. They have more
access to outside information than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In private seminars and in some scholarly journals there is
lively, if carefully worded, debate about political alternatives.
It is too soon to tell whether those limited discussions may now be
curbed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, national leaders stressed that they intended to
continue China's economic opening to the West, seen as vital to
China's modernization.
</P>
<P>
   But the bombing of the embassy in Belgrade may have strengthened
hard-liners in the Communist Party and its military, who already
felt that President Jiang Zemin was too cozy with the United
States. If China takes a more aggressive and anti-American
international stance, many liberals worry about harmful fallout for
domestic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Politics at the top remains opaque to outsiders, and no clear
evidence has surfaced of a serious split in the leadership, which
even before last week did not hesitate to stamp out any open
challenges to Communist Party rule.
</P>
<P>
   In coverage of the embassy bombing, the memorial services for
the three people who were killed and other events over the last
week, the official media have featured Jiang as the resolute
national leader. He may be scrambling to avoid appearing soft on
the West, particularly if party leaders who are more prone to
confronting America abroad and clamping down at home have been
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Communist Party is mounting new attacks on
Western ideas about human rights. Sunday's issue of the popular
newspaper Beijing Youth Daily carries an essay that reads,
``Chinese will have to emancipate themselves from the modern
superstition of blindly copying the West and blindly yielding to
the values of the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
