<HEADER>
A9187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAVINSKY-BALLET-REV     05-16 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAVINSKY-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BALLET: GREEK TRILOGY OF BALLET IN A STRAVINSKY
MINI-FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two straight weeks of Stravinsky's music is not what you
encounter in concert halls nowadays. But that is what the New York
City Ballet has been offering since Tuesday, when the company
returned to its repertory programs following the 10-day run of
``Swan Lake'' that opened its spring season.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the City Ballet 50th-anniversary celebration
has been divided into mini-festivals. The one devoted to
Stravinsky, which ends at the New York State Theater on May 23,
opened with the so-called Greek trilogy of Balanchine-Stravinsky
ballets: ``Apollo'' (1928), ``Orpheus'' (1948) and ``Agon'' (1957).
Stravinsky wrote the last two scores for George Balanchine. The
score of ``Apollo'' was commissioned by the Library of Congress and
originally choreographed by Adolph Bolm with a cast that featured
Gene Kelly's ballet teacher, Berenice Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   The version that Balanchine rechoreographed for Diaghilev's
Ballets Russes was whittled down over the years by Balanchine
himself at City Ballet. Whether the dancers can make sense of this
reductive staging is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   How it is danced is more important than what it says. Nikolaj
Hubbe, magnificent in his vigor and virility as Apollo, understood
this perfectly. The muses were all more awake than last fall.
Pascale van Kipnis as Calliope had power and grand gesture. Jennie
Somogyi as Polyhymnia was superb in her spring and perfect pique
turns into arabesque. Yvonne Borree as Terpsichore overcame some
prissiness to capture the seductive playfulness of her role. Hugo
Fiorato gave the limpid score some needed verve in his conducting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orpheus'' also has a vestige of a narrative pretext. It is a
difficult work, more lyrical drama than conventional ballet. Few
dancers can master its moments of stillness and significant
gesture. But this time proved exceptional, with Nilas Martins in
full command of the title role.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was there in his performance: Orpheus' poignant grief
over the death of Eurydice, the spellbound demeanor in his voyage
to Hades, the struggle of a masked Orpheus as he gropes to find a
Eurydice that he is not allowed to see. Helene Alexopoulos was
splendid, sensual and clinging to her partner in the celebrated
convoluted duet. Charles Askegard was rightly taut in his debut as
Orpheus' guide, the Dark Angel.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine and Stravinsky discarded storytelling in ``Agon,''
whose title is the Greek word for contest. Instead they created a
mythological world of the future. With its complex structures in
music and dance, ``Agon'' is still one of the company's most
avant-garde ballets. Monique Meunier and Jock Soto were sturdy
rather than electric in the acrobatic pas de deux, nonetheless
creating all the right astounding shapes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
