A9189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-EDUCATION-COX     05-16 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE OFFERS TEACHERS CARROT AND STICK
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Teachers should get more money and be held to
higher standards, Vice President Al Gore said Sunday in what was
billed as the first major policy address of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should treat teachers like professionals, we should pay
them like professionals, and we should hold them to high
professional standards,'' Gore said in a commencement speech at
Graceland College, a Mormon-founded
</P>
<P>
   The financial incentives would include $10,000 hiring bonuses
and higher pay. The higher standards would be imposed through
tougher licensing tests and weaker tenure protection.
</P>
<P>
   The new teacher policies were at the heart of his long education
agenda. Its two dozen points included suggestions that states offer
voluntary pre-school programs for every child, and that parents,
teachers and students be required to sign a disciplinary pledge on
the opening day of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of these proposals will be fully paid for within a
balanced budget,'' Gore said, though he did not estimate what they
would cost.
</P>
<P>
   His blueprint was far more detailed than that of his only
visible challenger for the Democratic nomination, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey. Bradley has said he will offer specifics of
his own education program in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the hiring bonuses would go to older people who switch
to the teaching profession and to young people who join a new
``21st Century Teacher Corps,'' and teach for four years in ``a
school that needs your help.'' Today, that school would probably be
in either an inner city or rural area, where recruiting qualified
new teachers is most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher unions that have backed Gore in the past already favor
better pay and bonuses as well as tougher licensing tests. But they
have offered only tepid support for programs that weed out weak
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Many other items on Gore's long list of proposals repeated or
extended suggestions that President Clinton has sent to Congress
for approval this year. For example, Clinton wants the average
class size in early grades limited to 18. Gore said he would reduce
class size in higher grades to 20.
</P>
<P>
   One completely new proposal was Gore's suggestion for creating a
new volunteer army of tutors and mentors who would help children
on-line, rather than in person.
</P>
<P>
   However, the vast bulk of Gore's proposals have been tested by
reform-minded officials ranging from Richard Daley, the Democratic
mayor of Chicago, to two Republican presidential hopefuls, former
Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee and Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gore endorsed efforts to make schools ``gun free,
drug free, safe and secure,'' encourage adults to volunteer as
mentors, run after-school and summer-school programs, stress
``civic'' and ``character'' education, and use tests to prod
schools toward efforts to narrow the gap between whites and other
students in drop-out rates and scholastic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike Alexander, publishing heir Steve Forbes of New
Jersey and several other GOP candidates, Gore opposes the use of
tax-paid vouchers for students in private elementary and secondary
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander scoffed at Gore's proposals as so detailed that they
amounted to proposing creation of a ``national school board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants teachers whose qualifications would be set in
Washington,'' Alexander told Reuters news service in an interview.
``It's a question of who knows what's best - Washington or the
local school boards, teachers and parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, spokesman for GOP presidential candidate
Elizabeth Dole, said, ``She will look at the vice president's
positions, but she won't comment on them in a partisan or negative
way. She doesn't think education should be a partisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
