<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      05-16 0050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 Sunday, May 16, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Editors:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (NASHUA, NH) _ A story will move at 9 p.m. CDT,
Sunday. By CRAGG HINES. Questions, call Jake Doherty at
713-220-7674.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WISDOM-2NDTAKE-N     05-16 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WISDOM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Saul Stone.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wisdom practiced law in New Orleans throughout the 1930s, and
then joined the Army Air Corps in World War II, serving in the
Office of Legal Procurement. He was discharged with the rank of
lieutenant colonel.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his early legal work dealt with business law. He
strongly opposed so-called fair-trade laws, legislation that
permitted manufacturers to set the retail prices of their products,
ostensibly to protect small retailers from competition from big
discounters. He told those attending the American Fair Trade
Council meeting in New York in 1953 that they could ``never sell
the American citizen on the justice or logic'' of fair trade.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom, a long-time Republican loyalist who served in the 1950s
as a national committeeman from Louisiana, worked hard to open
doors to the Republican Party in the South. In 1952 he broke with
the more traditional Southern Republicans, who strongly supported
the candidacy of the conservative Sen. Robert Taft of Ohio for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that year, he and Eldred P. Tuttle, a lawyer in Atlanta,
had met at the request of Herbert Brownell, Eisenhower's campaign
manager, to organize a campaign in the South to support Eisenhower
for the Republican nomination against Taft. Wisdom and Tuttle
became co-chairmen of the Southern Conference for Eisenhower, and
each led pro-Eisenhower delegations that won contested fights for
credentials at the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general in the Eisenhower administration, Brownell
became an important figure in selecting federal judges, and both
Tuttle and Wisdom were eventually put on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest civil rights cases Wisdom received after his
appointment came in 1959, when the 5th Circuit voided a Louisiana
ban on boxing matches between blacks and whites. The court's
decision was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 he dissented from the 5th Circuit's majority opinion,
which upheld the tradition of revealing the race of all candidates
for public office on the ballot. The Supreme Court ultimately
repudiated the majority decision and upheld his position.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the 5th Circuit's ground-breaking decisions
concerning discrimination were made in the 1960s, there were many
significant cases in the 1970s. Among them was a 1972 decision
striking down a Louisiana law barring biracial adoptions. ``It is
obvious,'' Wisdom wrote in the decision, ``that the Louisiana
statute making race a decisive factor in adoption subordinates a
child's best interest in some circumstances to racial
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom wrote several landmark opinions in employment
discrimination cases. In 1979, the Supreme Court adopted the basic
reasoning of his dissent in Weber vs. Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical
Corp. to uphold a hiring plan intended to overcome the effects of
past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Not all his major decisions concerned race. In 1974, he wrote an
opinion that found that psychiatric patients as a class had a
federal constitutional right to adequate treatment when such
patients were committed against their will to state institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But to the end he felt that no opinion drew more fully on his
intellect and imagination than U.S. vs. Jefferson, which took
almost a year to formulate.
</P>
<P>
   By requiring ``the organized undoing of the effects of past
desegregation,'' he placed an affirmative duty on school boards to
develop desegregation plans. Including a model school desegregation
order, he served notice that ``the only school desegregation plan
that meets constitutional standards is one that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge J. Harvie Wilkinson of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals wrote in a 1979 book, ``The Supreme Court from Brown to
Bakke,'' that Wisdom in ``Jefferson'' and related cases
``transformed the face of school desegregation law.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the storms that attended his civil rights decisions, he
attained such stature that in 1969, he was mentioned as a leading
candidate for the U.S. Supreme Court. Moderate Republicans advanced
his name after the Senate rejected President Richard M. Nixon's
nomination of Judge Clement F. Haynsworth, a candidate Wisdom
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon's attorney general, John Mitchell, scuttled the idea,
reportedly complaining that Wisdom was nothing more than a ``damn
left-winger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom once told a reporter in the 1960s, when the 5th Circuit
was issuing its most contentious rulings, his dogs were poisoned
and a rattlesnake was thrown in his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the liberal views about race and civil rights, he
maintained memberships in private clubs and Mardi Gras krewes that
discriminated against blacks and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I see in these clubs are the guys I went to school
with and have known all my life,'' he said. ``I would not resign
from any such club.'' He said, ``They know how I stand on these
matters'' and ``I certainly wouldn't change their views by getting
out of the club.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Bonnie Mathews Wisdom, and two
daughters, Kathleen Mathews Wisdom and Penelope Stewart Wisdom
Tose. A son, John Minor Wisdom Jr., died.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when he was 89, the 5th Circuit building in New Orleans
was named for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
