<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-490&AMP;ADD-N     05-16 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNOFFICIALLY, WHITE HOUSE SUPPORTS BARAK VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With ISRAEL-VOTE)  
(js) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clinton administration has maintained a
studied public neutrality in the Israeli campaign for prime
minister. But it has made little effort to conceal its interest in
a victory for Ehud Barak, the Labor Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Burned by his all-but-open endorsement of Shimon Peres, the
Labor candidate in the 1996 Israeli election, President Clinton has
said nothing in public about the contest between the incumbent
prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu of the Likud Party, and his
chief challenger, Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But there is scant doubt in Washington or in Israel about
Clinton's preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially,'' one senior White House official said, ``our
position is that Israel is a sovereign country, we don't meddle in
its internal affairs, blah, blah, blah. We're not messing around _
not that I'm aware of. But we're not completely dispassionate, I
won't kid you.''
</P>
<P>
   As the election turned into a two-way race in its closing days,
Clinton's advisers were increasingly optimistic that Labor's
candidate would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt now that it will be decided tomorrow and
little doubt about the outcome,'' one senior administration
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded pleased at the thought that Barak might win outright,
without the need for a runoff in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no affection between Clinton and Netanyahu,
who won three years ago despite _ perhaps in part because of _
Clinton's obvious tilt toward Peres. The Labor candidate was the
political heir of the slain Yitzhak Rabin, whom Clinton idolized.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared with Peres in Israel and in the United
States during the campaign and repeated Labor Party electoral
slogans almost verbatim, an act of interference that offended many
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   So this spring, the White House has given no obvious signal of
its desire for victory by Barak, who is seen in Washington as more
likely than Netanyahu to reach accommodation with the Palestinians.
That goal is much desired by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of voting takes place Monday, with Barak holding
an edge in most polls.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of Clinton's pro-Barak leanings are subtle but
unmistakable. The president has held several well-publicized
meetings with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, over the past
five months, designed to dramatize the White House's commitment to
rapid progress on the Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said that moderate voters in Israel
were worried about the state of relations between the United States
and Israel, which have deteriorated during Netanyahu's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the administration has been sending signals to
those voters that things would improve if Barak were elected.
``Dropping obvious hints has clearly had an impact in Israel and
the polling shows that,'' the official said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton sent a letter to Arafat last month containing the
American government's strongest endorsement yet of an eventual
Palestinian state on land once occupied by Israel. He also urged
quick resumption of stalled peace talks between the Israelis and
the Palestinians, a course that Netanyahu has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, administration officials said, is to strengthen Arafat
in his struggle against Palestinian extremists and to position him
for the restart of negotiations with what the White House hopes is
a new government in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has often expressed frustration with
Netanyahu's slow approach to carrying out agreements reached at the
Wye Plantation in Maryland last October under Clinton's direction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at a White House event honoring the late Rabin earlier
this year, proclaimed in Hebrew, ``We need friends of peace.'' It
appeared to be a clear endorsement of the approach the Labor party
and other liberal blocs in Israel take to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three political consultants close to Clinton are
advising Barak, writing advertisements, plotting strategy and
taking polls. The three advisers _ James Carville, Robert Shrum and
Stanley Greenberg _ were instrumental in Clinton's 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carville said in an interview that Clinton did not approve his
work for Barak in advance, but that Carville regularly briefs the
president on the progress of the Labor leader's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for aggressive neutrality'' by the White House,
Carville said, speaking by telephone from the Labor Party ``war
room'' in Tel Aviv. ``As for the president, well, all politicians
have personal preferences, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   One administration official involved in Middle East policy said
that the White House has been consciously avoiding the error of
1996, when the tilt toward Peres may have backfired and helped
bring about the election of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus this time is not on personalities but on the peace
process,'' he said. ``We're emphasizing the sense of Israel's and
the United States' long-term security interests.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``It's clear what we would like to see
prevail. We've been quite subtle about it, but no one has
misunderstood what we were saying. It was clear from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution and director of Middle East affairs at the
national security council in the Bush administration, said the
Clinton White House had learned a lesson from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've been careful essentially to keep their heads
down,'' Haass said. ``They tilted heavily the last time toward
Shimon Peres and it clearly didn't help. They realize it would be
counterproductive to make the same mistake as last time. They don't
want to give Mr. Netanyahu the argument that only he can stand up
to U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' he added, ``the administration has gone into a
crouch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
