<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-L.A.-TIMES-MEDIA-ART-     05-16 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-TIMES-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORTS TO REINVENT THE LOS ANGELES TIMES FALTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mark Willes, the chairman and chief executive of
Times Mirror Co., began a corporate meeting last September by
asking dozens of his top lieutenants how they felt about the
company's financial goals. As he watched the results tallied on an
overhead projector, his easy smile faded.
</P>
<P>
   Using a five-point scale _ five for very optimistic, one for
very pessimistic _ the tally showed a lot of threes and fours.
Times Mirror's executives were dubious about the company's ability
to achieve its aims. A major reason, participants said, was the
lackluster performance of The Los Angeles Times, the engine that
generates 40 percent of corporate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   At a later session, executives of other Times Mirror newspapers
wondered out loud how the company could increase revenue 5 percent
annually and profits 10 percent annually if The Times could not
match that performance.
</P>
<P>
   Willes, a former senior executive of General Mills who strode
out of the cereal business into the newspaper industry four years
ago, cutting costs, closing New York Newsday and attaching rocket
boosters to Times Mirror's stock price, has always made journalists
nervous. His revolutionary talk of reinventing the business raised
the specter that profit motives would endanger the integrity of
their work.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears have largely subsided. These days, the questions
focus on the business decisions Willes has made since he appointed
himself publisher of The Los Angeles Times 18 months ago. Even by
Willes' lights, his campaign to reinvigorate the flagship newspaper
is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of that trouble abound. Circulation growth has been the
prime directive of the Willes era, and daily circulation has grown
by 40,000, to 1.1 million, since Willes joined Times Mirror. But in
the last year circulation was flat and in April it declined.
Profits in 1998 were supposed to increase by 3.6 percent; instead,
they dropped about 15 percent, to about $165 million, according to
two people with access to the company's budget summaries.
</P>
<P>
   His widely debated system giving each newspaper section a
general manager or minipublisher to facilitate business and
editorial cooperation is in shambles. Meanwhile, two-thirds of The
Times' senior executives have raced, or been pushed, out the door
and most of their replacements are new to Los Angeles or new to the
newspaper business.
</P>
<P>
   Willes' frustration is evident, though his faith in his vision,
including the audacious goal of selling 500,000 more copies, for a
total of more than 1.5 million, has not waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we said 18 months ago was we've got to reinvent this very
large, very complicated newspaper,'' Willes said in an interview.
``There is going to be a large amount of change and breakage in the
process.'' But, he said, he is confident that the management team
now in place will be able to move the business in the right
direction. He has taken to reprising his old theme song: Businesses
that don't grow will die.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the agony we're going through,'' he said, ``is because
we're determined to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The year's events shook his faith in some subordinates, and
theirs in him. Kevin Gruneich, an analyst at Bear, Stearns, said:
``There is no reason why things can't work, and with Mark taking
over the publisher's role at The Los Angeles Times, they should
work. The strategy has been fine. The execution has not.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it is unusual for a radical change in business vision
to cause equally radical personnel shifts, which can disrupt the
business. The Times also was not a problem-free institution when
Willes arrived at Times Mirror in 1995; for several years its
executives had groped to reconcile a variety of business strategies
while struggling through harsh economic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the city of Los Angeles and the newspaper had been
undergoing a slow-motion nervous breakdown,'' said Steve Wasserman,
the book editor of The Times. ``The shattering of the defense
economy, the collapse of the retail economy, the 1992 riots, these
were body blows to Los Angeles' sense of itself. And the newspaper
has seen that many of the things it took for granted are up for
grabs. The demographics of its audience have changed enormously.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's financial performance did improve in 1996 after
several years in the doldrums; in 1997, the year Willes added the
publisher's title to his business card, the newspaper's profits
soared.
</P>
<P>
   As publisher, Willes has made a number of visible moves. He
added 11 new business journalists and gave their section 200 more
pages of space a year. Competitors say the improvement is
noticeable; a month ago, two Times reporters won a Pulitzer Prize
for coverage of the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Local news coverage has been reshaped to win readers. The Times
cut its regional reporting staff and put its emphasis on a dozen
new ``Our Times'' newspapers, which give local communities, from
Yorba Linda in the south to Ojai in the north, everything from high
school sports scores to neighborhood crime reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Times also created a new health section and a separate
Hispanic news desk, with 13 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Willes ticks off these initiatives with studied satisfaction.
But, he adds, ``If we were to find out how many additional readers
we've had because of this very expensive effort with the Latino
desk, I could probably count it on these fingers,'' as he held up
both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Some Times executives, dissatisfied with Willes' predecessors,
welcomed his fresh approach and optimism. But some of these same
managers are now gone. The pace of the exodus has quickened
recently; heads around the industry turned in late February when
Jaynie Studenmund, a banking executive who started work as a senior
vice president on Jan. 11, left after six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All Ms. Studenmund would say was: ``This was a gut-wrenching
decision in large part because I do like and respect so many people
at The Los Angeles Times. And I do happen to like and respect Mark
Willes tremendously. But I concluded for me personally it was not a
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven others of more than 15 managers who have left recently
were willing to discuss their experience at The Times on condition
that they not be identified. Their most common criticism was that
management operated in a helter-skelter, ad hoc manner, with serial
strategies that produced one exhausting experiment after another.
</P>
<P>
   The most ballyhooed management change, one that sent a shiver
around many newsrooms, was the creation of general managers for
news and feature sections. The fear was that the general managers,
dealing with both editors and advertising executives, would have a
pernicious influence on journalism. Less noticed were worries in
the advertising department that sections would cannibalize one
another's ads.
</P>
<P>
   Neither happened _ possibly because the general managers found
themselves without influence, and now the ranks of the general
managers are turning over as fast as those of the senior vice
presidents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of turnover,'' acknowledged Leo Wolinsky,
one of The Times' four managing editors. ``I suppose one could
argue that every organization making a radical change goes through
this before settling down with the right team. But it's going on
all the time. And new people are coming in who have to learn what
the old people knew already. It's hard to get a head of steam up.''
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the issue was: What does a general manager do? As
one former general manager explained, ``In terms of controlling
revenues, the ad department reported somewhere else, not to us. How
can you be responsible for a profit-and-loss statement when you
don't control any levers?''
</P>
<P>
   Willes' new second-in-command, Kathryn Downing, 45, who had
earlier run the Times Mirror legal publishing division, agrees with
the criticism. ``We should have spent more time up front deciding
what their role was,'' she said of the general managers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said, the lines of authority were unclear. Now James
Helin, a new senior vice president and chief marketing officer,
will supervise them. Advertising department strategies are being
developed by John McKeon, another new senior vice president, who
worked for two decades at Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   The circulation department had different problems. By one former
executive's account, 1998 began with directives to grow at any
cost, which were supplanted by directives to grow but cut costs
ever more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Willes and Ms. Downing said, the expensive direct-marketing
strategy _ telephone calling and door-knocking that pulled
potential customers from their dinner tables _ is being curtailed.
Subscribers who buy under those circumstances are less likely to
renew. More than 90 percent of new subscribers fail to renew,
forcing the sales staff to replace them just to keep circulation
figures stable.
</P>
<P>
   One new circulation strategy is joint distribution with
immigrants' newspapers like La Opinion, which The Times partly
owns, and Korea Times, the United States' largest Korean-language
newspaper, which started distributing The Times to some of its
20,000 Sunday readers a few weeks ago. But the net effect on
overall circulation is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the experimentation and executive churn contributed
to the newspaper's 1998 disappointing financial results would be
difficult, but it did not help. Still, the newspaper's operating
profit margin was 15 percent _ down from 18 percent in 1997, but
hardly embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of Times Mirror stock was well below the
industry average in 1998, according to an index of newspaper stocks
developed by Bear, Stearns, but this year it is doing slightly
better than the industry average. The stock price closed down 18.75
cents on Friday, at $58.875.
</P>
<P>
   As high-margin help-wanted advertising leached away in 1998, ad
revenues fell well behind projections, ending the year at $881
million, $20 million less than projected, according to the two
people with access to budget summaries.
</P>
<P>
   This eventually led to cuts in news space in the newspaper. The
editorial department has lost about 3 percent of the space it had
in 1998, according to Michael Parks, the editor of The Times. The
front section and the metropolitan news section have been among the
most affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some respects it's made us make better choices, but in
other respects it does pinch,'' Parks said. ``When we need the
space we go and get it for major stories. Where it pinches is on
daily coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that the newspaper was unable to account for
about 3,000 tons of newsprint, forcing the company to take a loss
of about $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The financial disappointments came as regional competition from
newspapers sprinkled around The Times' large circulation area
intensified. And for the third time in a decade, The Times is
trying out a new local news strategy, relying on 12 new small local
``Our Times'' newspapers, published by a Times subsidiary and
distributed with The Times in specific communities, to win reader
loyalty for their big sister.
</P>
<P>
   The bet is that this hyperlocal approach will attract more
readers than the broader regional coverage. At the same time, the
staffs at regional editions in Ventura County and the San Fernando
Valley have been trimmed. These regional editions are edited as
separate daily versions of The Times with particular emphasis given
to news of regional interest, such as scores of area sports teams
and the woes of county governments.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Valley Edition's newsroom staff dropped from 111
full-time staffers and seven part-timers to 84 full-time
journalists. The Ventura Edition went from 32 to 29 full-time
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   As for the grandfather of the regional editions, the 34-year-old
Orange County edition, which competes with the dominant Orange
County Register for the area's wealthier readers, Willes said, ``I
don't honestly know what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``What we're doing now is not working as well as it
needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   In reshaping the local coverage, the newspaper has also created
a two-tier salary system, with less experienced ``Our Times''
starting reporters paid $450 a week, less than half the starting
salary of a Times reporter. In some areas of Orange County, like
Brea and Laguna Hills, the Our Times editorial material is merged
with The Times metropolitan news section.
</P>
<P>
   While The Times' overall daily circulation increased by just 0.3
percent in the six months ended March 31, circulation in Ventura
County, which has three ``Our Times'' sections, grew by 3 percent,
according to Robert Magnuson, a senior vice president for the
regions at The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Willes is optimistic when he talks about such a harbinger of
circulation success. But his tone sometimes grows grim, when he
alludes to dire alternatives. In the Times Mirror 1998 annual
report, Willes was paraphrased as saying that if expectations of
growth proved unfounded, ``the result would mean dismantling the
company.'' In a recent interview, he said that the reference was
just a variant of the grow-or-die theme, nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``My frustration,' he said in a separate interview, ``has come
from not doing everything we could do to try things that have been
successful in other businesses. If we've tried all these things and
in four years they haven't worked, then they can say Mark Willes
did some damage before he left. But we haven't tried them yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
