<HEADLINE>
BLUES WANT TRAFFIC IN FRONT OF BELFOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Most of us spend our lives trying to avoid traffic.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues will spend tonight's game desperately trying
to create it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get more traffic in front of \RStars goalie\S Eddie
Belfour,'' Blues defenseman Al MacInnis said. ``We have to cause
more traffic and hope for some deflections and rebounds and bang
away. He's seeing the puck really well, and we have to do something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock called Belfour ``excellent'' after a
Game 5 performance in which he stopped 30 of the 31 shots he faced.
The Blues felt like they were getting a good number of good first
chances.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, they said, was they weren't getting very many
second chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just weren't any loose pucks, and we weren't there for
the rebounds,'' Blues defenseman Chris Pronger said. First and
foremost In this second-round series against the Stars, the Blues
have at times been better, been quicker, been faster.
</P>
<P>
   They have yet to be first.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five games of the series, St. Louis hasn't scored
the first goal. The Stars scored first in Game 5, a shorthanded
goal by winger Jere Lehtinen at 3:47.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dig ourselves a hole,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said.
``I mean every game we've given up the first goal, and shorthanded
goals are not the fun ones to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues scored first in four of their seven first-round games
against Phoenix. They were 2-2 in those games. Second helpings The
Blues might not start off well, but they sure can rebound. For the
fifth consecutive game, they dominated the second period.
</P>
<P>
   In Games 3 and 4, it was enough to get the Blues the victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5, it wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis outshot Dallas 12-5 in the second period of Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues have outscored the Stars, 7-4, in the second period.
But the Stars have outscored the Blues, 6-1, in the first period
and 3-2 in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew what the difference was,'' Pierre Turgeon said.
``Every game it seems like we are behind early.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
