<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little resolved as claims of racism mar Jefferson group meeting
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ Four women who claim kinship to Thomas
Jefferson and his slave, Sally Hemings, sought Sunday amid a
rancorous debate to join an all-white association that owns
Jefferson's graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Westerinen, a descendant of one of Hemings' sons, Eston,
said she is doubtful that the Monticello Association will extend an
invitation to her. That's despite recent DNA evidence suggesting
that Jefferson was Eston Hemings' father.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want them to say to my face that they do not want me,'' said
Westerinen, seeking admission along with her mother, Dorothy
Westerinen, Michelle Cooley-Quille and Shay Banks-Young.
</P>
<P>
   The association's 86th annual meeting adjourned without any
resolution in the centuries-old dispute over whether America's
third president fathered any of Hemings' seven children. But the
three-hour closed-door meeting did produce bickering that spilled
into the lobby of the Jefferson ballroom of the Omni hotel in
downtown Charlottesville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Only association members can be buried in the Monticello
Graveyard. Over the next year, the 700 members face the decision
whether to recognize Hemings' descendents, though most lack
genealogical evidence to prove a link to Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Association member Theresa Shackleford said she supports the
group's decision to assess further genealogical and historical
evidence of Jefferson's four-decade relationship with Hemings after
Jefferson's wife, Martha, died in 1782.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not racist; we are snobs,'' Shackleford said. ''I am
for any lineal descendent of Thomas Jefferson be they black, white
or purple being buried in the graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They never hired a genealogist on me,'' countered Lucian
Truscott IV, 52, a Los Angeles screenwriter who has belonged to the
association since he was a child. Last fall on national TV, he
invited three dozen black ''cousins'' to attend this weekend's
Jefferson family gathering as his guests.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's meeting, some members sought to reiterate that last
fall's DNA evidence was inconclusive, despite lead scientist Eugene
Foster's conclusion that ''Thomas Jefferson was the most likely
person to have fathered Eston Hemings.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some people who find it very hard to believe that
Thomas Jefferson fathered any of Sally Hemings' children,'' Foster
said afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon, association members were openly disputing
Truscott's allegations of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott urged the association to invite Hemings' ancestors to
join as nonvoting honorary members until admission guidelines were
set. Association President Robert Gillespie rejected the suggestion
and, later, he denied he was snubbing Hemings' kin.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said the association's executive committee _ not
members at large _ is responsible for nominating honorary members.
''The committee met yesterday,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
