<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS KITCHEN, GLUNKING, SHOVING AND SPLATTING GET JOB DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norah Hillis swears she has never written to a newspaper
columnist before. But she could no longer control her indignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading your column so many times, I must find out why
you feel it necessary to use such crude language in describing your
process of cooking,'' she explained. ``The English language is
beautiful until it is defiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't possibly see how using the words, `plunk, shove and
dump' come under the heading of good writing. I would like to
suggest that you buy a good thesaurus and use it frequently,'' she
adds.
</P>
<P>
   I don't deny that I am inclined to dump a half cup of sugar into
a mixing bowl. And I admit that my laptop computer is equipped with
a thesaurus.
</P>
<P>
   Can I ``jilt, renounce or disenfranchise'' a cup of sugar, as my
thesaurus suggests in place of ``dump''?
</P>
<P>
   I often ``shove'' a casserole into a 350-degree oven. Should I
instead ``bulldoze, elbow or jostle,'' the inoffensive pottery?
</P>
<P>
   My computer's thesaurus won't even cope with words like ``moosh,
gloop or plunk.''
</P>
<P>
   I do have a Webster's New International Dictionary heavy enough
to give NFL lineman Cortez Kennedy a hernia. Printed in 1913, it is
hardly ``new.'' Yet Webster understands ``plunk,'' and his
description suggests, ``With a plunking sound.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the noise raw oysters make when you plunk them
intoa skillet for a dish like thisone.
</P>
<P>
   Plunked Oysters
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pint oysters
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   half teaspoon chopped mint
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Short slug of Madeira or sherry
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a skillet. Plunk in the drained oysters.
Sprinkle with the garlic, mint, cinnamon mixture. Add two splats of
Tabasco and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Add the wine (a short slug is about one and one-half tablespoons
but who's measuring?) Simmer until the oysters have firmed up and
the edges have curled on the little buggers. Spoon into two
ramekins and serve with crisp toast points.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you think ``ramekins'' and ``crisp toast points'' add a
bit of class to this recipe? OK, so I portion out the Tabasco in
splats. That's the only way you can coax it out of the bottle in
portions large enough to properly clear the sinuses.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure most of my readers can distinguish between a
``splat'' and a ``short slug.''
</P>
<P>
   Plucked Poultry Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 barbecued chicken, skinned and boned
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce can diced green chilies
</P>
<P>
   1 to 3 teaspoons minced jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 Roma tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled and chopped jicama
</P>
<P>
   one-half cup cilantro leaves, minced
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   one-haf teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   If fryers or roasters are on special, buy two chickens and
barbecue or roast them both. Save one of them for the salad. Or you
can buy a barbecued clucker for about five bucks at the deli
section of supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Jicama and fresh cilantro were once available only in Mexican
markets but are now stocked in the produce departments of most
major supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   After you have plucked the meat off the chicken, whack it into
bite-size pieces then dump in a large salad bowl. Add the canned
green chilies, green onions, tomatoes, jicama and cilantro. Throw
in as much minced jalapeno as your personal thermometer can easily
tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Into a dressing jar with a lid combine the oil, vinegar, garlic,
salt and pepper. Cover and shake until ingredients are thoroughly
combined or until your tennis elbow begins to throb. Use as much
dressing as you need to moisten the salad ingredients, then toss
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   This should provide a light meal for you and three grammarians.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Norah Hillis is a wonderful cook and likely could give
Martha Stewart a lesson on kitchen etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   But some of us are destined to lurch through life glunking,
smearing and mooshing muck. It's a wonder anything gets from the
pots to our mouths without major environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The products of our efforts could be classified as
``gut-busters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody promised you ``pretty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
