<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARITIME-SCHOOL-SPI &LR;      05-16 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARITIME-SCHOOL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MARITIME SCHOOL HAS QUIETLY COME OUT OF CHOPPY WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Man overboard! Man overboard!''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Steve Powell has guided the Charles A. Kane beyond the
breakwater of Seattle's Shilshole Bay and is heading up sound when
he hears the crew's cries over the rumbling purr of the workboat's
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man overboard,'' Powell echoes into the loudspeaker, mustering
the crew to stations. He brings the 101-foot vessel about, cutting
speed and ordering the crew, ``Recover on the starboard side.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ruszala, a veteran skipper of 25 years in the merchant
marine, has toppled from the stern into the gray, 50-degree waters
off Seattle's Ballard neighborhood. Already he is 100 yards from
the boat and receding.
</P>
<P>
   But the water is calm, sun is breaking through and the 11 crew
members spot him easily.
</P>
<P>
   One grabs a life preserver and waterproof light, another a
first-aid kit. Two don life vests and stand on the gunwales to haul
Ruszala from the water. Others train fingers on Ruszala as Powell
guides the Kane toward him.
</P>
<P>
   A life preserver snakes through the air toward Ruszala _ direct
hit!
</P>
<P>
   ``Good job, get the line, save my butt!'' Ruszala yells. With a
line around his chest, the crew strains to haul him aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there's trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Ruszala goes limp. He bangs and catches against the side of the
boat, then slips back into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try turning me around,'' Ruszala yells. Arms strain to hoist
him. ``Get the yellow rescue sling from the captain's quarters.
Who's chief mate? Give directions. Assume command.''
</P>
<P>
   This time they haul Ruszala safely aboard. He stands, strips off
the red survival suit that protected him from hypothermia, then
gathers the crew that saved him.
</P>
<P>
   He's ready to critique the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   It's another lesson in a 12-hour day full of them aboard the
Kane, a former offshore supply vessel transformed into a working
classroom of the Seattle Maritime Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the nation's first workboat academy, the Seattle
Central Community College seafaring school is 30 years old this
year, and newly retooled after nearly going the way of the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought the school wouldn't reach a fourth decade after it
followed the nation's maritime industry into a slump in the 1980s.
Yet in the past six years the academy has quietly been resurrected,
renamed, and now runs on a $400,000-a-year budget.
</P>
<P>
   The school doesn't train the men and women who skipper the ocean
tankers and freighters of the deep blue. That's the job of
four-year merchant marine academies that award baccalaureate
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Seattle school's compass points to where there are
jobs: on workboats like tugs, oil tenders, factory fishing ships,
tour boats and ferries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the future merchant marine,'' says Bjorn ``B.J.''
Aune, academy director. ``This is a working-class school for people
who want to go to sea and who want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, a graduate of the four-year Texas Merchant Marine
Academy, recalls how he became a Naval Reserve officer after
graduation, when he found few blue-ocean merchant marine jobs
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American merchant marine is hanging by its fingernails,''
he says. ``Its workboat industry is the only one where there are
chances of work. This is not glamorous work; there are no white
linen tablecloths. It's grimy work, for people in coveralls, but
who are needed to keep the boats running.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, working seafarers learned at the knees of their
fathers or in apprenticeships. Now they can take classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1990, when the fishing industry hit a slump, I worked five
weekends for free to learn tugboats,'' says Kris Mullan, a
fourth-generation fisherman and port engineer for Fisherman's
Finest, a commercial fishing company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think these students realize how hard it was in the
past, or how good they have it,'' adds Mullan, who also serves on
the school's technical advisory bboard. He says the standardized
training allows students to work on a variety of boats.
</P>
<P>
   The school's mainstay programs _ for engineers and deckhands _
attract about 40 students a year. They pack academic and technical
courses into a demanding nine-month curriculum, building credits
toward academic degrees, and time and experience toward maritime
skills and licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Overall enrollment is about 750 a year, including
continuing-education courses tailored to industry, union or
government needs. For example, a joint venture with Fremont
Maritime Services created the five-day ``India Tango'' firefighting
school, named for the nautical flags ``I'' and ``T'' that signal
``I'm on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Tom Curley, who oversees merchant marine
licenses in the region, said the academy ``is building up and
expanding, and I think they are on the right track. I've been real
happy with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The school was launched in 1969 as Trident Marine Technological
Facility. Eric Erikson, then Seattle Community College chancellor
and president, literally hocked his family's farm to buy 2.2 acres
on the ship canal northeast of the Ballard Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Now board chairman of Pemco insurance, Erikson says he put up
the farm because ``the bank wanted something to hang onto'' until
other funding arrived.
</P>
<P>
   When the industry slumped in the '80s, enrollment plunged from
several hundred students to just a few dozen. The school lost its
main drawing card, a surplus Coast Guard buoy tender, and by 1989
the two-year associate degree programs were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, moves were afoot to close the school and sell the land,
but advisers and college officials argued for hanging on and
finding a niche.
</P>
<P>
   The technical advisory board, composed of industry and
government representatives, was an important development, Erikson
says. ``It forces the college to focus their instruction on the
real life out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Aune, who holds a limited master-mariner license and a doctorate
in ocean law from the London School of Economics, oversaw the
academy's overhaul. He walks a steep gangplank, however, abiding by
academic certification requirements as well as Coast Guard
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Simone is a 1972 graduate and senior port engineer for
Crowley Marine Services as well as the technical advisory board
chairman. He likes what he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The academy has the capacity to be a phenomenal program to
help the workboat industry,'' he says. ``I like the school's
real-world emphasis.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike students at the nation's seven four-year Merchant Marine
academies, those at Seattle Maritime Academy don't wear uniforms or
march to class. But they adhere to a rigorous tone set by Aune and
his staff.
</P>
<P>
   They emphasize safety, discipline and personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't apologize for being doctrinaire about goals like
teaching safety,'' Aune says. ``I will ram safety down their
throats. I work on the premise that they should be able to go to
sea and then go home to loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no grading on the curve; students can wash out. Sea
classes cast off at 8:55 a.m.; boats wait for no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not prompt, we sail and won't come back for you.
It's an attitude and an ethic,'' Aune says. ``We want people
prepared for the industry, because we want the industry's respect.
A ship delay can cost a company a fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   The school now has a fleet of six working vessels acquired
through the federal Maritime Administration's surplus program. They
range from a 26-foot motor whaleboat to the Encounter Bay, a
189-foot former salvage tug.
</P>
<P>
   The Encounter Bay and the Kane were seized by federal agents as
drug-runner vessels. The 72 tons of Thai hashish seized aboard the
Encounter Bay on June 30, 1988 _ it was headed for Vancouver, B.C.
_ remains a record U.S. drug bust.
</P>
<P>
   The Kane, originally built to tend oil rigs in the Gulf of
Mexico, was seized running a ton of cocaine from Colombia to
Louisiana in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Aune boasts that the academy has the largest operating fleet
among community colleges in the United States. ``Many schools don't
have boats because of the liability,'' he explains. ``We decided to
assume the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The boats provide coveted ``under-way experience.'' That's the
crucial sea time that must be acquired _ in addition to class work
_ to quality for licenses and ratings for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   When students aren't in classrooms and laboratories wrestling
with math, diesel engines, electrical engines or meteorology,
they're on boats all day Thursdays and Fridays using what they've
learned.
</P>
<P>
   At sea, students take turns filling billets or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One might stand watch one day; work the next in the loud engine
room logging hourly fuel, oil pressure and water temperature
readings; and take charge another day as chief mate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the students aboard the Kane this year is Corey Allan, 24,
who drove from Maine last summer to enter the engineer program.
</P>
<P>
   Allan, from a fishing family, has toiled since childhood in the
stormy and treacherous Georges Bank off Newfoundland for red crabs,
and lowlined in Florida for sharks.
</P>
<P>
   When that industry declined, Allan got a government retraining
grant to attend the Seattle academy.
</P>
<P>
   Full-time tuition for state residents is $500 per quarter; for
non-residents it's close to $2,000. Laboratory fees, textbooks,
tools and supplies add another $1,200 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only school of its kind in the nation that I could
find,'' said Allan, who scoured the Internet in his search.
</P>
<P>
   In two years _ and with enough sea time _ Allan said he can
acquire a third assistant engineer rating. His brother, attending
Maine's merchant marine academy, won't get that rating until he
graduates after four years of school and sea work.
</P>
<P>
   David Thomas, 38, said he is giving up 18 years as a journeyman
painter to go to sea as an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hands-on working guy,'' he said. ``Painting is seasonal;
engineering offers a good opportunity for travel. I'd like to work
aboard a research vessel.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a career move for Deborah Bellafonte, 44, who gave up
her landscaping business to join this year's engineering class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd only spent three days on a fishing boat before this,'' she
said recently, standing watch in the Kane's wheelhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The school has seen increasing numbers of women, though
Bellafonte is the only one in her class of 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a new area for women in a lot of respects,'' she
said. ``I've had a good response in school, but I know this is out
of the ordinary, so it's time to get thick-skinned.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others, Bellafonte has her eye on ferry work, which has
four-year waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my 15-year-old daughter is grown, I'd like to head to
Costa Rica and run my own charter boat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
