<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT &LR;      05-16 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC HEADING TO THE BELMONT STAKES AS A FAVORITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Charismatic was standing serenely in his stall at
Pimlico Race Course Sunday morning, one victory from completing one
of the most remarkable sagas in racing history. Three months after
being offered as a claimer to anybody willing to risk $62,500, he
has a chance to sweep the Triple Crown. His trainer, D. Wayne
Lukas, who won the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness with his
claimer in the last two weeks, said he would go on to the Belmont
Stakes determined to become the 12th horse in history to win all
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed greatness winning the Derby,'' Lukas said, ``and he
showed in the Preakness that he's progressed. He came out of the
Derby more aggressive, more cocky, a strut to his step, like he
knew he'd done something pretty special. He's getting to the point
where he's figuring this game out.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic won the Derby at 31-1 and won the Preakness at 8-1,
and now he must outrun his chief rivals at a mile and a half on
June 5 at Belmont Park in New York. It would be his fifth major
race at five different tracks in two months: the Santa Anita Derby,
the Lexington, the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after his latest tour de force, before a record crowd
of 100,311, it appeared that five or six of the horses from the
Preakness would meet again in the Belmont with perhaps another five
or six making late challenges from outside the Triple Crown series.
It appeared that Charismatic would finally get respect as the
betting favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But no horse has swept the Triple Crown since Affirmed did it 21
years ago. In the last two years, horses trained by Bob Baffert won
the first two races, but his Silver Charm was run down by Touch
Gold in 1997 and last year his Real Quiet lost in the final strides
to Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   Fate was playing a strange hand in casting this year's drama.
Elliott Walden, the trainer of Victory Gallop, also is the trainer
of Menifee, who ran second to Charismatic by a neck in the Derby
and by a length and a half as the beaten favorite in the Preakness.
Could Walden thwart a Triple Crown sweep at the wire for the second
year in a row?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the ending is the same,'' Walden said at his barn this
morning. ``Same story, same conclusion. Right after we got beat
pretty good in the Preakness last year, I wasn't all that anxious
to go to the Belmont. But this year, I feel good about going on and
trying him again in the Belmont, maybe because of the experience
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Charismatic and Menifee were resting at Pimlico, but they
will be traveling companions on a chartered flight Monday headed
for Louisville, Ky., where their trainers maintain stables at
Churchill Downs. Both are expected to stay in the relative calm
there until perhaps the Wednesday of Belmont week. Then they will
stage Act Three in their drama in a race that will take them
five-sixteenths of a mile farther than they ran in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extra 550 yards could make a big difference,'' Walden
said. ``I think he might like the distance. They all go a mile and
a half, but the big question is how fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Hancock, who owns Menifee with Jimmy Stone, the Louisiana
oil man, has been there before: In 1989, his Sunday Silence outran
Easy Goer in the Derby and Preakness but lost to him in the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic is a good horse,'' he said, ``and Wayne's got him
in a zone right now. He's a top horseman and knows how to keep one
that way. I'd hate to spoil someone's Triple Crown, but I know how
it feels to be on the other side after Sunday Silence.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Preakness field of 13, it seemed likely that the first
four finishers would go on to the Belmont _ Charismatic, Menifee,
Badge and Stephen Got Even _ along with Adonis (sixth) and
Kimberlite Pipe (eighth). But the Preakness marked the end of the
Triple Crown trail for some others.
</P>
<P>
   The chief casualty was Cat Thief, who ran in the money in 11 of
his 12 starts but faded to seventh in the Preakness. Lukas said he
would be pointed toward the Jim Dandy at Saratoga or the Swaps at
Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, after not racing all winter in Dubai, ran
seventh in the Kentucky Derby and 12th in the Preakness, and his
managers said they did not know yet where he would go next.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, the only filly in the Preakness, was pulled
up in the homestretch by her rider, Kent Desormeaux, and underwent
treatment for a displaced palate. Her departure seemed to mark the
end of the Triple Crown campaign for Baffert, who won the Derby and
Preakness in each of the last two years and opened this year with a
barn stocked with talented candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert flew back to Churchill Downs Sunday with Excellent
Meeting and her stablemate, Silverbulletday, who won the Black-Eyed
Susan Stakes on Friday for her eighth straight victory and now
reigned as Baffert's survivor of the wars of the 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINE
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ferrell of Bel Air, Md., the 22-year-old man who stood on
the track at Pimlico as horses raced past him in the seventh race
on Preakness Day, was being held Sunday on a first-degree assault
charge. Police spokeswoman Angelique Cook-Hayes said Ferrell was
first taken to Sinai Hospital for a psychiatric review, but was
released from the hospital Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
