<HEADER>
A9228 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARITIME-STUDENTS-SPI     05-16 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARITIME-STUDENTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL STUDENTS FOUND MARTIME SCHOOL TO THEIR LIKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After 11 years in the Army, Shannon Robinson went
through the Seattle Maritime Academy's engineering technology
course in 1995, and later its two-week captain's class.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 43, now skippers Argosy tour boats on the Seattle
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Ramsey-Bell, 45, took the academy's first engineering
course so she could continue going to sea after her post-doctorate
job in physics and atmospheric sciences ended in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   She's now third-assistant engineer on the University of
Washington's research vessel, Thomas Thompson, where she previously
worked as a scientist.
</P>
<P>
   They are success stories from the academy. Other students aren't
as satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jaross, 28, gave up his glass-blowing business in
Everett, Wash., to attend the academy's first-deck technology
course in January 1998. Although Jaross now works aboard a National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration research vessel, it's not
the kind of work he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us got anything. We ended up with ordinary seaman's
papers for bottom-of-the-bucket jobs like cooking, mopping decks
and cleaning toilets,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jaross is among a group of seven graduates of the school's
deckhand program who were not satisfied with their experiences
after graduation. While Robinson and Ramsey-Bell love the work they
got after graduating from the engineering program, Jaross claims
the school misled him and oversold the deckhand program.
</P>
<P>
   Post-graduate success _ and how Seattle Maritime Academy
graduates view the program _ depends largely on what they studied
and how much experience at sea they acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are in greater demand. Almost all of last year's
engineering graduates got jobs on workboats locally or in the Gulf
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Licenses are everything in the maritime industry, with Coast
Guard approval for them hinging largely on experience at sea, or
``under-way time.''
</P>
<P>
   Those, like Jaross, who enter the academy program without much
sea time, have less chance of acquiring more advanced licenses than
do those with prior experience, says Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Tom
Curley, who oversees regional merchant marine licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school was retooled in 1993, it has attracted students
ages 17 to 70 _ the oldest a retired trucker who now serves as an
engineer on fishing vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The majority are in their mid-30s. About a third come from the
marine industry. Some work shoreside but need to formalize skills.
Others retrain after losing jobs _ such as timber workers, Boeing
machinists and a member of the Lummi tribe, whose casino closed.
</P>
<P>
   Some simply want career changes, including nurses, academics,
even a bank executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most are more mature, demanding students who aren't
starry-eyed and innocent'' about the kind of the work they are
getting into, says academy director Bjorn ``B.J.'' Aune.
</P>
<P>
   After Robinson graduated from the engineering program in 1995,
she spent a year tending bar and building up time at sea. She then
returned to the school to take the two-week captain's course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have so much sea time in order to even sit for an
exam for your license,'' she says. ``For an inland 100-ton license
to operate our boats in Puget Sound and the lake areas, you need
360 sea days, and those each encompass an eight-hour time frame.
Basically, you need a year at sea before you can sit down to take
the captain's license test.''
</P>
<P>
   She passed the test and realized her ambition to skipper Argosy
tour boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job,'' says Robinson. ``I was impressed with the
whole school and everything they've done. We are responsible for
the lives of people on the boat, and I feel very prepared. I've
gone back (to the academy) to hire employees and sent some to the
school for training.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey-Bell had been at sea plenty of times before she signed up
for the academy, but it was as a scientist researching
pollution-free clouds over remote oceans, not as a crew member.
</P>
<P>
   When academic jobs dried up in 1993, Ramsey-Bell took the
academy's first engineering class. It was a way to remain on
research vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the guinea pigs,'' she says of the nine-month class.
``Nothing was definite as far as Coast Guard approval. It was kind
of hairy, but it came through at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   She can look back now and laugh, but Ramsey-Bell says some
students were upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very taxing and sometimes pretty heavy-duty stuff,''
she says. ``A lot of students weren't well-prepared _ I wasn't for
diesel classes. And some people didn't have the right temperament
to be on a boat and take orders from people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey-Bell says the UW research vessel on which she works ``is
a complicated ship with highly technical equipment, a lot of
electrical stuff. I think I've done well there partly because of
(the academy's) schooling.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaross says he and his classmates were sea novices who didn't
realize the difficulty of acquiring licenses. Though he works on a
research ship, he says he wishes he'd never taken the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the academy had a caveat in a brochure that the
(deckhand) course was pending Coast Guard approval, we were
verbally assured throughout the program that it was merely a
formality. We feel defrauded,'' Jaross says.
</P>
<P>
   Jaross said he and others were misled by director Aune on the
certification issue.
</P>
<P>
   Aune acknowledges that the Coast Guard approval he wanted didn't
come through for Jaross' deckhand class, but he flatly denies the
students were misled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never misrepresented anything,'' Aune says. ``We got some
of what we asked for (from the Coast Guard) and these students knew
the situation and had a choice, but (they) found it more convenient
to raise a ruckus.''
</P>
<P>
   If the academy wins an appeal to qualify deckhand students for
the Coast Guard's higher able-bodied seaman rating, it would be
awarded retroactively to the disgruntled students, Aune says.
</P>
<P>
   School officials and Coast Guard and industry representatives
say Jaross got appropriate ratings. He and others, however, have
little previous sea experience and need to work 90 days at sea to
acquire the able-bodied seaman rating.
</P>
<P>
   Curley says that while most new seafarers have a year to log sea
time before their certificates expire, the local Coast Guard office
allows students such as Jaross and his classmates three years to
acquire the 90 days of sea time.
</P>
<P>
   And the deckhand program will be offered again this September,
Aune says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
