<HEADER>
A9229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WISDOM-1STLD-WRI     05-16 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WISDOM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN MINOR WISDOM, JUDGE WHO HELPED TO END SEGREGATION, DIES AT
93 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs lede to correct date of death to Saturday.)  
 (ATTN: La., Fla., Ala., Miss., Texas, Ga. and Va. )  (Eds: Longer version ha s moved. ) 
(DW) 
 By JACK BASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge John Minor Wisdom, the New Orleans legal scholar who wrote
opinion after opinion that desegregated courthouses throughout the
South and put blacks on juries, in the voting booth, in state
legislatures and in integrated classrooms, died Saturday morning in
New Orleans. He would have turned 94 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He had remained active throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom wrote the opinion that allowed James Meredith to attend
the University of Mississippi. In 1967 he wrote the majority
opinion in another case, U.S. vs. Jefferson County, which, as he
recalled, ``really started affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   His wide-ranging judicial opinions over more than four decades
kept public schools open in Louisiana when officials tried to close
them rather than integrate, ordered Florida to desegregate even its
reform schools and told sports authorities to desegregate the
boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished this after President Dwight D. Eisenhower named
him in 1957 to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, a
jurisdiction that then included six states of the old Confederacy _
Louisiana, Florida, Alabama, Mississippi, Texas and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   It was four judges of the 5th Circuit whose opinions helped
shape the civil rights laws of the 1950s and 60s, changing the
South. Wisdom was the last survivor of the men who came to be
called simply the Four, a term used in a dissenting opinion by a
fellow judge from Mississippi who saw them as destroyers of the Old
South that he cherished. The others were Eldred P. Tuttle of
Georgia, John R. Brown of Texas and Richard T. Rives of Alabama.
All but Judge Rives were Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The judges of the 5th Circuit amplified the mandate of Brown vs.
Board of Education, the epochal Supreme Court decision of May 17,
1954, that nullified state laws and state constitutional provisions
allowing or requiring the segregation of black and white students
in public schools because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Wisdom made what he regarded as the most important
opinion of his career in U.S. v. Jefferson, in which the court
overturned the so-called ``Briggs dictum.'' This was the belief,
widely held by conservative judges in the South, that the
Constitution did not require integration but merely forbade
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom advocated ``the planned organized undoing of the effects
of past segregation'' and set in motion the philosophical framework
for what would come to be known as affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in awarding Wisdom the Presidential Medal of
Freedom in 1993, said that his opinions ``advanced civil rights and
economic justice, and his inspired words echo throughout many of
this century's most significant Supreme Court opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   John Minor Wisdom was born in New Orleans on May 17, 1905, the
son of Mortimer M. Wisdom and Adelaide Labatt Wisdom. His father
was a member of the city's elite and proudly remembered marching in
the funeral procession of Robert E. Lee in 1870. In 1925 the son
received his bachelor's degree from Washington and Lee University,
where he had an interest in literature. He studied literature for a
year as a graduate student at Harvard University, but then entered
the law school at Tulane University, where he graduated first in
his class.
</P>
<P>
   He practiced law in New Orleans throughout the 1930s, then
joined the Army Air Corps in World War II, serving in the Office of
Legal Procurement. He was discharged with the rank of lieutenant
colonel.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom, a long-time Republican loyalist who served in the 1950s
as a national committeeman from Louisiana, broke with the more
traditional Southern Republicans, who strongly supported the
candidacy of the conservative Sen. Robert Taft of Ohio for
president in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that year, he and Eldred P. Tuttle, a lawyer in Atlanta,
had met at the request of Herbert Brownell, Eisenhower's campaign
manager, to organize a campaign in the South to support Eisenhower
for the Republican nomination against Taft. Wisdom and Tuttle
became co-chairmen of the Southern Conference for Eisenhower, and
each led pro-Eisenhower delegations that won contested fights for
credentials at the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general in the Eisenhower administration, Brownell
became an important figure in selecting federal judges, and both
Tuttle and Wisdom were eventually put on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom wrote several landmark opinions in employment
discrimination cases. In 1979, the Supreme Court adopted the basic
reasoning of his dissent in Weber vs. Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical
Corp. to uphold a hiring plan intended to overcome the effects of
past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Not all his major decisions concerned race. In 1974, he wrote an
opinion that found that psychiatric patients as a class had a
federal constitutional right to adequate treatment when such
patients were committed against their will to state institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he was mentioned as a leading candidate for the U.S.
Supreme Court. Moderate Republicans advanced his name after the
Senate rejected President Richard M. Nixon's nomination of Judge
Clement F. Haynsworth, a candidate Wisdom opposed.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon's attorney general, John Mitchell, scuttled the idea,
reportedly complaining that Wisdom was nothing more than a ``damn
left-winger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom once told a reporter that in the 1960s, when the 5th
Circuit was issuing its most contentious rulings, his dogs were
poisoned and a rattlesnake was thrown in his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the liberal views about race and civil rights he
espoused throughout his judicial career, he maintained memberships
in private clubs and Mardi Gras krewes that discriminated against
blacks and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I see in these clubs are the guys I went to school
with and have known all my life,'' he said. ``I would not resign
from any such club.'' He said, ``They know how I stand on these
matters'' and ``I certainly wouldn't change their views by getting
out of the club.'' He is survived by his wife, Bonnie Mathews
Wisdom, and two daughters, Kathleen Mathews Wisdom and Penelope
Stewart Wisdom Tose. A son, John Minor Wisdom Jr., died.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when he was 89, the 5th Circuit building in New Orleans
was named for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
