<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAYADERE-DANCE-REVIEW     05-16 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYADERE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASSIC LOVE STORY ASSUMES A MODERN GUISE WITH VIVID PASSION IN
TACT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``La Bayadere'' has romantic intrigue galore, a death
by snakebite and a crumbling temple to recommend it. The Minkus
score is a similarly operatic bundle of grand _ and melodic _
passions.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the ballet is a scene that captures the essence
of ballet classicism, in the late 19th century and, remarkably
enough, in our own ``neoclassical'' times.
</P>
<P>
   Performers can take flight in dance passages of great beauty and
purity. The dancers of American Ballet Theater rose to the occasion
in performances on Friday night and Saturday afternoon at the
Metropolitan Opera House, where the sumptuous production, staged by
Natalia Makarova after the Marius Petipa original, may be seen in a
``Bayadere'' mini-season that ends on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1877 for the Maryinsky Ballet of St. Petersburg,
Russia, ``La Bayadere'' was seen in the West only in the excerpted
Kingdom of the Shades scene until this 1980 production by Ms.
Makarova, who took a well-deserved curtain call on Friday night.
The balletgoer who doesn't enjoy the scene, the dance critic Clive
Barnes once suggested, doesn't really enjoy ballet. The same might
be said for the entire work, despite its lumbering scenario. By
taking ``La Bayadere'' seriously enough to perform it without a
trace of camp, the two Ballet Theater casts made the work live not
just as history but as vivid contemporary theater.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night Susan Jaffe made of Nikiya, the Indian temple
dancer who loves and is betrayed by the noble warrior, Solor, an
ethereal creature whose fragility foretold from the start her cruel
destruction. Ms. Jaffe's long, supple arms seemed to evaporate like
mist as she danced, in much the same way her ghost or ``shade''
will later appear and disappear.
</P>
<P>
   There was something of that dreaming quality to Jose Manuel
Carreno's Solor, communicated through the sheer beauty and clarity
of his dancing, from precise, fluent preparations for steps and
phrases to turns that shimmered in their speed and control. Very
small gestures of the head and arms suggested undercurrents of
emotion. Paloma Herrera played the vicious Gamzatti as a spoiled
young woman determined to win Solor at any cost. The
characterization worked, but Ms. Herrera's dancing did not live up
to her clear, sharply etched best.
</P>
<P>
   Performing on Saturday afternoon, Julie Kent was a delicate
Nikiya whose love for Solor expanded her like a flower opening to
the sun. Her Solor, Vladimir Malakhov, was a creature of the air,
soaring effortlessly in perfectly shaped high traveling jumps and
touching earth eventually as softly as a cat. Irina Dvorovenko,
seen in a role debut as Gamzatti, communicated the character's
ruthlessness through the steely boldness of her dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Barbee was less acute than usual as the High Brahmin on
Friday. Joaquin De Luz's Bronze Idol solo was fascinating in its
measured dynamic shifts. On Saturday Robert Hill's Brahmin was a
figure of frighteningly eerie stillness. Michael Cusumano spooled
out the pyrotechnics of the Bronze Idol solo in a single thread of
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The luminous, seamless dancing of the female corps made it clear
at both performances why the Kingdom of the Shades scene is so
beloved by balletgoers. The three Shades solos were danced capably
by Yan Chen, Ekaterina Shelkanova and Michele Wiles (Friday) and
the charming Anna Liceica, Ms. Shelkanova and Veronica Lynn
(Saturday). John Selya's Head Fakir was a bullet charging awesomely
through the wild choreography for this ragged messenger on Friday,
while Vladislav Kalinin was exciting in pure dance terms on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The lead casts were completed by Ethan Brown, Christopher
Martin, Rosalie O'Connor, Erica Cornejo and Sara Mau. The score,
arranged by John Lanchbery, was conducted by Charles Barker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
