<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-2TA     05-16 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRIN GOVERNMENT BALANCES UNEASY PEACE AGAINST FEARS OF CIVIL
WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ This capital city nestled in mighty
mountains has been telling two tales since NATO's air assault on
Yugoslavia began.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface it remains the same slightly shopworn metropolis
of smart restaurants and sidewalk cafes where people sip sweet
coffee as a disco roar conceals conversations.
</P>
<P>
   But every evening, when Freedom Street fills with elegant
promenaders flaunting Versace jeans and Benetton blouses, heavily
armed guards in flak jackets and camouflage fatigues stand vigil
before government offices just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The weary officials inside, often with bags under their eyes and
exaggerated creases in their foreheads, are busy playing a
cat-and-mouse game with Yugoslavia's Second Army, which they
suspect of plotting some kind of coup d'etat in alliance with a
powerful segment of Montenegro's parliamentary opposition that
supports Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the situation has reached an extremely delicate
balance between civil war and uneasy peace that could be tipped by
the opposition or the army. For now the Montenegrin government, the
reluctant junior partner of Serbia in the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, retains tentative control.
</P>
<P>
   But officials worry, however, that their opponents _ acting
under orders from Milosevic _ are trying to destabilize Montenegro
and choke the economy, in effect conducting what they call ``a
creeping coup'' that will undercut the elected government and cause
it to fall.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, officials say, the Yugoslav army is acting as an army
of occupation, ignoring Montenegro's constitution, and imposing its
own order. Sometimes the civilian authorities persuade the army to
back down, as when they managed to get it to reopen the border with
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   But they had less success in other areas. Despite protests,
young men are still forced into the army. Foreign journalists can
still be stopped, searched and sent home, even though the
Montenegrin government welcomed them. And the government has been
unable to completely protect the thousands of Kosovo Albanians who
have sought refuge here.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident along the border a few weeks ago, seven
displaced Kosovars were killed in a skirmish with the Yugoslav
military. Now the government has stationed its own police around
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since March 24 we've had two sets of laws in Montenegro _ the
army's and the government's,'' said Milka Tadic, managing editor of
the weekly independent newspaper Monitor. ``But as we all know,
when you have two laws, you really have no law at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a month and a half of this struggle, the
Montenegrin government remains intent on resisting the army,
without provoking a violent reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``As reasonable people we seek to avoid conflict,'' said
Montenegro's foreign minister, Branko Perovic. ``But if they insist
on conflict, they will have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is a small theater in the current conflict, a
republic the size of Connecticut with 635,000 people and an ancient
history of stubborn resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the consequences of what is happening here are of great
concern to NATO and Washington because Montenegro looms as yet
another flash point in what remains of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have warned Milosevic that they will not stand idly
by if there is an outright attempt to overthrow Montenegro's
constitutional government. But the limited bombing of Montenegro's
airport and other sites by NATO jets has given the large number of
Montenegrins who support Milosevic a chance to further stir up the
resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unacceptable that the government of Montenegro has still
not condemned the aggression on its country but instead blames the
federal government,'' said Predrag Bulatovic, deputy leader of the
Socialist People's Party at a recent news conference.
</P>
<P>
   While the Socialist party is a minority in parliament, it enjoys
substantial support among hard-liners and former Communists, and
many of its leaders are closely aligned with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders accuse the current government of treason for not
supporting Serbia's war effort. They are suspicious of foreign
journalists and rejected requests for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Montenegro's current crisis go back to 1997, when a
majority of voters turned away from Milosevic and his policies by
electing a pro-Western, democratic president. The day before Milo
Djukanovic was inaugurated, more than 30 police officers were hurt
in Podgorica when they confronted a pro-Milosevic mob intent on
keeping the new government from taking power.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never given up the idea of a coup,'' said Dragisa
Burzan, Montenegro's deputy prime minister, referring to the
Socialist People's Party, and indirectly to Milosevic. ``Now they
want to misuse the situation with NATO to conduct their coup
because they know that in normal times they could not succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of the political uncertainty, Montenegro's economy is a
shambles. Tourism, the republic's top source of income, has been
devastated as vacationers have stayed away from Montenegro's famous
Adriatic Sea beach resorts.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the economy is not functioning, officials
said, and top industries have been severely cut back or completely
shut down because they cannot get raw materials and because Serbia,
the biggest buyer of Montenegrin exports, has been effectively shut
down by the current conflict with NATO. Unemployment is soaring and
the government is almost out of money.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The strongest weapon civilian authorities have used to hold the
Yugoslav army in check is the 3,000-member police force, backed by
a large number of reservists. The Montenegrin government has
refused to recognize Belgrade's determination that a state of war
exists, and it refuses to give the Yugoslav army the power it wants
to commandeer schools, hospitals and public buildings and to
confiscate private stores of goods for military uses.
</P>
<P>
   But outright confrontation is not the goal. ``Our strategy,''
said Burzan, ``is to buy time.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts indicate that as the crisis has evolved,
Djukanovic's government has gained confidence in its ability to
handle the opposition's challenges without overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But does that mean there are not going to be ongoing crises?''
said one western diplomat based outside Montenegro. ``The answer is
no. But on the other hand, the opposition is also showing a lack of
aggressiveness or boldness and they seem to have learned that it is
best not to cross certain lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is trying hard to preserve a sense of normalcy,
knowing that war fever could embolden the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Perovic, the foreign minister, said in an interview that he
believed Montenegro would be able to hold off its opponents until
the NATO bombing ended. He said he hoped that then the tensions
would ease substantially and the government would return to its
program of economic and political reform.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned Western leaders not to underestimate the
seriousness of Montenegro's crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Mr. Milosevic is pushing so hard to destabilize
Montenegro should be a clear warning to the international community
that he is trying to find some way to escape from the trap they
have set for him,'' Perovic said. ``What he is doing here is trying
to eliminate a political force that will give him trouble after he
survives the current conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
