<HEADER>
A9233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HBCU-FUNDING17-COX     05-16 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBCU-FUNDING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gifts to HBCUs on the rise
 &HT;    By Kimberly H. Byrd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While individual contributions to historically black
colleges and universities have been up over the last decade, they
are still smaller than the millions given to traditionally white
institutions every year.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Gray, president and chief executive officer of the
United Negro College Fund, says there's a reason for the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans have not had access to capital formation and
wealth accumulation like the white community,'' said Gray, whose
organization has raised $1.4 billion for black colleges and black
students. ``There are many more multimillionaire graduates from
Georgia Tech than there are from Morehouse. Therefore, over the
decades, they've been able to give more.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, actor Bill Cosby and his wife, Camille, were recognized
as black philanthropists when they donated more than $20 million to
build a new academic center at Spelman College. The couple has also
supported at least six other black colleges, including Morehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Gary, a prominent Florida attorney, pledged $10 million
to his alma mater, Shaw University in Raleigh, N.C., in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based talk show host Oprah Winfrey, who delivered the
commencement address at Morehouse on Sunday, established a
scholarship fund at Morehouse a decade ago with $1 million. In
1997, she gave $1 million to launch another scholarship at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the big donors are graduates of HBCUs, university
administrators said. Others have children who attended one of the
colleges. Some choose to support the schools because they provide
educational access to African-American students.
</P>
<P>
   Gray attributes the increase in giving at HBCUs to the fact that
the first group of ``extremely wealthy'' African-Americans surfaced
over the last decade with careers in sports, entertainment and
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, when you look at the wealthiest African-Americans and
compare their wealth to the wealthiest whites in America, there is
a huge gap,'' Gray said. ``So HBCUs continue to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   They struggle, Gray said, not only because black alumni from the
schools have limited wealth, but also because the HBCUs are
committed to educating students from low-income families. Out of
fear the students could otherwise be denied entry to other
institutions of higher learning, HBCUs are hesitant to raise
tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting alumni to contribute _ even if it's not in
the millions _ is to give them a cause or a building campaign to
support, said Trisa Long Paschal, vice president for institutional
advancement at Spelman College.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993-96, Spelman ran a fund-raising campaign that
produced $113.8 million, of which $3 million came from alumni. The
campaign was centered around building a science center, and now the
college is planning to renovate the historic Sisters Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that we'd never asked our alumni for help, and once
we asked they said yes,'' Paschal said. ``It was a matter of
helping them understand how they could support us.'' Carla Maxwell
Ray, associate vice president of institutional advancement at
Morehouse, said the school uses galas and affairs in various
locales across the United States to increase awareness about the
institution's goals.
</P>
<P>
   Getchel Caldwell, associate vice president for university
relations for Clark Atlanta University, said officials there are
negotiating sizeable gifts from three alumni and an anonymous donor
sometime during the 1999-2000 school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clark Atlanta has good experience with getting foundation
support,'' Caldwell said. ``But we're just getting into the
ballgame of individual, six-digit gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said Clark Atlanta averages about $1 million a year in
individual gifts, mainly from alumni. That's not surprising since
it mirrors nationwide statistics that show alumni giving ranges
between 11 percent and 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans are just getting into positions where they
have disposable wealth to give back to institutions of higher
learning,'' Caldwell said, acknowledging that their main competitor
is the black church.
</P>
<P>
   ``As increasing opportunities are made to African-Americans,
you'll see increased giving just as you saw with early immigrant
colleges like Notre Dame, Brigham Young and Yeshiva,'' Gray said.
``Black colleges will continue to survive and flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
