<HEADER>
A9234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-POLITICS-SMITH-AR     05-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-POLITICS-SMITH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH EMBLEMATIC OF NEW REPUBLICAN THINKING ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.Y., Ore., Utah) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Gordon H. Smith, R-Ore., was endorsed by the
National Rifle Association. He owns guns and has taught his two
sons and his daughter how to use them. And while he has ``always
melted in the face of Bambi,'' he occasionally goes hunting for
pheasant and duck.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his resolute defense of the Second Amendment, Smith
said he was dismayed by the position that he and his party found
themselves in last week, essentially standing in opposition to
requiring background checks on everyone who buys guns at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The morning news programs, portraying the Republican Party as a
captive of the NRA, only added to his unease. ``I voted, and I woke
up feeling ashamed and determined to change this,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, with Smith's help, the Republicans had reversed
course on the issue, even though the Democrats had said there were
still big loopholes in their approach. And Smith, a 46-year-old
businessman in his third year in the Senate, had become emblematic
of the new Zeitgeist on gun control, post-Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point for Smith, though, was not the killing of 15
people at a high school in Littleton, Colo., he said, but the
previous school shooting in Springfield, Ore., where two students
died and many more were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he went to Thurston High School after the shooting,
saw ``these survivors with the bullet holes scarred over on their
bodies,'' and heard ``their parents pleading for us to do
something.'' And, he said, ``It made me determined not to just talk
this away.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics would argue that the Republican Party's shifting stance
on gun control was less a profile in courage than an effort to get
in front of the public opinion polls, which many strategists
believe show an electorate increasingly open to regulating guns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, back home in Oregon, the Republican-led House was also
moving on a bill last week that would require background checks for
people who who buy firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But gun control, like abortion, is an issue with little
political territory that is truly safe. And when all the voting was
done last week, Smith did not sit in his office with the happy
certitude of the poll-driven politician, confident in his numbers.
Even as he spoke, his assistants were lining up interviews with
editors of rural newspapers, trying to get his position across back
home.
</P>
<P>
   Will he be punished?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Smith, who is not up for re-election
until 2002. ``I don't know. I know I feel at peace with myself, and
I'm determined to sell my view at home, which is that if you want
to protect your Second Amendment rights there come some
responsibilities _ and part of it is putting into place background
checks which separate good citizens from kooks and crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., a leader in gun control
efforts, said he had spoken to Smith at some length and concluded,
``I don't think that this, for him, was a political calculation as
much as it was, `Enough, already!''' The gun lobby, Schumer said,
had simply pushed Senate Republicans too far.
</P>
<P>
   Before their reversal on Friday, Republicans like Smith were on
record with a vote against a Democratic proposal that would have
required background checks for all sales at gun shows and for a
Republican proposal that would have made those checks voluntary in
some cases. Smith, who said he had supported the idea of mandatory
background checks all along, but thought the Democratic bill
``overreached,'' was one of those who demanded a stronger
Republican alternative. It passed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who notes he is the first Senator elected from mostly
rural eastern Oregon in nearly 75 years, clearly likes the idea of
finding middle ground, ``reasonable proposals'' that can link rural
and urban constituents, hunters and suburban parents. Although
considered a conservative, he prides himself on forging a good
working relationship with Sen. Ron Wyden, a liberal Democrat and
past opponent. ``I'm probably not pure enough for any single
interest group,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Could it have something to do with his childhood?
</P>
<P>
   He was the eighth of 10 children. His father worked in the
family's food processing business, then went to work in the
Eisenhower administration as executive assistant to the secretary
of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was a Udall, making Smith a cousin of the notable
Western Democrats Morris and Stewart Udall. ``I watched them make
enormous contributions to our country in Congress and in Democratic
administrations,' he said. ``So for me, the issues that divide
Democrats and Republicans have never been about good people and bad
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a Mormon, graduated from Brigham Young University in 1976
after a two-year missionary assignment in New Zealand. He obtained
a law degree, practiced law for a while, then bought the family
frozen vegetable company in eastern Oregon. In 1992, he won
election to the Oregon state Senate, and three years later was
elected Senate president.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the U.S. Senate after a brutal year in which he
sought two Senate seats: He lost a special election in January 1996
to Wyden for the seat left vacant by the resignation of Sen. Bob
Packwood. Then, with a campaign pitched more to the center, Smith
came back to win the election in November 1996 for the seat left
vacant by the retirement of Sen. Mark O. Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   So what, exactly, changed for him in Springfield and Littleton?
The week was winding down, the other senators scattering, and Smith
was groping, just a little. Then finally he said, ``It heightened
the sensitivity I felt Wednesday night when I saw my party being
unresponsive to the emotions I felt from places like Springfield
and Jonesboro and Littleton.''
</P>
<P>
   In that moment, change seemed in the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
