<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANQUERAY-ADCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANQUERAY RETIRES JENKINS AND INTRODUCES COOL BRITANNIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Texas, Mich. , Calif. , Fla., Britain)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The marketers of a well-known gin are shaking, not
stirring, its advertising, replacing a pitch based on fantasy with
one based on reality _ well, as realistic as you can get on Madison
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Tanqueray, the best-selling brand of imported gin, is ending a
five-year campaign featuring a make-believe character named
Jenkins, a dapper roue whose sybaritic adventures centered on
parties and gin martinis. Ads last month trumpeted the
``disappearance'' of Jenkins and the subsequent decision of the
``beloved Tanqueray figurehead,'' as he was described in one mock
headline, to retire to _ appropriately enough _ a make-believe
tropical island.
</P>
<P>
   New print, outdoor and postcard ads and promotions, now under
way, sell Tanqueray on attributes like authenticity and heritage.
They present traditional and contemporary images of London to
reinforce the Tanqueray identity as a brand distilled in Britain
since 1830.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the new campaign, with an increased budget of $25
million to $30 million, is underlined by a formal redesignation of
the brand on labels and packaging as Tanqueray London Dry Gin.
</P>
<P>
   The switch in campaigns is indicative of the need for
advertisers and agencies to rethink how they approach consumers,
even when ads are deemed successful.
</P>
<P>
   Tanqueray case shipments in the United States rose 2.8 percent
last year to 1.3 million, according to the Impact annual distilled
spirits survey published by M. Shanken Communications in New York,
even as shipments of domestic gins declined about 4 percent and
shipments of all gins fell about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In total sales for all brands, Tanqueray trails only Seagram's
Gin, sold by the Seagram Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Jenkins campaign ``made the brand a lot more relevant and
fun and hip and brought a lot more younger adult consumers into the
Tanqueray franchise,'' said Leah Russell, vice president and
product group director for the Tanqueray brand family at the
Schieffelin &AMP; Somerset Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's time for a change, time for something new and
different,'' she added. ``So it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign, carrying the theme ``Tanqueray London,'' also
serves as a fond ``cheerio'' to Deutsch Inc. in New York, which has
been the brand's agency for American campaigns since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo PLC, which owns Schieffelin &AMP; Somerset, is consolidating
the Tanqueray worldwide creative account at offices of the J.
Walter Thompson Company unit of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an excellent relationship with Deutsch,'' Ms.
Russell said. ``But this is the corporate direction, and we
understand it's meant to benefit the company as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she added, ``we are so excited and confident about the
`London' campaign that we will support it fully despite the
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Deutsch waxed bittersweet about the loss of the
Tanqueray assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great relationships and great advertising don't often come
into play'' in consolidations, said Andrew Beaver, executive vice
president and group account director at Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``we're told the `Tanqueray London' campaign will
run for a year at least.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign uses photographs of British icons interspersed with
men and women in their 20s clad in trendy outfits. The familiar
symbols include flags, an English bulldog and a swatch of Prince of
Wales plaid fabric; the modern symbols include the logo of the
Ministry of Sound, a group of London disk jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude is very much ``Cool Britannia,'' the sobriquet for
the chic, confident spirit of Britain under Prime Minister Tony
Blair, crossed with the tongue-in-cheek attitude of Austin Powers,
the comic secret agent played in two films by the actor Mike Myers.
(In fact, small type in some Tanqueray ads, to promote
``responsible drinking,'' uses the Powers catch phrase ``Oh
behave.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``There seem to be articles almost daily about new things in
fashion, art, design, style and music coming from London,'' Ms.
Russell said. ``These are fun, compelling images, unusual for
spirits advertising and refreshing in that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the campaign is not just about what's going on now,
because that would be just fads,'' she added. ``The background for
the cool London of today is 20, 30, 40 years of cool trends, from
the Beatles and Twiggy and punk to Oasis and Seal and Wallpaper
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Delaney, partner and executive creative director at
Deutsch, and Craig Markus, senior vice president and group creative
director, expressed enthusiasm about the elasticity of the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign of a big idea when you can just keep going and
going and going,'' Ms. Delaney said. ``We almost had to restrain
ourselves from putting together more ads'' beyond the initial 10.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent ads are already being planned. For instance, Ms.
Russell said, a distinctive London taxicab will be in an ad to
discourage drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which also promotes Tanqueray Malacca Gin, a
lighter-tasting variety, will appear in magazines including Black
Enterprise, Cosmopolitan, Ebony, Elle, Fast Company, GQ, The New
Yorker, Playboy, Rolling Stone, Saveur, Talk, Vanity Fair and
Wallpaper. The outdoor signs will appear in 12 markets including
Atlanta, Chicago, Dallas, Detroit, Los Angeles, Miami, New York and
San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
