<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING ELIMINATION NOTHING NEW FOR BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ Sometimes, it's all in the way you look at a situation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues trail the Stars 3-2 in their best-of-seven
Western Conference semifinal series. If they lose Game 6, scheduled
for 6:30 tonight in St. Louis, their season is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues think they are lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at it,'' defenseman Al MacInnis said, ``We're
in a better position now than we were in the first series.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first series, they trailed the Phoenix Coyotes 3-1 and
had to win three consecutive games to advance. They did, becoming
the 15th team in the Stanley Cup playoffs to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced elimination before,'' MacInnis said. ``We faced it
three times in the first round. It's not going to be anything new
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues realize what they have to do, too, if they are going
to again survive testing the odds. In NHL playoff series that were
tied 2-2, the Game 5 winners have won 81 percent of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do two things,'' Blues center Pierre Turgeon said.
``We have to play well on the power play, and we have to come out
strong early. If we do those things, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty big ``if.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues are 2-for-25 on the power play and have been outscored
6-1 in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we knew \Rwhat was wrong with the power play\S we'd have it
fixed, wouldn't we?'' Chris Pronger said.
</P>
<P>
   Blues coach Joel Quenneville said the Blues would work on the
power play to try to get it back to where it was in the first
round, when they were 9-for-33 with a man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of quality chances that didn't materialize,''
Quenneville said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues were getting plenty of first shots. MacInnis said the
Blues have to find a way to get more second chances. They would
also help themselves if they weren't always playing from behind.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five games of the series, the Stars scored the
first goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets back to we want to get out quick,'' Blues winger
Blair Atcheynum said. ``We have to start strong and get the Kiel
\RCenter\S rocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kiel Center hasn't been very friendly to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues are 2-0 at home against the Stars in the playoffs.
They were 3-0-1 at home against them in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, and maybe most important numbers, are 3-0 _ the
Blues' record in elimination games in this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think?'' Pronger said when asked if Game 6 was
like the last three games against Phoenix. ``It's definitely a
do-or-die situation. We have to win to stay alive in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   His solution on how to stay alive for Game 7?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at ourselves in the mirror and come up with a
better effort,'' Pronger said. ``Our attitude has to be desperation
and determination. This is the same thing as Phoenix; a loss and
you go home.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
