<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9245 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZDTV-ZDTV_SFCHRON &LR;      05-16 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZDTV-ZDTV </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 ZIFF-DAVIS SEEKING AIR TIME FOR ITS PC-TV CHANNEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Dan Fost  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
In its uphill quest to build a 24-hour cable television channel
with nothing but shows about computers, San Francisco's ZDTV last
week marked its first anniversary with impressive national growth
but without the prize it covets most: complete coverage in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   Locals can see the station on a select number of cable systems,
or via satellite services such as DirecTV and EchoStar.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do people in San Francisco and Silicon Valley represent
the country's most likely audience for all-computer all-the-time
television _ Wired magazine called it ``you-gotta-be-kidding TV'' _
but the 200 people who work for ZDTV would love to tell their
neighbors and friends where to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any one thing I could still do in this first
year, if I had a magic wand to wave, it would be to make ZDTV
available to everyone in the Bay Area,'' said Larry Wangberg, the
chief executive. ``Here we are in the middle of everything we're
talking about, and we're the only national network based in the Bay
Area, and to not be carried is disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Chegia, a news producer and anchor in ZDTV's news
department, notes that Kate Botello and Leo Laporte, the stars of
the ZDTV show ``The Screen Savers,'' are mobbed by fans when they
do store appearances from Las Vegas to New Jersey, but ``nobody
would even open the door for them at Staples on Potrero.''
</P>
<P>
   For ZDTV to pull it off locally, the network will have to get
picked up by Tele-Communications Inc., which provides cable
services to 1.3 million people in the Bay Area _ 90 percent of the
region's cable audience.
</P>
<P>
   That's why signs are popping up around San Francisco saying
things like, ``TV doesn't get any more PC than this,'' and ``Dot
coms, not sitcoms.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's part of a more-than-$5 million national ad campaign,
the blitz comes at a crucial time locally. TCI has sent surveys out
to its Bay Area customers, asking what new channels they'd like to
see and which ones they want bumped. The surveys are due to TCI by
July 10 and could have a quick impact on channel lineups.
</P>
<P>
   ``For ZDTV and any cable network, it's about customer demand,''
said Andrew Johnson, executive director of communications for TCI's
Western region. ``If they are successful in spreading the word
about what the channel offers, promoting themselves and creating
buzz in the community, certainly we'll have to give it a serious
look.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City, ZDTV officials note, is also high on the list,
but ZDTV hasn't persuaded the Big Apple's cable provider,
Time-Warner, to carry the network anywhere, much less in the
advertising capital.
</P>
<P>
   ZDTV is available on cable in some large cities, like Denver and
Phoenix, as well as places like Smyrna, Ga.; Muscatine, Iowa; and
Kennebunk, Maine. It boasts a total reach into 11 million homes,
but only about 4 million of those are via cable. And that reach is
out of about 76 million homes that get either cable or satellite
television services.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a typical story for a new network,'' said Alan
Breznick, national affairs editor for Cable World magazine. ``It's
very hard to get distribution at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Venerable computer magazine publisher Ziff-Davis launched the
station one year ago with two ambitious goals: to make interesting
programs about computers, and to sell those to a marketplace that's
saturated with television networks.
</P>
<P>
   It produces six hours of programming a day, which it then
repeats three times. Many of the shows are live. The station is
constantly considering new shows and trying out concepts in its
existing shows to see what might work as a spin-off.
</P>
<P>
   The current lineup includes ``Call for Help,'' which advises
viewers on how to use their home computers, and ``The Screen
Savers,'' a similar show with a geekier audience; ``Silicon Spin,''
sort of a high-tech ``McLaughlin Group'' hosted by the curmudgeonly
John C. Dvorak; a news show, ``Internet Tonight''; ``Fresh Gear,''
veteran tech writer Jim Louderback's look at the latest gadgets;
and ``The Money Machine,'' a primer on using computers and the
Internet to make money.
</P>
<P>
   Among ZDTV's striking differences are what it calls a ``Netcam
Network'' _ tiny cameras that the station has sent to 2,500 viewers
(with plans to reach 10,000 eventually) so that viewers can chat
live on the air as if they're guests on ``Nightline'' _ and
``live'' animated characters Tilde and Dash, who speak to viewers
in real time thanks to humans wired behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   At launch, Ziff-Davis said it was prepared to spend $100 million
on the endeavor, and analysts expect ZDTV to lose $30 million to
$35 million this year. Last year, ZDTV scored a $54 million
investment from Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, which gives him a
33 percent stake in the venture. Allen is one of the country's
largest cable operators, and ZDTV chief executive Larry Wangberg
said that should help get the network into more homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wangberg, 56, a cable industry veteran, booms with enthusiasm at
his new high-tech career. He points to eager viewer response and
advertising from big tech firms like Microsoft, Oracle, Dell
Computer and Sun Microsystems as evidence of growing success. The
next step is to sign up big mainstream advertisers, like carmakers;
Wangberg said it's about to happen, but he can't give specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ZDTV faces stiff competition from other cable networks, whether
they're already out there like the Cartoon Network or Robert
Redford's Sundance Channel, or whether they're even newer startups
like a planned National Geographic channel.
</P>
<P>
   Until it hits 20 million homes, Nielsen, the television ratings
firm, won't even assess ZDTV's share of viewership.
</P>
<P>
   TCI's Johnson notes the numbers that stack up against any new
network. ZDTV is one of 176 networks competing for slots. The
average cable lineup has about 60 slots. Stations that the Federal
Communications Commission requires to be carried take up about half
those offerings. Cable systems with digital offerings can fit an
extra 36 channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there's 70 spaces &UR;  &LR; and 170 competing,'' TCI's
Johnson said. ``We're no different than your local Safeway. If
there's demand for your product, we'll put it on our shelf. If it
doesn't sell, we'll take it off and replace it with something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   TCI is likely to hear from some of ZDTV's rabid fans. Jim
Gabbert of Sausalito, the former owner of KOFY-TV (Channel 20),
watches ZDTV over his DirecTV satellite dish. ``I think they do a
lot of neat things,'' he said. ``TCI should be crucified for not
carrying them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ZDTV is the only TV network dedicated to computers, it
isn't the only TV programming about computers. Silicon Valley's own
Stewart Cheifet pioneered computing television 15 years ago when he
created ``The Computer Chronicles'' for PBS, and Cheifet also
co-hosts the PBS show the ``Net Cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   Other network affiliates and cable stations offer computer
shows. In the Bay Area, KRON-TV produces ``New Media News,'' which
appears on KRON and BayTV (both of which are owned by Chronicle
Publishing Co.).
</P>
<P>
   Cnet, a San Francisco firm that competes fiercely with
Ziff-Davis' online publications, produces five television shows
with a sixth on the way. Most of those shows air on USA Networks
and the Sci-Fi channel, with some showing on local stations such as
KRON and KPIX.
</P>
<P>
   Although ZDTV says it doesn't view Cnet as competition, Greg
Drebin, ZDTV's senior vice president of programming and production,
offers a pungent assessment of Cnet's offerings: ``I defy anybody
to tell me when they're on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of Cnet's shows bounce around the programming
schedule, others have regular time slots on stations that have a
broad reach. USA and Sci-Fi are in 77 million and 55 million homes
respectively, said Dan Sexton, vice president of Cnet television.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet had initially contemplated a cable network well before ZDTV
launched, but Sexton said, ``Financially, it just did not make
sense to us. It made more sense to attach our programming to
existing cable networks that had more carriage.''
</P>
<P>
   While ZDTV works to get picked up by more cable systems, some
observers hope to see the channel look to Wall Street for more
financial backing. For one thing, said Larry Gerbrandt, senior
analyst with the Carmel media research firm Paul Kagan Associates,
no cable networks are traded on the public stock market; those that
were, like Black Entertainment Television, the Nashville Network
and the Family Channel, have either been taken private or been
acquired by larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   ZDTV doesn't reveal specifics about its finances, but Wangberg
says it operates at a loss and will continue to do so for the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   These days, that often spells success in the stock market, but
CEO Wangberg is coy about any potential public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's environment, some people can't help but think about
that, but there's nothing specific in the works that would be
happening any time soon,'' Wangberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Just because ZDTV is the first computer network out there is no
guarantee of success, but its timing and its deep pockets do give
it a leg up, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niche businesses like ZDTV are the future of video
programming,'' said Gary Arlen, president of Arlen Communications,
a Maryland media research firm. ``If Ziff is willing to sustain it
for three or four years, I think it has a good chance of long-term
success.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
