<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9246 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZDTVSIDE-ZDTVSIDE_SFC     05-16 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZDTVSIDE-ZDTVSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 A Day in the Life of ZDTV's `The Screen Savers' Show
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Dan Fost  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
``Geek'' is a word you hear a lot on the set of ``The Screen
Savers.''
</P>
<P>
   The hosts of the &UR;  &LR; daily hourlong ZDTV show refer to themselves
as geeks. The producer says he's a geek. The viewers? Geeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geekiness is good,'' says Kate Botello, the 27-year-old
co-host.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast veteran Leo Laporte plucked Botello as his co-host
from the geekiest of careers. She's gone from working in
Ziff-Davis' information services department to being a star on the
company's new television station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got caught doing my Judy Garland impression at the laser
printer, and that's how I bonded with Leo,'' Botello says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The computer-advice show includes a mix of interviews and
product reviews, but mostly it's Botello and Laporte chatting with
viewers about how to get the most out of their computers. Botello
is the young, female, red-headed, hyperactive foil to Laporte's
mature, silver-haired authority.
</P>
<P>
   Laporte, 43, has broadcast television and radio shows about
computers for most of the past decade. He and Botello are living
proof that television about computers does not have to be, in the
words of ZDTV chief executive Larry Wangberg, ``Two guys in lab
coats talking about the latest chip technology.'' It can be perky,
silly and interactive _ and actually help people solve their
computing problems.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day on the show starts at midmorning as the staff
files in to ZDTV's offices in the former San Francisco Fashion
Center at 650 Townsend St. With its white walls, white pipe
railings and bizarre curves and corridors, Botello calls the
building ``the S.S. Townsend.''
</P>
<P>
   Botello and Laporte maintain cubicles among the producers and
directors who work on the show; no dressing rooms with stars on
them here.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers spend at least part of the morning sifting through the
more than 600 e-mails Laporte gets each day, looking for trends and
for interesting questions that could be answered on the air. On his
drive home each evening, Laporte calls in from his car phone and
dictates answers to the questions.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, producer Ken Marcus, Laporte, Botello and a team of six
others gather in a conference room for the daily meeting. The
staffers have a variety of roles: working on the show's ``Netcam
Network,'' writing for the Web site tied to the show, lining up
guests for each day's episode and making sure the computers on the
set actually work.
</P>
<P>
   As they file in, Botello takes out a personal digital assistant
and shows off a drawing that a viewer e-mailed to her _ a cross
between Botello and Lara Croft, the animated star of the computer
game Tomb Raider. ``It's Screen Raider,'' Botello says. ``Isn't
that cool?''
</P>
<P>
   The fan response to the show is at times overwhelming to the
stars. On their first public appearance, in Las Vegas, more than
200 people lined up for four hours to meet Kate and Leo. More than
700 people turned out at Staples and Gateway stores in Pennsylvania
and New Jersey, including people wanting them to autograph their
motherboards, and a family of five wearing geeky glasses just like
Botello's and announcing, ``Amaze Yourself!'' _ the ZDTV slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Botello, who speaks in the rapid delivery of a stand-up
comedian, says her ``rubber face'' serves her well on camera. She
once pursued a career in theater, working as an understudy in the
San Francisco revue ``Beach Blanket Babylon,'' performing in skits
as Hillary Clinton, Ivana Trump and a dancing trash can. Of her
goofy television persona, she says, ``I actually am more weird than
I am on the air, and I have to tone myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   During the noon meeting, Botello throws in an occasional
wisecrack, but Marcus generally moves it along. They discuss that
evening's show and outline the show that will air one week later.
It's over in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members break for lunch and spends the afternoon
performing their tasks: updating the Web site, making sure the chat
software is working after a glitch sidetracked it the night before,
arranging the viewers who will appear on the show via their
netcams.
</P>
<P>
   The netcam network is huge. 3Com Corp., the computer networking
company, is giving &UR;  &LR; away 10,000 ``netcams'' for ZDTV viewers. These
little cameras sit atop viewers' monitors and are used to send in
video e-mails or to chat live on the air with the hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the netcam star has a superfast Internet connection, the
quality often is herky-jerky motions that don't synch with the
sounds. ZDTV has handed out the netcams to everyone from young
children to retirees, from Houston to Neptune City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a promotional video of a guy named Al in Shreveport,
La., touting ZDTV on his netcam, ZDTV Vice President Greg Drebin
says, ``What other channel would this guy get a chance to be on?
The Internet is a level playing field. You don't have to look like
Mary Hart or John Tesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, Botello hops in a ZDTV van that shuttles
her to the station's studio, in a converted industrial building on
Potrero Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The station runs two 8,000-square-foot studios, each with fully
digital control rooms. Each studio has several sets, which look
small in person but much larger and more sophisticated on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Screen Savers'' set has the look of ``Wayne's World,'' a
dorky basement cluttered with computers. Botello starts working on
the technical side of the show, installing software she might need
to use on the air. If she does it herself, she can talk about it
more cogently on the air.
</P>
<P>
   She crawls beneath a computer, unplugging and plugging in wires.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Laporte has arrived and gone straight to another set,
where he does another live show, ``Call for Help.'' That's the
less-techie sibling of ``The Screen Savers,'' in which Laporte
answers questions from children and new PC users. Botello calls it
``Mr. Leo's Neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Laporte used to talk for eight hours straight on the
radio, he says he can do two live shows in one day, when such an
endeavor would exhaust other ZDTV hosts. &UR;  &LR; Plus, he has what Botello
calls an ``encyclopedia brain'' crammed with computing knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   After his live episode of ``Call for Help'' ends, a tired
Laporte heads upstairs to a clothes rack and changes his shirt for
``The Screen Savers.''
</P>
<P>
   Laporte already has had his makeup applied by the time Botello
goes in to artist Kadidja Sallak's cramped office. Her red hair _
``it's my hair color; I paid for it'' _ is curled and combed, and
she comes out ready for show time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other staffers are arriving. Camera operators wheel
giant contraptions onto the set, snapping cameras in place. Marcus,
the producer, makes sure everything is set in the control room.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:20 p.m. _ 40 minutes to airtime _ Marcus convenes a quick
staff meeting on the set. Seventeen people form a circle. Everyone
runs through a script of each of the seven segments and the breaks
in between.
</P>
<P>
   While the final technical details fall into place, Laporte and
Botello warm up the crowd in the ZDTV way: They log into a chat
room. ``This is the live audience,'' Laporte says. ``If they get
bored, they'll write, `Snooooore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus takes his seat in a control room. A computer monitor
shows him the script. A wall of TV monitors shows what's happening
on the set. He's wearing a headset and has a row of buttons he can
push to communicate with different people, from the camera
operators to the directors to Laporte and Botello.
</P>
<P>
   The show's opening plays, and then it's Laporte and Botello,
yakking away on live television. They discuss the latest upgrade to
Windows98, ask viewers to respond to an online poll and take a call
from a young man in French Creek, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   When the caller rambles on with irrelevant questions, Marcus _
watching time tick away _ yells into his headset, ``Lose him!''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the show runs smoothly. Laporte and Botello tease
each other and banter with callers.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts continually tease an upcoming segment with Industrial
Light and Magic effects wizards Dave Latour and Rudy Bloss, who
will show the technology behind the movie ``The Mummy.'' The crew,
getting caught up in the hype, wraps production assistant Roger
Chang in toilet paper and has him stagger across the set on camera
as one segment segues to a break.
</P>
<P>
   As the show winds down, Wendy from Bethel, Conn., comes in on a
netcam. ``Right before we went on the air with her, she froze,''
Marcus says, looking at the still photo of Wendy on the screen. He
shrugs. ``It's the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus actually likes when things like that happen: It shows the
viewers that the show is truly live and that computers do screw up.
``It's good TV,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Laporte wraps it up: ``Remember, my friends, believe in
technology, but keep your hands out of the hard drive at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   The set is broken down almost instantly while advertisements
play on the air. Marcus gathers up his files in the control room.
``I gotta get out of here. News is coming in in half an hour,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Laporte and Botello close out the chat rooms, and the staff
files out of the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was show No.273,'' Marcus says. ``I have 273 hours of
live television under my belt. I think there were only 70 episodes
of `I Love Lucy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the dark studio, the sun is still shining on Multimedia
Gulch. Some staffers get into the van to head back to Townsend
Street; Botello and Laporte have their cars handy.
</P>
<P>
   On his ride back home to the North Bay, Laporte begins dictating
answers to viewers' questions for tomorrow's show, episode 274.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
