<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9247 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-NETFILES_SFC     05-16 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
 FILES _ SF CHRON  
 THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  Ruling May Mold Online Advice Giving 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
It lacks the sizzle of cybersex and economic clout of encryption,
but a First Amendment lawsuit now in progress could set the bounds
for government regulation of speech and commerce on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Ricardo Urbina of Washington, D.C., is
expected this week to rule in the case. At issue: whether the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission is trampling the rights of Web
sites, newsletter publishers and software developers that give
investing advice by subjecting them to stringent licensing
procedures that include taking fingerprints and conducting
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're being treated like criminals,'' said Scott Bullock,
senior attorney at the Institute for Justice, a civil-libertarian
law firm that is suing the CFTC on behalf of the plaintiffs. ``It's
amazing that the federal government is fingerprinting people before
they can establish a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if these advisers are taking people's money and
investing it in the market,'' Bullock said. ``This has cast a chill
over the investment community.''
</P>
<P>
   The CFTC, which regulates the commodity and futures markets in
the United States, contends that it must license individuals
working in those markets _ including anyone paid for opinions and
general information about commodities. In 1995, the four-member
commission, wary of the growing influence of the Web, began
actively enforcing its policy.
</P>
<P>
   Publications like the Wall Street Journal and Barron's are
exempt from the rule because they give ``incidental'' commodity
trading advice as part of a general-purpose news service. The
Institute for Justice's clients in the current case exclusively
provide commodity trading advice, according to Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Registration can be demeaning. Commodities advisers are not only
fingerprinted and investigated, but must divulge subscriber lists
and endure on-the-spot audits, according to Bullock. An adviser who
fails to register faces up to $500,000 in fines and five years in
prison, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable. There is no such registration process required
by any other government agency,'' said plaintiff Stephen Briese,
publisher of Bullish Review of Commodity Insiders, a Web site and
newsletter based in Gulf Breeze, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   CFTC officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The case has far-reaching implications, according to free-speech
advocates. A victory for the plaintiffs would ``send an arrow''
through future attempts by government agencies to regulate
commentary in newsletters and Web sites deemed ``expert advice'' by
the government, Bullock said. That could reverberate into other
areas as diverse as medical and legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   A favorable decision also may halt an alarming trend: government
suits against publishers of self-help information. In January, a
Texas federal district court ruled that Parsons Technology's
Quicken Family Lawyer software amounted to an ``unlicensed practice
of law.'' The court subsequently banned the product's sale in
Texas, presumably to protect the ``uninformed and unwary from
overly simplistic legal advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons of Hiawatha, Iowa, is appealing the decision to the U.S.
Court of Appeals In New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A STUDY IN CONTRASTS: File this under cruel fate: Less than a week
after Marimba went public in a stock offering valued at more than
$1 billion, PointCast was sold for relative chump change _ $7
million _ to an obscure Southern California software company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Both companies were pioneers of ``push'' technology, which
automatically delivered customized news and information to
consumers' desktop computers. Why such different outcomes?
</P>
<P>
   After push lost its, well, oomph, Marimba of Mountain View
refined its business plan in late 1997 and, with the guidance of
influential venture capitalist John Doerr, was able to mollify
investors. Virtually overnight, it recast itself from a news
provider to a distributor of software programs for corporate
networks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``They were smart enough to realize they needed to change
quickly or fall by the wayside like all the other push companies,''
said Allen Weiner, vice president of services at NetRatings Inc. in
Milpitas. &UR;  &LR; ``Marimba identified a problem that enterprise companies
had and turned its focus on a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Marimba also remained patient with its management team. Chief
executive Kim Polese doggedly sold the new and improved company
while pursuing an IPO. ``Kim did a fabulous job of holding things
together _ both as a leader and a strategist,'' said Jim Breyer,
managing partner at Accel Partners, a Palo Alto venture capital
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Added another venture capitalist, who requested anonymity, ``I
still don't have a clue what they do, but they're worth $1 billion.
PointCast would kill for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PointCast's sorry end was sad but hardly surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, LaunchPad Technologies of San Diego essentially
agreed to buy PointCast for $7 million in stock and cash. LaunchPad
makes eWallet, which lets online users store credit card
information on their personal computers to simplify e-commerce
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The price is a pittance for PointCast, which exploded on the
Internet landscape as the progenitor of ``push'' technology.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the Sunnyvale company was so hot that it spurned a
$450 million takeover bid from media magnate Rupert Murdoch in
early 1997 in hopes of striking it even richer with a stock
offering. In that instance, greed was not good.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street soured on push _ which was criticized for clogging
corporate networks with too much data _ and eventually balked at
PointCast's IPO. Chris Hassett, co-founder and CEO, was jettisoned
in mid-1997 and former Pacific Bell CEO David Dorman immediately
stepped in. By then, PointCast's number of subscribers was stagnant
at 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dorman _ who vowed to take PointCast public within a year,
scotched those plans in 1998 and vainly pursued a buyer _ resigned
in March to run a new $10 billion venture between AT&AMP;T and British
Telecommunications PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a technology pact in which PointCast would supply
high-speed Internet access to a consortium of Baby Bells fizzled,
and PointCast fired a third of its then 220-person staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``PointCast was slower than Marimba to make a transition from
consumer-technology provider to enterprise provider,'' said Ken
Andersen, assistant managing editor of Venture Finance newsletter
in San Francisco. ``It cost them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ZEEKS, NOT GEEKS: Parental alert: a kids-friendly Web site that
includes free filtering software. Pierian Spring Software of
Portland, Ore., has constructed and opened a portal site for
children ages 6-13. The rainbow-colored, accessible Zeeks.com
( &LR; www.zeeks.com &LR; ) is chock full of e-mail, games, Web design tools,
calendar, searches and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
KOSOVO AID RESULTS: Yahoo Auctions so far has raised $40,000 for
Kosovo refugees in a celebrity fund-raiser it organized last month.
Fetching the most dough were a Michael Jordan autographed
basketball ($7,210), signed size-22 shoes from Shaquille O'Neal
($4,510) and a life-size storm trooper figure from ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' ($2,260).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Will 21st century cemeteries be all-digital? See what you think,
at  &LR; www.memorialwebpark.com &LR; . Meanwhile, a digital temple to Sir
Francis Bacon ( &LR; www.sirbacon.org &LR; ) _ celebrated English essayist,
philosopher and statesman _ brings home the bacon on this literary
giant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't miss the party at  &LR; www.classreunionsearch.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
