<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZOOM-ZOOM_SFCHRON &LR;      05-16 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZOOM-ZOOM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 `Smart' Vending Machines Deliver Merchandise, Ads
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Care for an ad with that inkjet cartridge?
</P>
<P>
   Zoom Systems, a San Francisco company, has developed a ``smart''
vending machine that delivers targeted advertisements along with
merchandise such as printer supplies and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom's ``E-Station'' looks like a Space Age vending machine
crossed with a touch-screen ATM. The screen interface allows a user
to ask for product information, such as which kind of cartridge to
use with his or her printer. And the manufacturer can send
promotional messages tailored to users' buying patterns.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an office manager might go to an E-Station in her
building, insert her company credit card and order a
Hewlett-Packard inkjet cartridge. HP might then flash her an offer
for 50 percent off a second cartridge or explain why its
next-generation printer is better than the one she has.
</P>
<P>
   Because the office manager's credit card identifies her on every
visit, the machine can keep track of her purchases and remind her
when it's time to buy toner for the office photocopy machine.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, which are connected to the Internet, also can
monitor inventory, so manufacturers know which products are selling
and when to restock them. Information from each machine is
collected in databases that the product-makers can access from
 &LR; www.zoomsystems.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Although other vending machine-makers use Web technology to
track inventory, only E-Station has an interface that allows
information to flow between manufacturer and customer. Zoom has
filed 200 patent claims, the first in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing a customer is predisposed to buy a certain item
presents a very good opportunity for a manufacturer to make a
higher margin sale,'' said Shawn Milne, research analyst with
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's E-Services Group. ``The whole service world is
trying to drive repeat business from existing customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, privacy advocates aren't likely to take a shine to
E-Station's information gathering any more than they like similar
setups on Web sites and supermarket scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Gower Smith, Zoom's chief executive, said E-Stations do not know
users' names, demographic profile or other personal information.
Repeat buyers are known only through identifiers on their corporate
cards or employee numbers, similar to the way a Web site can track
an individual's behavior whenever she visits the site, but doesn't
know who the person is.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom plans to use more personalized information down the line,
but only if users voluntarily register, said Smith. The information
will never be sold to third parties, he added.
</P>
<P>
   HP is the first manufacturer to test the machines, installing 10
in Tempe, Ariz., in fall 1997. &UR;  &LR; Zoom's Smith said he is also
talking to Home Depot, Gap and Joe Boxer about using E-Stations.
</P>
<P>
   HP has ordered 200 more machines and plans to install the first
local E-Stations by the end of the summer in Silicon Valley
offices. A European rollout is in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines allow shoppers to avoid the hassle of finding
merchandise in a store and standing in a checkout line. And of
course, the machines are open around the clock: nights, weekends
and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Smith foresees potential sales of T-shirts, aspirin and other
consumer items at hotels and airports; office supplies in office
complexes; frequently purchased items such as nails outside stores
like Home Depot; and Barbie dolls in machines outside toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   For manufacturers, vending machines are an opportunity to
eliminate the high costs of selling through stores.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines can generate very high sales. For example, San
Francisco's Joe Boxer Inc. sells underwear out of about 20 vending
machines located mostly in department stores. Sales per square foot
from the machines run about $2,600 per year, said Joe Boxer chief
executive Nicholas Graham. That's about 10 times higher than sales
per square foot at an average mall store.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he considers his company's Web-wired vending
machines, which are able to track stock levels, a success. But he
said he is interested in E-Stations for their interactive
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   For now Zoom does not intend to go after the traditional vending
market of snacks and soda. Higher-ticket items are more profitable,
and the company's model makes more sense ``where information helps
make a sale,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom, which moved to the Bay Area in January from Sydney,
Australia, expects to roll out several hundred E-Stations this year
and thousands in 2000. In the next three to five years, Zoom
expects sales of merchandise through E-Stations to reach $500
million annually in the United States alone, said Dan Enright,
Zoom's sales director.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom will either lease its machines for a monthly service fee of
about $250, or sell them. The cost of purchase includes $2,000 to
$2,500 for the vending machine and additional costs for the PC, the
touch screen and other components.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is home to 6.6 million conventional vending
machines that generate sales of $19 billion to $28 billion,
according to the National Automated Merchandising Association.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
