<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers content with second pick
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A weighted lottery didn't help the Thrashers' seeding
in the upcoming entry draft Sunday. More importantly, it didn't
hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   They will pick second in the June 26 draft, giving Atlanta
general manager Don Waddell a shot at either of two high-scoring
natives of the Czech Republic: Patrik Stefan, who played this
season with Long Beach of the International Hockey League, or Pavel
Brendl of Calgary of the Western Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had only a 3.7 percent chance of holding the winning
number but had 3-4-6-7 among its allotment when those ping-pong
balls popped out of a machine at the NHL office in New York,
allowing the Blackhawks to move from eighth to fourth. But the
lottery did not affect the top three selections: Tampa Bay, the
Thrashers and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a (16.9) percent chance to move to No. 1, but there was
a much greater chance of us moving down,'' Waddell said. ``We
would've loved to move up, but it was crucial for us to not drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan is ranked by the NHL's Central Scouting as the top player
in North America in the draft, one ahead of Brendl. But the
Thrashers may have a shot at him because Stefan is a center and
Brendl is a right winger, a position of greater need for Tampa Bay.
The Lightning also may shop its pick to other teams. But there are
health concerns with Stefan, who suffered at least two concussions
this season and played only an abbreviated season. Daniel Sedin of
Sweden is considered the next best player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said if Stefan is healthy, ``He's the most talented
player in the draft.'' Waddell, who at Sunday's lottery clutched a
rabbit's foot given to him by his daughter, Chelsea, will get
another close look at Brendl this week in Ottawa when he attends
the Memorial Cup _ the Canadian juniors Final Four, which includes
Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
