<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORKS-SITCOMS-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS THRIVE, EVEN AS MEDIA BUSINESS SHIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even as a revolution rages around them _ one that
they acknowledge is changing their world in ways they cannot yet
begin to calculate fully _ television network executives have sat
in rooms in the last few weeks, huddled in small groups, taking
part in an annual ritual as old as the medium itself.
</P>
<P>
   They were picking sitcoms for the fall season.
</P>
<P>
   But the process is taking place with a greater sense of urgency
this year. Faced with a continuing loss in audience and an
explosion in technological advances, the networks are attempting to
transform themselves into far more versatile institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered headed for extinction, the networks are
beginning to add new, interactive dimensions to their relationships
with viewers and advertisers. They are seeking to develop multiple
uses for their shows and sell products related to programs they
broadcast. And they are preparing for the day when the functions of
a TV set converge with those of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the networks' repositioning is the ability to
build and market hit entertainment shows. But the popularity of a
television show is beginning to take on even more importance _ ``an
outright necessity'' in the words of NBC president Robert Wright.
</P>
<P>
   For the networks, the hit show is the hub in a growing wheel of
interests: promotion platforms for related businesses; sales of
replays on cable television or even Internet sites; and the
creation of direct links between advertisers and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In one example of the latter, Wright envisions a viewer watching
a commercial for a Silverado truck, clicking on an on-screen icon
and being directed to information on the vehicle, the places where
it can be bought nearby, and perhaps even a number to call to order
one.
</P>
<P>
   Networks have already moved into marketing and selling compact
discs based on the music offered in a television film _ in fact, a
CD from ``The '60s,'' a movie on NBC, is a hit. In coming years,
they may try to sell other items, like the fashions worn by the
star of a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   None of this would be happening if television shows were viewed
in the same way films or plays are. Partly because it became the
most pervasive and effective advertising medium ever created, and
partly because it is plugged into the home, television has always
been considered less art form than appliance.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the network industry tries to mutate from a model
that relies exclusively on commercials for its income to one that
also relies on electronic commerce, executives acknowledge that
they must not lose their focus on their core business _ show
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's still all about the content,'' said Robert
Iger, the chairman of ABC Group, a unit of Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   No one is convinced that the networks can transform themselves
from old media to new media. But a degree of rethinking is taking
place concerning what has been a foregone conclusion: that the
networks, whose share of the audience has declined from 69 percent
to 55 percent in the last five years, would die a not-all-that-slow
death.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than contemplate their deaths, the networks, in fact,
expect advertisers to set a record of nearly $7 billion in advance
purchases of commercial time for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The network prime-time sales process, not much different from
the days of ``I Love Lucy,'' begins this week in elegant locations
in Manhattan, from Carnegie Hall to Lincoln Center to the New
Amsterdam Theater. That is where the networks will introduce their
new prime-time program schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The situation seems to defy logic: Networks' advertising
revenues are soaring, even though their projected 8 percent
increase is matched by an almost identical percentage decline in
the size of network audiences this year.
</P>
<P>
   But competition for viewers has been multiplying exponentially
on cable and the Internet. So the power of even a diminished mass
medium to reach tens of millions of people at once makes broadcast
networks more valuable to advertisers, not less.
</P>
<P>
   That is just one incongruity the networks face as they try to
navigate a roiling media sea they once towered over. Among the
others: Networks in some ways are benefiting from the increasing
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Though they cannot begin to afford to buy high-flying stars of
the new media like America Online or Yahoo, the networks have
become the centerpiece of the marketing and promotion strategies
that such companies pursue. Internet companies are buying so much
commercial time that they are helping the networks set those new
ad-revenue records.
</P>
<P>
   And even in instances when networks have given Internet
companies commercial time in exchange for equity stakes in them,
the networks wind up benefiting indirectly. By cutting the overall
amount of time they have available, the networks can raise the
rates on their remaining inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Few network executives are entirely bullish about long-term
prospects, though. They cannot see an end point to the
technological advances, from Internet expansion to digital delivery
of television signals that are producing what Iger called
``monumental seismic shifts'' in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows where the earth is going to stop moving,'' Iger
said. ``Really, it's never going to stop moving. So it's almost
imperative to know when to jump in and when to jump out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, jumping in has meant, among other things,
investment in Internet companies. ABC and NBC acquired Internet
portals, Go and Snap, respectively, and CBS took interests in a
number of smaller Internet businesses like Marketwatch.com and
Office.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see the Internet as much more an opportunity than a
threat,'' said Wright of NBC, a unit of General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rogers, the president of NBC business development, said:
``The traditional network business may be challenged. But there is
upside potential as well, given a network's ability to reinvent
itself and develop value that is hugely bigger over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The same force that is driving up advertising revenue even as
audiences decline is providing the networks with what some predict
will be significant benefits as soon as next year. ``The incredible
promotional platform represented by the networks is going to
provide them with big opportunities,'' said Jessica Reif-Cohen, an
analyst for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have taken steps to exert more authority over their
affiliated stations and cut costs through layoffs and tightened
reins on program expenses, Ms. Reif-Cohen noted, and she predicted
that ``investor sentiment will swing wildly in favor of the
broadcast networks this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Such forecasts fly in the face of the expectations of rivals in
cable television and new media industries. Most of them continue to
dismiss the networks as dinosaurs trying to stave off extinction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one senior Internet executive called the networks'
Internet strategy largely meaningless. They will never be able to
be big enough in that industry to be significant players, the
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least some of what they are doing now is just trying not to
look left out,'' this executive said. ``I sympathize with them. If
I were in their business, I wouldn't know what to do either.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The networks want to protect their economic base, while they
reinvent themselves. That means squeezing every area of costs they
can. For example, networks have long paid studios a flat fee for
the rights to two broadcasts of a show. But Iger said the system
simply ``does not work anymore,'' because the fees have escalated
prohibitively after four years if the show turns out to be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   For networks now, he said, it becomes untenable if some other
party controls the economic future of a program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be able to gain some share of the upside that the
new technology allows,'' Iger said.
</P>
<P>
   One result of that strategy is a move toward even more vertical
integration, with networks trying to own every piece of programming
they can. Deal-making with the studios has become a blood sport.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, senior executives at Hollywood production studios said
the demands by networks for ownership in shows have turned
deal-making into, as one described it, ``the wild West _ there are
no rules at all, a deal isn't a deal anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks expect to capitalize by replaying _ or in their
term ``repurposing'' _ shows on digital channels or cable channels
that they own. ABC plans to do that with soap operas it owns on a
proposed Soap Opera Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the possibility, through the technology of video
streaming, of showing programs on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The networks also expect to sell products related to their
shows, though Wright of NBC said that is so far a very small part
of their business plan. ``Today it isn't much of a business, but it
may be quite attractive in two to three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the same desire to control as much of their destiny as
possible, the networks continue to press to own more television
stations. Federal regulations limit them to owning stations that
reach 35 percent of the country, and the networks are lobbying to
raise that percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said one threat facing the networks is consolidation by
cable companies _ typified by last week's deal in which Cox
Communications bought TCA Cable. He said cable systems could soon
reach enough viewers in a single city to become serious competitors
of local broadcast stations for local ad revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the revenue situation is going to get any worse
at the national level, but we're going to see impact on the local
component,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which is owned by News Corp., has been less active in
aligning with Internet sites _ though Peter Chernin, chairman of
Fox Entertainment Group, said the company would be announcing some
deals in the next few weeks. But he argued that any convergence of
the TV set with the computer would only enhance the company's
position, because of its 40 percent interest in the TV Guide cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   He called that channel, which identifies what TV shows are on
what cable channels, ``the mother of all portals.''
</P>
<P>
   But network executives still question how much interaction
viewers will have with their television sets, even after the sets
are wired to be online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the functions of television and computer will stay
separate,'' Wright said, ``with the notable exception of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports is already awash in informational asides _ like on-base
percentages in baseball and average yards gained after a catch in
football. Thus, sports is expected to be the first area that
technophiles dabble with when they can interact with their
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   With entertainment shows, though, ``I just think that people
still will want to watch just to relax,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   To Iger, much more in doubt is what the next generation of
television viewers _ what he called ``the mouse-click generation''
_ will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids have been raised to be multitaskers,'' he said.
``They're comfortable being active rather than passive, and that
should not be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   As the networks consider their priorities, a leading executive
in the wired world, Robert Pittman, the president of America
Online, has one helpful suggestion: ``My advice to the networks
would be, stick to your knitting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
