<HEADLINE>
GORE OUTLINES PLAN TO IMPROVE EDUCATION  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Iowa) (rk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAMONI, Iowa _ In what political aides described as his first
policy speech of the presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore
called Sunday for ``revolutionary change'' and substantial federal
investment in education. He advocated universally available
pre-school for 3- and 4-year-olds, the creation of a teachers corps
of new graduates for neglected schools, rigorous tests for new
teachers, the elimination of large high schools and legal
protection for parents who visit their children's teachers during
the work day.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a college graduation ceremony in southern Iowa a day
after opening his campaign headquarters in Des Moines, Gore said
education was the key to meeting the country's economic, social and
moral challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us realize that education is the greatest anti-poverty
program,'' he said, ``the most powerful anti-discrimination
strategy we could ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to international comparisons showing American high
school students to be far below those of many other countries, and
he asked, ``How long can we stay first in making new discoveries if
we stay dead last out of all countries surveyed in physics?''
</P>
<P>
   While the vice president's proposals reflect a growing consensus
among educators and contain elements found in legislative plans at
the state and federal level, certain aspects are new in a
presidential campaign, notably the call for the universal
pre-school and the commitment for a teachers corps for schools in
need.
</P>
<P>
   Though southern Iowa is not a Democratic stronghold, the vice
president was warmly received at Graceland College, a conservative
Christian institution affiliated with the Reorganized Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, which broke with the Mormons in
the last century.
</P>
<P>
   His comments about high-quality pre-school and elevating the
teaching profession drew enthusiastic applause, as did his
assertion of the need for renewed focus on discipline, values and
safety in schools, all signs that focusing his domestic agenda on
education will meet with public approval.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statistics show that there are more children in school
this year than in any previous year in American history and the
number will rise every year for the next 10 years. Many political
races across the country last November, including those for
governors, representatives and senators, centered on education.
</P>
<P>
   While the education goals of the two major parties often seem to
resemble each other _ higher standards, better teachers, improved
safety _ a principal distinction between Republicans and Democrats
has been the opposition of Republicans to involving the federal
government in education. Republicans favor local control and local
standards and see a federal role as creating unwieldy, costly
structures for distant bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander, a Republican and former education secretary who
is hoping to gain his party's presidential nomination, reacted to
Gore's speech by saying it was the ``right church, wrong pew.''
</P>
<P>
   From his hometown, Maryville, Tenn., where he also was a giving
a college graduation speech, Alexander dismissed the vice
president's proposals as ``adding up to a national school board.''
Alexander said that instead of creating more federal education
programs, federal dollars should be sent back to local school
boards, parents and teachers to let them decide what is best for
their students.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Gore's said: ``Some say there is no national
role in helping communities improve their schools. I say that
education is our No. 1 national priority for investing in the
future. And we must take dramatic steps to help states and
communities provide a quality education for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor his aides would put a price on his new
proposals but they said all would fit within a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made seven recommendations : pre-school for all children;
improved teacher quality partly through creation of a federally
subsidized teachers corps; renewed focus on discipline and safety;
a fundamental reduction in the size of high schools; turn around
failing schools; improved technology for schools, and a tax-free
savings plan for parents and grandparents to pay for college
education.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the recommendations fell into three categories: those
that required substantial federal investment; those that would
involve modest investment; and those that relied essentially on
leadership. The high-cost items are the universal pre-school
program and the teacher corps.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the pre-school program is needed for two reasons.
First, he said, family life is changing. He said that in seven out
of 10 households, both parents work all day. While a generation
ago, 7 percent of American households were single-parent families,
today it is 27 percent. Second, he said, research has shown how
critical early education can be, leading to higher IQs and
achievement levels.
</P>
<P>
   Many states provide voluntary pre-school programs. Gore is
proposing that every state develop and expand its existing programs
through federal bloc grants so that every 3- and 4-year-old can
attend a good pre-school.
</P>
<P>
   On improved teacher quality, Gore proposed the creation of what
he called ``a new 21st century teachers corps open to talented
young people across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, students above a certain level in their
graduating class would be eligible to commit themselves to four
years of teaching in a high-need school. In exchange, the federal
government would give them $10,000 to pay for college. After that,
those willing to make teaching a career would be eligible for
another $10,000 as well as getting their teacher training paid off.
The average debt with which graduates leave college is $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the teacher corps graduates would have to pass a
rigorous test and advocated the same test for all new teachers as
well as five-year evaluations of teachers for license renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``No teaching license should be a lifetime guarantee,'' Gore
said. But he emphasized that teachers, a traditional support group
for Democrats, deserve respect. ``When I see politicians bash our
teachers, I have to wonder: How long would they last in a classroom
with 24 14-year-olds?''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, hailed the vice president's speech, saying she supported
his calls for new tests and evaluations to improve the quality of
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For pupils with discipline problems, Gore advocated the creation
of second-chance schools where troubled youngsters and those caught
with guns ``can receive the strict discipline and intensive
services they need.'' In many of the nation's biggest cities,
troubled students are simply expelled and the idea of second-chance
schools is gaining attention.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid producing troubled students, Gore offered a proposal:
that parents, teachers and students meet on the first day of school
every year to agree on and sign a discipline code. This would
increase links between parents and schools. He added that parents
must be given the legal right to take off from work for that and
subsequent teacher meetings. Aides said that would come through
extension of the federal Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he favored increasing the ability of parents to choose
a public school for their children outside their neighborhoods but
opposed the use of vouchers supported by public money to send
children to private schools. Vouchers are favored by many
Republican candidates as a way to expand school choice and instill
competition in the system. Gore said that would siphon public
school financing.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ended by calling for a National Tuition Savings program
bringing together disparate state plans for tax-free,
inflation-proof savings for college by parents and grandparents. He
also urged that employers help employees save tax-free for college
and job training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We help people save for retirement tax-free and help them pay
their mortgages tax-free,'' he said. ``Now we must help them save
tax-free for one of the biggest expenses most families will ever
face in life, sending a child to college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
