<SLUG> BC-REAL-NETWORKS-SNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH ENGINE FOR AUDIO AND VIDEO WILL SHOW ADVERTISING WHILE YOU
WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ In a deal that will aim advertising at the
growing millions who listen to music and watch video on the
Internet, Real Networks Inc., a multimedia software maker, and
Snap.com, an Internet hub, plan to announce on Monday that they are
starting a search engine that will find content on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said the search engine would be embedded in copies
of Real Player G2, a free program from Real Networks that enables
people to listen to music and watch video over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Users of the Real Player program will be able to search the
Internet for music, other audio or video files that can be played
using the software.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that when users begin the process, they will be
taken to a Web site (http://real.snap.com), sponsored by both Real
Networks and Snap.com, that will display advertising while the
search is under way. Snap.com, an Internet portal site owned
jointly by CNET and NBC, will provide the search engine technology
behind the site.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks says that about 60 million people have downloaded
the Real Player software, but that only 30 million have the latest
version, which is the Real Player G2. To use the search engine,
they must download an enhancement to the G2 player.
</P>
<P>
   Jay J. Wampold, a spokesman for Real Networks, said he expected
huge traffic for the search engine. ``The uptake on this will be
very quick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes a week after NBC Internet and Snap.com
announced that they would team with Xoom.com, a direct-marketing
company, to start a publicly traded company called NBCi. That deal
is unrelated to the one involving Real Networks, which is not
taking part in the NBCi project, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the search engine announcement, Real Networks said it
would provide the new site with its Real Guide directory service,
which provides links to sites with real audio and video
programming. Some 400,000 Web pages have such programming, with 85
percent of them featuring content in a format that can be listened
to or viewed using Real Player; other competing formats include ASF
from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Snap and Real Networks said that they were also planning to
start a multimedia search site for people who have high-speed
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The site (http://speed.snap.com) will include richer graphics
and the ability to download audio and video at faster speeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
