<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW OR NEVER IF TRINIDAD WANTS BOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clock is winding down on a possible Oscar De La Hoya-Felix
Trinidad fight for September.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, said he has offered Trinidad
$10 million and a percentage of pay-per-view revenues beyond 1
million homes to face De La Hoya on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   And if Arum doesn't get an answer by Wednesday, he said, he will
turn his attention to Ike Quartey for that date.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Trinidad's handlers _ principally his father, Felix
Sr. _ have demanded equal pay for the fighters, even though De La
Hoya is by far the bigger name and moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who defends his WBC welterweight title against Oba
Carr on Saturday, would earn up to $15 million against Trinidad, a
figure only he can command outside the upper echelons of the
heavyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The offer) is appreciably more than we paid for Whitaker, and
it's more than double what we paid for Quartey,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(HBO brought promoter Don) King and the father to a meeting in
New York (at the end of last week) to tell them: `Hey, the gravy
train stops if you don't take this fight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For once, King doesn't appear to be an impediment to the fight.
</P>
<P>
   King, Trinidad's promoter, has what Arum called ``a stupid
contract'' with the fighter that requires the promoter to pay a
reported $43 million for 12 fights. In other words, he NEEDS this
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he's convinced that Felix Trinidad Sr. is pricing
himself out because he really doesn't want the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impediment to the fight is not King but the father,'' Arum
said. ``The father doesn't want his son to fight De La Hoya. Don't
believe anything different. That's what the people in Puerto Rico
are saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figure he can fight these opponents and make what for
them is considerable money, a million or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was discussing it with (De La Hoya's) father, Joel, and
asked, `If your son could make a lot of money fighting a guy that
you're pretty sure he can't beat, would you take the fight?' He
said, `No, it wouldn't be worth it.' That's the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract is there. If he doesn't sign it, he's scared of
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Trinidad's people simply have an inflated view of
their fighter's marketability. Let's hope they don't hold out for
an unreasonable purse so long that the fight the world wants to see
falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who knows what a victory over Trinidad would mean to
his legacy, is one of those who holds this sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fight I really want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ A million homes? Arum's offer of a percentage of pay-per-view
revenue beyond a million homes is probably meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   No fight outside the heavyweight division has had a million
buys. This is the biggest lower-weight matchup out there but isn't
likely to crack a million.
</P>
<P>
   __ In the wings: Arum believes he'll have no problem making a
bout with Quartey if he can't come to terms with Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey knows he can't command a huge payday after losing a
close decision to De La Hoya in February and is eager to get it
right in a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   For the fans, De La Hoya-Quartey II isn't as compelling as De La
Hoya-Trinidad but will draw a lot of buys because of the first
fight, which was extremely competitive and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   __ So long Gil: De La Hoya said the Carr fight will be his last
with trainer Gil Clancy.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya said Clancy, one of the most respected names in
boxing, has been a valuable in working with principal trainer
Robert Alcazar.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fighter said he wants to revert back to the
aggressive knockout artist he was before he began bringing in new
trainers, back to what Alcazar has preached all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be me and Robert,'' De La Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gil is an excellent motivator, he's a person who has a lot of
knowledge of boxing. It's nothing against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the team I want.''
</P>
<P>
   __ What about Carr? With all the talk about Trinidad, Carr seems
to be getting overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Carr isn't seen as the threat Trinidad or Quartey are, but he's
capable. De La Hoya said he's well aware of that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm focused on Carr. You'll see on (Saturday),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Enter Mosley: ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley, the undefeated IBF
lightweight champion confirmed rumors when he said he wants to move
up to weight classes and fight De La Hoya, possibly at the new
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense from a business standpoint. No one in or around
his weight class is going to get him the payday he would get
against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   However, he would have little chance of winning. Even a fighter
as talented as Mosley can't expect to move up 12 pounds in weight
and beat one of the best fighters of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Mosley disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be no mismatch. If I hit him, I'll knock him
out,'' the normally reserved Mosley told the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya doesn't seem interested, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He was criticized much of his career for facing boxers who moved
up to HIS weight. He doesn't want to go through that again.
</P>
<P>
   __ No Vargas: One matchup will probably WON'T see anytime soon
is De La Hoya-Fernando Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, the IBF junior middleweight champ from Oxnard, has been
publicly critical of De La Hoya's character _ and De La Hoya has
had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never give Vargas a chance, never,'' he said. ``He's been
very disrespectful, he has no respect whatsoever. He doesn't
deserve an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya can see himself fighting another Olympian, WBA junior
middleweight champion David Reid. The prospect of one gold medalist
facing another is enticing.
</P>
<P>
   However, what if Reid fights Vargas first and then loses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'm in trouble,'' De La Hoya said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hamed-Tapia? Naseem Hamed called Arum last week for two
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One, he wanted to voice his objection to Arum's use of the term
``English fraud'' when referring to the flamboyant but untested
featherweight. And, two, he wanted to suggest a bout with WBA
bantamweight champ Johnny Tapia, who probably would have to go up
two weight classes (from 118 to 126 pounds) for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, he complained I called him an English fraud and we
talked about it,'' Arum said. ``And then he said, `Tell Johnny
Tapia I'd like to fight him before the end of the year.' It was an
interesting conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, who defends his title against Paulie Ayala on June 26 in
Las Vegas, is interested in a Hamed bout but said he would probably
move up to junior featherweight (122 pounds) first.
</P>
<P>
   He also said his focus is on Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm thinking about is June 26,'' he said. ``Too many
fighters have looked ahead and got knocked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia's trainer, Fred Roach, doesn't think a jump to 126 is
unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In a recent bout) Johnny weighed 118,'' he said. ``Going into
the ring, he weighed 130 pounds. Johnny's 5-foot-7, very strong.
Naseem is 5-foot-3. Johnny's a bigger person in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, Hamed punches hard. That's the only problem. But I
can't see Johnny Tapia, with his boxing skills, even getting
touched by this guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very unorthodox fighter. I think a good, basic boxer
from the American style will beat this guy. He's fighting all old
horses. I'd love that fight for Johnny. I don't care what the
weight class is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
