r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COLONIAL-DRIVING-     05-16 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-DRIVING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTANCE IS GOLF'S DRIVING OBSESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
``Drive for show, Putt for dough'' _ Ancient golf wisdom
``Hit it long, And you can't go wrong'' _ Modern golf thinking FORT
WORTH, Texas _ With some of the best golfers in the world in Fort
Worth this week for the MasterCard Colonial, area golf fans will
have a chance to watch some of the best putters and some of the
longest drivers on the PGA Tour.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the choice of watching a master greensman such as Loren
Roberts _ who won the Byron Nelson Classic yesterday _ or a master
blaster such as John Daly, there really is no choice, though. The
big hitters capture the attention every time. From the PGA Tour to
the local municipal course, distance is everything. Clubs hit
longer, balls go farther and tees are set back farther.
</P>
<P>
   Pros and high-handicappers alike are in hot pursuit of length at
any cost, especially accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to hit it from the back tees these days,''
said David Bridges, who has been playing golf for 50 years and
teaching it for 20, including a stint at Randol Mill Golf Center in
Fort Worth?????. ``If I had a sign up that said I can teach you how
to hit it farther, and a guy down the street had a sign that said
he'd teach you to hit it straighter, they'd all come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The lust for long ball is manifest in PGA Tour statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Dan Pohl led the PGA Tour in driving distance with an
average poke of 274.3 yards. Hit the ball that far in 1999 and you
will be about 34 yards behind the drives of PGA Tour distance
leader John Daly, whose average whack pushes toward 309. The game's
top players, David Duval and Tiger Woods, each drive it about 290
yards on average.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Hale Irwin averaged 250 yards a drive and won
a U.S. Open. Hit it 250 these days and you'll need a cart to catch
up to your playing partners.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, a short hitter by PGA Tour standards, said after his
third-round 62 at the Nelson that his ball striking had slipped
this year because he is attempting to increase his distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'm out trying to hit it a little farther,'' Roberts
said. ``Every golf course we play they're moving the tees back. You
want to have the shortest iron in your hand you can. Golf courses
are getting longer and harder now.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers say club and ball manufacturers are also responsible for
the distance craze as they try to increase sales by developing and
promoting equipment they say will add yards. Others cite
television's influence, noting that Daly's ``grip it and rip it''
philosophy is seductive even to duffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just see all the blood running out of their fingers,''
Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for yardage off the tee is the subject of countless
instructional videos and books. In the May issue of ``Golf
Digest,'' several articles, including the cover story, deal with
how to hit it farther.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: One teaching pro offered thoughts on how to hit it ``10
more yards.'' In ``Tiger Tips,'' Woods suggests golfers widen their
stance ``when you really want to crush it.'' Another piece, ``How
to buy more distance,'' offers suggestions on what clubs will help
you hit it farther.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's cover boy Jason Zuback, the three-time reigning
national long drive champion, who is shown in an inside photo
spread, frame by frame, as he grips it and rips it. It's a hack
Mark McGwire would be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Distance isn't a bad thing, of course. For one, it allows you to
hit beyond troublesome traps and over water. Also, it can make for
shorter, easier approach shots, the kind that allow you to hit the
ball high and soft, and to drop it close to the pin, giving you a
better chance on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming you hit it straight, though, and that's assuming
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Penneman of Arlington, a competitor in long-distance drive
events, typically hits it longer than 300 yards, and when
conditions are right can near 400 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said, ``I'd give up 25 yards if I could put it in the
fairway 50 percent more often.''
</P>
<P>
   On the PGA Tour, length has been a sticky issue. Traditionalists
fear that many revered older and shorter courses will be rendered
obsolete as pros find they are able to fly over obstacles en route
to record-smashing scores. Woods' taming of Augusta National two
years ago fueled such paranoia. There has been much debate about
restricting club and ball technology so munchkins don't hit them
300 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so alarmist, however. Greg Norman, in Fort Worth
recently, downplayed the distance issue.
</P>
<P>
   Length, schmength, he seemed to say. High handicappers still
can't break 100, and even pros aren't firing sub-60s week in and
week out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at average scores,'' Norman said. ``They aren't much
different than 30 or 40 years ago. Sam Snead once shot a 59 with
older-style equipment. It doesn't make as big a difference as some
people think.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
