<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Monday, May 17,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-CRUSADING GRANDMOTHER (Seattle)_ Gladis Spencer stood on
the road where Maya Streeter died, and wept. She wept for Streeter,
dead at 23. She wept for Streeter's three children, left
motherless. And she wept for Derek Spencer, her 20-year-old
grandson, whom she believes was wrongly convicted of shooting
Streeter during an East Tacoma party in 1997. Spencer's beliefs
have propelled the retired phone company worker into a two-year
odyssey to prove her grandson's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   By Elaine Porterfield. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-ACTIVIST (Seattle) _ He was a verbal ``bomb-thrower'' with
ACT-UP, an AIDS activist whose tools of the trade were dramatic
civil disobedience and protest. Lately, Steve Johnson has been
wearing a suit and tie, meeting with bureaucrats and elected
officials to affect change through more traditional means _
lobbying in the marble halls of Olympia, Wash., and Washington,
D.C. The transformation of Johnson, 35, in many ways mirrors how
AIDS as a social and political issue has changed in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MARITIME-SCHOOL (Seattle) _ Billed as the nation's first
workboat academy, the Seattle Central Community College seafaring
school is 30 years old this year, and newly retooled after nearly
going the way of the salmon. Some thought the school wouldn't reach
a fourth decade after it followed the nation's maritime industry
into a slump in the 1980s. Yet in the past six years the academy
has quietly been resurrected, renamed, and now runs on a
$400,000-a-year budget.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBAR SLUGGED MARITIME-GRADUATES.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MARITIME-GRADUATES (Seattle) _ After 11 years in the Army,
Shannon Robinson went through the Seattle Maritime Academy's
engineering technology course in 1995, and later it's two-week
captain's class. Robinson, 43, now skippers Argosy tour boats on
the Seattle waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-AUCTION (OAK HARBOR, Wash.) _ Is a pocket dictionary
autographed by George and Barbara Bush worth more than an
autographed copy of John Gray's ``Men are from Mars, Women are from
Venus''? The Oak Harbor Friends of the Library decided to raise
money through a book auction. So the group's members came up with
500 books they liked and asked the authors to donate a signed
version of each. About 190 replied, and the list goes from qaulity
to kitschy, from Philip Roth to Robert Shapiro (``D.A.'s Brief on
the O.J. Simpson Case'') and ``The Day Diana Died.''
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MERCATA-ONLINE (Seattle) _ Mercata (www.mercata.com), which
takes its name from the Latin word for market, officially launches
its electronic commerce store on Monday. Mercata differs from other
e-commerce sites, allowing groups of users to form what are
essentially virtual co-ops where shoppers can get volume discounts
on merchandise ranging from garden tools to camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   By John Cook. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-MACARTHUR (Undated) _ ``He was vain, haughty, theatrical, an
incurable poser,'' series host David McCullough says at the start
of Monday night's installment of ``MacArthur,'' a four-hour
presentation on PBS' ``The American Experience.'' ``Given to
rhetorical flourishes. A born leader. Highly ambitious. Conscious
of himself as a man of destiny.'' After viewing all four hours, I'm
thinking McCullough is understating it a bit.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TITANIC (Undated) _ In 87 years, the story of the Titanic
has been reduced to slogans and soap opera. The Titanic, we are
told, was doomed from the start by arrogant certainty in technology
and progress. It was a time when rich people got out and let the
poor sink. Stephen Cox, in his book, ``The Titanic Story,'' doesn't
buy this.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Can I ``jilt, renounce or
disenfranchise'' a cup of sugar, as my thesaurus suggests in place
of ``dump''? I often ``shove'' a casserole into a 350-degree oven.
Should I instead ``bulldoze, elbow or jostle,'' the inoffensive
pottery?
</P>
<P>
   By John Owen. (Story has moved in the ``d'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-ROYALS (Seattle) _ Seattle hosts the Kansas City
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column on the Seattle Mariners and
their shortstop, Alex Rodgriguez.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
