<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ARABS-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A TRIP TO MEND TIES, IRAN'S PRESIDENT MEETS SAUDI PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Iran's president met Sunday in Saudi Arabia with
the kingdom's crown prince, taking a crucial step in a process of
fence-mending that is every bit as significant and tricky as the
warmer relationship he has begun with the West.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, part of the first foray into the Arab world by
President Mohammad Khatami, is clearly important to the moderate
Iranian leader, who has been trying to ease his country out of
years of isolation and external tensions. The visit is the first to
Saudi Arabia by an Iranian leader since Iran's 1979 Islamic
Revolution, which unnerved many of its Persian Gulf neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami has been using his mild manner and eloquence to reassure
Arab leaders that Iran is no longer bent on regional dominance. At
the same time, he has had to take care to avoid inflaming political
foes at home, who have remained hostile to Iran's longtime rivals
and are suspicious of any effort to reach out to either the Arabs
or the West.
</P>
<P>
   To many Iranian conservatives, Saudi Arabia and its neighbors
are little more than outposts of Western imperialism. The result,
midway through a three-nation trip, has been something of a
hodgepodge of statements from Khatami, who is proving adept at
delivering mixed messages.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria, a longtime ally, Khatami met last week with
Palestinian and Lebanese militants to emphasize his country's
support for their campaigns against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated Iran's call for Islamic countries to settle
differences among themselves, without the presence of foreign
military forces. The latter was shorthand for an Iranian policy
intent on persuading its Persian Gulf neighbors that they need not
rely on U.S. forces for their protection.
</P>
<P>
   As host to thousands of American soldiers and airmen, Saudi
Arabia has long irritated Iran by turning a deaf ear to that
message. But since his arrival in Saudi Arabia on Saturday, Khatami
has set it aside, and not just to be polite.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami met Sunday in the Red Sea city of Jedda with Crown
Prince Abdullah, who took over day-to-day management of the kingdom
some time ago because of the poor health of his elder brother, King
Fahd, who suffered severe strokes three years ago and is confined
to a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami and the crown prince reportedly discussed ways to
buttress an accord among oil-producing nations to cut output and
lift prices. Like Iran, Saudi Arabia has suffered in the last 18
months from historically low oil prices, and the lesson that both
countries learned from the agreement reached this spring was that
cooperation was necessary to force oil prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   By underscoring Iran's old demands from Syria, Khatami may
sidestep complaints from conservatives, but his demeanor in Saudi
Arabia leaves little doubt of his commitment to pragmatism over
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the two years since his landslide election, Khatami
has become the best-traveled Iranian leader since the Islamic
Revolution of 1979, which ushered in an era of xenophobia. He
addressed the U.N. General Assembly in New York last fall, and he
traveled to Italy earlier this year, making him the most senior
Iranian official to visit Europe in nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   On both trips, Khatami reiterated his call for a ``dialogue of
civilizations'' _ a metaphor for his quest for warmer political,
cultural and economic ties between Iran and the West. To Westerners
accustomed to hostility rather than graciousness, those journeys
were seen as landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   And equally, Khatami's Arab tour is being seen as enormously
significant in the Arab world, among countries that not long ago
feared that Iran's revolution might spread to topple their own
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Egypt, one of the few Arab states that has yet to
reinstate full ties with Iran, a headline Sunday in the
government-owned newspaper Al Akbar described Khatami's journey to
Saudi Arabia as ``historic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, it marks a turning point in relations between Shiite
Muslim Iran and the Riyadh government, which sees itself as
embodying Sunni Muslim orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation is likely to be reflected in a visit by
Khatami to the Islamic holy sites in Mecca, the scene of several
bloody clashes between anti-Western Iranian pilgrims and Saudi
security forces. Beyond that, in parts of the Arab world, Khatami's
journey has begun to inspire imaginings of a more lasting bond.
</P>
<P>
   If the Arabs and Iranians could put their ancient enmities
aside, wrote Talal Salman, editor of the Lebanese newspaper Al
Safir, they might establish a regional bloc strong enough to
counter ``Israel's territorial designs'' and American hegemony. In
practice, though, the strains remain deep.
</P>
<P>
   Iran remains deeply unlikely to reconcile with Iraq, its foe in
an eight-year war during the 1980s and its principal historical
rival. At the same time, its decade-old occupation of Abu Mousa and
two other islands in the Persian Gulf has kept it embroiled in a
dispute with the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Some Arab diplomats say that Qatar, the last stop on Khatami's
tour, may offer mediation in an attempt to resolve the conflict.
But the islands have become invested with so much symbolic
importance to both sides that a compromise is difficult to imagine,
the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem that may weigh on Khatami is how his messages in
the Arab world may be interpreted in the West, the other target of
Iranian overtures.
</P>
<P>
   The United States in particular has been watching Khatami
closely to see whether Iranian deeds run in parallel with his
public statements. Last month, the Clinton administration took some
small steps, including a slight easing of economic sanctions
against Iran, in a clear hint that it might entertain further steps
if Iran continued to show the world a generous face.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration has said that any further improvement of
economic ties will depend on three criteria: whether Iran reduces
support for terrorism, abandons pursuit of weapons of mass
destruction and halts its opposition to the Middle East peace
process. And on those grounds, Khatami's performance in Syria might
well be seen as a negative. In Damascus, the Syrian capital,
Khatami underscored Iran's longstanding support for Palestinian
fighters battling Israeli occupation, and he also convened a
meeting that included representatives of the militant Islamic
groups Hamas and Islamic Holy War.
</P>
<P>
   He also met personally with Sheik Hassan Nosrallah, leader of
the Shiite Muslim group Hezbollah, or Party of God, which has long
benefited from Syrian and Iranian support. Senior U.S. officials
have expressed concern about the meetings, saying that Iran
appeared to be showing hostility to a broader Middle East peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
