<HEADLINE>
PLAYING MUSICAL BEDS  
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review)  
(DW) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three copulating couples populate Peter Ackerman's
new sex comedy, ``Things You Shouldn't Say Past Midnight,'' but
only a single pairing arouses more than a few predictable snickers.
It's the one that pits straitlaced Jeffrey Donovan against naughty
Clea Lewis. He plays a prudish mobster with a hankering for
highbrow culture; she is, in Ackerman's symmetrical scheme, a randy
art historian looking for some down-and-dirty pleasure. When these
naturally funny actors are negotiating the terms of their bedtime
arrangements, they turn the mating dance into a ribald gavotte.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman's play, which opened on Thursday at the Promenade
Theater, is all about the mindless extremes we go to in
categorizing one another, by race, age and sex, and how these
labels get in the way of a good time. What is so endearing about
the work of Donovan and Ms. Lewis is that they transcend the
outrageous labels. Donovan's Gene is a hit man with an
obsessive-compulsive disorder _ the mob doesn't call him Clean Gene
for nothing _ and Ms. Lewis' Grace has a yen to be dominated,
gangland-style. Yet when engaged in the business of explaining
their wants and needs, they are any New York couple on the
believable brink of long-term connection or fast-approaching
flameout.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, a young actor receiving his first major
production, gives this pair its due of clever repartee. (Listen for
Ms. Lewis' witty thesis on how a shoe becomes art, or better yet,
make it your business to savor Donovan's smooth transitions from
tough guy to sensitive guy, and back again.)
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it is all the more disappointing that the other couples in
this bedroom farce, constructed in the spirit of a round-robin Alan
Ayckbourn comedy, are so awkwardly conceived and unevenly realized.
</P>
<P>
   Although the level of pep pumped into the intermissionless play
by the director, John Rando, is unassailable, ``Things You
Shouldn't Say Past Midnight'' is on the whole too obvious and
vulgar for the wicked look at sexual relationships that is
intended. Ackerman is of the belief that euphemistic discussions of
sex onstage are passe; one result is a coarse frankness in the
dialogue that suggests a rather jejune sensibility. But then any
romantic comedy whose complications are provoked by the coital
remark ``Do me, you hook-nosed Jew!'' is never going to inspire
comparisons to Noel Coward.
</P>
<P>
   This salvo is tossed in the opening moments of the play by Erin
Dilly, playing Nancy, a perky Midwestern Gentile, in the midst of
lovemaking with Mark Kassen, who portrays Ben, a studly young
Manhattan Jew. The flustered Ben artlessly poses a hypothetical to
Nancy in which he hints that he is gay, which sends the distraught
Nancy in the middle of the night to the apartment of Grace, who is
about to bed Clean Gene. Grace immediately calls Gene's gay
brother, Mark (Andrew Benator), who happens to be her therapist and
is himself in bed with Donald (Nicholas Kepros), an older Jewish
man.
</P>
<P>
   Among various portable and speakerphones, and between the sheets
of three beds, Ackerman's comedy works itself into a minor frenzy.
Rando, who recently directed ``Do Re Mi'' for the Encores series of
musicals in concert, keeps the traffic moving, even when the
plotting is at its most chokingly unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Odorisio's set, a wall of cushions dotted by night lights,
is functional and reflective of the tawdriness of much of the
playwright's material. Ms. Dilly and Kassen have the least
flavorful assignments; Kepros and Benator are mere caricatures.
Donovan and Ms. Lewis have all the fun: they're in the bed on the
left.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`THINGS YOU SHOULDN'T SAY PAST MIDNIGHT'  &QL; 
By Peter Ackerman; directed by John Rando; sets by Rob Odorisio;
costumes by Tom Broecker; lighting by Donald Holder; sound by Peter
J. Fitzgerald; production stage manager, Karen Moore; technical
supervisor, Rob Conover. Presented by Good Friends LLC, Jeffrey
Richards, Michael Rothfeld, Jean Donmanian, Ted Snowdon, Steven M.
Levy, Leonard Soloway. At the Promenade Theater in Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
With: Erin Dilly (Nancy), Mark Kassen (Ben), Jeffrey Donovan
(Gene), Clea Lewis (Grace), Andrew Benator (Mark) and Nicholas
Kepros (Donald).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
