<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR NOW, ALL QUIET ON THE YANKEE FRONT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During batting practice Sunday, Don Zimmer was
sitting in the Yankee dugout, talking about how Joe Torre's return
was approaching. One educated guess was that Torre will be managing
the Yankees on Friday night in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Joe hadn't come back any sooner,'' Zimmer said,
``because I wouldn't want him to go through what we have the last
10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was alluding to the Yankees' recent 4-6 slump, including
a five-game losing streak that had dropped the Yankees into a
Sunday morning tie with the Boston Red Sox for first place in the
American League East. But in the dugout now, Derek Jeter suddenly
sat down next to Zimmer. Moments later, they were laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was about George, our new batboy,'' Zimmer would say
later. ``Derek told me the players were telling him: `You're on
thin ice. We better win pretty soon or you'll be gone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was joking. George Steinbrenner has never fired a batboy.
Now and then a secretary, never a batboy. But through the years
``gone'' is a word many Yankee managers, pitching coaches and
players have understood. Shortly after noon Sunday, the man behind
that word strode into the clubhouse, then into the players' lounge.
Moments later, Bernie Williams noticed more than a dozen reporters
standing around in silence, staring at the door to the players'
lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``George just came in,'' the Yankee center fielder was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. But when the Yankees' principal owner was confronted by
reporters on the elevator to his upstairs office, he appeared to
accept the Yankee losing streak with rare serenity. Perhaps because
he had been on his own losing streak when he attended the Preakness
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had every other horse except Charismatic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Torre's return, he said: ``That's strictly up to
Joe. He's got to have a complete sign-off from the medical
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the recent slump after the Yankees had won 125 games
last year, including their World Series sweep of the San Diego
Padres, Steinbrenner steamed slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear about last year,'' he said. ``We just
want to win one more game than everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   He had checked how Yankee teams in 1928, 1937 and 1962 had
reacted to the Yankee record of the year before: 101 victories in
1928 after 110 in 1927, 102 victories in 1937 after 102 in 1936, 96
victories in 1962 after 109 in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the 1978 Yankees,'' somebody said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' he said. ``We were 14 games behind the Red Sox
in August.'' It really was July, but close enough.
</P>
<P>
   But what even Steinbrenner seems to have realized about this
year's Yankees is just that: it's this year, not last year. In
sports, teams, like players, have ``a year'' every so often. As the
Yankees did last year. As Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa did last
year. As Roger Maris did in 1961. As Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams
did in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   When ``a year'' is as historic as those years were, it's just
not going to happen again. The Yankees' five-game losing streak
wasn't an aberration. Their 125 victories, including a World Series
sweep, was an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sunday's 2-1 victory over the Chicago White Sox that
ended the losing streak and helped the Yankees claim first place
for themselves again, they know enough to realize that last year
isn't going to happen this year. Zimmer has been preaching that
philosophy ever since he was named manager while Torre was
recovering from surgery for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who expects a team to do that again?'' Zimmer was saying after
the losing streak had ended. ``All I said in the spring was, `I
hope we win the Eastern Division championship.' This is a different
team than last year's.''
</P>
<P>
   This year Tim Raines is in Oakland. Darryl Strawberry is in
court. David Wells, Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush are in Toronto.
When Wells pitched his perfect game a year ago today, the Yankees
not only were 28-9, but they were also about to sweep the Orioles,
then take two out of three in Boston to open a six-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, obtained in the trade for Wells, Lloyd and Bush,
is on the disabled list with a deceptive 2-0 record that includes a
5.47 earned run average. Jeff Nelson is on the disabled list, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night the Yankees will be in Boston again, playing for
first place in a three-game series before going to Chicago, when
Torre might return. Then the Red Sox arrive at Yankee Stadium next
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But it's this year, not last year. At least for now George the
batboy seems to be safe from George the principal owner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
