<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 4.5 SECONDS LEFT, HEAT TURN OVER GAME 7 TO THE KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BKN-KNICKS-HEAT) 
 (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When it was over, Tim Hardaway sat slumped against a
wall in the Miami Heat locker room, his face reduced to a lifeless
stare.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, the Heat's point guard, committed two turnovers in the
final three minutes of Sunday's playoff finale against the Knicks _
including a pivotal one with 19.9 seconds left _ as the Heat fell
in the final seconds, 78-77, at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my team down by turning the ball over,'' Hardaway said
softly, surrounded by a crush of reporters. ``I put it all on my
shoulders because those turnovers cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Heat ahead by 77-76, Hardaway passed up a 3-point
attempt to penetrate between Latrell Sprewell and Charlie Ward, and
Sprewell knocked the ball out of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost it,'' Hardaway said.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the Knicks for the fateful running jumper by Allan
Houston that hit off the front of the rim and the backboard before
going through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway failed to score in the second half, settling for 9
points. It was typical of his production in this series, as he
averaged almost 8 points a game less than his 17.4 regular-season
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of talking about my productivity,'' he said to a
question about his dropoff. ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   As reporters walked away, Hardaway covered his eyes with his
left hand and sat frozen in that pose for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He had plenty of company. Not far away, center Alonzo Mourning
studied the labeling on a mineral water bottle for the longest
time, forward Jamal Mashburn stared aimlessly into space and guard
Voshon Lenard peered down at the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adversity introduces a man to himself,'' Mourning said later.
``You can only get better from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Mourning if he felt particularly sorry for
Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you blaming this on Tim?'' Mourning said, glaring. ``I
feel for all my teammates, not just Tim. We came up 4.5 seconds
short.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sequence before Houston's shot, Miami's backup point
guard, Terry Porter, had grappled with Sprewell for a loose ball
that went out of bounds. Officials awarded possession to the Knicks
with 4.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he hit it out,'' Porter said. ``He reached out and
it looked like the ball went off his hand. But I'd have to see the
replay to be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat Coach Pat Riley said Porter's hustle turned out to be
fortuitous for the Knicks. ``Basically they had nothing with five
seconds to go,'' Riley said. ``It gave them a chance to get
organized and get a play set, and that's all she wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   During the timeout before the winning shot, the Heat went over
the scenarios involving the three Knicks most likely to get the
ball _ Houston, Sprewell and Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   After Houston got the ball, Ewing was able to screen Dan Majerle
out of position, allowing Houston to penetrate the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what the play was going to be in that situation, once
Allan got the ball,'' Majerle said. ``I probably should have gotten
on top of him and made him go the other way. Made somene else take
the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the ball left Houston's hand and bounced on the rim,
Majerle feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going in,'' he said. ``That's pretty much the
way things happened for us in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the Heat's season was over. ``I didn't want it to end
like that,'' Mourning said. ``It kind of makes you angry a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, Riley was brief with his players,
thanking them for their effort. Then he was gone, leaving his
players to wonder how many of them will return next season.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle, for one, wants to stay, but his contract is up and the
Heat has given no indication of its intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to play somewhere,'' he said. ``I'd like for it to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Near where Majerle sat, a sheet of paper bore what Riley was
trying to accomplish in Sunday's game. It said in part, ``All great
leaders since Moses have known that feared enemies must be crushed
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   A crushing of the Knicks would have sent them spiraling into an
off-season of doubt and changes. As it turned out, the top-seeded
Heat is the team facing serious doubt and probable changes.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning said the best team did not win Sunday's game and he
would like the Heat's nucleus return. After Riley left the locker
room, Mourning told his teammates his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to keep their heads up,'' he said. ``We don't have
any reason to hold our heads down. We all left it out there on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Except on this day, it wasn't quite good enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
