<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WATCHING FOR PITCHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers continue to monitor the potential
breakup of the Baltimore Orioles, who are 13-24 despite an $84
million payroll. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers likely would be interested in right-handers Mike
Mussina, Scott Erickson and Juan Guzman should the Orioles decide
to begin a rebuilding phase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mussina, a legitimate No. 1 starter, would be of most interest
to the Rangers. Mussina, whom the Cleveland Indians also covet, is
in the second season of a three-year contract worth $20.45 million.
However, Mussina (5-1, 4.89) is the one player the Orioles would
prefer to keep, major-league officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Erickson is in the first season of a five-year contract worth
$32 million, but his 1-5 record and 6.51 earned-run average could
scare some organizations. Guzman can become a free agent after this
season, but his inability to stay healthy remains a concern. Guzman
(1-4, 5.88) pitched only four innings Saturday before leaving with
stiffness in his lower back. &QL; 
The medical view &QL; 
Dr. John Conway, the Rangers' orthopedic consultant, examined
shortstop Royce Clayton and left-hander Eric Gunderson yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The results: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clayton (torn muscle, right shoulder) received medical clearance
from Conway, and manager Johnny Oates indicated the shortstop could
begin a brief medical-rehabilitation assignment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday's magnetic-resonance-imaging test revealed partial tears
of the rotator cuff and labrum in Gunderson's left shoulder. The
Rangers plan to treat the injury conservatively, and Gunderson will
be sidelined at least three to six weeks, Conway said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other injury updates: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oates indicated right fielder Juan Gonzalez (strained right
hamstring) could return to the lineup as early as Friday. Gonzalez
missed his fourth consecutive game yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile jammed his ankle at first base in the
sixth inning while running out a grounder. Reserve infielder Jon
Shave replaced Zeile, who is day to day. &QL; 
Briefly The Rangers promoted left-hander Robert Quarnstrom from
Class-A Charlotte to Double-A Tulsa and purchased Ryan Karp's
contract from the Atlantic League and assigned him to Tulsa. The
Drillers needed fresh relievers. Quarnstrom will return to
Charlotte in the near future, assistant general manager Dan O'Brien
said. Karp, a left-hander, made 16 major-league appearances for the
Philadelphia Phillies in 1995 and '97. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed Mel Rosario and assigned the 25-year-old
catcher to Tulsa. Rosario appeared in four games with the Orioles
in 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game was played with only three umpires. Durwood
Merrill missed the game with the flu. &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:Johnny Paul, (817) 390-7760 &QL; 
 &LR; tagbottom:jpaul &LR; star-telegram.com &QL; 
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
