<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG COMPANIES FALL BEHIND IN FIXING YEAR 2000 GLITCH
</P>
<P>
   The largest companies in the nation continue to fall behind
their schedules for fixing the year 2000 problem, and most suspect
that their budget estimates for the remaining work are too low,
according to a survey in April that was the latest in a closely
watched series that began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   About 22 percent say they do not expect to have all of their
critical systems tested and ready to adjust when the clock ticks
over to Jan. 1, 2000. That is up from 16 percent in November. The
number of companies that have encountered a failure stemming from
year 2000 problems jumped to 72 percent in April from 55 percent in
November.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE FOR AUDIO AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks, a multimedia software maker, and Snap.com, an
Internet directory service, plan to announce Monday that they are
starting a search engine for music and other audio or video files
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL ALLEN GETS A MAKEOVER Paul Allen, the co-founder of
Microsoft and owner of the Portland Trail Blazers basketball team,
looks a lot more dapper these days as he takes his accustomed seat
courtside at Trail Blazers games. Appearing on television
frequently as the Trail Blazers are having their best season in
years, the 45-year-old billionaire looks much more like a
high-technology investor than the guitar-playing hacker geek that
many recall. Gone are the rumpled sport shirts and the beard,
replaced by clean-shaven cheeks and well-cut suits.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET RADIO MOVES BEYOND NICHE
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, listening to the radio on the Internet was
considered the domain of the 20-something set. But recent deals
show the growth of a multilayered industry with players convinced
that the personal computer will be the radio tuner for the next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   BORROWING FROM FACTS FOR FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Andersen _ a staff writer for The New Yorker magazine, a
former editor of New York, a founding editor of Spy magazine and a
former writer for Time _ has drawn extensively from his media world
for the plot of ``Turn of the Century,'' a social satire set in
2000 that skewers cyberspace, television, Wall Street traders,
marriage and the media.
</P>
<P>
   GE CAPITAL TO BUY LOAN PORTFOLIO
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital, General Electric's financial services arm, said it
would buy the $11 billion U.S. commercial loan portfolio of the
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, its fifth deal in Japan since last
year.
</P>
<P>
   A HUMBLE GUY NOW WORTH MILLIONS
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, the 32-year-old editor in chief of TheStreet.com,
was once a humble radio sports announcer who then became a
newspaper reporter, writing about sports for Newsday and then about
the stock market for The Wall Street Journal. But last week,
TheStreet.com _ an Internet magazine that provides financial news
and analysis _ offered its stock to the public for the first time
and Kansas was suddenly worth $9.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   BID REMAINS SAME FOR TELECOM ITALIA
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, Europe's largest phone company, dashed
investors' hopes that it would sweeten its $82 billion offer for
Telecom Italia before Olivetti's bid expires.
</P>
<P>
   NEED FOR REFORM STILL SEEN IN ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Ministers from the 21-member Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
Forum expressed confidence in Asia's recovery from two years of
financial crisis but said serious risks loom and deeper reforms are
needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
