<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-VOTE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFERENDUM VOTE COULD GRANT RIGHTS TO INDIGENOUS PEOPLES  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMALTENANGO, Guatemala _ In a country where the indigenous
majority has faced genocide and poverty and long been excluded from
power, Elias D. Chitamul, like so many other voters on Sunday,
faced his chance to change Guatemala with tempered optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Casting his ballot in a referendum that would declare Guatemala
``multiethnic'' and rein in the military, Chitamul, 19, said he
expected ``not total change, but the beginning of change.'' To him,
that meant living in a peaceful country that no longer feared its
own army.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that people can leave their home and return the
same way they left _ without any harm befalling them outside,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another voter, Florentina Sintu, 28, said she would be satisfied
with even ``meager'' results. ``We want to change the way things
are for us but we have to resign ourselves to whatever we get,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the ballot measure, if approved as expected,
would for the first time grant equal status to the languages,
religions and traditional laws of the Mayan peoples, who account
for about 60 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, on 50 amendments to the Constitution, posed what
President Alvaro Arzu Irigoyen called ``a decisive test'' of
Guatemala's willingness to build a more just society after 36 years
of war between the government and leftist guerrillas that killed
about 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would make the first tangible changes in the army
and government called for by peace accords signed in 1996, which
supporters consider crucial to the country's lasting transformation
to an inclusive, democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments would restrict the army to territorial defense
and end its control of internal security, a role that has led to
scores of political killings and human rights abuses. The
presidential general staff, the military unit found to have engaged
in many abuses, would be replaced by civilians. The post of defense
minister could now be also filled by a civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Other important changes aim to increase checks on the executive
branch and reform the judicial system, which has routinely allowed
much crime to go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wide range of the proposals, public debate before
the vote focused almost exclusively on the handful of amendments
that recognize the rights of the Guatemala's indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, they have been excluded from government and
relegated to alarming rates of poverty and illiteracy in a country
where wealth and power have been dominated by the ladinos, the
mostly white and mestizo minority.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment would define this country of 11 million as
``multiethnic, multicultural, multilingual,'' specifically
acknowledging not only the Mayan majority but also minorities like
the Garifunas, descendants of Caribbean blacks, and the Xinca, a
nearly extinct indigenous group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another grants official status to 24 indigenous languages, a
change whose effect in making education, health care and other
public services available in languages other than Spanish will
depend largely on bringing indigenous people into civil service
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments also grant indigenous groups the right to visit
sacred places, denied by some private land owners. Another change
would acknowledge the legitimacy of indigenous traditional law,
currently used to settle disputes, as long it does not conflict
with the national legal system and is done voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms would boost a Mayan movement that has become more
united in the last decade, bringing together hundreds of groups
despite language and other differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're beginning is a new social contract for Guatemala,''
said Alvaro Pop, a founding member of the Coordinator of Guatemalan
Mayan Organizations, a major indigenous group, and a negotiator of
the proposed reforms. ``We're building the nation we never had, a
nation within our own diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reforms were vigorously opposed by powerful sectors,
including business people, politicians and intellectuals who warned
of the cost involved in carrying out some of the measures and of
the danger of ``Balkanizing'' the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can bring about another war,'' said Roberto Orozco, 50, a
businessman in the department of Sacatepequez, east of here.
``We're going to turn into Kosovo, with each tribe taking up arms
to go to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Many opponents objected to the decision by the Guatemalan
Congress, which designed the measures, to make voters decide on
blocks of reforms rather than to vote on each one separately.
Others criticized the reforms as an imposition by international
agencies and foreign countries, including the United States, which
have given $2.4 billion in loans and grants to carry out the peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measures charged that many of the arguments
against the reforms were tinged with racism and fear by the upper
classes that equal conditions imply a loss of political and
economic power.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was expected to be well below a third of four million
registered voters, some officials noted, because of the thin effort
to inform people about the measures in what is the first vote since
peace was reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     05-16 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN LIBERAL PARTY'S GAINS DRAW FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPINGTON, South Africa _ Even out here in this arid, desolate
part of the country where the polls say the National Party _ now
rechristened the New National Party _ will do well, Marthinus van
Schalkwyk does not make a stop without lashing out at the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he also hits out at President Nelson Mandela's party, the
governing African National Congress, saying it has failed to
control crime and to deliver on its promises of jobs for all. But
his real passion seems to be saved for warning voters about the
evils of South Africa's once tiny liberal party, known here as the
DP.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party, says van Schalkwyk, leader of the party
that created apartheid, is flirting with the racist right ``and
they will die of that political cancer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere the gods of politics must be howling with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   If South Africa's second postapartheid election campaign has
offered any surprise at all, it is the fuss that the Democratic
Party has engendered. The party and its antecedents, which
traditionally represented wealthy, English-speaking white liberals,
consistently opposed apartheid and were small but nagging irritants
to the white-supremacist Afrikaans-speaking former regime.
</P>
<P>
   But even the African National Congress, which is expected to
coast to victory, perhaps with a two-thirds majority, has turned
its guns on the Democratic Party. It began a poster war suggesting
that the party, which even fought to upgrade conditions in the
prison where Mandela was held, is now running a racist campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Leon, the boarding-school-educated chief of the party,
shrugs off the accusations. He is gaining in the polls and could
even displace van Schalkwyk as South Africa's official opposition
leader. But the contest for that seat has been bitter, laced with
assertions of racism and deceit and exposing the deep racial lines
that still divide South African society.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public statements that they are looking for voters of
all races, the Democratic and National Parties, running virtually
neck and neck, are engaged in a fierce fight for the allegiance of
the nonblack vote. (The majority of blacks remain loyal to the
African National Congress.)
</P>
<P>
   In luring supporters, they are both playing on the fears of
South African minority groups _ whites, ``coloreds'' and Indians _
who still have most of South Africa's wealth but worry about having
no say in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Though Leon's party won just 1.7 percent of the vote in 1994,
giving it only seven of the 400 seats in Parliament, it has been
hugely successful over the last five years as a burr under the seat
of government.
</P>
<P>
   By leaking stories to the press, harshly questioning Cabinet
ministers during public debates and filing lawsuits when it could
not stop legislation, the Democratic Party has become the chief
watchdog on government corruption, incompetence and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   All seven of its members of Parliament are nimble-tongued, but
none more so than Leon, who is a walking sound bite. When Mandela
recently sneered that white parties were ``Mickey Mouse,'' Leon
instantly shot back that Mandela was ``running a Goofy
government.''
</P>
<P>
   He has consistently pushed a liberal agenda _ more
accountability in government, less interference with private
enterprise, more power in local hands. And he has been particularly
visible in opposing affirmative action without quotas or time
limits, which he calls apartheid in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Leon suggests that giving the African
National Congress a two-thirds majority, which would allow it to
change the Constitution, would be a catastrophe. Thabo Mbeki, who
almost certainly will replace Mandela as president, could decide to
make it a job for life, Leon says.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he says, hitting South Africa's affluent whites squarely in
the wallet, he could ``fool with the property clauses'' in the
Constitution, which prevents the government from expropriating
property without paying fair market prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let it happen,'' Leon told white farmers near
Pietermaritzburg recently. ``Not because the ANC is the evil
incarnate. They aren't. But because no government in this country _
with our history _ should ever have that kind of power.''
</P>
<P>
   His pitch is clearly hitting home. Polls show that his party is
the fastest-growing one, with as much as 10 percent of the vote
now. Not much, perhaps, but maybe enough to beat the New National
Party, which got 20 percent in 1994, but has been sinking in the
polls ever since. At the moment, polls show them about even.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say they believe that a large chunk of Leon's
support is coming not from liberal Afrikaners but from conservative
ones, a traditional National Party power base.
</P>
<P>
   They deem the old right-wing parties like the Conservative Party
and the Freedom Front ineffective, and resent the old National
Party for handing over the reins of power to blacks in 1994. They
see the Democratic Party's fight for individual rights and minimal
government interference as the best protection for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seems to be happening is the opposite of what you would
expect,'' said Rod Alence, who heads the polling team for the Human
Sciences Research Council, a nonprofit research organization. ``The
DP is taking the far-right votes. These are people who are looking
for protection and see the DP as the party that can do that for
them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have said that the Democratic Party's campaign
slogan _ ``The Guts to Fight Back'' _ is directly appealing to the
right wing. At one point, the African National Congress put up its
own posters playing on the theme: In DP colors, they said, ``Don't
Fight Blacks.'' But when the DP threatened to sue, the ANC took its
2,000 posters down.
</P>
<P>
   Leon defends the slogan. ``It is the peculiarity of our times
that anyone thinks that an opposition party should spend 28 days of
campaigning saying nice things about the government,'' he said.
``If what my party does appeals to people who are fed up, so be it.
They have a right to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   In battling to keep his place as the official opposition leader,
van Schalkwyk has myriad problems. When F.W. de Klerk left the
National Party in 1997, his departure triggered an exodus of senior
party officials. Van Schalkwyk, at 37, too young to be held
responsible for any apartheid-era atrocities, emerged as the new
leader. But his stature does not approach de Klerk's. His round,
youthful face has earned him the nickname ``kortebroek'' _ ``short
pants'' _ a reference to the khaki shorts worn by Afrikaner farm
boys.
</P>
<P>
   And completely unfamiliar with opposition party politics, the
National Party has often seemed adrift. Early on, it often took a
day or two to issue responses to news events, by which time
newspapers were no longer interested. And it has not proved nearly
as adept as the Democratic Party at debating.
</P>
<P>
   But van Schalkwyk is pressing ahead with de Klerk's efforts to
transform the party into a nonracial party that will do a better
job of governing than the African National Congress, which has had
trouble improving schools, health care and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his campaign stops start with a prayer. Van Schalkwyk
bows his head, closes his eyes and clasps his hands. Then he points
out that in the one province where the National Party won a
majority in 1994, the Western Cape, 80 percent of the students
passed their high school exams last year. In the country as a
whole, 50 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   And he says, the economy is growing at four times the national
rate in the Western Cape. To get a grip on crime, he wants the
death penalty restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to govern,'' van Schalkwyk says at every stop.
``We know how to create jobs. We know how to provide a good
standard of education to our children. We know how to deal with
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party for decent people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
