u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NY     05-16 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRARDI HAS THE REINS AS PETTITTE HALTS SLUMP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner, who grabbed tickets on every
horse other than Charismatic on Saturday, tried picking another
winner Sunday at Yankee Stadium, a task complicated by the fact
that his team had lost five consecutive games. ``You've always been
our stopper,'' Steinbrenner told Andy Pettitte, the left-hander
with the broad shoulders eight hands wide.
</P>
<P>
   Every winner needs a good jockey, and it was left to catcher Joe
Girardi to guide Pettitte through the heavy traffic created by the
Chicago White Sox. Pettitte and the New York Yankees could have
been bumped off at several different turns in the game; they could
have faltered. But Girardi either made plays or coaxed Pettitte
through, and the Yankees edged Chicago, 2-1, before 51,046 at
Yankee Stadium. Somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some breaks, sure, a couple of things went our way,''
said Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager. ``After the past
week, I think we're entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer never claimed the Yankees suffered from bad luck in the
past week. No, the Yankees could take full credit for their losses,
caused by a collective hitting slump _ their batting average shrank
from .283 to .272 in six days _ and inconsistent starting pitching
and consistently erratic defense.
</P>
<P>
   After Pettitte allowed a first-inning run, Chili Davis correctly
anticipated a first-pitch fastball from Mike Sirotka in the second
inning and lashed a two-run home run, and Zimmer turned to Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, and said, ``It's all up
to you now, Pal.''
</P>
<P>
   With his gallows humor, Zimmer was referring to the fact that
the Yankees are not generating many runs, and that Stottlemyre and
the pitchers would be responsible for maintaining the one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi had already saved the Yankees a run in the top of the
second inning. With runners on first and third and two out,
Pettitte flipped a changeup that bounced in the dirt, and Girardi
blocked enough of the ball to keep it close to home plate and
prevent Chicago's Craig Wilson from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte nodded at Girardi, nice play, unspoken. Pettitte has
come to rely on the crew-cut Girardi, in the way a private looking
for structure relies on his sergeant. Pettitte likes Girardi to
call pitches for him, likes following his orders. Girardi:
Fastball, outside. Pettitte: Yes, sir.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really trusts Joe,'' said David Cone, whose own
pitcher-catcher relationship with Girardi is somewhat different _
Girardi is the sergeant, Cone the four-star general preferring
absolute control.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte never shakes off signs from Girardi, as he occasionally
does from Jorge Posada. The results are different as well:
Pettitte's earned run average when pitching to Posada this season
is 14.04, but it is 2.36 when throwing to Girardi. There's a
certain level of comfort working with Girardi, Pettitte said,
because they are familiar with each other; maybe Girardi helps
Pettitte's confidence, the pitcher agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte shut out the White Sox in the third inning, just after
Davis' home run in the second, and he continued to stifle them in
the fourth. Wilson singled and took second on a wild pitch leading
off the fifth inning, and Pettitte walked Brook Fordyce, Chicago's
No. 9 hitter. First and second and nobody out. As he prepared to
pitch to Ray Durham, Pettitte got a sign from the first baseman
Tino Martinez for a pick-off; neither Pettitte nor Martinez would
say how this was communicated.
</P>
<P>
   No matter: Martinez darted to the bag as Pettitte began his
delivery, the throw was perfect and Fordyce was out, the first out
of the inning. Pettitte would get the last out by striking out
Frank Thomas, who had been 10 for 21 in his career against
Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' lead was in jeopardy again in the sixth (and there
was always the sense they were going to blow the game). Magglio
Ordonez ripped a leadoff double between outfielders, and then Paul
Konerko extended his arms across the plate and flipped a single to
right, Ordonez stopping at third. First and third; nobody out,
again.
</P>
<P>
   Darrin Jackson dumped a grounder in front of home plate, about
15 feet away from Girardi, on the first-base side. Edging down the
third-base line, Ordonez waited, hesitated, until he saw Girardi
move in pursuit of the ball, and then Ordonez charged down the
line. Zimmer saw the play begin to develop, assumed Ordonez would
score and silently lamented the bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi reached down and barehanded the ball. Pettitte screamed
at him that Ordonez was trying to score, and Girardi reversed
direction, going back to the plate. The Chicago runner stopped and
tried going back to third, but was nabbed in the rundown. It was
the biggest out of the game, Zimmer agreed. Pettitte got two more
outs and was relieved by Jason Grimsley in the seventh and eighth
innings, and Mariano Rivera in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge win,'' Cone said. ``It stops the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first-base coach, held up a bottle
of red wine and asked Zimmer if he wanted to celebrate the victory.
Paul O'Neill slumped into the chair in front of his locker and when
asked if he was anticipating the start of the three-game series
with the Boston Red Sox on Tuesday. O'Neill said dryly, ``The only
thing I'm anticipating is a day off tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But the respite didn't come so easily for Zimmer and the
coaches. They joined Steinbrenner and manager Joe Torre and general
manager Brian Cashman for a staff meeting Sunday night, reviewing
the roster and the recent losing streak. Tuesday night, Cone and
the Yankees will face Boston's Pedro Martinez, the best pitcher in
the American League, and Steinbrenner will look for another horse
to take the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2121EDT &QL; 
