<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MININGCO-ABOUT-795&AMP;AD     05-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MININGCO-ABOUT-795&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THIS HAS BEEN ALL ABOUT.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a few days before Miningco.com was scheduled to go public
in March. Scott Kurnit, the company's founder and chief executive,
called its lawyer to ask whether there was any law that prevented a
company, on the day it goes public, from changing its name.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, the lawyer said _ but if he was going to do that,
Kurnit should alert Bear, Stearns, the investment bank managing the
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear, Stearns would freak and make me pull the offering,''
Kurnit said recently, explaining why he did not go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was only on Sunday that Kurnit told his bankers that
as of Monday morning Miningco.com was to become About.com. Kurnit
says the new name better expresses the nature of the service, a
collection of 600 sites on various topics, each run by a
specialist. His New York company hopes to compete with big sites
like Yahoo by being more selective and having more of its own
content.
</P>
<P>
   It may come as no surprise, however, to the bankers and others
that something has been up at Miningco.com. The company is behind
an elaborate $15 million teaser promotional campaign over the last
two weeks that spread the question ``Hello, is anybody out there?''
in advertisements, in anonymous e-mail messages, and through
tactics like holding up signs with the slogan behind the set of the
``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   The tease seems to have attracted some attention. ``Hello, is
anybody wondering about those mystery ads?'' wrote The Wall Street
Journal in a short item in its advertising column that quoted
advertising industry executives speculating that Miningco.com was
behind the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The whole affair shows how the fast-moving Internet and the even
faster-moving market for Internet stocks has warped the traditions
that companies have followed for generations. Not too long ago, for
example, it would have been considered bad form, at the least, to
change the name and key elements of a company's strategy six weeks
after raising $75 million from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so sure. Analysts were split when told of the
name late Friday by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about brand,'' said Paul Noglows, an analyst at
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, noting that at least some of the success of
Yahoo, for example, has been its lively moniker. ``But at the end
of the day, Miningco is taking a risk, given the success it has
achieved to date. It remains to be seen whether About.com will be
worth the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Williams, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan, one of the
underwriters of Miningco.com, was more positive. ``The old name was
fine,'' she said. ``In fact, I liked it more than some people. But
About is simple and easier to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger question, of course, is whether the name change, and
all the capital that the company is using to promote it, can blast
Miningco.com from the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix, the Web audience measurement company, said
Miningco.com was the 24th-most-visited site in March, just ahead of
the Weather Channel, owned by Landmark Communications, with 5.8
million users. So far the company's sales of advertising _ its
principal hope for making money _ have been modest, with $3.7
million in sales for 1998. Kurnit says another use for the money
from the initial public offering is to hire more salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond cosmetics, Kurnit says the name change is the centerpiece
of a strategy that will pit About.com more directly against the big
portal sites like Yahoo, Lycos and America Online's service.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost that battle once already. At first, the company
was positioned as a human alternative to what were then known as
search engines, which simply found Web pages with words that
matched whatever a user typed in. It hired part-timers, whom it
called guides, to create handmade lists of the best sites in their
specialties. The name, at first Mining Co., evoked images of the
guides panning for gold amid the dross of the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Miningco.com attracted a certain following, but it hardly kept
pace with the portal sites, which have added a wide range of
services, from e-mail to stock quotes. Kurnit said the company
would use some of the capital it raised to add features to match
the offerings of the portals.
</P>
<P>
   As for revenue, the site's new design gives a large portion of
each screen to links to various shopping sites, which all pay the
company a commission on sales.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the new name helps highlight some of the
differentiating features that the service has developed over the
last few years in addition to its Web directory. The guides write
articles on their subject areas, now amounting to the largest
collection of original content on any Web site, Kurnit says. And
they run chat rooms and message boards on related topics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kurnit says that each guide's site _ now called About Fly
Fishing, About Anesthesiology, and so on _ is positioned as a
center of information on its topic.
</P>
<P>
   So why didn't he change the name before he went public? That is
what Audionet did, becoming Broadcast.com on the eve of its public
offering. And Dejanews, a site that searches Internet news groups,
has just redubbed itself Deja.com in an effort to broaden its scope
in preparation for a stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Kurnit said he did not think he could afford the advertising
campaign that was necessary to change names until it became clear
the stock market was so hot that Miningco.com could raise twice as
much money as it had originally proposed. But if the company
delayed its offering to alert investors to the name change, the
froth on the market could subside and Miningco.com could lose its
windfall. Even now, he's not sure of the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the stock will go up by $20 or down by $20 _ I'm not
sure which,'' he said. ``But we're not going to be a $20 billion
company digging up the gems of the Web.''
</P>
</TEXT>
