<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRD OUTDUELS HERSHISER AS PHILLIES TOP METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Philadelphia Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd staggered
into Veterans Stadium Sunday looking like a man who had not had
much recent contact with his pillow or his hairbrush. He rubbed his
red-rimmed eyes and headed drowsily for the clubhouse, having spent
a nearly sleepless night trying to contain his toddler son Colby,
who recently learned how to get out of his crib.
</P>
<P>
   But Colby's father had just enough energy in his pitches _ and
just enough jump in his step on a wild defensive play _ to contain
the New York Mets for 6 1/3 innings and deliver the Phillies a 5-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' loss wasted an encouraging outing by Orel Hershiser.
Although he dropped to 2-4, he pitched six innings, and only in the
last one did he look vulnerable. Until then, Hershiser had allowed
no runs and scattered four hits.
</P>
<P>
   The vision problems that had diminished his ability to see where
he was throwing _ and which resulted in a terrible performance
against Arizona on May 7, in which he yielded nine runs on nine
hits in 4 1/3 innings _ have been solved by a trip to the doctor.
And, despite the inability of the offense to garner him enough
runs, Hershiser could take comfort in the improvement in almost
every facet of his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a normal loss, not a debacle, so it's something to build
on,'' he said. ``I felt better, more like myself. You look under
every rock when you're in a slump. The vision was a part of it.
Your vision affects your concentration and your balance and
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's only bad inning was the sixth. With the Mets
leading, 1-0, Hershiser gave up a Marlon Anderson leadoff single
that went over the mound.. He got Scott Rolen to fly out, but then
walked Bobby Abreu. Mike Lieberthal singled to tie the score. The
next batter, Rob Ducey, hit a 3-1 pitch high to left field. Matt
Franco, playing in left, made a run at it, but the ball sliced
toward the left-field line. As the ball plummeted, Franco tried a
desperate headfirst slide. The ball went past him, two runs scored
and Ducey ended up on third. He scored next, when Kevin Jordan
grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could catch it,'' Franco said. ``One or two steps
before I dove, I realized I was in trouble. It sunk more than I
thought. I had a split second of, `Try to stop and knock it down.'
But it was too late; I was already committed. I feel terrible for
Orel. That play cost us the game. I told him I was sorry about it.
It cost us three runs and we lost by three.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets, who generated plenty of runs even while their
pitching was shaky on this 4-5 road swing, had several
opportunities to make up for Franco. In the first inning, with one
out, Edgardo Alfonzo singled. John Olerud doubled to center field,
and the throw to the plate was wild. Alfonzo scored, but Byrd,
backing up the play, prevented Olerud, who went to third on the
throw, from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher flew to the edge of the Mets' dugout, like Charles
Oakley trying to prevent a basketball from bouncing out of bounds,
to grab the ball before it went into the dugout. Byrd, a
right-hander, banged his left arm on the top of the dugout, but he
struck out Mike Piazza, then walked Robin Ventura before striking
out Brian McRae to strand Olerud at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most athletic plays I've ever seen,'' Mets
manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally chased Byrd (5-2) in the seventh inning, when
he gave up a leadoff double to McRae, then, after getting Franco on
a fly ball, delivered two straight walks to load the bases. Roger
Cedeno singled to right to score McRae and make the score 4-2, with
the bases loaded and still only one out. But reliever Wayne Gomes
got Alfonzo, who had a full count, to chase what would have been
ball four. Olerud grounded out weakly to first base to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the right pitches at the right times,'' Valentine
said. ``We had the right guys up and we didn't cash in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was a relatively untroubling loss at the end of the
season's longest road trip. After going 2-4 on the Western leg of
this trip, the Mets (21-16) took two of three from the Phillies
(20-16) _ who entered the series ahead of the Mets in the National
League East _ and in the process got solid outings from two of
their three starting pitchers, Masato Yoshii and Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like the longest road trip of the season,''
Valentine said. ``I'm glad it's over. But I like the way the guys
are playing. We get to crossroads during the season, and we took
the right road.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
