<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      05-16 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY THREATENS GORE'S CHANCES; EX-BASKETBALL STAR COULD SPOIL
DEMOCRAT'S PLAN FOR PRESIDENTIAL RACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ A counselor hustles teen-agers into the Ash
Street community center, telling them that Bill Bradley is about to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?'' asks a kid in baggy jeans and a yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Good question, and one being asked all the way from this
early-primary state to the White House, where Bradley represents
the only challenge to the Democratic establishment's long-nurtured
plan for Vice President Al Gore to be the party's choice to succeed
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Is Bradley, at 55 still probably best known as a former
basketball star, a quixotic spoiler on an ego trip two years after
huffing out of Washington with a denunciation of the political
system as ``broken?``
</P>
<P>
   Or is the former three-term senator from New Jersey a serious
presidential prospect, whose intense intellect and disarming style
could prove irresistible to dispirited Democrats, independents and
maybe even some Republicans hungry for a different kind of national
leader?
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's most cautious and experienced political
observers, David Broder of The Washington Post, has formed a
tentative judgment that sent shudders through the Clinton-Gore
organization: ``The script for a possible upset is becoming
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 51, still leads Bradley among Democrats by as much as 2 to
1 in national polls, but incipient signs that a real race may be on
could be felt as Bradley traversed New Hampshire for three days
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Spiegelman is a die-hard Democrat. For a Bradley speech at
Londonderry High School he wore a T-shirt that read: ``I don't care
if he's dead, I still want to IMPEACH NIXON.''
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Bradley talk about his youth in Missouri, his
days as a basketball player in college, the Olympics and the NBA,
his views on Kosovo, racial division, campaign finance and a dozen
other issues, Spiegelman said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Gore is horrible. If Bradley weren't in the
race, I'd be for Gore. But Bradley is so appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Democratic activists, Bradley is a reminder of the days
of earlier party mavericks _ Eugene McCarthy, George McGovern, Paul
Tsongas.
</P>
<P>
   Also with Bradley, Spiegelman said, ``there's none of that ego,
that need to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first votes still nine months away, the main difference
between Gore and Bradley, in fact, may be their contrasting
personal seismic readings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, edgy and wound tight, seems consumed by the campaign.
Clinton, acknowledging concern about Gore's campaign, told the New
York Times last week that he had urged his vice president: ``Go out
there and enjoy this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, seems supremely comfortable running
a race he knows he may lose. He's loose, humorous and even admitted
to reporters he was unsure whether the natives were called ``New
Hampshirites'' or ``New Hampshireans.'' (It's the former.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting at the bottom; I only have one way to go,''
Bradley told early-morning radio host Don Imus. ``Some days I think
I ought to be paying people to do this, I enjoy it so much.''
</P>
<P>
   This exultation runs counter to the dour Bradley who, disgusted
with politics, decided not to run for a fourth Senate term in 1996
_ after passing up presidential runs in 1988 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a power in giving up power,'' Bradley says of his
decision to leave Washington. In just two years, as a college
lecturer, writer and investment banker, Bradley claims, ``I
rejuvenated.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore partisans are not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ``is a guy who couldn't stand the heat, so he got out of
the kitchen,'' said a vice-presidential adviser. ``And before that
he almost got beat'' _ a reference to Bradley's unexpectedly narrow
victory over Republican Christine Todd Whitman in his last race,
the 1990 U.S. Senate contest in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, occupied with weighty global macroeconomic work on the
Senate Finance Committee, failed to take account of a virulent
anti-tax backlash at home, and struggled at the last minute to hang
on to his seat by only 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is now the underdog, Bradley insists his fate is
not dependent on Gore making some big mistake or becoming the fall
guy for public disenchantment with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have gotten into this if I couldn't see 270,''
Bradley said of the number of electoral votes needed to win the
White House. ``My premise is that I go out and tell people what I
believe, present a positive vision of what I think the future can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley refuses to be drawn out on most major policy positions
and precise political plans. His campaign is in what he calls the
opening ``vision-thematic'' phase. Detailed position papers are
promised in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley says they will be about ``big ideas,'' not the
narrowly focused proposals that have marked the later Clinton-Gore
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley knows it would be difficult to sustain a hard-bitten
one-on-one campaign through three seasons, so more direct whacks at
Gore are down the road. ``At some point this will be comparative,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   But the sideway slams are already there. Bradley's emphasis on
reform of the campaign finance system is a not-too-subtle reminder
of Gore's own solicitations from the White House and the Clinton
administration's shady fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling money in campaigns, Bradley says, is ``the critical
issue in our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has trouble spelling out many significant policy
differences with Gore. They had similar left-of-center voting
records when they were both senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a more varied life experience,'' Bradley offered, when
reporters pressed for some sort of differentiation. Bradley
referred to Gore's upbringing in Washington as the son of a senator
and his own as the son of a small-town banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more cautious,'' Bradley added.
</P>
<P>
   In logistical terms, Bradley has the luxury of being able to
campaign full time, which can be a special boon in New Hampshire,
traditional site of the opening primary, and in Iowa, where the
first important presidential caucuses are held. Both states' voters
value face-to-face contact with presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's trip to the Granite State was his fourth since
announcing a presidential campaign in January. Although New
Hampshire may look small, Bradley said, ``it's a big state if you
have to measure it in terms of living rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening months of Bradley's campaign have been solid, at
least in terms of a man who is taking on the vast majority of his
party's loyal-to-Gore establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of the year, Gore raised $8.9 million, but
Bradley held his own with $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has run up a huge lead in endorsements, but Bradley has
scored key hits, including Sen. Paul Wellstone, the liberal
Minnesota Democrat who considered a presidential campaign of his
own; former Texas Comptroller John Sharp; former New York Mayor Ed
Koch; and former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volker.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bradley backers have their eye on national polls that show
Gore losing to at least two Republican presidential prospects _
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Cabinet official Elizabeth
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   That status soon will worry even establishment Democrats, said
Susan Calegari, who helped organize Gary Hart's New Hampshire
campaigns in 1984 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill Bradley doesn't beat Al Gore,'' Calegari predicted,
``then a Republican's going to beat Al Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
