<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S SHOT GIVES VAN GUNDY A SHOT TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Allan Houston was playing at the University of
Tennessee, his coach and father, Wade, used to tell him to block
out everything. Half-crazed fans. Defenders trying to bait him into
a bad shot. Off-court controversy surrounding the team. Everything.
</P>
<P>
   Two things were supposed to matter in a tight game: the rim and
putting the ball inside it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago, you can't let outside forces get
inside your head and affect how you play,'' Houston said. Then,
referring to New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, he added: ``Jeff
stresses that a lot. Be it family, media or stuff going on in the
organization, you have one job. And when you're doing it, only the
other 12 players and the coaching staff matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston spoke in the visitors' locker room at Miami Arena
Sunday, pausing to reach into a cooler and grab a can of
orange-flavored Gatorade. Thirty minutes earlier, the player with
one of the prettiest shooting strokes in the game hit a
hideous-looking shot to win Game 5 _ a running jumper that bounced
off the front of the rim, off the backboard and in.
</P>
<P>
   That shot ended a 78-77 heirloom of a victory over the Miami
Heat. It resurrected a Knicks season. It made the arena dead quiet,
a wake for Pat Riley's team. And, as Houston took a sip, the
magnitude of it began to set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty big, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   For at least another series, the son of a coach saved Jeff Van
Gundy's job.
</P>
<P>
   That thought was dismissed by Dave Checketts, the Madison Square
Garden president, after the game. But there has been no
endorsement, no guarantee, and if anyone had told you that Van
Gundy would still be the coach after a first-round exit, well,
let's just say it was not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Houston understood what long odds Van Gundy was facing Sunday.
Wade Houston, like Allan's current coach, worked hard and did his
job. But he was ultimately relieved of his duties after his son
graduated as the school's career leading scorer. It was one of the
three times in Allan's life when he learned about the heartless
side of sports and business.
</P>
<P>
   The first was when the University of Louisville, where Wade had
been a loyal assistant to Denny Crum for 13 seasons, would not
immediately release Allan from his scholarship so that he could
play for his father. When he decided to sign with the Knicks rather
than stay with the Detroit Pistons, the outpouring of criticism he
received from his former team reaffirmed the feeling that loyalty
goes only so far in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put so much into a shot,'' Houston said. ``Bottom
line, if we didn't get the bounce, now all of those things can be
talked about. We don't go out there thinking about Jeff's job, just
about the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he added, ``Just the same, everyone knows how I feel about
Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship started out on a bad note, with the coach
often sitting the new starting shooting guard down in fourth
quarters of the 1996-97 season. They had numerous meetings inside
Van Gundy's office. The usual subject: Houston's confidence, or
lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy likened it to the relationships he has had this season
with Latrell Sprewell, Kurt Thomas and Marcus Camby, new
acquisitions who were unhappy at times with their roles. ``Allan
thought John, Patrick and Charles were my guys,'' Van Gundy said,
referring to the veterans John Starks, Patrick Ewing and Charles
Oakley. ``And it was understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everybody that's given me the time eventually trusts me
after a while. And I end up trusting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston said: ``A lot of people want to question Jeff's decision
to use people, but you have to earn some belief in him at some
point. Jeff saw in me more than I thought I ever saw in myself
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston did not have the type of game to celebrate until that
shot. Harangued and bothered by a game Dan Majerle, he had made
only four of his 12 previous shots. His 12 points to go along with
four turnovers could have easily been seen as an indictment of his
ability to perform in a crucial moment _ if not for that softly
released shot that nearly touched every part of the cylinder before
going in.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Knicks' coach often says, ``Sometimes, this game
ultimately comes down to makes or misses.''
</P>
<P>
   With Van Gundy's job and his team's season on the line, the son
of Wade Houston delivered. He blocked out everything. The crowd.
His defender. And all the rumors and speculation about what's going
to happen to this flawed but fearless team after it gets done with
its wild and improbable ride through the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a coach's son, you got to think about the game and
nothing else when you're taking that kind of shot,'' Houston said.
``Otherwise, you don't make the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot went in. The coach stays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
