<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-RADIO-MEDIA-     05-16 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-RADIO-MEDIA-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO MOVE ONLINE RADIO BEYOND A NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (js) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Until recently, it might have been fair to
enlist the cliche ``those crazy kids'' to describe people who
listened to radio on the Internet. But a series of announcements
last week signals that the demographic profile of online listeners
is expanding beyond 20-somethings to include the corporate set.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Yahoo started a Web radio service called Yahoo
Radio (http://radio.yahoo.com/), comprising 10 audio channels that
visitors can listen to using software called the Realplayer G2 from
Real Networks. The audio programming for Yahoo's service is
provided by Spinner.com, a San Francisco company that announced
plans last week to go public in September. Separately last week,
Looksmart, another search engine, announced plans to produce an
online talk show devoted to Internet topics.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, these deals underscore the growth of a
multilayered industry with players convinced that the PC will be
the radio tuner for the next generation. The entrepreneurs driving
the convergence of radio and the Internet say that listeners will
flock to specialized audio programming delivered over the PC,
sponsored by advertising aimed at individual listeners. But the
emergence of the technology poses a question for the industry: Is
the business proposition sound, or is it more white noise about the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Spinner.com illustrates one example of the type of business
model these companies are relying upon. The company, founded in
1996 as TheDJ.com, offers 175,000 songs on 120 channels; the fare
includes punk, funk, gospel, gumbo, surf and swing. Visitors to the
site download a player called Spinner Plus, which enables them to
listen to the channels.
</P>
<P>
   Like traditional radio stations, Spinner.com and its competitors
license the songs at a per-play fee from music industry groups like
the American Society of Composers, Artists and Performers.
</P>
<P>
   Spinner.com makes its money by several means: displaying banner
ads on the site; embedding audio commercials within the programming
_ 90 seconds each hour _ and by taking a cut of transactions when
visitors buy music at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The company also displays banner ads on the audio player, but
because listeners can minimize the image of the player, they might
not see those commercials, the company acknowledges. Still, Josh M.
Felser, president of Spinner.com, said that the site's traffic was
growing 25 percent a month and that Spinner.com had 1.3 million
unique listeners last month.
</P>
<P>
   People who register to use the site's audio player must divulge
their sex, age and some musical interests, allowing the company to
give highly targeted information to advertisers. ``We do what radio
does, only better,'' Felser said. ``It's going to take time for ad
buyers to wake up to our capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment and the Spinner.com business model are copied by
several competitors, including Rolling Stone Radio, a partnership
between the online music hub Tunes.com and Real Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Another competitor, Imagine Radio, which was acquired in
February by the MTV Networks unit of Viacom, creates individually
customized radio stations. Visitors to the site can choose the
genre of music they want to hear and indicate which artists they
would like to hear more or less often.
</P>
<P>
   These Internet companies are vying for consumer attention with
some 1,600 traditional radio stations that have made their
programming available over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Verdino, vice president of Arbitron New Media, which
studies radio listening patterns, said more than 3,500 radio
stations were still not online. But he said they had better start
thinking about it, citing studies showing that people who listen to
radio on the Net listen to less radio on traditional stations.
``It's potentially'' a threat, he said. ``It's also potentially an
opportunity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A study released in April by Arbitron New Media found the
portion of Internet users who had listened to radio online more
than doubled in the previous six months to 13 percent from 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be huge,'' said Rotem Perelmuter, former chief
executive of Imagine Radio and now vice president for strategy at
MTV, referring to online-only radio content. ``The operating
profits from radio are $6 billion,'' he said. ``We're going to take
a big chunk of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so optimistic, at least in the short term. Some
industry analysts say that despite the recent growth, most radio
listeners will not regularly turn to their PCs for listening.
Skeptics point out that the audiences even for the most popular
online radio hubs remain in the low tens of thousands of visitors
daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``A radio advertising executive is going to look at that traffic
and go, `Come on, I can't sell advertising on that,' '' said Mark
Hardie, a senior analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass. Hardie thinks online radio will remain a niche market.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick H. Keane, an analyst for Jupiter Communications, a
market research firm in New York, is less pessimistic. Keane said a
new category of at-work radio listener was emerging. He said he
thought there was a growing market for online audio programmers to
reach into offices where employees may listen while they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're definitely looking at a niche audience, but I'm firmly
convinced it's going to grow,'' Keane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
