<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boone's 2 homers spark Braves' resurgence
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Bret Boone kept pounding away, and the Braves lineup
eventually followed his lead Sunday and broke out of its catatonic
state.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a left-field-bound breeze at Wrigley Field, the Braves
hit four home runs, two by Boone. His first helped them take their
first lead in a game since Tuesday, and the second started a
three-run eighth-inning rally that brought the Braves an 8-5
victory against the Cubs and a little peace of mind at the end of a
3-6 trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one, I smoked,'' said Boone, who was 3-for-5 with a
double, two runs scored and three batted in. ``The second one, the
wind helped it. I hit it 350 feet, it went 380 feet. I'll take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 5-3 after seven effective innings by Cubs rookie Kyle
Farnsworth, of Roswell, Ga., the Braves got their first taste this
series of a Cubs bullpen that has blown eight of 17 save
opportunities. They feasted on Rodney Myers for three consecutive
hits, including home runs by Boone and Brian Jordan, to take back
the lead, 6-5. They got two more runs off Rod Beck in the ninth to
seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The rally salvaged an uncharacteristically ineffective start by
John Smoltz. The five runs he allowed in six innings were the most
he has given up in 16 starts, dating to Aug. 9, and his earned run
average climbed to 2.59, the first time this season it has gone
above 2.00.
</P>
<P>
   The two home runs he allowed _ Mark Grace's with the bases empty
in the fourth inning and Tyler Houston's with a runner on base
during a four-run sixth _ equaled the number he had given up in
seven previous starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As off-kilter as I felt, I didn't feel like I'd give up five
runs,'' Smoltz said. ``Those two (home runs) were fly balls, but
that's what you get when you play in this park. We took advantage
of it too. We needed a win like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
