<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS PITCHING HITS ROCKY ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ There are no lazy Sunday afternoons in May, not with
Mark McGwire at the plate and the Dodgers playing reliever's
roulette.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of the Dodgers' 5-4 loss to the St. Louis
Cardinals, McGwire nearly won it with a home run that hooked just
foul. In the ninth, he was walked only to let Ray Lankford hit a
two-run homer off closer Jeff Shaw that sent the Dodgers home
wondering about their pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book on him is you don't let him beat you,'' Shaw said of
McGwire, whose record 70 homers last year weighs a lot more than
his 2 for 19 against the Dodgers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a reason they have Lankford behind him. The guy
is a hitter, too. I didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw entered the game eight for eight in save situations, but
this was not a day for perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Osuna relieved starter Ismael Valdes with one out in the
sixth and hit a batter to load the bases before pitching out of
trouble. Alan Mills came in for the seventh and appeared to give up
a two-run homer to McGwire, but the ball sailed a few feet foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely was gone,'' Dodgers catcher Paul LoDuca said.
``But it hooked at the end and we still had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills struck out McGwire but walked Lankford and Fernando Tatis
to load the bases. He retired former Baltimore teammate Eric Davis
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Eric could be a turning point for me,'' said Mills,
who has struggled since giving up a game-winning grand slam to
Florida's Bruce Aven 10 days ago. ``You just have to go out there
and give it everything you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson isn't worried about that as much as he is
his starters. He looked pretty drained in the clubhouse after
watching the team blow 4-1 leads in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers open a six-game homestand Tuesday, against NL
Central-leading Houston, with their most ineffective starter,
Carlos Perez (1-4, 6.23 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was hoping to leave St. Louis in first place in the
National League West and start putting a little distance between
the Dodgers and the rest of the division. But will he have the arms
to survive the long hot summer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Your starters have to go longer than 51/3 innings,'' Johnson
said after watching Chan Ho Park and Valdes get chased in the sixth
inning the last two games. ``That sets up everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes led 4-1 after two innings, 4-2 after three and was ahead
in the sixth when Lankford hit his first homer, an opposite-field
shot that landed into the Dodgers bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who has suffered from blisters on his throwing hand
throughout his career, was pitching with a split nail on his right
hand. He had endured a sprained left ankle running the bases in the
second but stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have his good stuff today. And when he started to
get the ball up in the sixth, it was time for a change,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals manager Tony La Russa should be so lucky. He entered
this series with his starters having failed to pitch six innings in
six of the last nine games. Sunday, he turned to his closer, Juan
Acevedo, to start against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo pitched only two innings and allowed five hits and four
runs. Three came in the second inning on RBI by Valdes, Jose
Vizcaino and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Dodgers, the St. Louis bullpen did not fall
apart. Four Cardinals relievers allowed four hits and no runs over
the final seven innings. This is a group that is groping, entering
games too early with a 4.92 ERA as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a tough game all around,'' Shaw said. ``We struggled
and I didn't do my job. But that is a life of a reliever. There's
always tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
