<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRAVES NOTEBOOK: Jordan homers without trying
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Brian Jordan knew when he left San Francisco that he'd
have to quit swinging for home runs, even though he was the cleanup
hitter and the team was slumping.
</P>
<P>
   He figured that would get him back into his game _ driving in
runs with singles and doubles and using the occasional home run to
clean the bases.
</P>
<P>
   His patience was rewarded with a two-run home run to center in
the eighth inning Sunday, which gave the Braves the tying and
go-ahead runs in an 8-5 victory against the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was only 6-for-29 on this trip entering Sunday's game,
and after going 0-for-3 on Saturday his average had dipped to .294.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team started slumping a little bit, instead of
playing within yourself, you try to carry the team on your
shoulders,'' Jordan said. ``I was overswinging, trying to hit home
runs. I'm not a home run hitter. My dad reminded me of that. I
should know better.'' Roster watch
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox replaced a slumping Otis Nixon (.181 batting
average) in Sunday's lineup with Gerald Williams, and the move paid
off with a 1-for-3 day from Williams, who also scored a run, drove
in a run and stole a base.
</P>
<P>
   Williams normally starts and bats leadoff against left-handers,
but against right-hander Kyle Farnsworth he batted in the No. 8
slot. Walt Weiss led off for the first time this season and reached
base twice in five plate appearances, with a walk and a single,
drove in a run and scored one.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Randall Simon is expected to rejoin the Braves
today from AAA Richmond, and catcher Pascual Matos will return
there. Matos was up to back up Eddie Perez while Javy Lopez was in
Puerto Rico after his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Hudek is unavailable for a day or two because of a
blister on his third finger, which burst during his inning on
Friday. Adjusting the rotation
</P>
<P>
   Cox originally wanted to pitch Odalis Perez today and Kevin
Millwood on Tuesday to get Perez back on the mound on five days'
rest, but he decided to go with Millwood on his regular four days'
rest and push Perez back a day.
</P>
<P>
   Perez has struggled in the two starts he's made with long rest _
of 12 and nine days _ but will have his next three starts with
somewhat regular rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be more comfortable,'' Perez said. ``It's hard when you
don't see a hitter for 10 days. The next three starts I'll pitch
regular, and it will be much better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez gave up a season-high seven runs in his previous outing
against the Giants, including six in the first inning, and his ERA
climbed to 5.46.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
