<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9345 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-LADN-(SLANG)     05-16 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY JACOBSEN LEARNED LESSONS WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ If you ask Casey Jacobsen where he learned
the importance of working hard without the ball, or where he
learned the necessity of having an inside game to go with an
outside game, or where he learned that the mind really does matter,
he'll point to the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that little Casey Jacobsen sat on the way home from
hundreds of basketball games of his older brothers, Adam and Brock,
and listened as they talked with their father, Von, about what went
right, what went wrong and what they would do better next time.
</P>
<P>
   It was basketball by osmosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the car rides home while my dad analyzed the game, I
must have soaked things in that I didn't even know,'' Jacobsen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I experienced two pretty good basketball players first hand.
They made mistakes and had some victories and I jotted all that
down in my mind why do they win, why do they lose? My brothers gave
me a mental advantage over everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these days Jacobsen needn't worry about taking a back
seat to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   He recently concluded his career at Glendora High as the CIF
Southern Section's all-time leading scorer, and nobody in the
nation has had a more eye-catching postseason. His performances
this year have helped Jacobsen become the leading vote-getter in
the 23rd annual
</P>
<P>
   Press-Telegram Best in the West poll.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, a 6-foot-6, 205-pound swingman, received 280 points
from college coaches and scouts, outdistancing the other unanimous
first-team selections, Artesia forward Jason Kapono (255) and
Juneau, Alaska, forward Carlos Boozer (245).
</P>
<P>
   THE TOTAL PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen is just as well regarded off the court.
</P>
<P>
   He's a thoughtful, articulate young man speaker
</P>
<P>
   who was the guest speaker at the Glendora Little League's
opening-day ceremonies, and last Sunday addressed his church on
Mother's Day. He carries a 3.9 grade-point average, has scored 1040
on the SAT and has accepted a scholarship to Stanford in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Casey there's an understanding that there's more to
school than just playing basketball,'' said Mike LeDuc, who has
also coached NBA journeyman Tracy Murray, his brother Cameron and
Adam Jacobsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've become a society that looks for players instead
of one that looks for great kids and great student athletes.
There's nothing you can say about the boy except that you'd like to
have him as your own son. He's just a classy young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Jacobsen has raised his four sons Adam, 24; Brock, 22;
Casey, 18; and Derek, 12; as a preacher might. But instead of the
good book, he's put a basketball in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten in their blood real early,'' said his wife, Becky.
``Some like it more than others, but they all really like the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FAMILY TREES
</P>
<P>
   Von, who played at San Diego State and in Europe, knocked down
citrus trees to build a regulation half-court in his backyard,
replete with lights, a regulation college 3-point line and
break-away rims.
</P>
<P>
   He later leased out the family's home in Glendora and moved them
20 miles west to La Crescenta so that Adam, in his senior year in
high school, wouldn't have to play a subordinate role to Cameron
Murray, who would go on to play at USC and Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   The end game was to garner a free education for his sons, and on
that account the Jacobsens are three for three.
</P>
<P>
   Adam played with Clippers center Michael Olowokandi at Pacific,
where he earned a Master's degree and was recently hired as an
assistant coach. Brock, meanwhile, played at the University of San
Diego, where he'll graduate with a business degree next weekend and
then begin working for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   That Casey is expected to surpass them is no surprise to his
older brothers.
</P>
<P>
   They came home from school three summers ago to find that they
were suddenly getting schooled by the scrawny 15-year-old kid they
used to pick on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was pretty hard when your younger brother is
kicking the crap out of you,'' said Adam. ``He didn't beat us every
single time like he can now, but it really opened both of our eyes
as to the development that he'd gone through and the potential that
was there. We realized he was going to be very, very good and be
one of the best players in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, as one might expect of such a prolific scorer, is as
polished an offensive player as you'll find in high school. He's an
excellent perimeter player he made 92 3-pointers his senior season
and is equally adept at beating defenders off the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what distinguishes him among the elite isn't his skill but
his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets Casey apart from most players around the country is
his toughness,'' said Joel Francisco, who runs So. Cal's Finest
Scouting Service. ``He wants to tear your hat off he wants to
compete. A lot of the top players I've seen are dogs. They kind of
coast until the competition gets better. With Casey, it doesn't
matter who's out there, he's out for blood. He wants to dominate
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch players you can usually point to a specific
game where they make an impression. Casey's the same every time. He
might be the most consistent player in Southern California. He's so
mentally tough. A lot of the top kids kind of float, and that's
what is going to set him apart among the top freshman. I think he's
going to be among the top five in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Determination didn't just arrive at the door one day. It came
long before his jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when he was 12 and I was 18, he thought he should be able
to beat me,'' Adam said. ``We're all pretty competitive whether
it's at the dinner table, in the back yard or in school with
grades. It's something that becomes part of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that I think makes Casey different from the rest
of us is he's a little stubborn. He doesn't take no for an answer
and doesn't see things other people's way. He's going to do
whatever he thinks he has to do to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   This has resulted in a clinical approach to the game. Each time
a roadblock is presented, Jacobsen examines it, analyzes it and
finds his way around it.
</P>
<P>
   After he distinguished himself as a freshman he scored 30 points
in the state playoffs against eventual champion Crenshaw Jacobsen
began seeing defenses geared to stop him the next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started seeing a box-and-one defense I was
getting shut down. I wouldn't even get double digits,'' said
Jacobsen. ``I thought, `No way am I going through my career like
this.' I worked on being able to catch and shoot very quickly. Then
I learned to develop my ball-handling skills and to shoot deeper.
Even the best defenders can't take away everything.''
</P>
<P>
   He's evolved into a player who can score consistently off the
dribble and this year he's learned to be even more relentless in
working without the ball, as opponents increasingly clutched,
grabbed and sometimes succeeded in wearing him down.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why teams would go to such extreme measures.
Jacobsen, as a junior, averaged 45 points per game in the playoffs
as Glendora won the CIF Southern Section Division I-A title. In one
game he made 11 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   This season at the Martin Luther King Classic a day-long series
of games at UCLA's Pauley Pavilion he scored an event-record 43
points against Capistrano Valley.
</P>
<P>
   His senior season came to a disappointing end when Glendora was
beaten by Mater Dei for the Division I title and eliminated in the
second round of the state playoffs by Artesia and Kapono.
</P>
<P>
   SEEING THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   When Jacobsen has stepped out of his Glendora uniform and onto
the national and international scene, he has acquitted himself just
as well.
</P>
<P>
   He captained the United States to the gold medal last summer at
the World Youth Games at Moscow as the Americans beat Russia in
overtime in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen counts the experience as the highlight of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had conflicts on the team and as the captain I was always
in the middle of it,'' said Jacobsen, who led the U.S. with 25
points per game. ``We had some characters who didn't get along and
I was very involved in trying to get everybody involved. All the
odds were stacked against us. We hadn't played with each other
before. We all really wanted to win the gold medal, we just didn't
know how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow along the way I still don't know how we all came
together. To represent your country rather than your high school or
your city is quite an amazing experience. You don't know what it's
like until you put on the jersey. Just to see the American flag up
there after we won the gold medal was pretty overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   To play in Moscow, Jacobsen passed up the Nike Camp, one of the
showcase summer events where reputations are cemented. Hence, out
of sight, out of mind, Jacobsen was not among the 20 players
selected for last month's McDonald's All-American Game the
nationally televised showcase for the nation's top high school
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   After some late lobbying, he was added as the game's 21st player
and justified his selection by scoring 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, at the nationally televised Hoop Summit, he
scored 31 points, including 6 of 8 3-pointers, to lead the U.S.
Junior Select team over an international all-star team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never played with a group so talented before in my life
and I could hold my own,'' Jacobsen said of the McDonald's game.
``It was a humbling experience that I could play with the best. I
think anybody who was at that game would say that. There wasn't one
guy that you'd say, `This guy doesn't belong here.' It was a big
confidence builder. I learned I can do whatever I want to do as far
as basketball is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it seems, Casey Jacobsen is in the driver's seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
