<SLUG> BC-BKO-KAPONO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASON KAPONO CREATED HIS OWN LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Jason Kapono didn't expect to be linked to
Ed O'Bannon when the basketball standout decided to attend Artesia
High. But like O'Bannon, Kapono won a CIF title, was named a
McDonald's and Parade All-American, and rewrote the school record
book during his tenure at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono and O'Bannon have another achievement in common: a
perfect score in the Best in the West basketball poll.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono joins O'Bannon as the only players from the same school
to be unanimous selections, and gives the Pioneers program five
first-team selections overall.
</P>
<P>
   During Kapono's freshman and sophomore seasons at Artesia,
O'Bannon and several other former Artesia stars would return to the
school in the summer to work out and share their experiences with
the current players. It was a moment not lost on Kapono, who was
well aware of the numerous accomplishments by O'Bannon on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell me to keep working and playing hard, and you had
to respect that because he was the college Player of the Year and
had made a name for himself,'' Kapono said. ``I had heard about him
being the best player in high school back (in 1990). I actually saw
his highlight tape, and it looked pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kapono never led the Pioneers to state titles like Ed and
sibling Charles O'Bannon did, he most certainly has created his own
legacy within the Pioneers program, according to Coach Wayne
Merino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of those guys is a different individual, but they're
all very talented,'' Merino said. ``Most coaches are lucky if
they've had one guy at that level and I've had three or four. But
Jason's left his own mark and his own level of excellence (on) our
program, as have the others before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Artesia went 119-14 during Kapono's four-year career, and the
player holds all of the school's major statistical records,
including the scoring mark with 2,678 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Pioneers won their second consecutive CIF Southern Section
Division I-AA crown this season, and came within a game of playing
for the Division I state title.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad legacy for a player who just wanted to make the
varsity team as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to fit in and play a little when I started
out,'' Kapono said. ``I didn't think I had a chance to get a
college scholarship or anything like that. But as each year went
on, Coach Merino started telling me I had a great shot at getting
one, and that fired me up.''
</P>
<P>
   His performances this season including a game in which he had 52
points, 18 rebounds and nine assists in only 24 minutes combined
with a 3.9 GPA and 1,120 SAT score are more than enough to have
fired up the college basketball coaching community. After putting
together a list of schools he was considering at the beginning of
his senior season, Kapono has a new one that includes Missouri,
Utah, UCLA and Arizona. He has tentatively planned to announce his
collegiate choice on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Making a decision) is a little tougher now because it's so
late in the game and I've been going through some family problems
with my grandpa,'' said Kapono of his grandfather, Joe Kapono II,
who is one of his biggest fans. The elder Kapono desperately needs
a liver transplant. He has found a matching donor, but must first
pass a battery of tests to determine if his heart is strong enough
for the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   While his grandfather's health will carry some weight on his
decision, Kapono said it won't be the determining factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't mind if I left home to go to college,'' Jason
said. ``My grandfather wants what's best for me, and I'm sure he
wouldn't be disappointed just because I left (the area) and he
couldn't see me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most high school basketball players, Kapono has dreams of
one day casting jump shots in the NBA. But he's also intelligent
enough to realize that basketball isn't a lifetime job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is only going to be with me for so many years,'' he
said. ``I may have to stop playing after college because I'm not
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I want to make it to the pros, but even that ends at
(the age of) 35. So I'm going to make sure I take care of business
in the classroom, because I know that life goes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
