</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BANGED-UP EWING WON'T TAKE BACK SEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Alonzo Mourning turned to face Patrick Ewing, with the
ball, to the left of the basket, a one-point lead set up perfectly
to become three. One on one, friend on friend, student against
teacher. There was a minute and a half left in Game 5 Sunday, the
Knicks and the Heat, survival at stake, and here was Mourning's
chance to emphatically state that his time had come and Ewing's had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning, brutish and quick-footed, against Ewing, 36 and banged
up. Pat Riley had called this play, the one that should have been
Miami's ticket to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The low post was where the Heat could supposedly punish the
Knicks, where Mourning could school his lame fellow Georgetown
alum. Ewing could not move laterally, remember? His injured left
Achilles' tendon had rendered him immobile, a relic in need of
grease and oil.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ewing, foot aching, knees creaking, hip muscle piercing,
found himself in the last place he wanted to be, positioned where
Mourning had only moments before blown past him, into the lane, for
a jump hook and that one-point Miami lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see Alonzo giving Patrick every move, trying to get
to the middle, and Patrick trying to force him baseline,'' said
Chris Dudley, the Knicks' backup center, who makes a living with
post defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the end of the game,'' Dudley said, ``and your emotions
and the adrenaline overcome a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not quite the end, but Ewing's defense resulted in a
24-second violation for Miami when Mourning gave up the ball and
Terry Porter failed to get off a shot. It was a symbolic conflict,
a prescient moment, of a friendly bounce to come for Allan Houston,
of a stunning 78-77 victory for Ewing's team over Mourning's.
</P>
<P>
   The body language of the big men on that one play was a
microcosm of the game, if not the series. The younger center,
promoted by even Ewing as the league's most valuable player, still
doesn't have a classic go-to move. He was not up to the task of
taking a first-round series when it was waiting for him, a quick
first step away.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't get around the old man, to the lane or the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let the young fellow know he wasn't getting to the
basket,'' said Herb Williams, from the locker stall next to Ewing.
``He did that on one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   On one leg, in obvious pain, Ewing outscored Mourning, 22-21,
and outrebounded him, 11-5. If anyone deserved the friendly bounce
on Houston's runner off the inbounds pass by Charlie Ward with 0.8
seconds left, it was him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the playoffs,'' Ewing said, ``and we've lost a lot of
games on last-second shots. It was sweet for it to be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times when the game's winning shot should not be its
lasting memory, and this was one of those games. Ewing, often
defined by the shots he has not made, carried the Knicks to the
threshold of victory, first against Mourning and then by dragging
his brittle bones to the basket at the other end, after two free
throws by Porter had given the Heat a 77-74 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell backed Porter into the lane, and Mourning
jumped out to help. The shot bounced off the rim, to Ewing on the
right side. He was fouled by Mourning on the put-back. Ewing walked
to the line, where he has disappointed people so many times before,
and made two shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest play of the game,'' Riley said, though he later
admitted he would have a sleepless night or two recalling Mourning
and Ewing on the left side, the floor balanced, set up as if the
players were those little men on the magnetic board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick's who he is,'' Riley said, not bothering to say more.
</P>
<P>
   The past failures are still there, and there are still clouds in
the Knicks' long-range forecast. This was not about the last 13
years or coming ones, though. It was not about Ewing's headstrong,
even foolish, insistence that he won't play for Phil Jackson any
more than it was about saving Jeff Van Gundy's job.
</P>
<P>
   This was about Ewing being just as stubborn about stepping aside
for the next generation, much in the way Utah's John Stockton and
Karl Malone held their ground against the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bittersweet,'' Ewing called the victory, referring to his
friendship with Mourning, taken out in the first round by the
Knicks for a second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's your boy?'' Williams teased Ewing in the locker room.
``Probably home by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mourning was up in the interview room, sounding much
like Ewing in post-season defeat, insisting the Heat were the
better team.
</P>
<P>
   Williams looked down at a seated Ewing, and said, ``You let him
know you're still in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing smiled. He sat there with his left foot in an ice bucket,
with packs on his knees, on his hip and on last season's broken
right wrist. He was still in the house, refusing to move. The proud
man plays on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
