<HEADLINE>
A NICE PIECE OF CHANGE FOR A SIMPLE GUY  
 NEW DICTIONARY DEFINES AND ADVISES  
 PULITZER PRIZE JUDGES SPEAK THEIR MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Individual bylines follow first two items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet is responsible for some odd things _ the ability to
monitor strangers' lives 24 hours a day comes to mind _ but last
week it created something truly weird: a wealthy magazine editor.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, 32, editor in chief of TheStreet.com, was once a
humble radio sports announcer on WKCR-FM, the radio station of
Columbia University. Later, he was a newspaper reporter, writing
about sports for Newsday, then about the stock market for The Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   While he was an undergraduate at Columbia College, he sang with
the Kingsmen, an a cappella group, and remarked about that period,
``My favorite moment was singing the national anthem and then
broadcasting it live right before a basketball game.'' In short, a
man of simple humility and earthy flair.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, TheStreet.com _ an Internet magazine that
provides financial news and analysis, and of which The New York
Times is a backer _ offered its stock to the public for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the first day of trading, the shares rose $41, to
$60, and the 3-year-old money-losing operation suddenly had a
market value of $1.41 billion. And Kansas, who shares an apartment
with a roommate and says he has a hole in the toe of his right
loafer, was worth $9.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, James Cramer, 44, the hedge-fund manager,
financial columnist and a co-founder of TheStreet.com, saw his
stake grow to $202.6 million. In a profile in the June issue of
Vanity Fair, Cramer is reported to have looked around the room at a
wedding in the early 1980s, at which many of the guests were
journalists, and remarked, ``These are all $30,000-a-year men.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has surely proved that journalists need not all be
$30,000-a-year men, or women. And Kansas defends TheStreet.com,
even if it has not made a profit. ``We have a great product and a
good brand and popular writers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one overnight change. ``Everyone expects me to
buy them dinner now,'' Kansas said. ``And of course I do, because
I'm from Minnesota.'' Which means what? ``That I'm a generous
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Kansas cannot have access to his wealth for six months,
he is rich only on paper. But his desires are minimal. ``The one
thing I think about is: Wouldn't it be nice to have my own place to
live? Or to buy a really nice titanium bicycle?'' He paused. ``And
maybe a bed,'' he said. ``Right now I sleep on a futon on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   New Dictionary Defines and Advises
</P>
<P>
   The newest version of the Random House Webster's College
Dictionary makes its debut this spring with ``New Words for the New
Millennium'' plus a reader-beware feature: warning labels for some
300 words that are flagged for odiousness.
</P>
<P>
   The editors reserved their harshest description for a racial
epithet that they called ``probably the most offensive word in
English.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Its degree of offensiveness has increased markedly in recent
years, although it has been used in a derogatory manner since at
least the Revolutionary War,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Wendalyn Nichols, the dictionary's editorial director, said she
was considering adding the usage warnings earlier this year when a
language snarl hit the rival dictionary publisher Merriam-Webster
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In that episode, the publisher and America Online Inc. removed
an electronic version of Merriam's classic collegiate thesaurus for
revisions after complaints that a word list for ``homosexual''
included synonyms without any warning that the words were slurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That only confirmed to me that it's not only a good idea but a
great idea'' to provide warnings, Ms. Nichols said. ``Increasingly,
people also expect a dictionary to give guidance about words that
are better avoided for fear of accidentally causing offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Random House is owned by Bertelsmann AG. The bright-red dust
jacket for its new 1,571-page dictionary promises ``more new words
than any other dictionary'' and ``clear guidance on avoiding
offensive language.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the word warnings appear even before the
definitions. ``Holy roller,'' for example, is first labeled: ``A
slur and must be avoided. It is perceived as insulting.'' Then
comes the definition: ``A contemptuous term used to refer to a
member of a Pentecostal sect.''
</P>
<P>
   Milder words with double meanings come with weaker alerts.
``Babe,'' for instance, is first defined as ``a baby or small
child.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dictionary adds a final note, leaving it to the reader
to decide whether to use it as a term of endearment or insult:
``sometimes used with disparaging intent and perceived as insulting
or demeaning to women'' as well as ``an affectionate term of
address used by a man or woman to a sweetheart.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize Judges Speak Their Minds
</P>
<P>
   Every April, the Pulitzer Prizes are announced with trumpets
blaring. But the selection process, which is run by the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University, usually goes
unexamined.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Columbia Journalism Review, the curtain is pulled
back, if only a bit. An article asks the question: What did the 77
nominating jurists _ senior journalists and academics, who pored
over entries for three days in March _ think of the process?
</P>
<P>
   Those who judged the coverage of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal
said, among other things: ``I was so sick of that story''; ``The
stories were all about the same''; ``Even the best of the coverage
was flawed in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at the
University of California at Berkeley, said of the entries reviewed
by his international panel: ``Fully half to two-thirds of those 48
submissions never would have been written were there not a Pulitzer
Prize. They were complex and not read by many people, though
they're essential for a small number of people to be well informed
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Opotowsky, ombudsman for The Press-Enterprise in Riverside,
Calif., described the competition in his beat reporting category as
tough: ``Of the 150 entries we had in my panel, I'd say that only
about 10 shouldn't have been there, and of the rest, 20 or 30 were
serious, serious contenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Some editors complained about the length of articles, saying
that the unwieldiness of several entries damaged their chances.
``We started calling it the spare-tire problem _ good stories that
were too fat in the middle,'' said Wendy Zomparelli, vice president
of The Roanoke Times in Virginia, who judged in the feature-writing
category.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Shales, television critic at The Washington Post, was the
most blunt: ``There is so much sameness and flatulence and
pomposity in the writing I read about film that it didn't seem to
me that any film critic this year really stood out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
