<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSEVERANCE PAYS FOR ROBERTS AT THE BYRON NELSON CLASSIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The first six times that Loren Roberts entered
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic, he missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts kept coming back, however, never succumbing to the
disappointment, always believing one of his trips to Texas would
result in victory.
</P>
<P>
   That perseverance paid off for Roberts Sunday, as in his 17th
appearance at the Nelson, he found the winning formula. After
surviving several precarious moments on the back nine, Roberts
outlasted Steve Pate, who bogeyed the first hole of a sudden-death
playoff to open the door for Roberts, who made a winning par.
</P>
<P>
   Both Roberts and Pate set a tournament record, finishing at 18
under par (262), and ran away from the rest of the field. Four
players finished tied for third at 11 under par _ Lee Janzen,
19-year-old Sergio Garcia, Chris DiMarco, and Brian Watts. Garcia
earned $144,000, taking a major step toward earning a PGA Tour card
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth tour victory of Roberts' career earned him a $540,000
check, the largest of his career, and it was his first victory
since the 1997 CVS Charity Classic. Roberts shot a two-under-par 68
today, but it was his sizzling 62 on Saturday that vaulted him into
the lead at the TPC of Las Colinas. Pate shot a final-round 66. But
this time, instead of leaving the Nelson discouraged, Roberts left
with a trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two months ago, I was thinking, `I'm 43 years old, maybe
I'm too old for these young guys,''' said Roberts, whose
83-year-old father, Hugh Roberts, watched from the gallery to
witness a victory by his son for the first time. ``I can't tell you
how good it feels to get back in the winner's circle. You start to
doubt yourself. It feels really good to play well under the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament ended at the par-4, 479-yard No. 18, the first
playoff hole. After their drives, both players missed the green on
their approach shots. Pate hit a 4-iron shot that was caught by the
wind and drifted right into the green-side bunker, 60 yards from
the pin. Roberts hit his approach shot into the left bunker, about
20 yards from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   After Pate pitched to 15 feet, Roberts hit a great bunker shot
that stopped 3 feet short. Pate knew that if he missed his 15-foot
putt for par, he would probably lose. He hit a firm putt, but it
slid past the hole and he tapped in for bogey. Roberts ended the
tournament by making the three-foot par putt, then raising his arms
in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second runner-up finish for Pate this year, but with
four top-10 finishes, he is enjoying a career season, having
already earned $1,334,637, fourth on the tour money list. Pate was
also the runner-up at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic in January,
when David Duval shot a final-round 59.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played very well; unfortunately, it wasn't good enough,''
said Pate, who has recovered from a serious 1996 car accident that
forced him to take a year off the tour. ``If I hang around the lead
enough times, something good will happen. I can't really control
what Loren did, or what Duval did at Palm Springs.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day with a two-stroke edge over Pate, Roberts lost
the lead at No. 14 when he hit his second shot into the water and
double-bogeyed. That gave Pate a one-stroke lead, but Roberts
bounced back with a birdie at No. 15, hitting an approach shot to
within four feet, followed by a three-foot putt to tie Pate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty impressive comeback,'' Pate said of Roberts'
birdie at No. 15. ``That's not an easy hole. Hitting a 3-iron to
four feet is pretty good, especially after making a double-bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate and Roberts parred the last three holes to force sudden
death, though Roberts had a chance to win in regulation at No. 18.
Pate's approach shot was short and left of the green, about 40
yards from the pin, while Roberts hit a fine second shot that
landed 20 feet below the cup.
</P>
<P>
   After Pate chipped to five feet, Roberts could have ended the
tournament by making his 20-foot birdie attempt. But Roberts' putt
stopped a foot short and Pate converted his five-foot putt to force
the playoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
