<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IDLE HANDS IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 17:
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that it would be a good political ploy. To rally
support for their candidate for a state Senate seat north of New
York City, several Democrats endorsed what has long been little
more than a suburban whim. They announced that they wanted the
state Legislature to end a commuter tax for suburbanites who work
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   State Republicans, not to be outdone on what is normally a
Republican issue, quickly supported the concept, adding that the
Republican-controlled state Senate would approve legislation.
Because the governor could be expected to endorse the measure, the
Democratic Assembly with its Democratic speaker, Sheldon Silver of
New York City, was considered the fail-safe that was sure to stop
it this week.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for a muddle of mostly political reasons, Silver
has promised that his Democratic Assembly will vote with the
Republicans. So, New York City stands to lose at least $210 million
a year in taxes from commuters who live elsewhere in New York. If
the state ends this tax on its own commuters, the commuters from
Connecticut and New Jersey, who pay an additional $150 million a
year, are sure to challenge their contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Silver argues that the city has a fat surplus and can afford the
loss. This shortsighted view does not recognize that the surplus is
probably temporary while the loss of commuter revenue would
undoubtedly be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's supporters accuse Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov.
George Pataki of playing pre-election games that could force
Democrats to defend this tax while Republicans, especially Giuliani
in a possible statewide race, would benefit. However, Giuliani has
spoken out vehemently against the end of the commuter tax, an
appeal that certainly cannot help him in the city's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic speaker is also said to be mindful of Democrats
in ``marginal'' seats that are often challenged during elections.
Given that no incumbents lost in the legislative elections last
year, this would seem to be a dubious concern. Nevertheless, if
Republican state senators vote to abolish the commuter tax,
Silver's Democratic state legislators are set to do the same soon
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   This legislative battle feels like a schoolyard dare. Silver's
excuses have a particularly hollow ring for someone whose home base
is New York City. For years, New Yorkers have negotiated to keep
this crucial income as a way to help pay for services used by
commuters who often earn far more than city residents. It is not
clear what, if anything, Silver gained for the city in exchange for
this whopping loss.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is what happens in Albany when nothing else is
happening in Albany. The state budget is stalled, the governor is
often absent and an entire state Capitol full of unpaid legislators
is idle. It is time to end the games. A very large city could get
hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
