<SLUG> BC-CAR-RICHMOND-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS HELPS EASE JARRETT'S MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Dale Jarrett had been stuck in second for much
of this season. Consistently good, he had not been good enough for
victory lane. The frustration of coming so close week after week _
he had finished second three times _ was wearing at his team's
morale, and his own.
</P>
<P>
   But the frowns in his pit disappeared on Saturday night, when
Jarrett coupled another good run with some rare good luck at
Richmond International Speedway and got that elusive first victory
in the Pontiac Excitement 400. His face and body language were the
picture of relief. Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief, smiled for
the first time in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By leading the final 32 laps, and holding back the hard-charging
Mark Martin and Bobby Labonte, Jarrett drove his Ford Taurus from
second place in the Winston Cup point standing to first. And if
this season becomes Jarrett's season, Saturday will be the day it
was defined.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's victory was worth 118 points, moving him from 55
points behind Jeff Burton to a 63-point lead. Burton dominated
Saturday's race but succumbed to a transmission problem and
finished 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to take the points lead,'' Jarrett said, beaming
after the victory. ``We've fought back since the accident at
Daytona and kept battling.'' Jarrett went spinning into the wall on
Lap 135 of the Daytona 500 in a crash that took out 12 cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even on days where it seemed we might not be the best car or
we were struggling,'' he said, ``it was real important for a couple
of reasons for us to take this points lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, 43, is a veteran of 13 seasons and a son of the
two-time Winston Cup champion Ned Jarrett. He has won the big races
_ the Daytona 500 (twice), the Coca-Cola 600 and the Brickyard 400
_ but he does not have a championship. He has come close, finishing
second to Jeff Gordon in 1997 and third twice, most recently in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend figured to be a challenge for Jarrett and his team,
owned by Robert Yates, because their luck had not been good lately
at Richmond International. Last year in this race, after a
controversial red flag with six laps left, he lost the lead to the
eventual winner Terry Labonte, who bumped Jarrett's car with two
laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Jarrett started seventh in the Exide 400 here but
finished 16th. That cost him 60 points when Gordon and Martin ran
second and third to Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a good car coming to Richmond,'' Parrott said.
``This was the same car we had last year, but we've made some
changes to it. The extra effort adds up and makes the end result so
sweet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just as Jarrett's season seems to be coming together, everything
seems to be falling apart around Gordon, the two-time defending
series champion. He nursed an ill-handling car all night and
finished 31st.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's troubles began on Lap 81, when he was bumped from
behind by Steve Park. After the nudge, Gordon's car shimmied and
then slowed. As a result of the contact, the front end of his car
began to vibrate. By Lap 94, the vibration was so bad that Gordon
pitted for repairs. He lost two laps, which, in effect, ended his
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what really ruined our night,'' said Gordon, who is in
fifth place in the point standing. ``We probably still would have
had tire problems that we would have had to deal with, but I think
we could have worked with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another blow to Gordon's hopes of repeating as champion.
Gordon's 250-point deficit in the point standing is by no means
insurmountable, but it will certainly be an uphill battle for him.
Gordon has three victories and three thirds this season, but he
also has four finishes of 31st or worse.
</P>
<P>
   And a struggling Gordon can mean nothing but good things for
Jarrett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
