<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROM-COX     05-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school prom ends abruptly after bomb found on premises
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Prom night ended three hours early for
Palm Beach Lakes High School Saturday when security guards
discovered a powerful bomb just outside the Sheraton Hotel
ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The nail-studded bomb was not set to explode, but someone could
have detonated it within seconds and injured or killed any of 500
students, said Ed Halley, spokesman for the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown number of guests and hotel staff were also in the
building. Anyone on the first floor was in harm's way, Halley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very powerful kind of bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County School District officials on Sunday were
planning heightened security for the one remaining prom of the
year: this Friday's dance for Spanish River High School students in
Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   They also planned a security sweep of Palm Beach Lakes High
School before the start of classes today.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach and the ATF had no suspects Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All that was certain was that this prom night would be
remembered for all the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel security guards discovered the device sometime between
8:30 and 10 p.m. inside an indoor tree planter by the ballroom
entrance. Authorities had varied accounts of the timing. No threat
had been received.
</P>
<P>
   Students were evacuated around 10 p.m. and sent to the parking
lot. They were told only that it was an emergency and that they
would be allowed back in soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the students would not return.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's bomb squad dog sniffed the device before West Palm
Beach police destroyed it with a powerful stream from a water
cannon, Halley said. He described the explosive as similar to other
homemade pipe bombs, simple enough to build with directions on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Halley would not elaborate further on its contents or its size
except to say it was ``considerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in the ATF's Atlanta lab are now examining the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Police and school officials are working with the ATF.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they searched the school campus but turned up nothing,
said Jim Kelly, chief of school police. Kelly said the school would
conduct a security sweep sometime before classes start today and
that staff would be on a heightened state of alert.
</P>
<P>
   Halley could not recall hearing of a similar incident in his 18
years with the ATF.
</P>
<P>
   The prom's theme was ``These are the Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Lynne Humphries, a chaperone who has missed two, at
most three, proms since she began teaching at the school 35 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Humphries remembers what were previously considered notorious
prom incidents. One year, a girl drank a little too much and got
sick, publicly. A boy was caught smoking marijuana in the bathroom.
Such problems now sound quaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this what we have to look forward to now every time we have
large gatherings?'' Humphries wondered. ``Should we give up
graduation?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the prom officially started at 8 p.m., students started
arriving en masse between 9 and 10. Many had yet to enter through
the two archways of dark green and gold balloons. Some hadn't seen
the centerpieces or cast their ballots for king and queen.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Suit, 17, spent 30 minutes inside the prom before school
officials ``shuffled us out into the parking lot.'' Her date had
taken her to dinner. They shared a black limousine with two other
couples.
</P>
<P>
   She did ``the hair, the nails, the toes, all the jewelry,
everything.'' It probably cost $600, including the long champagne
dress with the sparkled top and the gloves. Others spent more, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if school officials decide later this week to hold a
replacement prom, Suit doesn't think she and her friends can afford
to recreate the evening. And there's really no way to recreate the
whole thing anyway, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my senior prom,'' she said. ``It's very sad that we
didn't have any time to spend there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the students were sent to the parking lot, many milled
around for 60 or 90 minutes until they realized they wouldn't be
allowed back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever informed us what was going on,'' said Danielle
Solomon, 19, a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon wore a purple dress with matching shoes and a long scarf
to the go-cart park. Her mother had saved money for the special
occasion, so she wasn't about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Celita Lozado said everything had gone perfectly for her, until
the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us were actually crying because, I mean, this is our
senior prom and we don't have a second chance,'' Lozado said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, the schools police chief, said the county has just one
prom left this year. Spanish River High School's prom will go on as
scheduled Friday, at the Boca Raton Resort and Club, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do a sweep of the place well before the prom and keep it
secured,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton's banquet room was back in use Sunday, as the Hugh
O'Brian Youth Leadership organization held a banquet for 150
Florida sophomores who have shown leadership in their schools and
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's Grand Regency Ballroom, where the prom was held, is
6,615 square feet. The hotel employs about 250 workers.
</P>
<P>
   It underwent a four-month renovation that ended last December.
There have been no construction workers on site recently, said Saun
Lightbourne, the manager on duty.
</P>
<P>
   The ballroom _ the hotel's main banquet room _ opens into a
small lobby with easy access to a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb was found in a large tree planter, in a corner about 12
feet from the far-right entrance to the ballroom, according to one
employee.
</P>
<P>
   The planter sits next to an entrance about 15 feet from a
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Humphries, chairwoman of the social studies department, lamented
how the world of high schools has changed since 12 students and a
teacher were massacred in Colorado last month.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's incident was ``a marker of our time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what this person wanted,'' Humphries said.
``They wanted all those kids' night to be ruined. And guess what?
It was.''
</P>
<P>
   Noah Bierman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Sanjay Bhatt and Jennifer Peltz contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
