<SLUG> BC-CUNY-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 U.S. FAULTS MEDICAL STUDIES IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A government watchdog agency has warned the City
University of New York and the Mount Sinai School of Medicine to
comply with ethical rules for federally financed research on human
subjects, an agency official said Sunday. Violating those rules
could imperil the institutions' permission to engage in such
research.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Michael Carome, the chief compliance officer of
the Office for Protection From Research Risks, which monitors
research centers to make sure they are following the rules, said he
did not have access over the weekend to records that would indicate
the nature of any violations, which were mentioned in this week's
U.S. News and World Report magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that Mount Sinai had been placed on restrictive
status in March, making it subject to tighter federal oversight
until it complies with the rules, while the university's research
has been under a similar restriction for two years. The university
does not have a medical school, but some of its colleges conduct
medically related research.
</P>
<P>
   The university received the warning in February in a letter from
the agency, which is part of the National Institutes of Health. The
letter laid out in detail what the university still needed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Carome said Sunday that there had been ``persistent problems''
at the university, and that the violations over the last few years
were similar to those that led the agency to suspend briefly all
federally financed research on humans last week at Duke University
Medical Center in Durham, N.C. Duke was cited for 20 violations,
some of them involving insufficient record-keeping by its
Institutional Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   Such boards must follow federal rules in determining which
experiments are allowed and the risks to which participants may be
exposed.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY's vice chancellor for university relations, Jay Hershenson,
said on Sunday: ``The university is working with the Office of
Protection From Research Risks to improve precautionary procedures
where warranted. CUNY has requested greater specificity from OPRR
to assure accuracy, and a plan will be filed by June 15 addressing
any revisions of procedures that are necessary to minimize risk.''
</P>
<P>
   A university official said there were no allegations that the
``procedural problems'' had harmed any subjects. The official said
that some of the problems seemed to stem from having separate
institutional review boards at all 20 of its colleges, as well as a
central research foundation, and that the university was working on
a way to bring greater uniformity to its institutional review.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the federal agency visited the Mount Sinai
School of Medicine in March, Carome said, and the warning followed.
Its license to continue research using human subjects in federally
financed experiments was placed under review, Carome said, until it
implements a plan to correct the deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Phillips, an associate dean at the medical school, said in
a statement on Sunday that the federal agency had ``approved Mount
Sinai's full continuation of its clinical research activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But her statement said: ``The review did identify several issues
for which OPRR asked that Mount Sinai take corrective action. None
of the identified issues involved risks to those individuals
participating in research at Mount Sinai.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate investigation into whether psychiatric experiments at
the New York State Psychiatric Institute at Queens College, which
is part of CUNY, and the Mount Sinai School of Medicine violated
the federal ethical guidelines is continuing, Carome said.
</P>
<P>
   In those experiments, which took place over three years and
ended in 1996, 100 boys in New York City were given the now-banned
drug fenfluramine, which researchers believe triggers the
production of chemicals in the brain. The study sought to determine
whether measuring the levels of such chemicals could predict
violent behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
