<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-16 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ WON'T SPUR CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Shaquille O'Neal never lacks for motivational
tools. And wherever motivation lacks, he invents something. His
imagination might be the only thing more active than his low-post
game.
</P>
<P>
   So here are O'Neal's favorite play toys for conjured motivation,
the San Antonio Spurs, and what does he do? He goes conservative.
This must be the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't gonna say anything to get the town pumped up. . . .
I'm gonna watch what I say this time,'' O'Neal said Sunday, on the
eve of the Lakers' conference semifinals opener against the San
Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Neal began the season in a snit over a national
publication's prediction the Spurs would win the Western
Conference. Then he dissed Spurs big men David Robinson and Tim
Duncan. All part of the complex Shaq psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's silent, even complimentary toward the Spurs, apparently
saving his energy for those low-block wrestling matches with
Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Neal found new material for his unique brand of
self-motivation. Now he's grumbling about being picked third team
All-NBA, a notion he dreamed up himself. The votes have not been
released.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Lakers are concerned, he can manufacture whatever
bogeymen he wants as long as he keeps producing as he did in the
Lakers' 3-1 first-round victory over the Houston Rockets. O'Neal's
inspired 37-point, 11-rebound performance in Game 4 clinched the
series, setting up this best-of-seven showdown with the top-seeded
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities in the series are worth noting. Like the
Rockets, the Spurs lost twice to the Lakers early in the season,
then routed them in late April. Like the Rockets, the Spurs can
knock the Lakers off balance with a dominant frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs finished the season with the NBA's best regular-season
record and the best performance over the last two months before
dispatching the Minnesota Timberwolves 3-1 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, and Glen Rice when healthy, have
been more than a match for any team lately. The Lakers have won
seven of their last eight games, by an average of almost 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neal: ``I like our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend once again on J.R. Reid. Installed as the
Lakers' starting power forward just a month ago following the
termination of Dennis Rodman, Reid has become the defensive focal
point of their postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Reid did just enough to slow Houston's Charles Barkley in the
first-round series, earning high praise from teammates for his
aggressive, physical play. Now he'll be counted on to keep Duncan,
the most versatile low-post player in the league, from
single-handedly dismantling the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough, he's one of the best big men out there,'' Reid
said. ``Everybody in this league loves a challenge. I'm a very
competitive guy and I love to get after it. It makes it a physical
game. I'm not a shot-blocker or anything like that, so we have to
keep him off the box and keep him off that sweet spot in the low
post. Its gonna be a lot different (than guarding Barkley). He's
not a physical player, but he mixes it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And certainly, Reid has proven now that he can play the role of
sacrificial lamb on defense. A 15-point-per-game scorer in
Charlotte before his trade to the Lakers in March, Reid is fine
with his new station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of confidence in what he can do,'' coach Kurt
Rambis said. ``I think he gained some confidence in himself in how
valuable he can be to this franchise and to our success. . . . We
asked him to do a particular thing and he put all his energy into
that, and that's why he had a lot of success and we had a lot of
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers face a true test of how far they've come in the
last few weeks, since the routs by Houston and San Antonio and the
amazing turnaround that's followed. But they don't have the luxury
of relying on prior experience to gauge this matchup. Are the Spurs
such an improved team that they can beat the Lakers by 27 points,
as they did April 24? Or were the Lakers just that bad then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, we really can't say,'' Derek Fisher said. ``I
mean, we beat them early, when they weren't playing that well. They
beat us late, when we weren't playing that well. So we really don't
know how good they are, because we haven't played our best (against
them). We'll find out (tonight) how good they really are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
