A9370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      05-16 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PREDICT FIRST-ROUND VICTORY FOR BARAK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With Israelis heading to the polls Monday to vote
for prime minister, two images of the candidates in the campaign's
11th hour seemed to capture their political character and the
direction this race is headed.
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, the Labor party's challenger to incumbent Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, is enjoying a commanding lead in the
polls. At a sun-drenched rally Sunday in an open field north of Tel
Aviv, Barak told voters, ``Our way will bring us to unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, meanwhile, his hold on power threatened, scowled
under the glaring lights of television cameras at a press
conference inside the prime minister's office in Jerusalem and
lashed out at Israel's traditionally left-leaning media for ganging
up against him.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, whose rightist coalition unraveled last winter,
forcing him to call early elections, Sunday turned up the heat on
his opponent, warning voters that Barak ``cut deals'' with the far
left and Israeli Palestinians that threaten the nation's security.
</P>
<P>
   A swirl of activity Sunday, including the withdrawal from the
race of the Center Party candidate, Yitzhak Mordechai, who gave his
support to Barak, left the highly decorated general poised to win a
majority Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a five-way race for prime minister became a
showdown between Barak and Netanyahu. Hours after Mordechai
withdrew, ultranationalist Benny Begin also pulled out, but
declined to endorse Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai and Begin, both former Cabinet ministers under
Netanyahu, defected as his fractious coalition crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the first-ever Israeli Arab candidate for prime
minister, Azmi Bishara, also pulled out. That meant that the Arab
vote, about 15 percent of the electorate, would not be drawn away
from Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The narrowing of the race to two candidates means Israel will
not, as most analysts predicted, face a runoff June 1. And this,
most analysts said, will benefit Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the last-minute political jostling, Israel's most
established and independent pollster, Hanoch Smith, forecast Barak
would win 54 percent of the vote and Netanyahu 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu insisted Sunday the polls would be proven wrong, just
as they were in 1996 when he won an upset over Labor's incumbent
Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to surprise people. We're going to determine the
outcome of this thing and we're going to win,'' Netanyahu said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, sounding as though he was delivering a victory speech,
told supporters, ``We now have a real challenge of unifying the
country, of switching from divisiveness and dissension to unity and
hope for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's 4.3 million voters will cast two ballots Monday, one
for the 120-member Knesset, or parliament, and the other in the
direct election for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the campaign focused on personalities and
soundbites more than substantive issues, an American approach to
politics imported to Israel by both Barak and Netanyahu. Both of
the candidates have enlisted some of America's top political
strategists to shape their message.
</P>
<P>
   For Netanyahu, the message worked on by Ipswich resident and
conservative political consultant Arthur Finkelstein was security,
as Israel heads toward the final phase of the peace agreement with
Palestinians. The prime minister warned that Barak would cede too
much land to the Palestinians, allow them to establish an
independent state, and allow them to divide Jerusalem by declaring
a Palestinian capital in East Jerusalem, which Israel captured in
the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has also talked tough on security and assured voters that
Jerusalem is the eternal and indivisible capital of the Jewish
state. But his message, honed by Washington's liberal strategist
James Carville, is how Netanyahu has left Israel ``stuck'' in a
deadlocked peace process and faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because Netanyahu succeeded in creating more security
through his hard-line policies and partly because Barak convinced
voters that he, too, will be tough on security, Israeli voters have
not focused attention on relations with their Palestinian
neighbors. Instead, they have looked within Israeli society to its
deepening ethnic tensions and its religious-secular divide.
</P>
<P>
   On these issues within Israel, the differences between the
candidates, both their personalities and their political heritage,
became stark.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it appears that Barak, who at the beginning of the
race was seen as a brilliant military thinker but a bungling
politician, has out-maneuvered Netanyahu whose MIT education and
polished marketing skills gave him the image of a political wizard.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are a study in contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, is a mixture of hawk and dove, the most highly
decorated general in Israel's history who also relaxes by playing
Beethoven piano sonatas.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, 49, is a tough-talking hard-liner who showed his
world-class ability to communicate as a frequent guest on
``Nightline'' when he was UN ambassador from 1984 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Barak enjoys tinkering with the mechanisms of pocket watches and
clocks. Netanyahu unwinds with a Davidoff cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was raised on a kibbutz. He was a rising star in Israel's
liberal, secular elite who was groomed for leadership. He became a
national hero in 1972 by leading the storming of a hijacked Sabena
Airlines passenger jet by elite Israeli commandos disguised as El
Al mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu came of age in a conservative home steeped in his
father's scholarly research. The father's right-wing politics
alienated him from a liberal academic establishment, friends said,
and fostered family resentment against the elite. Netanyahu had a
respectable, though not distinguished military career. He lived in
the shadow of his gifted and gregarious brother, Jonathan, who died
a national hero while leading the raid at Entebbe, Uganda, to free
103 Israelis from a terrorist hijacking in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was a protege and admirer of Yitzhak Rabin, the prime
minister whose assassination in 1995 and bold moves toward peace
transformed him into a national martyr. Barak has vowed to continue
Rabin's legacy for peace.
</P>
<P>
   One of Israel's leading political commentators, Zeev Chafetz,
who writes a weekly column for the Jerusalem Report, said that
Sunday the two men were both in their element on the final day of
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak was out there in a field playing off the image of a
Zionist kibbutz and acting like a commander marshaling his military
general buddies,'' said Chafetz.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was Bibi hunkered down with TV lights bouncing off
his forehead,'' he added, ``looking like a cornered animal and
surrounded by the tattered remains of his party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
