<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUTO-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE SET TO RELAX RESTRICTIONS ON RENTAL CAR COMPANIES  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After two years of intensive lobbying by rental
car companies, the Legislature appears poised to repeal, or at
least soften, the state's stringent law on insuring rental cars,
several lobbyists and key legislators say.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have chafed for a decade under the law, which caps
a driver's liability for damage to a rental car and outlaws the
sale of collision-damage waivers, added insurance that consumer
advocates have long condemned as a waste of renters' money.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates say that the law, the nation's toughest, has
curbed the abusive practices of rental companies. But the industry
has protested that it costs too much, raising rental prices and
sending small companies out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has by far the most restrictive laws in the
country,'' said Ray Wagner, legislative vice president for
Enterprise Rent-a-Car, based in St. Louis. ``They are oppressive to
the industry and to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   While the industry has occasionally found a sympathetic ear in
the Capitol, particularly in the Republican-controlled Senate, its
requests for action have never gone far in the Legislature. But
this could be the year.
</P>
<P>
   A bill now moving through both houses would eliminate the cap on
a driver's liability for car damage _ currently $100 _ and allow
the sale of collision damage waivers again. The bill is expected to
reach the Senate floor for a vote this week, and lobbyists and
lawmakers say it is likely to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The potential turnabout is a tale of fierce debate over the
merits of the law, but it is also a lesson in the workings of
Albany. Each year, hundreds of interest groups seeking changes in
state law are unable to rise above the din and inertia of the
Capitol. The advantage belongs to those who put large sums of money
to the task.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, there were widespread complaints about rental car
companies, and a particular irritant was the collision damage
waiver. Critics said the waiver was too expensive, a huge profit
maker for the industry, and that drivers were often pressured to
buy it even if they did not need it, because they had their own
insurance, or their credit cards covered the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Growing interest in the bill follows an aggressive effort by
several of the Capitol's most powerful lobbyists, on behalf of
Enterprise, Avis, Hertz Corp. and Republic Industries, which
recently changed its name to Autonation, owner of Alamo Rent-a-Car
and National Car Rental.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, rental companies would be allowed to charge up
to $9 a day for the collision-damage waiver for most cars, and up
to $12 for luxury cars, but they could not require that anyone buy
it. Industry officials say that nationally, about one renter in
eight buys the policy.
</P>
<P>
   At $9 a day, the waiver would be equivalent to paying more than
$3,000 a year. On average, New Yorkers pay less than $1,000 a year
for auto insurance _ about $2 to $3 a day _ and that covers all
manner of things, like medical bills, while the waiver covers only
damage to the car.
</P>
<P>
   New York's current rules force rental companies to buy more
insurance for their cars or to absorb the cost of damages. Critics
say that significantly raises rental rates, which are higher in New
York than around the country. And they say that repealing the law
would lead to lower prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
