<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DON'T HELP THEIR CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now the decision lies in the hands of the
selection committee. That's not what the UCLA baseball team wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins needed a victory over fifth-ranked Stanford Sunday
afternoon to solidify their chances for an at-large berth in the
NCAA playoffs. Instead, the Cardinal, with a Pac-10 championship
already secured the day before, pummeled the Bruins 14-4 at Jackie
Robinson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (30-29) finished 13-11 and in a tie for third place in the
Pac-10 with Arizona. Four teams are expected to be taken from the
conference for the 64-team tournament field, which means the Bruins
could get invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're good enough to be tied for third place . . . you
think there would be room enough to take a few more Pac-10 teams,''
said UCLA head coach Gary Adams. ``We deserve to go. We've earned
the right to go. I don't care if we're greasing our way in. I'll
bet there's a lot of teams that don't want to play us.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing two weekend games to Stanford (40-13, 19-5) _ and getting
blown out in game it had to win _ didn't help UCLA's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tough loss Friday,'' said sophomore outfielder Bill
Scott, referring to a game the Bruins were leading 7-0 through
seven innings and lost 8-7. ``I don't think we got over that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal hit four home runs Sunday, including a ninth-inning
grand slam by designated hitter Craig Thompson, but their battery
was the story. Catcher John Salter _ a backup who entered the game
with a .182 batting average, no homers and 1 RBI _ went 4 for 5
with two homers and four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Salter, a senior who was starting his third game of the season,
hit a three-run homer in the fifth to give the Cardinal a 5-0 lead.
That was enough for freshman right-hander Brian Sager, who showed
why he was among the nation's top recruits last year.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA only hit the ball hard against Sager (5-0) in two innings _
the fifth and sixth. Scott's record-breaking two-run homer in the
sixth cut Stanford's lead to 5-4. It was the sixth consecutive game
in which Scott hit a homer, and it was also the 25th homer for the
former Alemany High standout.
</P>
<P>
   Sager wobbled after Scott's homer, giving up a single to Garrett
Atkins, but UCLA's Eric Reece grounded into an inning-ending double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Sager allowed seven hits, struck out six and came two outs away
from his second complete game of the season. He also walked one;
four UCLA pitchers combined to walk 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a great pitching performance and that helped us,'' said
Stanford coach Mark Marquess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
