<HEADLINE>
MEMPHIS BACKS DOWN ON EFFORT TO RENAME CONFEDERATE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEITH CHROSTOWSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a bluff overlooking the Mississippi River, a statue of
Jefferson Davis stands tall in the middle of Confederate Park in
Memphis, Tenn. Appropriately, his back is turned to the river, and
he peers east into downtown.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was here that Memphians gathered on June 6, 1862, to watch
the Battle of Memphis in the river below. The Yankee ironclads
quickly whipped the Southern gunboats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But May 11, the Confederacy -- or its descendants -- won one.
The Memphis Park Commission retreated from a plan to oust the Rebel
president and rename the 90-year-old park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The name would have been familiar to those in Kansas City, Mo.:
the Richard and Annette Bloch Cancer Survivors Park, similar to the
one west of the Country Club Plaza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback, the R.A. Bloch Cancer Foundation is still
willing to give Memphis up to $1 million for a park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have no quarrel with a cancer survivors park -- so
long as it's not in Confederate Park. To them, the park board's
plan was an attempt to sweep away a symbol of a lost cause. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say `Confederate,' people have been brainwashed to
think slavery and racism,'' said Ronnie Mangrum, heritage director
of the Tennessee Division, Sons of Confederate Veterans. ``They
picked this park because they thought, `Who'll support a
Confederate symbol?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Malmo, the park board chairman who said it was his idea,
rejected suggestions of ``political correctness.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he's backing down. ``Even my wife and son think it was a
nutty idea,'' he said. ``I didn't want that fringe ... of the
public here to hold a grudge against the survivors park.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memphis is now an African-American majority city with its first
black mayor. The park board says it offered up Confederate Park
because the Bloch money would help maintain the 2.5 acres of green
space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Fred Davis, a former city councilman and one of two
African-Americans on the five-member park board, played down any
racial element of the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't have much heritage in Jefferson Davis,''
he said, ``but I don't want it responded to on that level.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the park board selected Confederate Park, the editorial
cartoonist for the Memphis Commercial Appeal drew a cartoon that
asked: ``Which symbol speaks better for Memphis?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over a rebel soldier carrying a Confederate flag, a caption read
``Fought to preserve slavery and lost,'' while the caption over a
cancer survivor in a wheelchair read ``Fought to preserve life and
won.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that sad?'' Richard Bloch said of the dispute. H&AMP;R Block
Inc.'s co-founder, who has twice survived bouts with cancer, said
his foundation had nothing to do with selecting Confederate Park,
and he regretted the hard feelings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before last week's turnaround, Bloch sounded like a man ready to
compromise. Even the Davis statue could have stayed where it was. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't have to do a thing. We can build around
anything.''  &QL; 
Another Kansas City link &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 1907, Kansas City, Mo., landscape architect George
Kessler, who earlier had designed Kansas City's park and boulevard
system, laid out the Memphis parks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Confederate Park, with its trees, walkways, flowers and benches,
is considered the best remaining example of Kessler's work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson Davis didn't arrive until 1964, after a public fund
drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its two-year search for a place to direct the Bloch effort,
the commission rejected two other sites. Malmo said Confederate
Park was ideal because of its downtown location accessible to
pedestrians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the statue could have been moved to the smaller
Jefferson Davis Park about 300 yards away. That would have left the
city with two parks dedicated to Civil War figures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other is the much larger Forrest Park, the site of the tomb
of Gen. Nathan Bedford Forrest, the first grand wizard of the Ku
Klux Klan. &QL; 
Voice of opposition &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John T. Wilkinson III, second in command of the Tennessee
Division, Sons of the Confederate Veterans, can see Confederate
Park from his downtown law office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's the great-great-grandson of a Confederate soldier, and he
disputed the park board on nearly every point: One of the other
sites more centrally located would have been perfect; Confederate
Park is in good shape except for some repair needed on a stone
rampart; and he didn't want to move the statue into Jefferson Davis
Park, a sliver of land he calls a park in name only. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rallies were planned. The park board and the Bloch Foundation
received complaints from people across the South. Wilkinson was
ready to mount a legal effort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He hesitates to speak directly to the motives of those who
wanted to rename the park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``monuments as our ancestors saw fit to erect
should be preserved ... . People ought to respect each others'
heritage and let them be proud of what they want to be proud of and
work toward a little mutual education.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slavery, he said, ``might have been the occasion for the war,
but certainly not the cause of war. The problem primarily was a
sectional conflict with economic overtones.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colin Pulley, national heritage director of the Sons of
Confederate Veterans, said ignorance of history is behind
``heritage violations'' across the South, whether efforts to keep
rebel flags out of cemeteries or to ban the wearing of Confederate
symbols in schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As heirs of Confederate soldiers, we are the legitimate heirs
of Confederate symbols'' and have the right to control their use,
he said. He opposes hate groups that ``misuse the Confederate flag
in a racist manner. That is offensive to us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie R. Turner, executive director of the Memphis branch of
the NAACP, wasn't surprised that the park board backed down. ``I
knew they would have a fight on their hands, that those Civil War
buffs would come out of the woodwork.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her group took no stand on the matter, although Turner thinks a
remake of the park would have meant ``one more reminder of slavery
gone.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To her, Confederate symbols are detestable. ``You would have a
hard time convincing my Jewish friends that anything having to do
with Hitler has any historical value.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blacks in Memphis, she said, also have to put up with Forrest
Park, where the Klan founder is buried. ``We despise and detest
that park.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
