<HEADLINE>
THE HANDS THAT GUIDE RUSSIA ARE SHAKING, UNCONTROLLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be that a reliable psychiatric diagnosis cannot be
rendered on the basis of pictures in the newspaper. But all the
same, the photos that accompanied the report of yet another
shake-up in the Russian Cabinet were more than a little
disturbing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Probably it does not matter so much whether Yevgeny Primakov or
Sergei Stepashin occupies the post of prime minister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It would matter a great deal, however, if one of the largest and
most dangerously disordered nations on the face of the planet
happened to be led by a man whose years of dissipation and
consequent wretched health have left him too unstable to govern
even himself and his erratic impulses, much less the affairs of his
country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two pictures of Boris Yeltsin that ran with stories about
his dismissal Wednesday of his premier presented the swollen,
flushed and contorted visage of a sick man _ a man out of control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were, one might almost think, portraits of a madman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before these words see print, events in Moscow may have taken
yet another lurch, with a vote in the Parliament on a motion for
Yeltsin's impeachment. He has weathered legislative storms before,
and his gift for surviving _ if not for leading _ is as prodigious
as his thirst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But however this crisis plays, it is clear that time has run out
on the West's implicit policy of ``better Boris, with all his
faults, than the dangerous unknown.'' What Yeltsin provides isn't
stability but paralysis, and the two are not to be confused. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the spectacle of his disintegration resembles
nothing quite so much as the last years of the old Communist bosses
before Mikhail Gorbachev. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling and witless, they were propped up like puppets on
ceremonial occasions to watch the tanks and missiles grind across
Red Square -- the theory being that a dead man at the helm was
better than the risk of change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, in the end, the theory was absolutely right. Gorbachev
brought change that cost the Communists their monopoly of power and
Russia its empire, but opened the way to the possibility, at least,
of a better and decent future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty? Of course that will come with the transition. It's
said that the Chinese character for ``crisis'' can serve to mean
either ``danger'' or ``opportunity.'' In any case, what could be
more dangerous than the confusion and drift that characterize the
present state of affairs in the Kremlin? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is much greatness in Russian culture and in the suffering
Russian people. The land is a storehouse of natural riches. Though
disfigured by history, it is a country waiting to be led to
greatness. But there's no use pretending Boris Yeltsin is the man
for the work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he had an important role to play in Russia's time of
transition, just as Lech Walesa played a role in the winning of
Poland's freedom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget those dramatic days and nights in August 1991,
when, barricaded inside the Russian Parliament building, he defied
the guns and armor of the hard-line junta drawn up on every side? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Walesa's, though, his moment passed. He's finished --
politically, physically, emotionally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The need now isn't for an icon but for competence, a quality
that Yeltsin seems notoriously unsuited to provide. It's time to
identify and prepare to work with the ones who must shortly
follow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
