<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY REFORMS WOULD PERPETUATE THE SYSTEM'S PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prospects for Social Security reform between now and next year's
election appear nil, which is probably just as well given the fact
that Washington doesn't understand what needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   For the next decade or so, Social Security will be substantially
overfunded. Given that most of the reforms are designed to ``save''
the surplus Social Security revenue, real reform won't be possible
until the law is changed to allow Washington to ``save'' in the
sense most people understand the concept.
</P>
<P>
   What needs fixing are the legal barriers to true reform. As
things stand, Washington can either spend its revenue or pay down
federal debt. Period. Savings can be achieved only as a pretense,
with bookkeeping entries representing offsetting assets and
liabilities. Then everyone makes believe the result has actual
financial value.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer is a leading would-be reformer, but he seems to
suffer the same blind spot as most other agents of change. He
doesn't trust taxpayers with their own money. The House Ways and
Means Committee chairman's plan would create private retirement
accounts, which sounds like a step in the right direction. Archer's
approach, however, gives government control over all the money,
which is the root of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel J. Mitchell, a Heritage Foundation expert on Social
Security reform, denounces the plan as the worst of all worlds,
because it addresses the wrong problems. The problems of
excessively high payroll taxes and shamefully low rates of return
on Social Security contributions are ignored, Mitchell says.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Archer plan, Social Security tax levels would remain
unchanged, while government would fund each personal retirement
account with contributions amounting to 2 percent of the taxpayer's
wages up to a maximum of $1,500. When the taxpayer retires, the
government would use the money to pay the retiree's Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words,'' Mitchell recently explained in an analysis
in The Wall Street Journal, ``the legislation makes all of us pay
twice. We (continue to pay) a payroll tax to Social Security. But
now the government will take a big chunk of our income taxes,
redistribute those funds to savings accounts for the overall
population, and then use the interest and principal from these
accounts to fund our Social Security benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, Mitchell contends, ``borrows the worst features of
the Clinton plan and then adds some warts for good measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell doesn't get into it, but the Archer approach also runs
into the same legal wall that is a barrier to nearly every proposal
for real reform. It apparently works off the assumption that
government's money can be ``saved,'' when it can't under current
law. For reform to make a difference, personal retirement accounts
must be funded with real-world assets having marketplace value
rather than fictional government accounting contrivances. As the
system is currently constituted, this can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, no matter what form change takes, the only Social
Security reform worthy of the name will provide for real people
channeling real money into real investments. In other words, more
control of the process must be given to the taxpayers in whose name
the funds are being set aside for retirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
