<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBLICANS-GUNS-KAN &LR;      05-16 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-GUNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LITTLETON, REPUBLICANS REPOSITION THEMSELVES IN GUN DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last month, Sen. John Ashcroft could be heard
throughout Missouri trumpeting the benefits of a ballot question to
remove the ban on carrying concealed weapons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the Missouri Republican was in the thick of the
Senate gun control debate, winning passage of an amendment to
restrict the possession of assault weapons by juveniles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the staunchest supporters and biggest financial
beneficiaries of the gun rights lobby _ and Ashcroft is one _ are
scrambling for political cover after the massacre last month that
left 15 dead at a Colorado high school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton has crystallized this debate, making it
significantly more salient in the minds of voters and moving this
up to one of the top concerns people have,'' said Neil Newhouse, a
Republican pollster. ``Republicans have got to be more responsive
to American public opinion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And they tried to be last week by agreeing to limited weapons
restrictions for juveniles. But by week's end, the political chaos
on Capitol Hill offered proof that the fallout from the Littleton
shootings would linger and become one of the currents in the 2000
election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has set herself apart from other Republican
presidential candidates by backing child safety locks and the
assault weapons ban, and opposing the right to carry concealed
weapons. The leading contender, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, favors
background checks for those who purchase guns at gun shows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Post-Littleton politics is a vastly changed landscape when it
comes to guns, an issue that the Republican Party has long relied
upon to galvanize opposition to Democrats and produce a healthy
stream of campaign money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, gun rights groups gave Republican candidates almost
$1.6 million, with the bulk coming from the National Rifle
Association. Democrats received $310,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polls after the Colorado school massacre show the public
supports stiffer gun control laws. And suburban voters,
particularly women, could become a potent force for the candidate
who taps into their concerns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader,
described a recent moment in his St. Louis district that he said
captured the mood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to a meeting,'' Gephardt said.``Two women outside
the meeting cornered me, and they kept saying, `What are you going
to do to protect our children? We want to take our kids out of the
school because we're afraid for their safety. What are we -- what
are you -- going to do to help solve this problem?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is a strong supporter of gun rights who faces a
re-election battle -- and suddenly is exposed to a different
political climate. Gun rights groups contributed $15,850 to him
between 1993 and 1998, according to the Center for Responsive
Politics. Only seven other senators received more during that
period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat seeking to unseat
Ashcroft next year, has been trying to paint him as politically
extreme. And the gun control debate might have given him a broader
brush. Carnahan was quick to attack Ashcroft on Wednesday after
Ashcroft opposed a Democratic amendment requiring mandatory
background checks at gun shows that was part of a youth violence
bill. Ashcroft voted for a Republican version that called for
voluntary background checks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Ashcroft has proven once again that he cannot be trusted
to make sound decisions about gun safety issues,'' Carnahan said.
``He continues to carry the (NRA's) water.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft spokesman Steve Hilton said he saw no connection or
conflict between the senator's strong support of Proposition B, the
NRA-backed measure to lift Missouri's ban on concealed weapons that
failed last month, and his efforts to curb juvenile violence.
Hilton mentioned Ashcroft's push, which dates back to last summer,
for tougher penalties for disturbed students who bring weapons to
school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in post-Littleton politics, Republicans are playing defense
and Democrats have the momentum. The response to the first Senate
vote Wednesday was quick and stinging. Voting largely along party
lines, senators defeated an amendment that would have required
background checks for anyone who purchased guns at a gun show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stunned that less than one month after the worst school
shooting in our nation's history, the Senate has decided to make it
easier for felons, fugitives and other prohibited purchasers to buy
guns,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news conference
Thursday morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By that afternoon, Republicans had regrouped. Republican Sen.
Larry Craig of Idaho, an NRA board member, offered a plan that the
NRA helped craft that would require background checks for all
purchases at gun shows. Their version required the checks to be
done within 24 hours, not 72 as the Democrats had envisioned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It passed 48-47, with Ashcroft in favor, and with 40 Democrats
and seven Republicans opposed. Opponents claimed that it was a sham
proposal, merely a political veil to protect them from criticism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, Ashcroft trumped Democratic Sen. Dianne
Feinstein of California, who had been pushing a juvenile
semi-automatic assault weapons ban for some time. Ashcroft offered
an amendment to require parental consent for youths to obtain such
weapons. But it also contained more exceptions than Feinstein's,
including loopholes if the weapon is used for work, the military,
ranching, farming, hunting, target practice or self-defense. Her
exception largely dealt with military uses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ashcroft measure passed 96-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Yang, a Democratic pollster working for Carnahan,
called Ashcroft's positioning in the gun debate ``transparent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, he was the poster boy for Proposition B,'' Yang
said. ``Now he's reversed course and tried to say he really
believes in gun control. It's saying they're worried about this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
