A9403 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-COLLEGE-KAN &LR;      05-16 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-COLLEGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE GENDER GAP MEANS MORE WOMEN THAN MEN ARE GRADUATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Peggy Nothnagel was fed up with trying to
raise two kids on the pay she earned from minimum-wage jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She decided to go back to school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's a student at Penn Valley Community College in Kansas
City, Kan., and plans to become an administrative assistant, a
position she hopes will bring better job security, pay and
benefits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothnagel, 27, is part of a wave of women swamping college
campuses today. Women graduates will outnumber men at many
commencements this spring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, men's share of bachelor's degrees declined from 81
percent in 1900 to less than 45 percent today. Missouri and Kansas
mirror that decline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trend is cause for both celebration and concern, educators
say. While increased education may help women take a step forward
in salaries and prestige, it could create new tensions among men
and women as they adjust to changing roles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``(The trend) is absolutely staggering. It's a change that's so
profound and pervasive,'' said Thomas Mortenson, a higher education
researcher from Iowa who has analyzed the graduation gender gap.
``But because it's happening so slowly we don't perceive it or talk
about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody agrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joni Finney, vice president of the National Center for Public
Policy and Higher Education in California, believes the trend
unfairly has eclipsed concerns such as improving higher education
access for poor people and racial minorities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a bit more of it than is really there,'' she
said. `` ... Men were ahead for so long and people didn't have the
same reaction.'' &QL; 
By the numbers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women in 1900, then not quite half of the U.S. population,
earned less than 20 percent of the bachelor's degrees. By 1997,
women -- now 51 percent of the population -- earned more than 55
percent of the degrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-seven percent of all 1997 college graduates in Missouri
and Kansas were women. Women earned 55 percent of the bachelor's
degrees and 62 percent of the graduate degrees in Kansas. Women
earned 57 percent of both bachelor's and master's degrees in
Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trend has set off debate about the the college gender gap's
effect and what it says about our society and economy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bernard, president of the American Association of
University Women, said highlighting the college gender gap deflects
attention from women's continued inequality in the work force,
including college teaching. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bernard and other educators also argue that although women earn
the majority of college degrees, they are still overrepresented in
traditionally female disciplines such as education and nursing.
Women still lag in earning degrees that lead to higher-paying jobs
in engineering and computer technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony Carnevale, vice president for public leadership with
the Educational Testing Service, said 85 percent of women with
bachelor's degrees in 1959 worked in education and health care.
Today, fewer than 40 percent do. &QL; 
Financial reality &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amber Eppinger graduated Saturday with a master's in business
administration from Park College in Parkville, Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Kan., resident sought self-fulfillment and
financial security with her degree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've always wanted,'' said Eppinger, 26, who
works in the insurance industry. ``I also want to be able to be
self-sustaining. I want to know I can get a job and take care of
myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finney said the need for financial security usually drives
women's educational success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold, hard reality is that (higher education) pays,'' she
said. ``For women, the payoff is pretty significant.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some high-paying jobs that typically attract men -- such as
construction and manufacturing -- don't require college education.
Women who don't go to college face bleak financial prospects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women need far more education than men to achieve the same
income, Carnevale said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, he said, women with bachelor's degrees earned
$33,000 on average in 1997, compared with $53,000 for men with
bachelor's degrees. Women with graduate degrees earned $43,000. Men
with graduate degrees earned $70,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other, harder-to-measure social reasons besides economic
motivation may underlie women's success in higher education,
observers say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some educators say women are more focused in school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doug Toma, an assistant professor of education at the University
of Missouri-Kansas City, works with graduate students. His female
students tend to do better, paying attention to details and
striving to do everything the best they can. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that power through tend more often to be women,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In high school, girls generally get better grades while boys
tend to get higher scores on standardized tests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toma said habits learned early on have prepared women to
persevere in college. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a law student back in the late '80s, I spent most
of my time drinking coffee and drinking beer and reading novels and
eating donuts,'' he said. ``The women in our class were just more
serious. Maybe they felt they had something to prove.'' &QL; 
Implications &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With more women taking their new skills into the career world,
salaries and promotions could equalize. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men's lagging success in higher education also could mean
problems for men financially and socially. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. economy moves from manufacturing to service, men
without post-high school training could be squeezed out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are angry and women are stressed,'' Carnevale said.
``Women are working and raising families and not making enough
money. Men are angry because they're losing their place ... . A lot
of men feel disenfranchised.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap also could affect personal relationships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The most immediate consequence is a huge number of
college-educated women who are not going to find a college-educated
man to marry,'' Mortenson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recent college graduate Trina Philpot understands the
predicament. She and her sorority sisters at William Woods
University have lamented the dearth of men to date who share their
intellectual interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very frustrating,'' said Philpot, 21, who went to Park
Hill High School in Kansas City, Mo., and plans to apply to law
school. ``Many guys are complacent with just working. Complacency
is just not where I'm at.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
