<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CAN SUMMERS EXTEND RUBIN'S WIN STREAK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never succeed a legend.
</P>
<P>
   That is good advice for college sports coaches asked to replace
a man who set the standard for excellence. If the new coach manages
to carry on the tradition, he gets little credit. If not, he is
hounded out of town by disappointed fans.
</P>
<P>
   All of which brings us to Larry Summers, who gets to follow
Robert Rubin as Treasury secretary. Rubin is viewed by almost
everyone as having done a brilliant job while presiding over the
most amazing economic growth this country has seen in many decades.
</P>
<P>
   It often seemed as if Rubin and Summers, as his peripatetic
deputy, were running the State Department, not the Treasury
Department. When Mexico collapsed, they were the people who decided
what to do. Ditto for Asia. It was Rubin who played the leading
role in deciding to arrange an International Monetary Fund package
to help Russia last year, and who then decided, when things got
much worse, not to pony up more billions.
</P>
<P>
   In all the commentary that accompanied Summers' nomination last
week, it was remarkable how much of it dealt with overseas events.
Would he be diplomatic enough to not offend Japanese sensibilities
while pushing Japan to adopt growth-oriented policies? Could he do
anything to repair our relations with China? It was as though the
American economy were the least of the concerns for a Treasury
secretary, circa 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Summers knows better. He knows that he is walking into a
situation ripe with complacency from Washington to Wall Street to
Main Street. Politicians assume that the unusually favorable
economic conditions that have produced budget surpluses, full
employment and low inflation will last forever. The stock market is
valued as if recessions and inflation had been abolished, while
computer-related productivity gains were certain to boost growth
for years to come. Consumers have _ at least until the past couple
of months _ been spending with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complacency,'' said Summers in a recent speech, ``will be
self-denying prophecy if it leads to unrealistic expenditure plans,
excessive capacity creation, inappropriate asset valuations, or
misguided credit expansion.'' In fact, it is probably doing all of
those things.
</P>
<P>
   One part of that complacency has been Wall Street's confidence
that the Federal Reserve Board will not dare to try to slow things
down by raising interest rates. That assurance was shaken a bit by
Friday's report that consumer prices rose faster than expected last
month.
</P>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that inflation is ticking up. The
pressures that forced down prices last year _ rising unemployment
and collapsing currencies in Asia _ are reversing. That does not
mean prices will zoom, but it might alarm investors who have
assumed inflation is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Summers has also called attention to the country's trade
deficit, which is rising to record levels. Without last year's
chaos in world markets _ and the current crises in Europe _ the
rising deficit would have caused the value of the dollar to fall,
as foreigners who were being paid in dollars for their goods tried
to sell the bucks.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been no currency that people were eager to buy.
The yen is hurt by the sluggish Japanese economy, while the euro
suffers from government policies that limit growth and from worries
over Yugoslavia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing on the immediate horizon to spoil this party.
But the kind of excessive trade deficit now being run cannot
continue indefinitely. If, or when, other currencies start to look
more attractive, we could run into an old-fashioned
foreign-exchange crisis, with inflation up and the Fed tightening
credit to protect the currency. With interest rates rising and the
economy slowing, stock-market valuations might come down rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens in the next 20 months, it will not be Summers'
fault. But he will be blamed as people recall how good things were
before he got the job. If our good fortune continues, however, he
probably will not be given much of the credit. That is what happens
to people who succeed a legend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
