<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WOLDEYES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASRAT WOLDEYES OF ETHIOPIA, DOCTOR AND DISSENTER, DIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (rk) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asrat Woldeyes, a British-trained Ethiopian doctor who was a
leader of opposition to his country's present government, died on
Friday in the hospital of the University of Pennsylvania in
Philadelphia. He was in his early 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The causes were complications from a heart ailment and general
physical deterioration, said a nephew, Youm Abey Fesseba, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The nephew said Asrat, who taught medical students in Addis
Ababa, the Ethiopian capital, arrived in Philadelphia last month
and was hospitalized for three weeks before his death. He also had
high blood pressure and diabetes that gravely affected his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Asrat had led the All-Amhara People's Party, which has
criticized the government.
</P>
<P>
   He was fervent in his own criticism of Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi's government, and in particular of the formation of new
autonomous regions reflecting ethnic and linguistic considerations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 he became a political prisoner in Ethiopia, and he
served out a five-year prison sentence on charges of having incited
an armed rebellion against the government through his party and of
complicity in organizing an anti-government uprising in part of
northwestern Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   The British medical journal The Lancet reported in March that he
had been hospitalized for months in Ethiopia, had spent nine days
in the intensive care unit at Black Lion Hospital in Addis Ababa
after suffering cardiac failure and had been the subject of appeals
by Amnesty International and other medical and human rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He was waiting to face another trial on similar charges when he
was temporarily freed from detention last December so that he could
travel to the United States for medical care. Then the prosecutor
withdrew the charges and said he was physically unfit to be tried
again.
</P>
<P>
   When Asrat was released, the British foreign minister, Tony
Lloyd, said, ``I believe this signals a clear commitment by the
Ethiopian government to uphold their human rights obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Asrat practiced medicine in Ethiopia for more than a
quarter-century and was personal physician to Emperor Haile
Selassie, who reigned from 1930 to 1974 and died in 1975. When the
present government took power in 1991, Asrat founded the All-Amhara
People's Party. Soon afterward he was dismissed from his post at
Black Lion Hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990516.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERCATA-ONLINE-SPI &LR;      05-16 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCATA-ONLINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CO-OP SHOPPING ONLINE IS AIM OF NEW MERCATA VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In September, Tom Van Horn sat in a room with
Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen discussing the hottest trend in
business: electronic commerce. Thinking in grandiose terms _ in a
way only a multibillionaire can _ Allen asked Van Horn if he would
like to build an e-commerce company that sells everything.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who had previously run two of Allen's software
companies, knew it was a huge opportunity. But he still had one
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said would it be OK if we started with less than everything
and built our way up,'' Van Horn recalls. Allen agreed, and
Bellevue-based Mercata was born.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata (www.mercata.com), which takes its name from the Latin
word for market, officially launches its electronic commerce store
today. Mercata differs from other e-commerce sites, allowing groups
of users to form what are essentially virtual co-ops where shoppers
can get volume discounts on merchandise ranging from garden tools
to camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata is by no means the largest e-commerce site on the
Internet, nor the first to sell a wide range of products. Still,
some industry analysts say that Mercata could transform the way
goods are sold on the Internet through a flexible pricing system
called PowerBuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is major,'' said Jack Staff, chief economist and director
of e-commerce at Zona Research in Redwood City, Calif. ``They are
going to be a potent player.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Cassar, a technology analyst at Jupiter Communications,
agreed. He said Mercata's method of selling products is intriguing
and one that could have wide appeal for shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what they are doing is what I call syndicated
buying,'' said Cassar. ``They get people together who want to buy
the same product, and then they try to negotiate the best price for
that group with wholesalers.''
</P>
<P>
   As more people sign up to buy an item _ say, a set of golf clubs
_ the price drops.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike EBay's auction site, where only one person ends up with a
winning bid, Mercata's model allows multiple buyers to be winners,
Van Horn said. Unlike Amazon.com, which warehouses and ships the
books and music its customers order, Mercata is strictly a broker.
</P>
<P>
   Working solely as a middleman, Mercata could be the biggest
winner of all. Van Horn would not comment on revenue projections
but did say he is confident the company can reach profitability
sooner than other e-commerce start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Although some say Mercata provides an interesting spin on
electronic commerce, it is not an entirely new concept.
</P>
<P>
   For years, corporations have used their buying power to
negotiate discount prices with manufacturers. Mercata is using the
Internet to organize Web shoppers into a massive consumer
co-operative that works much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bring people together through the Internet both to
have buying power and to share their common interests in a way that
you never could (before),'' said Van Horn, who came up with the
idea he calls ``We-Commerce'' after evaluating dozens of other
electronic commerce businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the new venture has generated a lot of interest
among analysts, Mercata now has the tough task of wooing customers.
After all, the company's success depends on the number of users who
place orders to buy on the products.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mercata only brings together 10 people to buy the same
product, then they are not going to be able to successfully
negotiate with manufacturers,'' Jupiter Communications' Cassar
said. ``So at the end of the day, their success will be determined
by their marketing budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports are circulating that Mercata may spend more than
$10million on an advertising campaign beginning this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, a Connecticut company which launched its
innovative airplane ticket buying service in April 1998, last year
spent
</P>
<P>
   $24 million on a sales and marketing push that included
advertisements narrated by actor William Shatner. Van Horn has not
yet beamed up the services of Captain Kirk, but the chief
executive's goals are just as ambitious as Priceline or EBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people in a diner in Kansas City to be talking about
this while they are sipping a cup of coffee,'' he said. Already,
the company has doubled employment in the past two months to more
than 50 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn would not comment on the $10 million marketing figure
or the amount of financing the company has raised through Vulcan
Ventures, Paul Allen's venture capital business.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Horn did say the company has developed some unique
marketing tricks to lure users. One feature on the Web site is
called ``Share The Power,'' a button that allows users to e-mail
friends and family about product offerings. If one or two of those
people place a buy order on a product, the price will drop for all
involved, Van Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it as the power of six degrees of separation,''
Van Horn said. ``This uses word of mouth marketing in a way that is
very different than most e-commerce sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition is looming just around the corner. A San Francisco
start-up called Accompany.com recently launched a similar service
for computer hardware, and several Silicon Valley companies are
rumored to be eyeing the market.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany.com _ which recently closed on $4 million in financing
and boasts Forbes publisher Rich Karlgaard as a board member _ does
not view Mercata as a major threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bit of a different model than Mercata; they are
trying to build a destination site,'' said Accompany.com co-founder
and chief executive Jim Rose.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Van Horn, who has an MBA from the Wharton School at the
University of Pennsylvania, is not too worried about the
competition. Instead, the veteran businessman is concentrating more
on expanding the company's customer base and product mix.
</P>
<P>
   Just how many products does Van Horn hope to add in the coming
months? Put it this way: Mercata has already registered the Web
address for www.everything.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
