<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-PGA-TEX </SLUG>
 
Putt master Roberts takes sandy playoff win 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
IRVING, Texas _ Steve Pate never ventured into a bunker during the
GTE Byron Nelson Classic until his 73rd hole of the tournament. It
proved to be one trip too many.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loren Roberts, meanwhile, established himself as the Sultan of
Sand Traps at the Four Seasons Resort and Club. He saved par after
every misadventure, with the most pivotal coming during yesterday's
one-hole playoff at the TPC at Las Colinas course.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Roberts closed out the biggest birdie barrage in
Nelson history with a sandy par. It was not the most artistic way
to end a two-year victory drought on the PGA Tour. But, at age 43,
it felt long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd started doubting myself. I wondered if I had gotten too
old, with all these young guys out here,'' Roberts said. ``It's
nice to know I still have enough game to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed the ``Boss of the Moss'' because of his putting
prowess, Roberts instead leaned on his sand wedge to pocket the
$540,000 winner's check. He closed with a 68, allowing Roberts and
Pate to finish 72 holes in a tournament-record 18-under par (262).
</P>
<P>
   To break the tie, the competitors returned to the 18th tee box
for a sudden-death playoff. Roberts stood over his second shot,
which he played from the right rough, with one thought in mind at
the par-4 hole guarded by multiple, greenfront bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I didn't want to do was put it in the right
bunker,'' Roberts said, reflecting on a front-left pin placement.
``The way the wind was blowing, it was an almost impossible
up-and-down. It was too long of a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he deposited a 5-wood approach in the left-hand bunker.
Pate, in turn, pushed an approach from the middle of the fairway
into the front-right bunker that Roberts took pains to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Pate's lone bunker blast of the tournament hung
up in a 30 mph wind gust and stopped 20 feet short of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I thought it would be within six feet,'' Pate
said, shrugging. ``I couldn't have done much more with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, in turn, blasted to within 18 inches to set up his
fourth sand save in four attempts during the tournament. It proved
to be the stroke that ended the first Nelson playoff since 1994 and
provided the third consecutive 40-plus winner at a PGA Tour stop in
Fort Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, 49, is the defending champ at this week's MasterCard
Colonial. Roberts, 43, succeeds John Cook, 41, as the Nelson champ.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Pate, 37, he stood tall in swirling winds that blew
young hotshots such as Sergio Garcia (11 under) and Tiger Woods (9
under) out of contention. Garcia was in a three-player group that
tied for third, seven strokes short of participating in yesterday's
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   As their lead expanded throughout the final round, Pate said his
pairing with Roberts began feeling like a match-play competition.
If so, Roberts hit the most telling shot of the match with a
momentum-turning, 3-iron approach at No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The 190-yard shot stopped three feet from the cup, allowing
Roberts to tap in for a birdie that offset a waterlogged, double
bogey at No. 14. The double bogey marked Roberts' lone over-par
score on his final 37 holes of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty impressive comeback,'' Pate said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts called it ``one of my best swings of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his other greatest hits were struck from sand traps,
including his tournament-clinching bunker blast at No. 18.
Suddenly, the ``Boss of the Moss'' had proved he could win more
than a putting contest on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Tiger, Sergio and \RDavid\S Duval, that's the
future of golf right there,'' Roberts said. ``Mr. Nelson and Gene
Sarazen, that's the greatness of the past. I kind of fit somewhere
in the rest of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know the young guys can't win every week. So I want to
be there with a chance to win when they're not on their games.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether Roberts needs a hot putter or a timely
bunker blast to return to the winner's circle on the PGA Tour. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
