<SLUG> BC-BKN-MATCHUP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW LAKERS AND SPURS MATCH UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Centers: When the Spurs' David Robinson was in his
prime, he could handle Shaquille O'Neal, and the Spurs won all five
matchups against O'Neal's Orlando Magic teams. Then O'Neal joined
the Lakers and his teams won five straight against the Spurs in
games in which he and Robinson both played. The Lakers' loss to San
Antonio on April 24 was their first with O'Neal in the lineup.
O'Neal averaged 26.7 points, 11.7 rebounds and 2.33 blocked shots
in three games vs. the Spurs this season. Robinson averaged 12.7
points and 6.0 rebounds. __ Edge: Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Forwards: For the second straight series, the Lakers'
frontcourt will have its hands full. Tim Duncan, in just his second
year, is the premier power forward in the league and an MVP
candidate (21.7 points, 11.4 rebounds) who could overwhelm the
Lakers' J.R. Reid and Robert Horry. San Antonio's Sean Elliott, a
career of injuries behind him, averaged 11.2 points this season,
and his quickness could pose problems for Glen Rice. If Rice's
right elbow holds up, his 20 or so points per game could help even
this matchup. __ Edge: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Guards: Kobe Bryant will make the difference here, playing
against the older, less agile Mario Elie. Bryant averaged 17.0
points in three regular-season games against the Spurs. In Derek
Fisher and Avery Johnson, the Lakers and Spurs have two of the more
underrated point guards. Each has struggled, but each has turned
heads with strong playoff performances, particularly Johnson (19.5
points, 6.3 assists in Round 1). Fisher has cooled a bit since
scoring 36 points in the Lakers' first two playoff games. __ Edge:
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bench: The Lakers' reserves have come on strong since a poor
Game 1 against Houston. Robert Horry (7.0 points, 6.5 rebounds),
Derek Harper (7.0 points) and Rick Fox (6.5 points) have made key
postseason contributions. The Spurs have plenty of toughness off
the bench in Jerome Kersey, Will Perdue and Malik Rose, but little
scoring punch. Jaren Jackson led Spurs reserves with 5.8 points per
game in Round 1 of the playoffs, followed by Antonio Daniels (2.8
points). Ex-Bull Steve Kerr has yet to make an impact. __ Edge:
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach: If Gregg Popovich were a more hasty boss, the GM-coach
might have fired himself earlier this season when the Spurs
stumbled to a 6-8 start. But Popovich stayed cool and his team was
the best in the league over the final two months, earning top
seeding in the Western Conference. Lakers rookie-interim coach Kurt
Rambis survived his own shaky stretches, turning his team around
just in time for the playoffs. He has his players believing in each
other and working together, winning seven of their last eight. __
Edge: Even.
</P>
<P>
   __ Overall: The Spurs routed the Lakers by 27 points in their
most recent meeting, on April 24, but the Lakers are not the same
team. The Lakers won the first two meetings of the season, in
February, but that was a different San Antonio team, as well. Both
teams are playing at their peak and no one will stop O'Neal or
Duncan from getting 25 to 30 points per game. The series will come
down to the Lakers' patience running their offense against the
Spurs' tough defense. As long as O'Neal, Bryant and Rice are all
involved, the Lakers have the edge. San Antonio doesn't have the
offensive firepower to match them.
</P>
<P>
   __ Prediction: Lakers 4-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-16-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
