<HEADER>
A9502 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER MAKES QUICK WORK OF K.C. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's unclear just how many 10-year-olds in
double-knits showed up at the Kingdome Sunday. But 36,637 fans came
out for the finale of Little League Weekend, and this time the
Mariners brought their big-league game.
</P>
<P>
   This was a short-attention-span kind of day, completed faster
(2:37) than any other M's win this season and featuring timely
heroics by Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr. And if the players in
the stands kept close attention, so did the players on the field,
thanks to Jamie Moyer's eight shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer's performance, which highlighted the Mariners' 5-1 victory
over the Kansas City Royals, was welcome on a weekend that saw the
M's allow 23 runs while losing Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice when we can get a solid performance like that; it
takes the heat off us and makes it a lot easier to win,'' first
baseman David Segui said. ``Especially on defense, in the later
innings you're not mentally exhausted. It's a lot easier to
concentrate and play defense when you know a guy's in the strike
zone, not throwing ball after ball after ball. It makes it easier
to keep your concentration level high.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners played flawless defense behind Moyer, twice turning
double plays to end innings. The veteran left-hander struck out
five and walked two, speading eight singles over eight innings.
With runners in scoring position, he limited the Royals to one hit
in seven at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of outing that has eluded Moyer for much of this
season. Only twice in eight starts had he worked six innings and
allowed three runs or fewer, and one of those times _ Tuesday's win
at Boston _ he was not especially pleased with his command.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Moyer threw a greater percentage of strikes than he did
in Boston and lasted deeper into the game than he had all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie's a veteran,'' catcher Dan Wilson said. ``He's always
looking for ways to improve. We all knew it wasn't very far away.
Today, he made his pitches and just pitched outstanding. That's his
type of ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer (3-4) threw 121 pitches, a figure he's topped only once
since last July. The effort was needed, as manager Lou Piniella was
undermanned in relievers he uses when he needs a win. Jose Paniagua
had thrown 40 pitches Saturday, leaving a bullpen of three rookies
and closer Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said he was vaguely aware of bullpen activity in the
eighth inning, but he didn't know who was up and didn't concern
himself with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes,'' Moyer said. ``To me, it's just another
area to waste energy in. I have to put my energy toward what I'm
doing on the mound and how I'm pitching. If they want me to give
them nine, I'll do my darndest to get to nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella needed only eight Sunday, turning to Mesa for the
ninth. Jermaine Dye doubled and scored to spoil Seattle's chances
for its first shutout this season, but by then the M's already had
scored five runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight losses among their previous 11 games, the Mariners
had surrendered 84 runs, never giving up fewer than six. But the
way Moyer pitched, Seattle got all the runs it needed right away.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter led off the first inning with a single _ his first
hit in 15 at-bats _ and took second when rookie Chris Fussell's
pickoff throw eluded first baseman Jeff King. Hunter scored on a
double by Rodriguez, who scored on a Butch Huskey sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez set up the Mariners' next rally. After Fussell had set
down six M's in order, the shortstop doubled down the left-field
line and scored on a single by Griffey. John Mabry's single brought
in Griffey, who delivered again in the seventh, wrapping a Scott
Service pitch around the foul pole and into the second deck in
right.
</P>
<P>
   It was Griffey's major league-leading 14th home run and third in
as many games. The homer was for insurance, not for catch-up, a
pleasant change for an offense that scored 17 runs in losing the
first two games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, however, said the whole team shares the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season; even the best teams go through it,'' he
said. ``We win as a team, we lose as a team. That's just the way it
is. It's not one man's fault. Two days ago, if I would have gotten
a base hit, we could have tied the game. It would have changed
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's clear the Mariners will take plenty more games like
this, where pitching and defense reward offense for a job done
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball's a game of pitching, isn't it?'' Piniella said.
``Five runs, when you get a good-pitched game, is enough to win a
ballgame. That's exactly what we did today. It goes to show you if
you get good pitching, defense and timely hitting, you can win with
regularity. Today, we got some good pitching. It's a start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
