To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ After more than 50
days of bombing and with his troops still entrenched in Kosovo,
President Slobodan Milosevic is prepared for a settlement, so long
as the process can be portrayed as negotiation and not
capitulation, Yugoslav officials and analysts say. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Chinese liberals and political
dissidents are assessing what last week's nationalistic,
anti-American outburst, and the possible worsening of
Chinese-American relations, will mean for their struggle for a more
free and democratic society. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica) _ Montenegrins fear a ``creeping
coup'' by their Serb partners in the Yugolsav federation. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Los Angeles) _ The Clinton administration has
maintained a studied public neutrality in the Israeli campaign for
prime minister. But it has employed little guile in concealing its
rooting interest in the victory of Ehud Barak, the Labor Party
candidate. By James M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Uppington, South Africa) _ If South Africa's
second post-apartheid election campaign has offered any surprise at
all, it is the fuss that the Democratic Party has engendered. The
party and its antecedents, which traditionally represented wealthy,
English-speaking white liberals, consistently opposed apartheid and
were small but nagging irritants to the former white supremacist
Afrikaans-speaking regime. But even the ANC, which is expected to
coast to victory, perhaps with a two- thirds majority, has turned
its guns on the DP. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ARABS (Cairo) _ With his first foray into the Arab world,
Iran's president is taking a crucial step in a process of reaching
out to other countries. It is every bit as significant, but also as
tricky, as the rapprochement he has begun with the West. By Douglas
Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PENSIONS (Ludony, Russia) _ Russian debts are a funny
business, as big Western banks have learned to their horror and
chagrin. A pensioner here long ago stopped trying to figure out
when she will get her money. As she sees it, retrieving a pension
from the backlog that has piled up at the regional administrative
center of Pskov is sort of like a lottery. Either your number comes
up, or it doesn't. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRIALS-II (Whittier, Calif.) _ Dr. Robert Fiddes' Southern
California Research Institute was one of the most corrupt research
enterprises ever discovered by law enforcement. And the abuses of
this one doctor point to weaknesses in the new system that has
developed in recent years for testing experimental drugs, which,
for thousands of private-practice doctors, has become a sideline
for making money. Part two of a two-part series. By Kurt Eichenwald
and Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   HAWAII-BAYWATCH (Haleiwa, Hawaii) _ The biggest economic fish
caught in Hawaii this year is not a new factory or a high-tech
software start-up or a new planeload of Asian tourists, whose
financial troubles continue to keep them away in droves. No, the
biggest fish is David Hasselhoff, the head-lifeguard of
``Baywatch,'' which is to begin filming here in July, rechristened
``Baywatch Hawaii.'' By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-POLITICS (Glastonbury, Conn.) _ There may soon be a
parade of professional wrestlers who hope to duplicate last fall's
upset victory by Jesse Ventura, formerly ``the Body'' of the WWF
and now the governor of Minnesota. With huge built-in followings
and a sweaty instinct for pleasing the masses, these candidates
hope to tap voters' disgust with the same old political faces.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-REUNION (Charlottesville, Va.) _ If descendants of
Thomas Jefferson ever accept as their relatives people who claim as
forebears Jefferson and Sally Hemings, one of his slaves, the first
steps were taken over the weekend. However small they were. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-DECLINE (Undated) _ Crime in the United States dropped
dramatically last year, the seventh consecutive year it has fallen,
according to preliminary figures released by the FBI. The number of
violent crimes and property crimes each fell 7 percent in 1998,
creating the largest annual decline since crime began to decrease
in 1992. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   BREASTCANCER-STUDY (Undated) _ A new survey of women who took a
drastic measure to prevent breast cancer, having both healthy
breasts removed, shows that nearly 70 percent are satisfied with
their decision and would make the same choice if they had it to do
over again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-CAMPAIGN _ For all his devotion to Elizabeth Dole, and for
all the blessings he offers her campaign for president, Bob Dole is
nobody's compliant, stick-with-the-script,
gaze-lovingly-at-your-mate political spouse. In his first extensive
interview about the progress of his wife's campaign, Dole said he
wanted to give money to a rival candidate who was fighting for much
of her support. He conceded that Mrs. Dole's operation has had
growing pains, was slow to raise money early and was only beginning
to hit its stride. And while Dole was hopeful, he allowed that he
was by no means certain she would even stay in the race. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-POLITICS-SMITH _ A profile of Sen. Gordon Smith, at ground
zero of the gun debate. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NETWORKS-SITCOMS-MEDIA (Undated) _ The network process of
picking sit-coms for the fall season is taking place with an even
greater sense of urgency this year. Faced with a continuing loss in
audience and an explosion in technological advances, led by the
drive to connect the television set with the computer, the networks
are attempting to transform themselves into far more versatile
institutions. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHPOINT-DSL (San Francisco) _ Northpoint Communications,
which just went public, is emerging as a leader among the growing
crop of companies offering a type of high-speed Internet access
over telephone wires, known as digital subscriber line _ or DSL _
service. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GOVT-WEB-SITE (Undated) _ EXCLUSIVE: The federal government
plans to put a World Wide Web service into operation Monday that is
designed as a quick and easy way to find government documents and
resources online. But the service will not be free, stirring
criticism that the Clinton administration has forgotten its promise
to make the Internet and government data more accessible to
everyone. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-TIMES-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ The campaign by Mark Willes,
who appointed himself publisher of The Los Angeles Times 18 months
ago, to reinvigorate the flagship newspaper is in trouble.
Circulation was flat last year and fell in April, profits
reportedly dropped 15 percent in 1998, and two-thirds of the
paper's senior executives have raced, or been pushed, out the door.
Nonetheless, Willes' faith in his vision has not waned. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MININGCO-ABOUT (Undated) _ Miningco.com is changing its name as
of Monday to About.com _ a name the company says better captures
what this newly public Internet company is all about. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   TANQUERAY-AD-COLUMN _ The marketers of a well-known gin are
shaking, not stirring, its advertising, replacing a pitch based on
fantasy with one based on reality _ well, as realistic as you can
get on Madison Avenue. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BILLS-ONLINE (Undated) _ A growing number of Internet commerce
companies are delivering bills on line, with some of the nation's
biggest billers adopting online systems and one of the Internet's
most popular Web sites expected to offer similar billing services
by the end of the summer. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-NETWORKS-SNAP (Undated) _ Real Networks and NBC's Snap plan
to announce an alliance on Monday. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SURVEY (Undated) _ The largest companies in the nation
continue to fall behind their schedules for Year 2000 repairs, and
most suspect that their budget estimates for the remaining work are
too low, according to the latest survey in a closely watched series
that began in 1994. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-NOVEL-MEDIA (New York) _ Kurt Anderson, ultimate New
York media man, former editor of Spy and New York Magazine and now
a writer for the New Yorker, writes a novel about _ what else? _
the New York media world. But why should anyone care? By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-RADIO-MEDIA (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ A series of
announcements last week signals that the demographic profile of
people who listen to the radio on the Internet is expanding beyond
20-somethings to include the corporate set. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-ACTORS (Los Angeles) _ Profit-starved TV networks are in a
fever to develop fall series that attract younger audiences, and
Hollywood has been suffering an acute shortage of actors and
actresses in their teens and 20s for the pilot season. By James
Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   DEGAS-NEW-ORLEANS (New Orleans) _ A Degas exhibit in New Orleans
reveals much about his extended family and the character of this
boisterous, mysterious city, which now claims the artist as one of
their own. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   REVISIONS-THEATER (New York) _ There is certainly a civil war
going on in the American musical theater. On one side is the
musical as a big costly spectacle; on the other is the musical as a
vocal and physical ritual. By Margo Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   MIDNIGHT-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Peter Ackerman's latest
play, ``Things You Shouldn't Say Past Midnight,'' is all about the
mindless extremes we go to in categorizing one another, by race,
age and sex, and how these labels get in the way of a good time. By
Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   KORDA-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ As Michael Korda notes in
``Another Life: A Memoir of Other People,'' his engaging memoir of
a life in publishing, the daily chores of a book editor do not make
for dramatic narrative. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire on U.S.-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports column on
Chicago-Yankees game. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS (New York) _ Kerry Collins, a high school and
collegiate all-American and a National Football League star by the
time he was 24, once saw his life unravel in swift and ignoble
steps, a descent that transformed him from hero to cad while he was
still just 25. But if his resume was suddenly crowded with
offensive, unwholesome and disturbing demerits, it did not stop the
Giants from believing there was a better Collins if examined in the
whole. While other NFL teams ignored Collins' availability, the
Giants on Feb. 19 signed the troubled Collins to a four-year,
$16.9-million contract and set about helping him bring order in a
life where there was only a developing chaos. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on Knicks-Heat game.
By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
