Thomas Jefferson included people who claim to have Jefferson as
their father and Sally Hemings, one of his slaves, as their mother.
Julia Westerinen, left, a descendant of Hemings's son Eston Hemings
Jefferson, attended with her son Marshall and Ruby Cooley, the wife
of a descendant of another son, Thomas C. Woodson. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 16, 1999 -- GUN-POLITICS-SMITH, 5-16 --
Sen. Gordon H. Smith, R-Ore., who has been endorsed by the National
Rifle Association, is also part of a Republican shift on gun
control. Still, critics would argue that the Republican Party's
shifting stance on gun control was less a profile in courage than
an effort to get in front of the public opinion polls, which many
strategists believe show an electorate increasingly open to
regulating guns. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TOKYO -- May 16, 1999 -- WRESTLING-POLITICS-2, 5-16 --
Bob Backlund in Japan in 1980 in a match against ``Dusty Rose.''
Today, Backlund is on the campaign trail as a Republican
congressional candidate in greater Hartford, is leading a parade of
professional wrestlers who hope to duplicate last fall's upset
victory by Jesse Ventura, formerly ``the Body'' of the WWF and now
the governor of Minnesota. (George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GLASTONBURY, Conn. -- May 16, 1999 --
WRESTLING-POLITICS-1, 5-16 -- Bob Backlund, a former two-time
champion of the World Wrestling Federation, lecturing students at
the Hooker Elementary School in Hartford, Conn. Backlund, on the
campaign trail as a Republican congressional candidate in greater
Hartford, is leading a parade of professional wrestlers who hope to
duplicate last fall's upset victory by Jesse Ventura, formerly
``the Body'' of the WWF and now the governor of Minnesota. (George
Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LUDONY, Russia -- May 16, 1999 -- RUSSIA-PENSIONS, 5-16
-- A 75-year-old impoverished pensioner, Aleksandra Varfolomeyeva
speaks with her sister-in-law, gesturing at left, whose horse had
just run away. Ms. Varfolomeyeva keeps ``lending'' her meager
pension payments to the Russian government, but not cheerfully.
Mrs. Varfolomeyeva long ago stopped trying to figure out when she
will get her money. As she sees it, retrieving a pension from the
government backlog that has piled up is sort of like a lottery.
(Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
