u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-     05-16 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/16/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 16, 1999 -- DOLE-CAMPAIGN, 5-16 -- Bob
and Elizabeth Dole after his defeat by President Clinton in 1996.
With her campaign, they are breaking new ground in presidential
politics. Three times she stood by his side as he ran for the
presidency and lost, and recalling her tireless campaigning, he
says, ``I'm her biggest fan and supporter, and should do for her
what she did for me.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LOS ANGELES -- May 16, 1999 -- L.A.-TIMES-MEDIA, 5-16 --
The slow pace of change at The Los Angeles Times has frustrated
Mark Willes, center, the chairman and chief executive of Times
Mirror Co. ``What we said 18 months ago was we've got to reinvent
this very large, very complicated newspaper,'' said Willes.
``Still, there is going to be a large amount of change and breakage
in the process.'' (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW ORLEANS -- May 16, 1999 -- DEGAS-NEW-ORLEANS, 5-16
-- Degas family members: Elain Musson, seated, and from left,
Amanda Belge, Joan Prados, Charles Musson, Emma Glenny and Marie
Estelle Moyer; at far right, from left, Dolores Rillieux Turner and
Sidney and Edwina Rillieux. Two years ago a book by Christopher
Benfey, ``Degas in New Orleans,'' set the city astir by revealing
that a branch of the Degas family in this city is descended from a
black woman, Constance Vivant, who had six children with Vincent
Rillieux, a brother of Degas' maternal grandmother. (Lee Celano/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) RAANANA, Israel -- May 16, 1999 -- ISRAEL-VOTE, 5-16 --
Ehud Barak bringing his campaign for prime minister of Israel to a
close Sunday in Raanana. In a stunning turn of events, two minor
party candidates withdrew from the prime minister's race on Sunday,
paving the way for what polls predicted would be a conclusive
victory in Monday's elections for Barak, the leader of the Labor
Party. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- May 16, 1999 -- WASH-KERMIT-NYTRNG, 5-16
-- Sen. Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Sen. Mary
Landrieu, D.-La., pose with Kermit the Frog. Environmentalists are
complaining about the muppet's appearance in newscasts with
Louisiana lawmakers and Lott to chat up a bill that critics say
could promote increased offshore oil drilling. (George
Tolbert/Senate Photography via New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HALEIWA, Hawaii -- May 16, 1999 -- HAWAII-BAYWATCH-2,
5-16 -- Fans and citizens around Hawaii are hoping that the arrival
of ``Baywatch'' will bring back headier times to their state's
sluggish economy. The arrival of the ``Baywatch'' brand name is
being heralded as a return to the heady boom years when ``Hawaii
Five-O'' and ``Magnum, P.I.'' symbolized Hawaii's international
appeal and seemingly limitless growth. (David Scull/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HALEIWA, Hawaii -- May 16, 1999 -- HAWAII-BAYWATCH-1,
5-16 -- A quiet street in Haleiwa, Hawaii, reflects the state's
sluggish economy, but there is hope that ``Baywatch'' will bring
back headier times. The arrival of the ``Baywatch'' brand name is
being heralded as a return to the heady boom years when ``Hawaii
Five-O'' and ``Magnum, P.I.'' symbolized Hawaii's international
appeal and seemingly limitless growth. (David Scull/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- May 16, 1999 --
JEFFERSON-REUNION-3, 5-16 -- Taking a place on sacred ground at
Monticello, a reunion of Thomas Jefferson's descendants on Saturday
included people who claim as forebears Jefferson and his slave
Sally Hemings. Emily Westerinen, left, and Lucy Boettcher are of
the Hemings' line. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- May 16, 1999 -- DRUG-TRIALS-II-2, 5-16 -- Dr.
Robert Fiddes, far left, in a photo taken in the mid-1990's, as his
staff and his wife Rebecca, center, celebrated another successful
year of drug studies at a Christmas party. The festive mood soon
ended, as some of his employees and research assistants revealed
that Fiddes was conducting research fraud of audacious proportions,
cutting corners and inventing data to keep the money flowing from
the drug industry. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WHITTIER, Calif. -- May 16, 1999 -- DRUG-TRIALS-II-1,
5-16 -- Susan Lester, a former study coordinator of Dr. Robert
Fiddes, says patients were ``pushed'' to participate in drug
studies. Fiddes was conducting research fraud of audacious
proportions, cutting corners and inventing data to keep the money
flowing from the drug industry. ``Patients often would say, 'I
don't want to participate in this, but I don't want to make him
mad,''' says Ms. Lester. (Ed Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- May 16, 1999 --
JEFFERSON-REUNION-2, 5-16 -- United for the first time, decendants
of Thomas Jefferson and of his slave Sally Hemmings gathered over
the weekend at Monticello, his plantation, in Virginia. While
Jefferson descendants have been meeting here for the last 86 years,
no previous reunion has matched this one for sheer drama. In
November, geneticists supported what Sally Hemings descendants
always contended, that at least one of Hemings' sons, Eston, was
probably fathered by Jefferson. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- May 16, 1999 --
JEFFERSON-REUNION-1, 5-16 -- A weekend reunion of descendants of
Thomas Jefferson included people who claim to have Jefferson as
their father and Sally Hemings, one of his slaves, as their mother.
Julia Westerinen, left, a descendant of Hemings's son Eston Hemings
Jefferson, attended with her son Marshall and Ruby Cooley, the wife
of a descendant of another son, Thomas C. Woodson. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 16, 1999 -- GUN-POLITICS-SMITH, 5-16 --
Sen. Gordon H. Smith, R-Ore., who has been endorsed by the National
Rifle Association, is also part of a Republican shift on gun
control. Still, critics would argue that the Republican Party's
shifting stance on gun control was less a profile in courage than
an effort to get in front of the public opinion polls, which many
strategists believe show an electorate increasingly open to
regulating guns. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TOKYO -- May 16, 1999 -- WRESTLING-POLITICS-2, 5-16 --
Bob Backlund in Japan in 1980 in a match against ``Dusty Rose.''
Today, Backlund is on the campaign trail as a Republican
congressional candidate in greater Hartford, is leading a parade of
professional wrestlers who hope to duplicate last fall's upset
victory by Jesse Ventura, formerly ``the Body'' of the WWF and now
